<HEADLINE>
WELLS: LET YANKEES FANS KNOCK TRADE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- After winning the World Series in 1998, the
Yankees felt they could get better by trading for Roger Clemens,
sending David Wells, second baseman Homer Bush and reliever Graeme
Lloyd to the Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a one-sided trade in favor of the Blue Jays, and
would have been even if Wells and Clemens were traded straight up.
</P>
<P>
   In 1 seasons since the deal, Wells is 32-12 with a 4.32 ERA,
Clemens is 20-16 with a 4.51 ERA. Sure, Clemens has a 1999 World
Series ring, but the Yankees would have won it without Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Said Wells, who has become the leading candidate to win the A.L.
Cy Young award: ''I'm sure they (Yankees) all regret it. I think
the fans are upset by it. But I'll let the fans scream and holler
at George Steinbrenner, and I'll go out and do my job. I don't hold
any grudges.''
</P>
<P>
   MOONLIGHTING: Tigers reliever Todd Jones has something to fall
back on if baseball doesn't work out. He writes a sports column for
a small newspaper in Georgia. These are his thoughts from the
All-Star game.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the biggest things I noticed is how patient the
superstars were with everyone,'' he said. ''With the fans, the
media and with us other players. There are definitely two tiers of
players at these things. The ones who know they'll be an All-Star
again and the ones who can only hope. I was glad to see there
weren't any big egos in the clubhouse, but it took awhile for some
guys to let their guard down. Unlike me -- I don't have a guard to
let down.''
</P>
<P>
   YOU CAN'T PLEASE EVERYBODY: All-Star managers often are
criticized for selecting their own players over others that might
be more deserving. But Yankees manager Joe Torre drew the ire of
one of his own players for NOT selecting him.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees reliever Jeff Nelson, upset he wasn't chosen by Torre to
the A.L. squad, said: ''If I am not going to get the respect from
my manager, I am not going to be a bulldog and suck one up for the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Yankees GM Brian Cashman spoke with Nelson about it, and Nelson
later apologized to Torre.
</P>
<P>
   ESCAPE FROM NEW YORK: Orioles players Scott Erickson, Sidney
Ponson and Jeff Conine were fined by manager Mike Hargrove for
taking an unauthorized trip from New York back to Baltimore to
attend a July 4 Metallica concert.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson was the winning pitcher in a victory at Yankee Stadium
in a July 4 afternoon game, and the three left after the game and
went to the concert that night in Baltimore. They returned early
the next morning. One day later, on July 6, Ponson gave up six runs
in 1 fr 1/3 innings in a 13-9 loss.
</P>
<P>
   RIPKEN WATCH: Rumors are circulating that Cal Ripken Jr.,
because of an ongoing back problem, will retire before the end of
the season. Ripken, 40, is expected to be activated from the
disabled list today. His current back problem apparently is related
to last year's back surgery. Doctors believe there is a disk
fragment floating around in his back. Ripken, obviously, isn't one
to give up easily and denies he is close to retiring.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to put the uniform back on and see what happens,'' he
told the Baltimore Sun. ''I want to play as much of the second half
as I possibly can.''
</P>
<P>
   SHORT HOPS: A's first baseman Jason Giambi thanked fans in
Oakland for helping vote him into the All-Star game as a starter by
taking out a full-page ad in the Oakland Tribune. ... Since manager
Charlie Manuel ordered the ping-pong table out of the clubhouse and
banned card games, the Indians are 6-3.
</P>
</TEXT>
