<HEADLINE>
DODGERS SHOULDN'T GIVE AWAY THE FARM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Deep, talent-rich farm systems are the reason the
New York Yankees and Atlanta Braves have been atop baseball for the
past decade, and every other organization is striving to get to
that level.
</P>
<P>
   So why would the Dodgers contemplate further depleting their
near-naked farm system to make a run at the second-tier pitcher who
guarantees them nothing but the loss of prospects, which will only
be felt with more impact later?
</P>
<P>
   The answer: a $90 million payroll, $200-per-game seats behind
home plate and luxury boxes that cost up to $300,000 per season.
</P>
<P>
   The big-market mentality says a team must win every year, but
the Dodgers shouldn't succumb to that. They shouldn't go out and
acquire a middle-of-the-road pitcher as the July 31 trading
deadline nears. They shouldn't think only about the next two
months, but about the next five years. By then, the farm system
should be mature and winning won't come sporadically, but
consistently.
</P>
<P>
   So far, managing general partner and CEO Bob Daly and general
manager Kevin Malone have said they'll exhibit the patience needed,
which means hanging on to young pitchers like Eric Gagne and Mike
Judd.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to trade Gagne,'' Daly said. ``A long time ago
I said to Sean Connery when he said he would never do James Bond,
'Never say never again.' I learned from that statement, never to
say never. But the truth of the matter is a lot of teams are
interested in Gagne, but he's a guy the Dodgers are very high on.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the only way to go if the Dodgers are to end a
more-than-a-decade dry spell when it comes to winning the World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   It may not bode well for this season, particularly if Darren
Dreifort and Gagne don't pitch better and Devon White can't be
effective when he returns from the disabled list, but it does hold
enormous meaning in the upcoming years.
</P>
<P>
   Not only in developing talent to play at the major-league level,
but to put the organization in better position when future trade
deadlines roll around.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were able to acquire Denny Neagle because their farm
system is loaded with talent. The Dodgers wanted Neagle but didn't
have the prospects to make the kind of deal the Yankees could.
Ditto with Philadelphia moving Andy Ashby to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it's frustrating for the Dodgers' front office, but it's
something they must muddle through.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a philosophy and a plan,'' Malone said. ``If you
have goals and a plan like we do, then you stick to it. To trade
two or three prospects away from our system, that's not part of the
plan. We'd like to upgrade, but we don't want to make a trade for
the sake of making a trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get to the point of where the Yankees are. They
have depth and quality because they have numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   If it's the playoffs, fine. If it's short of the playoffs, then
it's not what the cash being doled out dictates, but it's the way
it is. It takes time to build a system, to build a winning
organization. Before Gene Michael revamped the Yankees'
minor-league system, they spent like mad but didn't win.
</P>
<P>
   But trying to bring in a second-line pitcher at the cost of
giving up prospects isn't the answer, especially when it will cost
the Dodgers more in the short and long runs. Get rid of a young
player making $200,000 this season and the Dodgers will have to pay
millions upon millions in the free-agent market to fill that void
later. And that's millions of dollars the Dodgers could use to
upgrade another area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to sacrifice our farm system to get a player
who would have only limited use this year, and maybe, at best, a
marginal player,'' Daly said. ``If we could get some player who has
long-term, positive effects on the organization, obviously anybody
would listen to that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're not going to go out and get a pitcher who pitches
.500, who costs us a lot of money and costs us two or three
prospects.''
</P>
</TEXT>
