<HEADLINE>
GREENE, JONES DASH INTO OLYMPICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL OBERJUERGE  
 San Bernardino Sun 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO -- Maurice Greene and Marion Jones have been faster.
</P>
<P>
   They may never have been happier.
</P>
<P>
   The world's fastest humans were nearly giddy with joy Saturday
after clinching berths for the Sydney Summer Games at the U.S.
Olympic Track and Field Trials at Sacramento State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the Olympic team, I made the Olympic team,'' Greene
sang in childish delight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been 17 years now going at this thing called track and
field,'' Jones said. ``My dream always was to be an Olympian.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene, the world-record holder in the 100-meter dash at 9.79
seconds, recovered from a near-disastrous start to finish first in
10.01 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Jones also fought through a sluggish start, but won the women's
100-meter dash more convincingly (but still off her personal best
of 10.65), in 10.88 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to feel that Olympic spirit that everyone has always
talked a bout,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones led Inger Miller (11.05) and Chryste Gaines (11.13) in the
race for the top three spots.
</P>
<P>
   Greene was followed across the finish line by fellow HSI
teammates Curtis Johnson (10.06) and Jon Drummond (10.07).
</P>
<P>
   Drummond promptly predicted U.S. success in the 100 meters at
Sydney, even though American hegemony in the event has waned in
recent Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sun shines on a dog's behind every now and then, and now
it's flipped,'' Drummond said. ``It's time for world dominance.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Greene nor Jones has been in an Olympics, and their
reactions Saturday indicated what a void it has been -- despite
their various and sundry world and national championships.
</P>
<P>
   Greene flamed out in the first round of the 1996 trials; Jones
missed the 1996 season after suffering a broken bone in her foot
while playing basketball, which she has since given up.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said she expects the other American sprinters to work
well with Jones on the sprint-relay team in Sydney. ``I don't
dislike her,'' Miller said of Jones. ``I just get tired of
answering questions about her.''
</P>
<P>
   Two-time defending Olympic champion Gail Devers finished a close
fifth , at 11.149 seconds. The top three compete for the individual
medal, and the top four typically make up the relay team.
</P>
<P>
   Devers also is competing in the 100-meter hurdles here.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was asked about the long jump final, scheduled for today,
and exclaimed in mild exasperation, ``Can't I just enjoy this for a
couple of hours?''
</P>
<P>
   She predicted she would get a good night's sleep Saturday, ``as
opposed to last night,'' and be primed for an attempt to make the
team in the long jump, the weak link in her quest for an
unprecedented five track-and-field gold medals at Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   In other events on a scorching Saturday before another capacity
crowd at Hornet Stadium:
</P>
<P>
   -- Adam Nelson, a former linebacker at Dartmouth, was the
surprise winner of the shotput, in a meet-record 72 feet, 7 inches.
Nelson, 25, began intensive training in the discipline only three
years ago, and as recently as a month ago held a full-time job at a
Silicon Valley firm.
</P>
<P>
   C.J. Hunter, also known as Mr. Marion Jones, qualified second at
71-9, and Andy Bloom third at 70-10. John Godina's hopes to double
in the shot and discus ended with his fourth-place finish in the
shot, at 69-2 1/2 .
</P>
<P>
   Bloom said ``anyone who has been paying any attention could have
known '' the shot would produce outstanding competition. ``We came
here with four guys who have gone 70 feet this year, and I don't
think that's ever happened in one country.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter said Saturday's results, ``should scare the hell out of
the Europeans.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Dawn Ellerbe won the women's hammer throw with an effort of
227 feet. The women's hammer is a first-time Olympic event.
</P>
<P>
   -- Michael Johnson sailed into the 400-meter final with a
semifinal-best clocking of 44.63. ``I ran only as hard as I had to
run to win and as sure myself a good lane'' for today's final,
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he might make an assault on his world record of
43.18, Johnson said, ``the goal here is to get to the Olympics.
It's about placing, not about time.''
</P>
<P>
   -- DeDee Nathan scored 6,343 points to win the heptathlon by
four points over UCLA alumnus Shelia Burrell.
</P>
<P>
   Finals Sunday include the men's and women's 400, the men's and
women's 1,500 and the women's long jump.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
