<HEADER>
A3495 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-OLY-TRACKTRIALS-HNS &LR;      07-16 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TRACK </SLUG>
 TRIALS-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Jones, Greene lead the way in 100
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JERRY WIZIG &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ One down, two to go for Marion Jones at the
U.S. Olympic Track and Field Trials.
</P>
<P>
   Waving a toy Australian koala bear to the crowd, Jones might
have felt it was slightly lighter than the 100-meter gold medal she
now will have a chance to win at the 2000 Olympics in Sydney.
Jones, the event's favorite in this meet since winning the gold at
last year's World Championships at Seville, Spain, smoothly
accelerated down the track to lead the seven other finalists by a
comfortable margin in the 100 Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing Jones' time of 10.88 seconds were Inger Miller, last
year's 200-meter world champion, in 11.05 and Chryste Gaines in
11.13.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Greene didn't have as easy a time of it in the men's
100, trailing several runners out of the blocks after two false
starts (neither by Greene) and staging his usual burst of blinding
speed the final 50 meters.
</P>
<P>
   The world-record holder and two-time world champion, Greene,
like Jones, made his first U.S. Olympic team with a notable time of
10.01 into a slight head wind. Joining him on the American 100 team
will be runner-up Curtis Johnson and Jon Drummond in third, both
clocking 10.07.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crossing the finish line, I couldn't believe the emotion of
it, realizing what had just happened,'' said Jones, whose husband,
C.J. Hunter, was second in the shot put Saturday and also qualified
for the U.S. team.
</P>
<P>
   Jones now has today's long jump final, then the 200 next weekend
in her remaining work load for a chance at five Olympic gold
medals. She virtually is assured a spot on the 400 relay team and
will be considered for the 1,600 relay as the fastest American thus
far this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something I have dreamed of since I was 9 years old, and it's
finally going to happen,'' Jones said of her Olympic aspirations.
``It's going to be the second time (today) I have been able to
compete against my idol (Jackie Joyner-Kersee) in the long jump,
and that also will make it a wonderful experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``People keep asking me about the pressure (of attempting to win
the five golds). I just wish I had a penny for every time I have
heard that. It's no pressure. It's just a goal I have set for
myself, and I will try the best I can to go and do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones sounded like the hardest part was over, even though the
long jump has been her most troublesome event of late.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't you just let me enjoy this for a couple of hours? Now I
can have a nice dinner, focus on the long jump and not have to
worry about going back and forth between the two (as in the
qualifying),'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gail Devers, the '92 and '96 gold medalist in the 100, and a
favorite to make the U.S. team in that event and the 100 hurdles
this week, faded to fifth in the final 25 meters after a fast
start. Nanceen Perry was sixth and Carlette Guidry, a two-time 400
relay gold medalist, was seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Greene, referring to his upcoming 200-meter meeting with Michael
Johnson next weekend, sounded a conciliatory note after the two had
exchanged verbal shots recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot has been said this week, '' Greene said. ``The bottom
line is, I've made the team. I took the first step.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Marsh is left looking forward to the 200 after failing to
advance past the 100 semifinals. He never found his usual
acceleration gear and placed sixth, missing a berth in the final by
.009 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``My worst race of the year,'' said Marsh, the '92 Olympic gold
medalist in the 200. ``You hate for it to come at a time like this.
I didn't have the acceleration at the end like I usually have. I
have a week now to get refocused for the 200.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene, Curtis Johnson and Drummond all had to overtake Brian
Lewis, who blazed out of the blocks only to finish fourth in 10.09.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Greene, who was only seventh in the '96 trials
semifinals at Atlanta, was confident and relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a terrible start,'' he said, ``but I didn't let it worry
me. Ten seconds is a lot of time when you're running the race the
right way.''
</P>
<P>
   Within the space of about 15 minutes, Greene and Jones staged a
clinical demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
