<HEADLINE>
OLD RIVALS ARE NEW MATES IN WOMEN'S 100
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ On Friday, presumably under the influence
of a tight deadline, gold-medal Olympian Michael Johnson wrote in a
national newspaper that he didn't think sprinter Inger Miller would
make the U.S. Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, alas, Miller came looking for the golden one.
``Where's Michael Johnson?'' she wanted to know, after finishing
second in the 100 meters of the U.S. Olympic Track and Field
Trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think maybe he should untwist those beads he's got in
his hair. They're on too tight.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was too busy, cruising in the final steps of his
400-meter semifinal. The better story was the three rivals suddenly
turned teammates: Miller, Marion Jones and Chryste Gaines, a native
of Dallas who went to South Oak Cliff High School. Or three men
letting loose 70-foot throws in the shot put.
</P>
<P>
   Blasting from the blocks in the women's 100 final, Jones torched
the testy Miller and the rest of a talented field. She was clocked
in 10.88 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, the closest pursuer, who had boldly said that she was
the one who could beat Jones, finished a well-beaten second in
11.05. Gaines was third in 11.13, and after 10 world-class seasons
on the track scene will be going to her first Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Gail Devers finished fifth in 11.149 and lost a chance to become
the second woman to win consecutive Olympic 100 meters.
</P>
<P>
   While Jones was winning the 100, her husband, C.J. Hunter, found
himself in a dogfight to make the medal podium in the men's shot
put. Expected to be a two-man show between Hunter and 1996 Atlanta
silver medalist John Godina, the competition instead started
raining 70-foot throws.
</P>
<P>
   Relative unknown Adam Nelson let loose a personal-best throw of
72 feet, 7 inches on his final attempt of the day to win the
competition. Hunter had to toss the shot 71-9 on his final attempt
to secure a place on the Olympic team. And Andy Bloom grabbed the
third place on the team by throwing 70-10 3/4, also on his final
try.
</P>
<P>
   All three are members of the Nike Track Club, prompting the
oft-injured Bloom to remark: ``We knew this was going to happen for
a year. There's no doubt this was going to be the event it was.''
</P>
<P>
   The winner himself, however, wasn't so certain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surprised? Yes,'' Nelson said. ``I'm so elated, I can't
believe what just happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson's 72-7 is the longest throw in the world this year.
Godina, on the other hand, threw 69-2 1/2 and has the distinction
of being the farthest thrower in any U.S. trials not to make the
Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   In the women's heptathlon which concluded Saturday, DeDee Nathan
won by four points with 6,343 and ended a personal run of
heartbreak in which she had finished fourth in the two previous
Olympic trials.
</P>
<P>
   Shelia Burrell and Kelly Blair-LaBounty finished second and
third, respectively, and joined Nathan on the U.S. team.
</P>
<P>
   In the men's 400, meanwhile, Johnson found himself in the
unusual position of not being in the lead as he turned for the
stretch in his semifinal heat. But Johnson seemed to take one peek
at Jerome Young in Lane Two, and then found a passing gear for the
next 30 meters or so. The Dallas resident was timed in 44.63.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the women asked for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said I wasn't going to make the team,'' Miller explained.
</P>
<P>
   To her right sat Jones, whose Olympic quest for five gold medals
_ in the 100, 200, long jump and both relays _ figures to be a
dominant theme as the Sydney Olympics near. Next to Johnson, Jones
has become track and field's most recognizable face, even though
only half of hers is visible in Nike's popular ``Mrs. Jones'' ad
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   No, she said once again Saturday, she doesn't feel pressure in
going for five gold medals.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had a penny for every time someone asked me that, I'd be
rich,'' Jones answered.
</P>
<P>
   Miller and Gaines immediately turned to Jones and, in unison,
shrieked, ``You're not now?''
</P>
<P>
   Oops, Jones winced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the wrong choice of words,'' said the impending queen of
track and field.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's events, Jones will try to secure her Olympic place
in the long jump. Finals are also scheduled in the women's high
jump, 400 and 1,500 meters, and in the men's pole vault and 1,500,
as well as Johnson's bid to win the 400. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
