<HEADLINE>
TRACK'S CLOWN PRINCE GETS THE ULTIMATE LAUGH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Hard to believe, but nine years have passed
since sprinter Jon Drummond wore a TCU track uniform.
</P>
<P>
   That would be nine years, three Olympic trials and a decade's
worth of run-on sentences. Wind-aided.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why, but people seem to lose confidence in me and
they don't have faith in me,'' Drummond mused Saturday at the U.S.
Olympic Track and Field Trials. ``They forget about me or
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, rumors of his track demise seem to have been sadly
misreported. Jon Drummond, who once dubbed ``himself'' ``The Clown
Prince of Track and Field,'' is headed back to the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   Note to global media: Bring plenty of notebook paper.
</P>
<P>
   Bolting from the blocks in the final of the Olympic trials' 100
meters, the Philadelphia native actually led for the first 60,
before finally being passed by world-record holder Maurice Greene.
</P>
<P>
   Greene finished in 10.01 seconds, followed by somebody named
Curtis Johnson, who nipped Drummond at the tape. The finish photo
pegged Johnson's second-place time as 10.066 to Drummond's 10.070 _
barely an inch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to the Olympics, I'm going to the Olympics,'' Greene
nyah-nyah-nyahed in the interview tent.
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise that Greene is going, of course. Two-time
defending world champions and world-record holders are supposed to
survive even the cutthroat U.S. method of picking an Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   But with Drummond, who knows, even though he has been ranked in
the top nine in the United States every year since his senior
season at TCU?
</P>
<P>
   For the third time in his life, Drummond endured a bout with
spinal meningitis in 1999. Earlier this track season, he was
hampered by a strained hamstring. His entire career at TCU, in
fact, seemed like one long injury.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that the footnote that, all rankings aside, Drummond has
never won the 100 meters at a major meet _ not the NCAAs (injured
in '90, second in '91), not the U.S. championships (second in '94,
cramps in '98, etc.), and not the Olympic Games (sixth in his
semifinal in Atlanta).
</P>
<P>
   ``The last Olympics,'' Drummond explained Saturday, ``that was
just a mind-blowing experience. It was like I made the team and,
oh, I forgot you've got to go run a race there.''
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth, Texas, remains a distant memory. Drummond lives in
southern California now, where he trains with Greene and Johnson as
part of HSI International's world-class stable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like you saw today _ that's our practice,'' Drummond said of
the post-race, chest-thumping, we-the-man celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of trash-talking,'' Greene interjected.
</P>
<P>
   Greene did put on a veneer of interview-tent humility and tried
to sound humbled just to have made the Olympic team. But he had
talked a lot louder on Friday night, when he won his heat in 9.93
seconds and clucked at how some people (Michael Johnson,
presumably) thought he might not be ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of things have been said, but the bottom line here is to
just make the Olympic team,'' Greene declared Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Well, whatever. Johnson, 26, is a North Carolina product who,
like Drummond, has never won the 100 in a major national or
international meet. And Drummond will be 32 when he toes the
starting line in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, Drummond clearly has the credentials. But you have to wonder
what the rest of the sprinting world is going to think of a U.S.
team in the 100 meters that doesn't have Carl Lewis (very retired),
Dennis Mitchell (finished last) or Mike Marsh (sixth in semis) on
it.
</P>
<P>
   Lest we forget, a U.S. sprinter hasn't crossed the finish line
first in the Olympic 100 meters since Lewis did it 16 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's Ben Johnson won the 1988 Olympic final, only to be
disqualified for running on something more than unleaded. Great
Britain's Linford Christie took the gold medal at Barcelona in
1992. And Jamaica-born Donovan Bailey, running for Canada, led a
stunning 100 finish in Atlanta in which no U.S. runner finished in
the medals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sun's going to shine on a dog's butt sooner or later,''
Drummond observed Saturday. ``It's time to flip it. It's time for
world domination _ ``Pinky and the Brain'' stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   While he mended from his recent hamstring injury, Drummond
lamented, nobody came to interview him. Fine, he said. Saturday was
a much better day to talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``For every man who suffers tribulation, he triumphs,'' Drummond
declared. ``Today was just a pit stop.''
</P>
<P>
   The Olympics, he predicted, is going to be much better for Jon
Drummond the second time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want a gold medal,'' he said. ``I think I've been through
enough that I want a gold medal.''
</P>
<P>
   Stayed tuned. And bring plenty of notebook paper. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
