<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON CAN'T STOP FIRED-UP RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The Texas Rangers pulled off the almost impossible
Saturday, a feat that could make catching the Seattle Mariners a
piece of cake by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Texas trailed the National League's most dominant pitcher, 5-1,
after six innings in his own ballpark, and rallied for what could
be their biggest victory of the year in what easily was a classic
baseball game.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, this might have been the Rangers' most complete
team victory because they needed contributions from almost
everybody on the roster to pull out a 6-5 victory against Randy
Johnson and the Arizona Diamondbacks at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, and Thursday's thrilling ninth-inning comeback,
gave the Rangers two of three against the first-place Diamondbacks,
who entered the series with second-best home record in the NL.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tremendous win,'' Rangers closer John Wetteland said. ``Some
guys stepped up today; it was awesome. The guy announcing the game
referred to them as the shock troops. That's awesome. Guys who
rarely get to play got in there and won the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Luis Alicea delivered the game-winner, a two-out triple in the
11th inning off reliever Greg Swindell that scored Mike Lamb from
first base with the go-ahead run. But Alicea was merely the last in
a long line of heroes on a day when the Rangers' starting lineup
didn't include Rafael Palmeiro, Rusty Greer, Ivan Rodriguez or
Lamb.
</P>
<P>
   ``A great team win,'' starter Matt Perisho said. ``The bullpen
came through, great clutch hitting. That was baseball at it's
best.''
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Jeff Zimmerman might have been at his best at a time
when the Rangers need him most. Showing some flashes of the form
that made him an All-Star last year, Zimmerman pitched 21/3
scoreless innings to get the victory. He kept the go-ahead run at
third base in the eighth inning by striking out Jason Conti to end
the inning and kept the Diamondbacks from scoring in the 10th after
Matt Williams led off with a double.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zim, no doubt, is throwing the ball as good as we've ever
seen,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said. ``He's throwing some
nice sliders, and he's throwing his fastball by people. He got some
real big strikeouts.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman and five other Rangers pitchers showed their grit by
holding the Diamondbacks to 1-for-11 with runners in scoring
position, including 0-for-6 from the eighth inning on, when one bad
pitch could have meant the ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the Diamondbacks' one hit with runners in scoring
position may have led to their downfall. It was a two-out, two-run
double by Johnson in the sixth inning that gave the Diamondbacks a
5-1 lead. Johnson was thrown out trying to stretch the double into
a triple, and his jaunt around the bases might have zapped him of
some needed strength.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' comeback began the next inning when Scott Sheldon
singled with two outs and scored on pinch hitter Kelly Dransfeldt's
double into the left-field corner. That made it 5-2, and the
Rangers added three more off Johnson in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt pretty deflated after the eighth,'' Johnson said. ``I
didn't put them away. There are no excuses. I let them back in the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Scarborough Green, who struck out in his first three at-bats,
led off with a walk, and, after Chad Curtis flied out, David Segui
singled to left. Bill Haselman then lined his second run-scoring
double to right, scoring Green and moving Segui to third.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona manager Buck Showalter then replaced Johnson with
right-hander Vicente Padilla, but the Rangers weren't through.
Greer, pinch hitting for Gabe Kapler, bounced out to first base to
score Segui, and, after Rafael Palmeiro was walked intentionally,
Lamb singled to center to bring home Haselman.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers _ who had one run, three hits and 11 strikeouts in
the first six innings _ had tied the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two nice ballgames to win here,'' Oates said. ``You come in
here and you're able to battle back. A lot of clutch performances
out there.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
