r s BC-OLY-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     07-16 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRACK STARS ALSO RUNNING AT THE MOUTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO - We went to a track meet Saturday and a professional
wrestling match broke out. Oh, for a few breathtaking seconds it
was all above board; Marion Jones and Maurice Greene made the 2000
U.S. Olympic team just like everybody assumed they would, Jones
leaving rival Inger Miller and Chryste Gaines in her vapor trail
and Greene breezing by Curtis Johnson and training partner Jon
Drummond on the second day of the U.S. Olympic Track and Field
Trials at Cal State Sacramento's Hornet Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Then the winners reported to the big tent for their postrace
press conferences and the atmosphere turned from sublime to silly
in around eight seconds flat, which we're pretty sure is some kind
of record.
</P>
<P>
   It began with Miller, of all people, posing the first question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's Michael Johnson?'' the Canoga Park resident wanted to
know, her interest in locating the world's fastest 200 and
400-meter runner tied to a guest column he had penned for Friday's
editions of USA Today that read, in part, ``I think Inger Miller
will have a tough time making the team. I think she and some of her
teammates ... have lost focus and rested on what they did last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   And people think our pen is poisoned?
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who had won his semifinal heat in the 400 meters
shortly before the 100 finals, was nowhere to be found, thereby
breaking the first commandment of responsible journalism: He who
rips shall promptly show his face for the figurative or literal
slap he may have coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael has a lot to say,'' Miller sniffed. ``Maybe he should
untie some of those beads in his hair. They're too tight.''
</P>
<P>
   Sigh. So much for taking the higher road. Lord knows it is the
one less-traveled in track and field these days, since impertinence
was discovered to be a shortcut to celebrity and lots of newspaper
and magazine column inches.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, no sooner had Miller finished dissing Johnson than
someone asked: Since Jones has announced her intentions to win five
gold medals in Sydney, where does that leave Miller?
</P>
<P>
   ``That puts me, I guess, stopping her from doing that,'' Miller
said, the irritation rising like bile in her throat.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 24, joined Miller, 28, and Gaines, 29, on the podium soon
thereafter and immediately the temperature in the tent fell
precipitously. Though they were sitting no more than two feet
apart, Jones and Miller didn't exchange so much as a glance, much
less a hello or a handshake.
</P>
<P>
   The Cold War? It's alive and well in Sprintville, where nobody
gives anybody credit and everybody feels under siege.
</P>
<P>
   Even Jones, the fastest living sprinter on the planet, cannot
outrun the slings and arrows. Asked if she feels any added pressure
because of her brash Olympic predictions, the former Thousand Oaks
and Rio Mesa high school standout sighed and replied, ``If I had a
penny for every time somebody asked me that, I'd be very, very
rich.''
</P>
<P>
   That got Miller and Gaines giggling like sorority sisters. Uh,
Marion, they reminded her in so many words, you (begin ital)are(end
ital) very, very rich.
</P>
<P>
   Touche, said the suddenly sheepish $7 million woman. ``Maybe the
wrong choice of words,'' Jones said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   That was as warm as the exchanges between Jones and her sprint
court would get. Let's hope their baton handoffs in the 400 relay
in Sydney are keener.
</P>
<P>
   The women's signal that they were through having to pretend to
be happy to be U.S. Olympic teammates was none too subtle. Greene,
25, burst into the tent, screaming in a sing-song voice, ``I made
the Olympic team. I made the Olympic team.''
</P>
<P>
   Forget that Greene is the world record-holder in the event and
remember this: The 1996 Olympics proceeded without him after he
failed to get out of the first round at the U.S. Trials.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, this day should have belonged to the 31-year-old
Drummond, who had the run of his life when you consider his
near-death experience last year. He was stricken twice with spinal
meningitis and was bedridden for almost three weeks with
excruciating pain because of inflammation of the membrane
surrounding his brain. He lost 20 pounds but not one ounce of his
faith in God.
</P>
<P>
   It's a heartwarming story, to be sure. But there's no place for
sentiment in today's mud-slinging scene. And so Drummond was
content to trade one-liners with Greene, playing Dean Martin to
Greene's Frank Sinatra while the very quiet (by comparison) Johnson
played the straight man a la Sammy Davis Jr.
</P>
<P>
   There was one moment when we thought Drummond was going to lose
it. Somebody recounted what Miller, one of his training mates at
UCLA, had said about Johnson and Drummond, in mid-swill, spit out a
mouthful of water and squealed.
</P>
<P>
   All this in the name of promoting track and field. Frankly,
their methods struck us as all wet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
