<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUMMER-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MADSEN MAKES GOOD IMPRESSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAMES MELROY  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ An injured wrist has limited Laker
first-round draft pick Mark Madsen to just three games during the
2000 NBA Summer Pro League at the Pyramid.
</P>
<P>
   But, a word of advice for anyone that comes in contact with
Madsen.
</P>
<P>
   Never bring up the word ``limit.''
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 90 seconds after entering the game for the first
time in the first quarter, Madsen was on the ground, diving for a
loose ball and giving his team a jump-ball possession.
</P>
<P>
   Tenacious? Scrappy? Yes, those adjectives apply. But Madsen's
given nickname says it all: ``Mad Dog.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to give you 100 percent all the time and that's the
kind of guy we like,'' said Laker assistant coach Tex Winter, after
the Lakers' 114-112 loss to the Warriors on Saturday afternoon.
``He's a very tough competitor. They don't call him `Mad Dog' for
nothing, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   What made the hustle even more impressive was the fact that
Madsen has only been able to compete in three games this summer due
to a wrist injury suffered before the summer league began.
</P>
<P>
   Madsen appeared to be a bit rusty early on, and the wrist injury
clearly bothered his shooting. In fact, according to Winter, Madsen
should not even be attempting to shoot much, if at all, because of
the injury.
</P>
<P>
   But Madsen said that getting out and getting his blood pumping
in a game situation was the most important thing right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt good to get out there and run up and down,'' said
Madsen, who finished with seven points and four rebounds in just
under 30 minutes of action. ``Getting my wind back and my timing
back will take a little time, but I felt good and I feel like I am
contributing to the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he hasn't been able to take the court as often as he may
have liked, Madsen has found time to do other important things
while in Long Beach, such as visit his grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Madsen family as a whole, has strong ties to the
Long Beach area.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandfather, Bill Gould, lives right down the street (from
the Pyramid) as a matter of fact,'' Madsen said after the game.
``And my mom (Erlyn Gould Madsen) went to Millikan High. Her
picture is up at the school. She's a great violinist. She's one of
the best violinist that has ever gone through that school.''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the highlight of the whole summer thus far, occured
last night for Madsen. But it was no where near the basketball
court.
</P>
<P>
   Madsen was asked what it felt like to slip on a Laker jersey,
even if it was just a summer league version. Madsen's face broke
into a smile, thinking about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh it felt unbelievable,'' Madsen said. ``In fact, they gave
me my old No. 35 (to wear next season) and I was wearing it last
night in the hotel room.'' Porter trying to rise again
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the 1999-2000 college basketball season,
Chris Porter was on top of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Porter was on the cover of Sports Illustrated and expected to
lead Auburn to a final four appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Less than one year later, Porter is trying to show the Golden
State Warriors that he deserves to play this season, despite being
a second round draft pick this past June.
</P>
<P>
   But Porter, who was talked about as being a potential lottery
pick for the 1999 NBA Draft, is not letting his situation get him
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am just trying to go out, have fun and prove myself out
here,'' Porter said after helping lead Golden State to a win over
the Lakers. ``That's what this league is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Porter, a 6-7 forward, was impressive for the Warriors, scoring
14 points and giving the crowd a chance to see his high-flying
abilities.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Porter made what seemed to be an impossible layup with
just over one minute left in regulation during a tie game, falling
out of bounds while drawing a flagrant foul from Lakers' guard John
Celestand.
</P>
<P>
   Porter made the free throw, but was unable to stay in the game,
suffering a thigh injury on the play.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the injury though, Porter remained positive on his
future in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``People know what I can do,'' Porter said. ``I just need to get
the ball and do my thing, then everything will take care of itself.
I am just going to work out and work on the things I need to do to
improve my game.'' Kobe vs. Magic?
</P>
<P>
   As the days' games neared end, there was still no confirmation
as to whether a much-anticipated match up would occur tonight at
7:30 when the Magic Johnson All-Stars take on Olimpia Milano of
Italy.
</P>
<P>
   No, the match-up of the teams is somewhat inconsequential in
comparison to the rumor that Magic Johnson may suit up to play with
his team, while Olimpia Milano may have the services of Kobe
Bryant, the team's owner.
</P>
<P>
   Though there was no confirmation that the two will take the
court tonight, Marni Colbert, the Director of Operations for the
Pro Summer League, did say that the summer league has ``extended an
invitation to both players.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
