<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY WASTES BIG CHANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA - With a chance to claim the Western Division lead and
Major League Soccer's best record, what was left of the Galaxy
finally surrendered to what was left of D.C. United, 2-1, Saturday
in front of 15,714 at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   World Cup qualifying hit both teams hard. The Galaxy missed six
starters - Cobi Jones, Robin Fraser, Greg Vanney, Mauricio
Cienfuegos, Luis Hernandez and Ezra Hendrickson - to their national
teams.
</P>
<P>
   United, fighting for its playoff lives after winning three of
the first four MLS championships, benefited from having Bolivian
playmakers Marco Etcheverry and Jaime Moreno, who were both sent
back after reporting late to Bolivia's World Cup qualifying
training site.
</P>
<P>
   United was without Eddie Pope, Raul Diaz Arce, Ben Olsen and
Jeff Agoos because of injuries and national team commitments, but
the services of Etcheverry and particularly Moreno made the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   Moreno assisted on both of United's goals by Pete Marino and
A.J. Wood to keep United's (5-13-6, 21 points) playoff heart
beating while the Galaxy (10-6-7, 37 points) failed to pass
West-leading Kansas City (11-4-5, 38 points), which dropped a 2-0
decision to Columbus earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a frustrating loss because D.C. was there to be beaten,''
said Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid. ``I've always said that they're much
better than their record indicates, but tonight I didn't think they
were as good as D.C. has been in the past, so we let them off the
hook.''
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy goalkeeper Kevin Hartman made a bad decision that led to
United's first goal in the seventh minute.
</P>
<P>
   Moreno chipped a pass over Paul Caligiuri for Marino, who barely
beat the Galaxy's offside trap. Instead of holding his position
while Caligiuri recovered to chase Marino down, Hartman started to
charge out of his area, then stopped when he realized he couldn't
get to the ball before Marino.
</P>
<P>
   It left the D.C. striker with an empty net. All he had left was
a simple chip over Hartman's head for his ninth goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy answered quickly thanks to a United mistake. With
Galaxy midfielder Pete Vagenas nearby, D.C. defender Geoff Aunger
tried to drop a pass back for Carey Talley, but the ball slipped
off his foot. Talley and Aunger looked at each other instead of
chasing the ball, leaving Vagenas alone to run on and pick it up.
</P>
<P>
   Vagenas hurried in to challenge Talley, cutting outside to his
right, then finishing with a hard strike to the left corner to even
the match at 1-1 in the 17th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Vagenas had a chance to put the Galaxy in front early in the
second half, but a bad first touch following a perfectly placed
pass from Simon Elliott prevented him from beating United
goalkeeper Mark Simpson in the 51st minute.
</P>
<P>
   Moreno made the Galaxy pay again. The crafty striker beat Zak
Ibsen to the left endline, then slipped a pass in front for A.J.
Wood, who finished from 5 yards straightaway past Hartman to give
D.C. the game-winner in the 53rd minute.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy defender Danny Califf, sporting a new blond hairdo, said
the Galaxy spoiled a golden opportunity with a road game at Tampa
Bay next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This win would have buried D.C. and put us in a great spot,''
said Califf. ``It's hard to accept because we really feel like we
outplayed them but let it get away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
