<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARKS SAVED AT THE STRIPE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Sparks guard Tamecka Dixon scored two
crucial free throws with 1.3 seconds to play to give the Minnesota
Lynx their sixth consecutive loss in a 58-57 decision in front of
6,071 at the Forum Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   It was a physical game from start to finish. The foul-plagued
Sparks got the victory without forward DeLisha Milton, who was
ejected after picking up her second technical early in the second
half. Overall, there were five technical fouls called, four on the
Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   It looked as if the Lynx would spoil the Sparks night when Betty
Lennox scored an 18-footer from the right baseline to give
Minnesota a 57-56 advantage with 6.8 seconds to play. But Dixon got
the inbound pass from Mwadi Mabika, drove around to the right
baseline and drew a foul from former UCLA standout Maylana Martin,
who fouled out with her sixth.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks had the lead much of the second half until the rookie
Lennox hit a 3-pointer from the top of the key to make it 55-54
Minnesota. But Lisa Leslie, who redeemed herself with 24 points, 13
rebounds and five blocked shots after a poor showing against the
Houston Comets Friday, scored two free throws with 12.8 seconds to
play to put the Sparks back up 56-55.
</P>
<P>
   It was a hard-fought win for the Sparks, who pulled within a
game of WNBA leader Houston in the Western Conference leader
Houston, to improve to 18-3.
</P>
<P>
   They had to find a way to get it done without Milton, who was
ejected after picking up her second technical foul with 18:25 to
play. Milton, who got into a little talking duel with the Lynx'
Keitha Dickerson, had just been called for an offensive foul on
Dickerson. Milton came down the court and was clapping her hands
when the official hit her with the technical. She said she was only
applauding the call, but the official obviously didn't see it that
way and ejected her. She left with two points and three rebounds in
16 minutes of play.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks squandered a 10-point lead in the physical first half
when technicals were called on Sparks coach Michael Cooper, Leslie
and Milton and the Lynx' Keitha Dickerson. Things got heated
between Milton and Dickerson, but the confrontation was quickly
diffused after an exchange of words.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie, Milton and Mwadi Mabika each picked up three fouls in
the half, which closed with a 26-25 Sparks advantage. Tamecka Dixon
sparked a 10-0 run with an 18-footer, but the Sparks weren't able
to maintain the momentum. Katie Smith scored 10 of her team's next
14 points to pull the Lynx within one point at the break.
</P>
<P>
   Katie Smith had 20 points and Martin finished with 11 points and
six rebounds for Minnesota (10-11).
</P>
<P>
   SPARKS NOTES: Allison Feaster suffered a bruised right knee with
three minutes to play in the game. ... Leslie, Milton and Mabika
are off to the WNBA All-Star Game in Phoenix Monday, while the rest
of the Sparks enjoy a two-day rest. ... Lennox and Smith are
All-Stars for the Lynx. ... The Sparks return to play Thursday with
a home game against New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
