<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BURRELL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURRELL MAKES TEAM BUT FALLS SHORT OF VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO - Heaven help the competition if Shelia Burrell ever
masters the high jump. She came within four points of winning the
heptathlon at the U.S. Olympic Track and Field Trials on Saturday
despite finishing 15th out of 17 competitors in the event on the
first day of the two-day competition.
</P>
<P>
   Burrell, 28, beat DeDee Nathan by nearly five seconds in the
competition-concluding 800 meters but couldn't overtake Nathan in
the standings. Nathan finished with 6,343 points to Burrell's
6,339.
</P>
<P>
   Nathan, 32, twice had missed the Olympic team by one spot,
finishing fourth at the 1992 and 1996 Trials. If there's anything
worse than coming close to making the Olympic team, it's not coming
close at all.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Burrell, who was 14th at the Trials in 1996. She was so
crushed by the result, she turned her back on track. ``I stopped
running track in '97 because I was so frustrated,'' Burrell said.
``So making the Olympic team is a huge deal for me. I've been
through so much to get to this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Burrell was working as a personal trainer in 1998 when she
decided to take on a very high-strung client: herself. She chose to
resume her relationship with the heptathlon, with Cal State
Northridge coach Jeff McAuley acting as a mediator.
</P>
<P>
   Burrell lived in Reseda until last fall, at which time she moved
to Manhattan, Kan., to get intensive coaching in the high jump.
``As you can see, I need help,'' she said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   She continues to seek out McAuley for coaching, sharing ideas
with him the way she does a water bottle with Nathan when they're
both competing. Marion Jones and Inger Miller, the two heptathletes
decidedly are not.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are they Jackie Joyner-Kersee, the American who put her
stamp all over the heptathlon before retiring in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be considered a great athlete like Jackie,'' Burrell
said. ``I aspire to be like her both on the field and off the
field. But nobody's going to break her (American) record (7,291
points).''
</P>
<P>
   Burrell's own career is proof you should never say never.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you what,'' she said, her eyes sparkling, ``If I figure
out the high jump, it's over. Look out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-00 0203EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
