<HEADER>
A3515 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-OLY-TRIALS-SIDE-LADN     07-16 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TRIALS-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEFLEZIGHI SEES VISION COME TRUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO - This is why Mebrahtom Keflezighi turned down the
chance three years ago to make history; this is why he passed on
becoming the first track athlete to represent his native Eritrea at
the World Championships:
</P>
<P>
   So that on a warm and windless July night in the capital of his
adopted state he could take a victory lap while clutching the
national flags of Eritrea and the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   ``Months before the Olympics I was visualizing this. I'd be
visualizing it, visualizing it and visualizing it and then I'd tell
myself snap out of it because I had to stay focused,'' Keflezighi
said late Friday night upon becoming the first athlete at the U.S.
Olympic Track and Field Trials to earn a berth to Sydney with a
victory in the 10,000 meters.
</P>
<P>
   Keflezighi, 25, was timed in 28:03.32, his personal best by 26
seconds and .03 better than runner-up Alan Culpepper, who sneaked
up on Keflezighi in the final meters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have been happy making the team, but I would have been
mad if he had passed me,'' said Keflezighi, who has been slowed
recently by tendinitis in his knees.
</P>
<P>
   The knees held up just fine Friday. The prohibitive prerace
favorite, Bob Kennedy, didn't compete because of injuries he
suffered in a car accident in May. Kennedy's absence created a
window of opportunity that the 5-foot-7 Keflezighi was able to slip
through. He took the lead on the 17th lap around the Hornet Stadium
track and, in his words, ``hung on'' the final two laps.
</P>
<P>
   Keflezighi, a former NCAA champion in the 5,000 and 10,000, fled
Eritrea with his family in 1985. He became a U.S. citizen in 1998.
Last year he finished fourth at the U.S. Championships and fifth at
the Pan American Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four years ago when I graduated from UCLA, I talked with Coach
(Bob) Larsen and we set our goal for Sydney then,'' said
Keflezighi, the third of 10 children born to Russom, a taxi driver,
and his wife Awetash. ``The talent was there. I just needed the
chance to work hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Larsen, who knows better than most the price Keflezighi paid in
beads of sweat for his berth to Sydney, was uncharacteristically
emotional after the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish you had film of me in the stands after he won,'' Larsen
said. ``People who know me know I'm low-key, but I was jumping up
and down.''
</P>
<P>
   Local update: USC junior Angela Williams, running in the same
100-meters semifinal heat as Marion Jones, finished sixth and
failed to advance to the finals. The 20-year-old was timed in
11.33, off her 1999 best of 11.04. ... Another casualty was John
Godina, the 1996 Olympic silver medalist in the shot put. Adam
Nelson put the shot 72 feet, 7 inches
</P>
<P>
   the best mark in the world in three years - and C.J. Hunter and
Andy Bloom posted career bests to surpass Godina, who fouled on his
final attempt. ``I just didn't have a big throw in me,'' a glum
Godina said. ... Frances Santin, a sophomore at Cal State
Northridge, advanced to the semifinals of the 400-meter hurdles
with a personal best qualifying time of 56.67. ... One of the
attending physicians at the meet is Dr. Eric Heiden, who won five
gold medals in speed skating at the 1980 Winter Olympics. Heiden is
an orthopedic surgeon at the UC Davis Medical Center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-00 0205EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
