A3518 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKL-SPARKS-WRITETHRU-     07-16 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-WRITETHRU-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARKS SAVED AT THE STRIPE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Sparks guard Tamecka Dixon scored two
crucial free throws with 1.3 seconds to play to give the Minnesota
Lynx their sixth consecutive loss in a 58-57 decision in front of
6,071 at the Forum Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   It was a physical game from start to finish. The foul-plagued
Sparks got the victory without forward DeLisha Milton, who was
ejected after picking up her second technical early in the second
half. Overall, there were five technical fouls called, four on the
Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very gritty, defensively,'' Sparks coach Michael
Cooper said about the Lynx. ``In some games you have roll up your
sleeves and get down and dirty.''
</P>
<P>
   This was definitely one of those games with all the pushing and
showing going on.
</P>
<P>
   It looked as if the Lynx would spoil the Sparks night when Betty
Lennox made an 18-footer from the right baseline to give Minnesota
a 57-56 advantage with 6.8 seconds to play. But Dixon got the
inbound pass from Mwadi Mabika, drove around to the right baseline
and drew a foul from former UCLA standout Maylana Martin, who
fouled out with her sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We diagrammed that play perfectly,'' Cooper said. ``She was
aggressive and able to get the call from the official.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks led much of the second half until the rookie Lennox
hit a 3-pointer from the top of the key to make it 55-54 Minnesota.
But Lisa Leslie, who redeemed herself with 24 points, 13 rebounds
and five blocked shots after a poor showing against the Houston
Comets Friday, scored two free throws with 12.8 seconds to play to
put the Sparks back up 56-55.
</P>
<P>
   It was a hard-fought win for the Sparks, who pulled within a
game of WNBA leader Houston in the Western Conference leader
Houston, to improve to 18-3.
</P>
<P>
   They had to find a way to get it done without Milton, who was
ejected after picking up her second technical foul with 18:25 to
play. Milton, who got into a little talking duel with the Lynx'
Keitha Dickerson in the first half when double technicals were
called, had just been called for an offensive foul on Dickerson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He called a charge and I knew that I charged,'' said Milton,
left with two points and three rebounds in 16 minutes of play. ``I
came back down the court and clapped my hands, good call, good
call' ... and he threw me out. What can I do about it. They (the
officials) were sensitive tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper said the official most likely took the gesture as a bit
of sarcasm. After the game he told Milton she had to be smarter in
situations like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't costs us a loss, but it did costs us D,'' Cooper
said. ``She apologized for it. ... These are the learning processes
for a championship team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks squandered a 10-point lead in the first half when
technicals were called on Cooper, Leslie and Milton and Dickerson.
</P>
<P>
   Katie Smith had 20 points and Martin finished with 11 points and
six rebounds for Minnesota (10-11).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-00 0228EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
