<DOCNO> NYT20000716.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 08:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3524 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      07-16 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    FAIRNESS AS A FOREIGN LANGUAGE(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By E.J. MONTINI(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The people trying to brand Dave Richert a racist didn't bother
asking Diane Garner about the time Dave stopped by her house
demanding clothes and furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Dave's wife had told him about a Hispanic family who'd lost
everything. Richert rented a U-Haul truck and drove from friend to
friend, collecting whatever each could spare. He then delivered
everything to the grateful family.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw Dave labeled a racist in the paper, it just made me
sick,'' Garner says. ``Doesn't a person's life count for anything
anymore?''
</P>
<P>
   No. Not in politics
</P>
<P>
   Richert is the director of the Phoenix Planning Department. Last
April, he was at a meeting with a group of mostly Latino mobile
food vendors. One of the men at the meeting was translating for
another. Richert, who thought everyone in the room understood
English, interrupted the men and said, ``Speak English, I need to
understand you.''
</P>
<P>
   For this, local attorney Stephen Montoya filed a formal
complaint against Richert. An investigation of the director and his
department was ordered by City Manager Frank Fairbanks, who hired
an outside law firm.
</P>
<P>
   From what I read, the law firm's report condemns Richert for the
gruff comment, declares his department ``very White'' and lists the
complaints of a number of minority employees who no longer work
there.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, investigators didn't note the time Richert
contributed $400 toward the funeral of a young Hispanic boy who had
died of cancer. Richert's wife, Diane, a long-time school nurse,
was acquainted with the child.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how much time and money Dave has poured into
our school,'' Diane says. ``We have about a 66 percent minority
population. You could say a lot of things about Dave. For one
thing, he's not a Cubs fan, which I hold against him. But he is
absolutely not a racist.''
</P>
<P>
   Richert has worked for the city for 28 years. He's taught Sunday
school, coached youth sports. Each year, he works at a
back-to-school clothing drive for kids.
</P>
<P>
   He has apologized directly to one of the men at the meeting and
apologized through the media to any Latino who may have been
offended. Still, the lawyer Montoya tells me it's not enough. He's
``disturbed'' Richert hasn't apologized in person to the other man
at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Richert did not curse at anyone. He didn't use an ethnic slur.
He didn't threaten.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter. These days, being called a racist is as bad
as being one. Worse, if the accusation somehow makes the papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think his career should be derailed,'' Montoya said of
Richert. ``Why? Because I think it was a mistake and I think people
need to forgive others as long as they acknowledge they made a
mistake and don't do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not about forgiveness, though. It's about appearances. It's
about politicians and bureaucrats who can't bear the weight of
controversy because they have no spines.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it would have been nice if the people calling Richert a
racist had first spoken to his daughter, Jenny. She would have told
them her dad paid for an extra year of college so she could learn
Spanish. And how she uses it, now, as a teacher in a bilingual
education program.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Montini at Ed.Montini(a)ArizonaRepublic.com or (602)
444-8978.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
