<DOCNO> NYT20000716.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 08:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3528 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-WNBA-AZR &LR;      07-16 2018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WNBA-AZR </SLUG>
  
I like how she plays. She plays hard and to have fun.
<TEXT>
<P>
   WNBALeague trails NBA,
</P>
<P>
   but is still No. 1 with fans
</P>
<P>
   WNBAWNBA is No. 1 &QC;
</P>
<P>
   - with its fans &QC;
</P>
<P>
   League trails &QL;
</P>
<P>
   men's sports, &QL;
</P>
<P>
   but blazes as &QL;
</P>
<P>
   cultural force &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Someday, WNBA President Val Ackerman wants her women's summer
basketball league to be uttered in the same breath with the ``four
majors'' - men's professional football, hockey, baseball and
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   By the measures of TV deals and sponsorship packages, as well as
player salaries and fan support, the 4-year-old summer league
doesn't come close to the elite ranks of men's professional sports.
</P>
<P>
   But Ackerman insists nobody expected it to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our growth will be incremental,'' she said. ``It's
step-by-step, fan-by-fan, ratings point-by-ratings point, and it
will take a period of years to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Even still, as the league readies for its biggest event of the
year, the 2000 WNBA All-Star Game, to be played at America West
Arena on Monday night, there are subtle signs the WNBA is making
its mark in the cluttered iconography of American sports.
</P>
<P>
   Consider, for a moment, a 13-year-old boy named Daniel Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   He shows up at Mercury home games wearing a red T-shirt bearing
center Maria Stepanova's name and number.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Thompson why he admires Stepanova, who looks like the WNBA's
answer to tennis cover girl Anna Kournakova, and his politically
correct answer could not have been scripted better by the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like how she plays,'' said the teenager from Amarillo,
Texas, who spends summers in the Valley with relatives. ``She plays
hard and to have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   NBA backing a big help
</P>
<P>
   Bankrolled by the NBA, the WNBA was created in 1997 to change
how basketball is experienced - and by whom. In effect, it gave the
NBA a chance to expand its already formidable brand franchise to
millions more T-shirt-buying, TV-viewing, ticket-buying fans who
just happen to be women and children.
</P>
<P>
   But a funny thing happened along the way.
</P>
<P>
   The WNBA evolved into a cultural phenomenon that's loved by
devotees, who appreciate how hard the women play, and loathed by
critics, mostly men, who call anything less than above-the-rim, Top
Gun-style basketball a big, fat joke.
</P>
<P>
   In the WNBA, the emphasis is on basketball fundamentals -
shooting, passing and ball handling. So far, no player has ever
dunked in a WNBA game, which gives women, especially, a style of
play they can relate to.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can look at our games and see it's a predominantly female
audience, which is very different from traditional sports,'' said
Seth Sulka, the Mercury's vice president of operations.
</P>
<P>
   Likely here to stay
</P>
<P>
   And so, unintentionally it seems, the WNBA represents a new
skirmish on the gender-equity battlefront.
</P>
<P>
   As such, if the NBA ever decided to kill its women's league,
regardless of how much scratch it lost, it would be, as one sports
industry consultant put it, ``political suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, NBA Commissioner David Stern describes the NBA's
support for its money-losing women's league in gentler terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The WNBA helps keep organized professional basketball in the
minds of fans and would-be fans and new fans 12 months a year,'' he
said. ``That's an extraordinary opportunity for us.''
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, Stern is right.
</P>
<P>
   Look around the stands at a Mercury game, or in any venue where
the league's 15 other teams play, and you see how the WNBA has made
its mark with its target audiences.
</P>
<P>
   There's the family-filled conga line snaking across the
hardwoods during fourth quarters.
</P>
<P>
   There's a dad and two daughters, the girls decked out in
mini-Mercury uniforms, cozy in their season-ticket seats behind the
basket.
</P>
<P>
   There's the women, everywhere, in pairs, in groups - even garbed
in nun drag, ala the habit-wearing Mercury fans known as the
Sisters of No Mercy.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball purists gripe that the atmosphere at WNBA games is
more like a carnival than a serious athletic competition. And it's
true the NBA does not embrace such WNBA antics as hip-hop dances
and free-throw contests during critical time-outs.
</P>
<P>
   Not the same game
</P>
<P>
   But then again, the NBA doesn't attract many young families, who
are lured to WNBA games by ticket prices that start in the same
range as movie tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Niche-wise, the WNBA positions itself as a ``family-friendly''
experience, which, in the case of the Seattle Storm, one of four
expansion teams this year, meant acknowledging the team's large
lesbian following with a gay pride night two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the notion of gender equality in sports appeals to
women, straight and gay, who are starved for women's professional
athletics.
</P>
<P>
   But lesbian fans have long complained the league downplays their
strong support of the WNBA product, while the league says it leaves
it up to each team to figure out their own promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of who loves the WNBA, the emotional connection that
fans have with teams and players is unique in professional sports,
Mercury center Jennifer Gillom said.
</P>
<P>
   Players, fans are closer
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different than in the NBA,'' she said. ``Fans get
attached to the players because we're out in the community so much.
We have to be in order to get ourselves promoted.''
</P>
<P>
   Witness, for example, the outpouring for Mercury forward Brandy
Reed.
</P>
<P>
   The slight she received from Western Conference coaches, who
overlooked her stellar performance this season when selecting the
reserves for Monday's All Star game, sent fans into a rage that
prompted the league to add Reed to the roster at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   It's this kind of visceral connection that gives the NBA an
opportunity to extend its brand name, even in the face of a
16percent drop in average WNBA game attendance, to 8,545 a game,
compared with last season.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, the WNBA brings long-term value to the NBA, which is
why NBA owners are willing to subsidize it, Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   The WNBA, which has placed a moratorium on expansion, claims
empty pockets, and Ackerman said she can't project when the league
will begin to show a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Teams keep the gate receipts, meaning the league must generate
revenues in other ways.
</P>
<P>
   Despite league TV deals with three networks (NBC, ESPN and
Lifetime) and sponsorship support by 14 blue-chip brands, the WNBA
says operating expenses exceed marketing revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: Unlike established sports leagues, the networks
don't pay the WNBA a broadcast rights fee. On the contrary, the
WNBA shells out a portion of its overall sponsorship revenues to
the networks and, in addition, reimburses them for production
costs.
</P>
<P>
   As for sponsors, the league pays the costs of courtside signage,
player appearances and scorecard ads that come as part of marketing
agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in the regular costs of league events (such as the
All-Star Game), referee fees, and domestic and global trademark
registrations, and the well goes dry, Ackerman said.
</P>
<P>
   Players tired of excuses
</P>
<P>
   So far, WNBA players have accepted this explanation as the price
of building a viable women's league. They settled for a collective
bargaining agreement that this year pays rookies $26,500 and top
players $80,000 for a 32-game season. In total, the WNBA says
player salaries will cost the league $11million this season, more
than triple what it spent the first year.
</P>
<P>
   But there are signs that the players feel the league is building
itself up at their expense. And they are growing impatient for
better deals.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Jennifer Azzi, a former Olympian and one of
the WNBA's marquee players, announced she would leave the league
rather than play for $44,000. Azzi was lured back only after the
league agreed to pay her $62,500.
</P>
<P>
   Two other veterans, Andrea Congreaves and Cindy Brown, walked
away, citing low pay as one consideration. At the same time, a
handful of European players opted to stay home and prepare for the
Olympics because the WNBA didn't make it worth their while to cross
the pond and play.
</P>
<P>
   Agents predict it could become an exodus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next year, the league will see that players have had it,''
said Bruce Levy, who represents 26 WNBA players, including the
Mercury's Bridget Pettis and Amanda Wilson. ``They'll see they
won't be content to be forced to go overseas, or take coaching jobs
or work at McDonald's just to make a living wage.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts say labor issues could be the stumbling block
for the WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``As leagues emerge, you see players become emboldened,'' said
David M. Carter, a Los Angeles sports business consultant. ``They
get their bearings and become much more formidable. All of a
sudden, it gets adversarial.''
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Wheeler, operations director for the Women's National
Basketball Players Association, said the union, which is not privy
to league financial information, has reason to believe the WNBA is
an ``excellent position'' based on the number of its national
sponsors and TV partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   ``It opens the landscape for sharing that success with the
players,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Success still awaited
</P>
<P>
   But proclamations of success are premature, according to
Ackerman, who is bullish about the league's prospects but careful
not to claim the WNBA is a sure bet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NBA has been very patient with us because the sense going
in was the league would be an investment to create something out of
nothing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   National TV broadcasts and intensive marketing are expensive,
but necessary, drains, she added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women's basketball has never had that strategic emphasis
before, but the sense is there is a business (in) women's ball and,
long term, our revenue streams will develop.''
</P>
<P>
   If it happens, it will be the first time in 15 attempts. Since
1972, at least that many women's professional sports leagues have
tried and failed to carve a niche for themselves. Meanwhile, the
WNBA's perceived staying power helped set the stage for the Women's
United Soccer Association, which is scheduled to launch next spring
with teams in eight cities.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Cavalli, a co-founder of the ABL, a women's professional
basketball league that lasted 21/2 seasons before filing for
bankruptcy in late 1998, believes that if any women's league can
make it, it's the WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a better product and concept,'' said Cavalli, a public
relations consultant in Portolo Valley, Calif., who saw many of the
ABL stars take significant pay cuts when they were absorbed by the
WNBA. ``But we didn't have a big brother with the leverage of the
NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   But even the NBA's muscle can't do much about the WNBA's
ultimate challenge: overcoming a strong cultural bias against
women's athletics so that finally, women's professional sports
become a fact of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have girls that (have come to games) for 30 years and
supported it and now they're passing it on to their daughters or
granddaughters or little boys,'' said Nancy Lieberman-Cline, coach
and general manager of the Detroit Shock ``Time is our greatest
ally here.''
</P>
<P>
   And for now, it seems, time is on the WNBA's side.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at Nena.Baker(a)ArizonaRepublic.com or (602)
444-8256.
</P>
<P>
