   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-SUMMIT _ THURMONT, Md. _ Spot coverage of the final
status peace talks between Israel and the Palestinians, as they
kick back into high gear following a day off for the Sabbath. The
talks still focus on three issues: the future of Jerusalem; borders
of a Palestinian state; and fate of millions of Palestinian
refugees around the world. Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Expected to move on the NYT Wire in both International and
Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-IVILLAGE _ SANGPO VILLAGE _ In the words of a local
official, Sangpo Village was once a ``poor, backwards, uneducated''
speck in central China. Now, thanks to a thriving business in
sheepskin processing, it boasts private cars, cell phones and yes,
Web surfers. A look at how this village of 5,000 people got so
rich, and so wired. (Chao, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH PHOTO. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CONVENTION _ LOS ANGELES _ When 4,300 party delegates begin
arriving here in about two weeks for the Democratic National
Convention, they'll book their meetings with each other online with
an Internet scheduling program. From the floor of the Democratic
National Convention, they'll be able to talk the their colleagues
on the other side of the massive Staples Center with Internet
phones or by email at kiosks throughout the building. Back home,
folks can submit party platform ideas by email, and watch every
second of the convention with Web cameras connected to the party's
extensive Internet site. Democrats are touting their Aug. 14-17
convention as the most technologically advanced ever, and _ like
the Republicans _ are relying on the Internet like never before to
get their message out. ``It's really all about providing better
access for the American people,'' said convention CEO Lydia
Camarillo. But it's also about reaching out to a new breed of
potential voters that parties can't reach through CSPAN or CNN -
and closely controlling the message they get. (Keefe, Cox News
Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   With box listing some bells and whistles and photo of workers at
Staples.
</P>
<P>
   INFECTION _ Live coverage of the the International Conference on
Emerging Infectious Diseases, including speeches from major CDC and
WHO disease experts and the former editor of JAMA, on Sunday.
(Toner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
