<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Comedy camp leaves 'em rolling in the aisles
 &HT;    By Keith Still
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Who says camp can't be a hoot? For 20 metro kids,
summer camp turned out to be a laugh riot as they honed their
comedic skills at Kennesaw State University's Comedy Camp.
</P>
<P>
   The two-week camp, which ended Friday, was a joint effort
between the school's continuing education program and the Alliance
Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   The third- through eighth-graders split their time between two
teachers from the Alliance Theatre: artists Josh Ruben and Koko
Chalfant.
</P>
<P>
   Ruben focused on comedy acting. He used scripts from sitcoms,
commercials and even Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   Chalfant taught the kids to perform improvisational comedy
similar to that in the TV program ``Whose Line Is It Anyway?''
</P>
<P>
   Improv is when actors don't have a script. Instead, they make up
a scene as they go along.
</P>
<P>
   Besides teaching kids how and why comedy works, Ruben and
Chalfant introduced them to the basics of acting.
</P>
<P>
   They also taught them to combine humor with slapstick, physical
comedy, stage fighting and improv to be funny in ``an appropriate
way,'' Ruben said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People may laugh at bathroom humor,'' he said. ``But you want
to make everybody laugh in an entertaining way without getting into
trouble _ things where Mom and Dad would not be embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   On the final day, the campers had a chance to shine for their
folks by performing several short comic scenes and a mini version
of ``Whose Line Is It Anyway?''
</P>
<P>
   Think you're funny? Here are some hints from Ruben to help pep
up your stage-fighting performance.
</P>
<P>
   (Remember this is fake fighting. Do not hurt your friends while
practicing. This stuff is meant to be funny!)
</P>
<P>
   1. Choose a fighting technique for your act, then learn to
perform it safely. The photo at left shows the classic hair-pulling
technique.
</P>
<P>
   2. Practice the move until you're comfortable with it.
</P>
<P>
   3. Act out your fight in a heightened way, adding funny facial
expressions or exaggerated movements. These help make the routine
funny instead of violent. Check out instructor Ruben's facial
expression in the photo. He exaggerates his reaction to Nick
Revard's pulling his hair _ and it makes you laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
