<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3577 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BRAIN-RESEARCH0717-CO     07-16 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAIN-RESEARCH0717-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Study gives picture of brain's inner life
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Researchers at the University of Texas and
Stanford University have taken a first step toward unraveling one
of great mysteries of the universe: how the human brain works.
</P>
<P>
   The team is studying how the brain responds to what the eyes see
and has discovered a relationship that has confounded
neuroscientists. The team, studying monkeys and humans, found that
the amount of blood oxygen in brain cells, or neurons, corresponds
exactly with how active the brain is. As visual images register in
the brain, the blood-oxygen level rises, just as the neural
activity increases.
</P>
<P>
   Making that connection is significant, said UT psychology
professors Wilson Geisler and Duane Albrecht, because it sheds
light on the inner workings of the brain. Understanding how the
brain functions, ultimately, will help doctors diagnose and treat
disorders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the neural activity in the brain that does all the
seeing, hearing, thinking and remembering that humans can do,''
said Geisler, director of UT's Center for Vision &AMP; Image Sciences.
``So, if we want to understand disorders that affect our ability to
see, hear, think and remember, we need to be able to measure the
neural activity that underlies these abilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Such measurements also could show whether a particular drug
therapy is effective.
</P>
<P>
   The work of Geisler, Albrecht and Stanford researchers David
Heeger and Alex Huk appears in this month's issue of the British
journal Nature Neuroscience. The four present their own findings
and comment on similar work being done at the California Institute
of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gregg Bennett Wells, a physician and neuropathologist at the
Texas A&AMP;M University System Hea ``It gives us a window on diseases
that are uniquely human,'' Wells said, citing learning disorders,
addictions and Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   Brain research is exploding as the tools for studying it grow
more sophisticated.
</P>
<P>
   With imaging equipment that has been developed in the last 10
years, researchers can measure oxygen levels in the blood that
nourishes the human brain. The measurements are done with a special
kind of magnetic resonance imaging, or MRI, machine called a
functional MRI. While a regular MRI scans a part of the body, such
as the brain, and presents a cross-section of the body part, a
functional MRI shows the oxygen concentration in groups of body
cells.
</P>
<P>
   It cannot, however, measure nerve impulses in human brains.
That's why monkeys are used, Albrecht and Geisler said.
</P>
<P>
   The UT/Stanford team thinks the monkeys they are using _
macaques, or rhesus monkeys commonly found in Asia and Africa _ are
visually wired almost identically to humans.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers make an incision and insert an electrode into
the back of the monkey's head so that neuron measurements can be
taken. The monkey does not feel pain and generally is euthanized
within a few days, said Albrecht, director of the Visual
Neuroscience Lab at UT.
</P>
<P>
   The macaques and humans are shown televised images of patterns
that vary in contrast from very low, or faint, to very high, or
bold. The bolder the pattern, the more neurons that fire in the
brain. Geisler and Albrecht said they were astounded to learn that
the neural responses in monkeys and the functional MRI results were
identical. That was the discovery that made them say, ``Wow.''
</P>
<P>
   But such research is not without controversy. Neuroscientists
don't always agree on how their peers interpret functional MRIs.
Some groups object to using animals, and there is no agreement on
comparing humans and animals.
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy to misinterpret functional MRI results, Geisler
and Albrecht acknowledged. But the comparison is powerful, they
said, because the macaque is more than 99 percent similar to a
human.
</P>
<P>
   ``This validates a lot of the work that's been going on for the
last 10 years,'' Geisler said.
</P>
<P>
   Wells said he expects the work to encourage more research using
functional MRIs.
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect all of the mysteries of the human brain to be
uncovered anytime soon, Geisler and Albrecht said.
</P>
<P>
   The brain is so complicated that what is known is dwarfed by
what remains to be discovered, they said. ``Astronomy is better
understood than the brain,'' Geisler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been studying this for three decades,'' Albrecht added,
``and it's very humbling. . . . I'll be doing this all my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
