A3584 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-LIFESTAGES0717-COX     07-16 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIFESTAGES0717-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lifestages Boutique specializes in women's well-being
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ At first glance it looks like a lovely women's
boutique. And it is.
</P>
<P>
   But take a closer look at the items on display and you realize
there's more to each one than meets the eye. All the products are
designed to help women as they move through the stages of their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   The Lifestages Boutique for Women at Samaritan North Health
Center represents a partnership between Good Samaritan Hospital and
Davue Ob-Gyn. According to Chris Hurak, chief operating officer for
Lifestages, the shop represents a trend _ similar facilities are
cropping up all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a natural offshoot of our medical and nursing care
education-awareness focus,'' she explains.
</P>
<P>
   Retail manager Kay Earnhart says the inventory must make clients
``feel good and look good and help them with medical health-care
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   That inventory includes everything from nursing pillows and
support hose to beaded bags and jewelry. There are glass flowers
and music boxes, magnifying mirrors and wigs for chemotherapy or
alopecia patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of a professional woman who doesn't feel very good and
maybe she's had radiation or chemo,'' says Earnhart. ``She's still
going to work and wants to look the best she can.''
</P>
<P>
   Dressing rooms are designed for complete privacy for women being
fitted for a prosthesis, postmastectomy bra, nursing bra or a wig.
</P>
<P>
   Other products:
</P>
<P>
   _ Nursing tops from Prego allow moms to nurse without being
exposed. The baby can be tucked inside a flap that reaches from the
shoulder to below the breast and eliminates the need for a diaper
or blanket ($44).
</P>
<P>
   _ The Pregnancy Survival Kit includes a basic black stretch knit
wardrobe for moms-to-be: a dress, skirt, long-sleeved top and
slacks, all for $177. The shop also stocks maternity dresses,
jumpers and casual wear from Prego, Olian and Rebel ($20-$150).
</P>
<P>
   _ Former cancer patient Maureen Langeman makes sparkly hats and
donates a portion of her earnings to the American Cancer Society
($45). The shop also stocks turbans, and there's a nonmetallic
deodorant for chemotherapy patients.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reading glasses range from rhinestone-studded to hand-painted
(from $8-$22).
</P>
<P>
   _ You can express on the expressway with the shop's breast pump.
It plugs into a cigarette lighter in your car but we're not
advising you to do two things at once!
</P>
<P>
   _ What the display of pretty purses have in common is that they
are all easy-care and lightweight.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``This is the big thing right now!'' says Earnhart, showing
off the Prenatal Cradle, a device that supports the baby and takes
pressure off the mother's back ($49.95).
</P>
<P>
   _ The shop also stocks rubber gloves that make it much easier to
put on compression hose ($5.75).
</P>
<P>
   Earnhart says she and her staff are eager to please and will be
happy to gift wrap or mail packages. Gift baskets from $25 also can
be put together.
</P>
<P>
   Scented candles, small fountains, relaxation tapes and pretty
journals are also on display, and the shop stocks the Camille
Beckman line of bath products.
</P>
<P>
   Says Earnhart: ``We want to encourage women to take time for
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO GO
</P>
<P>
   _ What: Lifestages Boutique for Women.
</P>
<P>
   _ When: 9 a.m. to 6 p.m. Monday through Friday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Where: Samaritan North Health Care Center, Dayton, Ohio
</P>
<P>
   _ Telephone: 937-832-7852.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
