<P>
   CALIF-VIOLENCE (Los Angeles) _ In more than two dozen interviews
with teenagers, middle-aged ex-gang members, mothers of murdered
children, social workers, elected officials, neighborhood
advocates, police officers and a woman whose disabled brother was
shot to death the day before, people here said they were afraid and
baffled by the rise in violence and just as determined to stop it.
``There's no quick fix,'' said Gary Honroe, who speaks to youth
groups about the perils of the streets and has buried a daughter, a
brother and a sister murdered in the last decade. ``But if we don't
start today, there won't be a tomorrow.'' 1,300 words. By Don
Terry.
</P>
<P>
   ZOO-ELEPHANTS (Indianapolis) _ Indianapolis had a scientific
breakthrough in March with the birth of Amali, the first African
elephant in the world born after artificial insemination. It was a
popular breakthrough as well, and while the little 201-pound baby
has thrived, growing to a sturdy 400-pound toddler, she has become
the talk of the town. And to prove the pregnancy was not a fluke,
another African elephant, also impregnated artificially, is due to
give birth next month. The zoo is arranging to repeat the birth
watch, in which video cameras, paid staff members and volunteers
maintain a 24-hour-a-day vigil to make sure all goes well at the
crucial moment. 900 words. By Carl H. Lavin.
</P>
