<HEADER>
A3638 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PATENTS-NYT &LR;      07-16 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB SITE FOR CARGO RATES LAYS CLAIM TO A BUSINESS METHOD 
</HEADLINE>
   By SABRA CHARTRAND  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The patenting of methods used in e-business has sparked anger
and outrage in the world of Internet commerce, especially in the
case of several high-profile companies that have received broad
patents for widely used retail techniques. The dispute over
Amazon.com's patent for its one-click shopping technology is an
example.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the heat, the Patent and Trademark Office has made clear
that it intends to continue issuing patents on digital business
practices, and entrepreneurs, therefore, will likely continue to
stake out as much as they can of the new markets created as nearly
every industry moves online. Inevitably, the debate over whether
these patents foster innovation, or whether they stifle
competition, will continue.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction could go either way for a patent awarded last month
to two childhood friends: ``Method for Online Display and
Negotiation of Cargo Rates.'' The patent covers a method of pooling
the prices that various freight carriers charge for land, sea and
air cargo shipments, posting them on a central Web site, and
allowing customers to browse and comparison-shop for their shipping
needs.
</P>
<P>
   The patent also allows shippers and customers to negotiate rates
and routes, and to hold interactive auctions to set shipping rates.
The inventors say they won a patent because no one else in cargo
transportation had created a hub to consolidate shipping
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just came out, and I don't know who has seen the news or
is privy to it,'' Daniel Miller, one of the inventors and a lawyer
in Mahopac, N.Y., said of the patent issued in May. ``But we
haven't heard any objections to it from shippers, carriers or
competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   Until last year, shippers ranging from corporations like
Pepsi-Cola International to an independently-owned antique store
had to contact individual freight carriers to get price quotes.
That usually meant lots of phone calls, faxes and e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Web site, www.cargosphere.com, was launched last
February, the inventors say 500 customers and shippers have
registered.
</P>
<P>
   With hundreds of thousands of trucking, rail, air and ocean
shipping companies in the United States, and millions of potential
customers, the number registered so far is small. Miller said he
and his fellow inventor Neil Barni are promoting their patented
business model and Web site at trade shows, through trade
publications and with individual cargo companies and freight
associations in an effort to add shippers and cargo brokers to
their registry.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the service is free, but by fall the inventors plan to
charge both buyers and sellers a $5 fee for any shipment smaller
than a freight container, or $10 for one or more containers.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the patent started with Barni, who lives in Dallas
and has been friends with Miller since elementary school. Until
recently, Barni worked for Pepsi, where he handled shipping and
often spent a great deal of time on the phone, seeking competitive
cargo prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neil saw a real need for a way to get the best rates,'' said
Miller. ``That was the genesis of the idea. I said it would be nice
if people could negotiate online. We moved pretty quickly to get a
patent application filed because we thought this was a very
innovative, unique idea and there was nothing like it in the cargo
transportation industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The patent, and the Web site, allow customers to anonymously
review posted shipping routes and prices. Customers can negotiate
with shippers, but a carrier's name is revealed only after a price
offer is accepted.
</P>
<P>
   The process is not binding. If either the customer or the
shipper decides they don't want to do business with one another,
they can back out of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main reason for anonymity is that carriers are very
sensitive about having their rates published,'' Miller said. That
is because prices can change frequently, he said, sometimes even
fluctuating between morning and evening.
</P>
<P>
   Individuals can use the site as well, Miller said. The only
caveat is that the service does not cover the shipping of small
packages. ``We are open to anyone above parcel service,'' Miller
said. ``We can't get into that and don't want to.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said he expected no objections to the patent from the
cargo industry or from large, established shipping companies that
already have their own Web sites. ``If we can help them get rid of
excess capacity or help customers find the best rates for shippers,
then everyone stands to gain,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But in announcing the patent, CargoSphere.com also stated that
the invention made it ``a front-runner in the competitive area of
Internet shipping platforms,'' and the company's patent attorney
said, ``The patent affords the company the right to exclude or to
license others in that industry with respect to the patented
business model.''
</P>
<P>
   But restricting the patent's umbrella to cargo shipping alone
may not give CargoSphere that exclusivity _ even if it is the first
in its industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that they put in the claims that it is limited to
cargo or freight doesn't mean that it can't be challenged by
something broader that was out there before it,'' explained Robert
Perry, a patent attorney with Kenyon &AMP; Kenyon in New York City who
has found himself dealing increasingly with business method
patents.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that Internet business method patents have yet to
be tested in court. Uncertainty over their impact, he said,
prompted Congress to add a new layer of protection to patent law
last year for people who might be accused of infringing a business
method patent. Under the new law, someone who can prove they used
an electronic business method for a year before a patent
application was filed cannot be sued, even if they did not make
public their practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``What will shake down when the courts come into it in five or
six years is that there are a lot of people doing business in-house
that is not the subject of patents, but will certainly be valid
prior art,'' Perry explained, using the term for existing designs
or practices. ``It will require a lot of digging, but that is how
these business method patents will be challenged.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Miller and Neil Barni received patent 6,064,981.
</P>
<P>
   Patents may be viewed on the Web at www.uspto.gov or may be
ordered through the mail, by patent number, for $3 from the Patent
and Trademark Office, Washington, D.C., 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-00 1534EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
