   &UR; MEDIA-BUSINESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Coding varies.)
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT-STRIKE-MEDIA (Detroit) _ Did the bitter newspaper strike
in a union town irreparably damage the newspaper industry in
Detroit? By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-EBONY-MEDIA (Durban, South Africa) _ After five years
struggling to generate revenue, the South African edition of Ebony
magazine has shut down. Although the United States edition is still
sold here, the failure of the local edition is a sign of the
slower-than-hoped-for growth of a black South African upper-middle
class. By Henri E. Cauvin.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-POLITICS-MEDIA (Undated) _ In the experimental
environment of Internet-based political information, two commercial
Web sites, including one whose news operation is directed by the
prominent journalist Carl Bernstein, are covering the upcoming
elections and political conventions while maintaining partnerships
under contract with the political parties. By Rebecca Fairley
Raney.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-TALK (Undated) _ Renata Adler reveals her John Sirica
``evidence''; the story behind Jack Welch's book deal; and Stephen
Chao, the USA Cable president, just can't get a break when it comes
to the World Wrestling Federation. By staff.
</P>
<P>
   TV-HITS-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ The breakout this year of sudden
hits like ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' and ``Survivor'' has
created a new type of strategizing by advertisers _ trying to
determine which programs to sign onto early and how to scramble
when a property that didn't seem to have much potential suddenly
becomes hot. And while the Nielsen jury is still out on ``Big
Brother,'' that program, too, illustrates the new kind of
odds-making by marketers and media-buying agencies. By Stuart
Elliott.
</P>
