<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3660 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ALBERT-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     07-16 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBERT-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DRIVING MR. ALBERT': SEARCHING FOR EINSTEIN WITH HIS BRAIN IN
TOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Michael Paterniti happened to mention the urban myth about
Albert Einstein's AWOL brain to his landlord, he was in for a
surprise that would prove useful. Not only had the landlord also
heard stories that Einstein's brain had disappeared after his
death, but the landlord also had a lead on its whereabouts. He
helped point the author toward Dr. Thomas Harvey, the pathologist
who absconded with the brain after he performed a 1955 autopsy on
Einstein in Princeton, N.J. For nearly half a century Harvey had
hung onto this grisly souvenir.
</P>
<P>
   So Paterniti, sensing the makings of the magazine article (for
Harper's) that he has now inflated into book form, made a
pilgrimage to Harvey in Princeton. And when Harvey expressed a
desire to go to Berkeley, Calif., Paterniti offered to take him
there. Along came a high-concept, cutely titled account of a
cross-country road trip involving an eccentric octogenarian
scientist, a pensive young acolyte and a celebrity body part in a
Tupperware container.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming that ``simply having Einstein's brain in the trunk
rearranges the way you see everything,'' Paterniti took to the
road. And he began the trip with a handy predilection for finding
whiffs of Einsteinian thinking everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the themes of my earlier life, as I recall it now, is
that I was forever projecting myself forward and backward at the
same time, negating the present moment, changing my mind with
alarming frequency,'' he reports in suitably scientific mode. Thus
equipped, he could find that in a Kansas City vista ``shots of
light glance off the glass windows of skyscrapers, electrons and
quanta firing past us like an invisible hail of bullets.'' Or muse
that ``Pennsylvania is its own kind of in-between, not really east
and not west, the pulse between neurons.''
</P>
<P>
   Because ``Driving Albert'' in fact revolved around a brief,
largely uneventful car trip involving a not very chatty passenger
(``Way-ell, it sure has been a wonderful specimen'' is Harvey at
his most communicative), Paterniti often found himself reaching for
something more. And so he had ample time to recall Einstein's life
and its implications, or to wonder about his girlfriend home in
Maine. Had she hit a moose on the road? Had she run off with the
Federal Express man?
</P>
<P>
   Naturally there was ample time to contemplate the brain itself,
cut into 240-odd fragments, and to endow it with suitably cosmic
implications. After wondering whether it feels like tofu, sea
urchin or bologna, Paterniti reflects, ``I mean, it's not really
Einstein and it's not really a brain, but disconnected pieces of a
brain, just as the passing farms are not really America but parts
of a whole, symbols of the thing itself, which is everything and
nothing at once.'' Everything-and-nothingness serves as the book's
dominant motif.
</P>
<P>
   So Paterniti is ever alert to parallels between Einstein's life
and anyone else's. (Einstein and Harvey each had multiple
marriages; Einstein and a Japanese scientist, whom the author also
visited on a separate jaunt described here, both failed important
exams as students, and both had difficulties with postcollege
employment.) And he likes to imagine what Einstein's thoughts might
have been.
</P>
<P>
   A train goes by in Arizona, prompting the author to write,
``Were this 1931, Einstein might very well have been on that
train,'' and adding, ``Undoubtedly, he would occasionally have
looked up from his equations to see America beyond the window.'' At
another juncture he decides that Einstein would have been horrified
by MTV and Microsoft but amused by tae-bo, Jesse Ventura and penis
augmentations.
</P>
<P>
   Eager for newsworthy encounters Paterniti brings Harvey to visit
William Burroughs, who was the doctor's neighbor in Lawrence, Kan.,
even though the two elderly men had met only once before. And
always alert to the possibility of larger meaning, Paterniti thinks
he glimpses evidence of Burroughs' most notorious exploits in the
famous old author's wrinkles. For his part, Burroughs, the
legendary wild man, downs five Coke-and-vodkas on top of his daily
methadone, smokes a joint and then begins addressing Harvey as
Senegal. This is easily one of the more newsworthy encounters along
the book's otherwise pedestrian journey.
</P>
<P>
   Matters grow desperate. Paterniti is prompted by the offer of
more coffee from a waitress in Lawrence to reflect that she might
have been blown up in the 20-year-old television movie ``The Day
After.'' He and Harvey call Evelyn Einstein, the scientist's
granddaughter, and ask to visit her in Berkeley, to which she
replies: ``I don't know. My house is a mess.''
</P>
<P>
   They stop at carefully chosen places of Einsteinian import, like
Los Alamos, N.M., without prompting more than a ``Way-ell'' or two
out of Harvey. The author dodges a truck bearing the name
``Marianne,'' which is the name of his mother. And he does his
laundry, a process described with typically indiscriminate fervor.
``It feels powerful to drop the dirty stuff of a long week into a
tub of sudsy water,'' he relates, ``and have my pants and shirts
come out clean.''
</P>
<P>
   In the latter stages of the journey, Paterniti takes to
buttonholing strangers for journalistic effect. ``I'm on a trip,''
he says to two tourists in Las Vegas, ``and I was wondering what
you two know about Albert Einstein?'' A blackjack dealer says, ``I
don't know anything about him, but that man over there should be
able to help you.'' The casino manager, asked about Einstein,
curtly answers: ``Haven't seen him in here tonight. Sorry, pal.''
</P>
<P>
   In his search for the real meaning of his experience, which
ultimately includes sleeping with the brain on a pillow in his bed
``just to see,'' Paterniti grasps ambitiously and self-importantly
at every available straw. But the best assessment of his studiously
cerebral journey comes from Independence High School in San Jose,
Calif., where Harvey stops to display his treasure to students
``repulsed and captivated by the man whose fingers are wet with
brain.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvey, ``heady on the perfume of social studies teachers,''
meets one woman who sees what Paterniti works overtime to
aggrandize. ``I'm meeting a footnote here,'' she tells him, and
she's right.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `DRIVING MR. ALBERT'
</P>
<P>
   A Trip Across America With Einstein's Brain
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Paterniti
</P>
<P>
   210 pages. The Dial Press. $18.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-00 1647EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000716.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3661 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DETROIT-STRIKE-MEDIA-     07-16 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DETROIT-STRIKE-MEDIA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE STRIKE THAT DETROIT CAN'T FORGET 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STERLING HEIGHTS, Mich. _ As traffic sweeps north on Mound Road,
past the Detroit newspapers' printing plant, the air horns of some
passing semitrailer trucks offer supportive blasts to the cluster
of picketing newspaper workers. Other drivers offer staccato
salutes on their car horns.
</P>
<P>
   But the noise is irregular at best, as most cars and trucks
speed silently by. On its fifth anniversary, the last great
newspaper strike of the 20th century, a ghost with a living
grievance, still haunts Detroit, but the city moves on.
</P>
<P>
   If the strike is a memory, though, its consequences are not.
Since the walkout on July 13, 1995, Detroit's two daily papers have
made do with replacement workers and, eventually, many returning
strikers.
</P>
<P>
   But a union-led boycott has helped erode the daily circulations
of the morning paper, The Detroit Free Press, and the evening
Detroit News, by a third. Between 1995 and 1999, the two newspapers
lost paying customers eight times faster than the industry as a
whole.
</P>
<P>
   The various union chapters, meanwhile, have seen their
memberships dwindle. And on July 7, in a further blow to the
Newspaper Guild of Detroit, a federal appeals panel overturned the
National Labor Relations Board and ruled that the papers' managers
had not engaged in unfair labor practices by adopting a merit-pay
system.
</P>
<P>
   Besides ending expectations that the strikers would receive
millions of dollars in back pay, the ruling stripped the union
loyalists of the judicial support that had seemed to give them the
moral high ground. ``We feel the legal system failed us,'' said
Louis Mleczko, the guild's president.
</P>
<P>
   Given the bitterness, management knows that winning back many
readers will require ending the boycott by settling with the six
striking unions, and by finding ways to manage newsrooms and
mailrooms and printing presses with workers who once cursed each
other across picket lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredibly tragic that the unions and companies couldn't
come to some middle ground,'' said David Crumm, a religion writer
for the Free Press. ``As it is, we've educated a whole generation
of readers that they don't need to read our newspapers. So we all
lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Can the mutual antipathy be overcome, allowing the unions to
call off the boycott, before the subscriber erosion is so great
that one newspaper must fold? Will Detroit, like so many other
cities, be left with one major daily? Or will the digital
technology that has streamlined costs _ and helped render the
picket lines impotent _ let the papers find new ways to market
themselves, keeping them healthy?
</P>
<P>
   The News, owned by the Gannett Co., had daily circulation of
359,000 in 1994, the year the paper won a Pulitzer Prize for
exposing fiscal mismanagement in state government. Now its daily
circulation is about 237,000.
</P>
<P>
   The News' competitor, Knight Ridder's Free Press, ranked ninth
nationally in March 1994, with a daily circulation of 551,000. Six
years later, it sells 361,000 daily copies and ranks 22nd.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if both papers will still exist in five years, Frank J.
Vega, the Gannett executive who is president of the Detroit
Newspaper Agency, which runs the business operations of both
newspapers, confidently predicts they will. ``We need to get
contracts now,'' Vega said. ``We want to get contracts. The unions
want to get contracts. But it's going to be difficult to get it
done. They want to turn the clock back.'' Last week, Vega rescinded
proposals the agency had made in informal bargaining.
</P>
<P>
   His office is filled with strike memorabilia, like the
hate-filled cards he has defiantly framed and a Darth Vader statue,
memorializing the strikers' epithet, ``Darth Vega.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been strikes that were more violent; there have
been strikes that went on longer,'' Vega said. ``But we probably
have a lock on this: This will be the longest, in terms of the time
it's going to take to heal.''
</P>
<P>
   The strike was called in July 1995 a week after management put
in place a merit-pay system over union objections. In the early
days of the strike, both newspapers published under a joint
masthead. A rival paper, The Detroit Journal, was published by the
strikers for four years. By the end of 1995, the News and the Free
Press resumed separate publication, although some advertisers and
many readers shunned them.
</P>
<P>
   The strike lasted formally for 19 months, until the six unions
agreed to return to work. The advertisers, too, have returned. But
no contracts have been signed.
</P>
<P>
   And vivid memories linger: The burning truck. The picketer hit
by a delivery truck. The bruises left from clashes with riot
police. The stalking of replacement delivery workers, the epithets,
the fury, the hatred.
</P>
<P>
   For the strikers, it was a just fight for collective bargaining
and workers' rights. For Vega, it was a just fight against a
bloated payroll and an arrogant union leadership that led more than
2,000 workers into the wilderness for no good reason.
</P>
<P>
   The News and the Free Press are now staffed by replacement
workers and former strikers, with a total of 1,478 full-time jobs _
766 fewer than before the strike. It is a more efficient and more
ethnically diverse work force, Vega said.
</P>
<P>
   All sides agree that Gannett and Knight Ridder, which formed the
Detroit Newspaper Agency under a joint operating agreement in 1989,
together lost more than $100 million in the strike. But the profit
picture improved at the end of 1996. Analysts say the agency's
profits climbed to between $60 million and $70 million in 1999,
surpassing 1994 levels.
</P>
<P>
   The agency took in almost $350 million in advertising revenue
last year, according to the estimates of a Merrill Lynch analyst,
Lauren Rich Fine. That was almost $80 million more than in 1996.
Fine said the strike had not hurt the two companies with investors:
``They did what they had to do. They are happy where they ended
up.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jim St. Louis ended up without his old job as a mailroom
worker. He is now an organizer for the Teamsters' International
Union. Like people on both sides, he clings to memories that seem
to support the justness of his actions, like the visit of Martin
Luther King III in support of the strike.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Different unions had different issues. The Newspaper Guild
objected to the merit-pay plan leaving most annual pay raises to
management's discretion. For the mailers, it was disputes over pay
and the use of subcontractors. For drivers and circulations
workers, job security.
</P>
<P>
   Now union membership is way down. In 1995, Teamsters Local 2040
had 365 full-time workers and 300 part-time workers at the
newspaper agency, according to its president, Al Young. Now he
said, only 165 pay dues and just 68 are back at work.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the Newspaper Guild of Detroit had 600 dues-paying
members _ reporters, photographers, copy editors and janitors. Now
there are 235.
</P>
<P>
   Robert G. McGruder, who was the managing editor of the Free
Press at the time of the strike and is now its executive editor,
said he felt vindicated by the panel's ruling. ``But I didn't think
it symbolized a victory or the end of a difficult situation,'' he
said. ``There's a long, long road to go to negotiate fair
contracts.''
</P>
<P>
   And a long road to winning back readers. Yet, even some labor
loyalists, among the first to desert the paper, have begun to
trickle back. Bob Celestini, a retired test driver for Chrysler,
said he had stopped subscribing to the News in late 1995 but
started buying it again last year: ``I threw my hands up. It was a
deadlock.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Silverman, who became publisher of the News in mid-1997,
said that circulation figures did not represent the paper's full
reach. He said a survey in January indicated that the papers may
have a so-called pass-along readership _ people who read papers
purchased by someone else _ 21 percent higher than the official
circulation data. That compares with an 8 percent pass-along
readership before the strike, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin Small, a history professor at Wayne State University, is
part of the pass-along group. He subscribes to The Oakland Press, a
suburban daily. But if he finds the Free Press ``in an airplane
seat, I'll pick it up and read it,'' Small said, although he added,
``my wife won't.''
</P>
<P>
   And a few Democratic politicians like Rep. David E. Bonior,
D-Mich., and some city council members, along with scholars like
Small, some clergymen and union leaders, still will not talk to
reporters from the Free Press or the News.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Giles, the senior vice president of the Freedom Forum who
was the editor and publisher of the News when the strike began, now
finds his candidacy to become curator of Harvard University's
Nieman Foundation under attack by union leaders. His critics
contend that Giles distorted the News' coverage of the strike to
favor management's viewpoint; they recall an article about a group
of four civic honorees, which mentioned three award winners and
omitted the name of a prominent striker.
</P>
<P>
   But Giles has received a letter of support from the current
leaders of the American Society of Newspaper Editors, calling him
``an innovative and ethical journalist.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Giles defended the News' strike coverage as
being fair, considering that ``the union spokespeople would not
speak to our reporters.'' As for the article that omitted the name
of a striker, he said he did not know that had happened and that
the name should have been included.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Giles said: ``The Detroit newspapers were able to
introduce what we consider to be modern newspaper management
practices. That fact alone will be seen years from now as being a
very important part of the survival of two newspapers in Detroit.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``the emotional toll was extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Wowk, a suburban reporter at the News, believes the
strike failed because ``they outmuscled us.'' At 53, he is training
to become a schoolteacher, and he said his current managers at the
newspaper accommodated his scheduling needs.
</P>
<P>
   But still, when he thinks of editors and reporters who crossed
the picket line, he said: ``I don't know if everything will ever be
forgiven. But we're professionals. We work together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
