<P>
   PERU-INNOCENTS (Lima) _ Peruvians call the more than one
thousand people, mostly poor, who were unfairly imprisoned on
charges of terrorism or treason between 1992 and 1995 by special
antiterrorism courts, ``the innocents.'' Most have been pardoned or
absolved of any wrongdoing over the last three years; but their
lives and the lives of their families have been irreparably
tattered. Such injustice was the product of the chaos that gripped
Peru in the early 1990s, when the Shining Path, a brutal terrorist
group bent on creating a radical Maoist state, was in the final
throes of a rampage of bombings and massacres. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-HATE (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ Bernard Kouchner, the
emotional French doctor who runs Kosovo for the United Nations, has
made it through a year of ups and downs that illustrate the
failures, the progress and the strain of trying to bring together
Serbs and Albanians who are divided by the deepest hatred this
world-traveled man says he has ever encountered. By Steven
Erlanger.
</P>
