<DOCNO> NYT20000716.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3676 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TV-HITS-AD-COL-ART-2T     07-16 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-HITS-AD-COL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: BETTING CORRECTLY TO STAY `ON THE ISLAND'
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT1 and NYT2 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Madison Avenue these days, you're either on the island or off
the island.
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive summer, couch potatoes have
unexpectedly switched from traditional fare like sitcoms, news
magazines and dramas to offbeat offerings like reality series and
prime-time quiz shows. With the breakout of sudden hits like
``Survivor'' and ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' ad agencies are
scrambling to adapt to these abrupt shifts in viewing patterns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think it's harder,'' said Bob Igiel, president for the
broadcast division of the Media Edge in New York, part of Young &AMP;
Rubicam. ``We have to be smarter and more innovative than ever
before.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the executives at agencies who try to determine in
advance which television shows will succeed, then try to buy
commercial time on those programs at the lowest possible prices,
have always been playing poker for high stakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really hard to predict a hit, and anybody who tells you
they can is lying,'' said Laura Caraccioli, vice president and
director at Starcom Entertainment in Chicago, part of the Starcom
Worldwide media agency owned by the B Com3 Group.
</P>
<P>
   The aim of the poker game is to get in on the opening hand
before a series becomes must-see TV, but avoid wasting precious ad
dollars on shows that turn into must-skip TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be involved in the next `water cooler show' everyone is
talking about is great,'' said Stacey Lynn Koerner, vice president
for broadcast research at TN Media in New York, owned by True North
Communications. ``But nobody thought `Millionaire' would be what it
was until we saw the first two weeks and said, `Hmmmmmm,'''
recalling the program's debut as a summer fill-in last year.
</P>
<P>
   The big danger that agencies confront, then, is failing to help
clients keep pace with rapidly changing consumer habits. That's a
fate worse than being voted off the island on ``Survivor,'' or
missing an easy $100 or $200 question on ``Millionaire.'' So
agencies are stepping up efforts to clamber aboard band wagons
before they begin rolling _ or at least jump aboard before they
gain much momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a calculated risk when you're considering an
unproven program,'' said Bret Itskowitch, vice president and
account director at Mediacom in New York, part of the Grey Global
Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now there's a different way of looking at things,'' he
added. ``There's greater opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Mediacom executives were early fans of ``Survivor,'' Itskowitch
said, and ``we did everything we could'' to persuade one client,
Reebok International, to become a sponsor of the unusual series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reebok had not been a huge network advertiser,'' Itskowitch
said, referring to the company's recent reluctance to advertise
during prime time on broadcast TV when prices are highest.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this was an obvious fit,'' he added, ``and it's worked out
perfectly for us.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the sponsorship package Mediacom bought for Reebok,
one of nine sold by CBS, the 16 contestants wear Reebok apparel and
footwear, which are continually seen during each episode. And the
Reebok creative agency, Berlin Cameron &AMP; Partners in New York, was
permitted to use contestants already voted off the island in
commercials that run during subsequent episodes of the show.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a spot that ran last week featured Stacey Stillman,
an early deportee, jogging through a jungle as a ``Survivor''-like
explorer plucks lagoon leeches from his skin. Other sponsors like
Anheuser-Busch are also running commercials with desert-island
themes.
</P>
<P>
   Another ``Survivor'' sponsor, the Pontiac division of General
Motors, followed a recommendation by its media agency, GM
Mediaworks, to promote a new product _ in this instance, a sport
utility vehicle named Aztek _ during the new series. That was a
risk because ``Survivor'' was still an unproven show when the
decision was made.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, my first thought was that we'd rather go with
something more established,'' said Don Butler, Aztek brand manager
at Pontiac in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the more I thought about it,'' he added, ``the more I
thought: `It's risky, it's on the edge. But it might make sense.'''
The last ``Survivor'' contestant not voted off the island will win
prizes including an Aztek.
</P>
<P>
   The Media Edge bought sponsorships in ``Survivor'' for two
clients, Ericsson and the U.S. Army. The agency hooked up another
client, AT&AMP;T, with ``Millionaire'' on ABC, sponsoring the
contestant aid known as the ``phone a friend'' lifeline.
</P>
<P>
   ``A producer of `Millionaire,' Michael Davies, came to me before
the show ever went on the air'' in August 1999, Igiel recalled.
``He showed me some of the footage from the original version in
England and I came out of my chair like a landed tuna.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you I thought it would be the mammoth hit here
that it is, but I thought it had potential,'' he added. ``And with
the lifeline, where in a stressful situation, dependability is
wonderful, AT&AMP;T could really showcase itself.'' The sponsorship
includes mentions of AT&AMP;T by the host, Regis Philbin, when a
lifeline call is placed as well as superimposing AT&AMP;T logos on
screen.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Sure things' are too often, I hate to say it, sure
failures,'' said John Mattimore, senior vice president and
associate media director at BBDO New York, part of the BBDO
Worldwide unit of the Omnicom Group. ``You're better off going the
other way once in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Mattimore and his colleagues bought a ``Survivor'' sponsorship
for Visa because, he said, ``I've been doing this for 25 years and
we keep telling the networks: `Take chances. Don't keep doing the
same things. We don't need 10 ``Friends'' wannabes.' So if we say
it, we should be able to support it.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, that is music to the ears of the top sales
executives at the broadcast networks. They have been stung by
complaints from agencies about having to pay higher prices each
year for commercial time despite declining ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought `Survivor' would be fairly successful,'' said Joseph
Abruzzese, CBS sales president in New York, a unit of Viacom Inc.
``But it's been wildly successful.''
</P>
<P>
   The reality series is attracting viewers far younger than those
usually watching the network, he added, as well as advertisers that
don't typically buy prime-time spots on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   The last episode of ``Survivor,'' on Aug. 23, will run 2 hours,
twice as long as the first 12. And commercial time will be
``double'' the $275,000 to $350,000 that NBC charged for each
30-second spot during the baseball All-Star Game last week,
Abruzzese said. That's also about double what CBS has charged for a
30-second spot on ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first heard about `Survivor,' I said, `You've got to be
kidding me,''' said Marv Goldsmith, president for network sales and
marketing at ABC in New York, part of the Walt Disney Co. ``But I
give CBS credit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were talking about `Survivor' two years ago, to get a feel
for it from advertisers,'' he added, ``and Coca-Cola said, `Can
they drink Coca-Cola?' We said: `It's a desert island. You don't
have a vending machine on a desert island.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But ABC is consoling itself with ``Millionaire,'' which
initially also ``had trouble getting advertisers,'' Goldsmith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the first show,'' he added dryly, ``it was slightly
easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Agencies continue to worry when gauging the odds for or against
sponsoring programs before their potential can be determined, as
evident in the mixed reception for another CBS reality series,
``Big Brother.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Starcom has not bought commercials during ``Big
Brother,'' Caraccioli said, but some clients may get so-called
make-good spots on the show to compensate for ratings shortfalls
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, TN has bought time during ``Big Brother'' for
clients like Schering-Plough, a ``Survivor'' sponsor, and S.C.
Johnson, Koerner said, adding: ``You can't write it off. It's still
outperforming what CBS would have had on in its place.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Fox Broadcasting unit of the News Corp. is just starting
to sell commercial time during ``American High,'' a documentary
reality series to begin on Aug. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``The audience is not accepting the same-old, same-old,'' said
Jon Nesvig, president for sales at Fox in New York. ``We have to
try new things, and the advertisers have to take chances also.''
</P>
<P>
   In the new TV landscape, the highs can be higher, as the record
summer viewership for ``Survivor'' has proved. But the lows can be
lower, too, as Fox learned from the fiasco surrounding a reality
special in February, ``Who Wants to Marry a Multimillionaire?''
</P>
<P>
   ``God knows they're lower,'' Nesvig said, laughing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-00 1735EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
