<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPDAVID-COLOR-0717-Cox </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Snapshot Diplomacy
</P>
<P>
   By Bob Deans
</P>
<P>
   Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. Every picture tells a story, or so the saying
goes.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, pictures were the only story as Mideast peace talks at
nearby Camp David lurched through day six on Sunday amid a strictly
enforced news blackout.
</P>
<P>
   Like sheep at a trough, an international press corps, accustomed
to news gathering in the digital age, has been reduced to gathering
at bulletin boards in the temporary media headquarters at Thurmont
Elementary School.
</P>
<P>
   There, in a classroom with dull wooden floors the honey color of
faded shellac, White House press officers have pinned two dozen
photographs, each one a carefully chosen 8X10 glossy glimpse into
diplomacy behind closed doors at the presidential retreat five
miles down the road.
</P>
<P>
   Here, for instance, is President Clinton, a grey shirttail
trailing from behind a pair of faded blue jeans, strolling through
the Catoctin Mountain woods early on in the talks. Shuffling along
at his side is Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, in his trademark
olive military dress and black and white keffiyeh, the traditional
Arab headdress.
</P>
<P>
   Here's another shot of Clinton seated, with Arafat to his left
and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak at Clinton's right, eating
dinner with negotiators Saturday night in the pale green clapboard
Laurel lodge.
</P>
<P>
   And beside that is a black and white picture of Clinton's
National Security Adviser, Samuel Berger, and Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright presumably pursuing peace in a golf cart that
looks like Fred Flintstone's stone-mobile.
</P>
<P>
   In an exercise that gives new meaning to the term interpretive
reporting, White House and State Department correspondents camped
out here from their Washington posts have been left to scrutinize
these photos for some hint of summit atmospherics.
</P>
<P>
   It's clear, for instance, that Clinton is drinking a lot of Diet
Coke, and that Arafat isn't wasting much time shaving.
</P>
<P>
   If Barak is using the Camp David pool or gym, the exercise
hasn't taken a serious toll on his waistline - if the bulges in his
collarless black shirts are any indication.
</P>
<P>
   We know these are high-stakes talks. Why else would Clinton and
Arafat be chatting in one shot in front of a World War II era
poster of Winston Churchill the first foreign leader ever to visit
Camp David, in a 1943 meeting with President Franklin D. Roosevelt
in Clinton's informal office at the presidential compound.
</P>
<P>
   While the prints show the leaders and negotiators amiably if
intently engaged in what look like serious talks, White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart, not to mention common sense, insists that
the pictures tell only part of the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to create the false impression that because they
come together each evening for a meal in a positive atmosphere that
that permeates all the discussions,'' Lockhart told reporters
Sunday. ``These issues are difficult. The atmosphere can be
tense.''
</P>
<P>
   That's about as precise as Lockhart gets in his daily press
briefings here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to try to provide a progress report,'' he said.
``I'll give you the bare minimum of what the schedule is and let
those who are in these sessions at Camp David concentrate on the
difficult issues that face them, and spend a minimum amount of time
worrying about what's getting written in the paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the ground rules of the talks, all information to the
press comes from Lockhart or one of his deputies.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters have no access to the people who are actually
negotiating, much less the leaders themselves. And Lockhart won't
say anything about the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to prevent negotiators from using the press to try
to drive public opinion while the talks are underway and to prevent
bargaining positions from leaking out and becoming cemented in
place.
</P>
<P>
   For Arafat and Barak, there's no point in having the world know
how far they were willing to bend unless and until a deal can be
made public that comes with at least the possibility that the agony
of painful compromise might be at least partly offset by the
promise of peace.
</P>
<P>
   All of which leaves reporters - and the public - largely in the
dark.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' e-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
