<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAHAM-FROSTBURG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROSSFIRE OVER MARTHA GRAHAM'S LEGACY CATCHES UNIVERSITY DANCE
PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md.)   By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hosts of a long-scheduled retreat at Frostburg State
University that was to be focused on the work of Martha Graham had
hoped their campus in the Allegheny Mountains of western Maryland
could be the Camp David of modern dance.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of settling the bitter war over the Graham company
and its legendary founder's contributions, the university itself
was swept up last week in the turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Frostburg University abruptly eliminated all of Graham's dances
from a three-week educational retreat that began Sunday, after
Graham's legal heir, Ron Protas, demanded the dismissal of several
teachers who were scheduled to participate. His lawyer also sought
a ban on readings from any of Graham's writings on the basis that
Protas had inherited the rights to her works, including books and
letters. They also sought a ban on the discussion of the spiraling
dispute that has pitted Protas against dancers from the foundering
Martha Graham Center of Contemporary Dance.
</P>
<P>
   The dancers are urging other dance companies not to license
Graham's choreography from the trust that Protas controls.
</P>
<P>
   The university refused Protas' conditions and instead stripped
the retreat of Graham's name, replacing it with the muted title
``Dance Legends.'' Students will no longer perform Graham's 1934
``Panorama,'' but a work donated last week by another modern dance
pioneer, ``Harmonica Breakdown'' by Jane Dudley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has got to put their egos on a shelf and figure what
this is all about,'' said Barry Fischer, an associate professor of
dance at the university who organized the retreat and offered to
play the role of mediator.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about Graham's legacy,'' he said. ``This is about
sharing what Graham has contributed to the 20th century. This is
about healing and demonstrating her virtuosity. And this is a
horrific global arts tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   The university is caught up in the crossfire over Graham's more
than 180 works, which constitute a cornerstone of modern dance. The
rights to those works belong to Protas, who earlier this year was
dismissed as artistic director of the company amid tensions with
the board of the Graham Center, the company's parent organization.
The board has temporarily suspended operations of its 500-student
school, the company and the junior troupe because of its financial
turmoil, blaming Protas for alienating donors.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, he complains that the board and company have turned him
into a scapegoat for their own mistakes, arguing that much of the
resentment toward him is based on petty envy over his rights to
Graham's works.
</P>
<P>
   Last week dancers from the company started circulating a boycott
letter, urging other companies not to license and perform Graham's
dances until Protas and the board strike a new licensing agreement
that would allow the Graham company to use her dances, something
that Protas is prohibiting.
</P>
<P>
   It was that boycott letter, university officials said, that
prompted Protas and his representatives to ask for the dismissals
of three of the retreat's dance teachers who had signed the letter:
Janet Eilber, Elizabeth Auclair and Christophe Jeannot. The trust
was not aware at the time that each of the five visiting teachers
had signed the letter, including the choreographer Pearl Lang.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it's personal and antagonistic,'' Fischer said.
``They told us that we cannot do the repertoire for any
performances unless these people are dismissed.''
</P>
<P>
   The 30 dancers enrolled in the retreat _ who range in age from
13 to 27 _ were initially promised that their lessons would
culminate in a campus performance of Graham's ``Panorama.'' Fischer
said the audience would have consisted largely of the family and
friends of the dancers. In addition some of the retreat's teachers
were scheduled to perform in two community events.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Quinn, the lawyer representing Protas, said that the
Martha Graham Trust had offered to let the university use the
licensed works without charge for teaching lessons. But he said the
trust took issue with allowing supporters of the boycott letter to
choreograph and perform Graham works.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would we give these individuals the opportunity to
participate in any Martha Graham performance?'' Quinn asked. ``It's
unfortunate they took this tack, and they have to realize they're
responsible for these reactions. They are completely to blame for
this fallout.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that he considered the dancers' call for a licensing
boycott by other companies ``wrong, both legally and morally,'' and
said that the trust was exploring legal options. ``I'm not saying
there will be a lawsuit,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Protas, who initially asked to lecture at the dance retreat,
declined to comment, referring questions to his lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Late last week the university sent a letter to Protas' lawyer,
barring his client from attending the retreat, but as of Friday the
trust was seeking permission to send a nonparticipating observer to
monitor the classes to make sure there is no teaching of Graham.
Fischer said Protas' lawyer had also asked the university for any
videotapes of the dance classes and performances for later review,
along with a pledge that the teachers would not read any of
Graham's writings aloud to students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have all these dancers coming to teach, and they have fear
and trepidation about Ron confronting them on campus,'' Fischer
said. He added that he had tried to persuade the various factions
to use the retreat to discuss reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had offered to be a mediator, hands across the water,'' said
Fischer, who wrote his doctoral dissertation based on the early
Graham work ``Steps in the Street.'' ``I thought they could come
here to speak and start the healing. The Graham Center board was
open to that, but I got very little response from the other side.''
</P>
<P>
   With the loss of Graham's repertory, Frostburg University
scrambled to obtain the rights to other dances. Lang offered three
of hers, and other choreographers also offered theirs, Fischer
said. Then he contacted Dudley, who had danced with Graham
beginning in the 1930s and was later dispatched by her to London to
build the modern dance movement there. Dudley granted permission
for ``Harmonica Breakdown.''
</P>
<P>
   At 88, Dudley uses a wheelchair, but Fischer said that she
considered going to Frostburg with an attendant to watch the
performance. But late last week she decided that she was not well
enough to attend to show her support. So she added her name to the
list of dancers signing the boycott letter.
</P>
</TEXT>
