<DOCNO> NYT20000716.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3682 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NEW-ECON-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-16 1301
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-ECON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO DIFFERENT FRONTS OF GROWTH IN SATELLITE RADIO INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is not every day that the trailblazer of a
multibillion-dollar niche of the satellite industry is an
entrepreneur betting on the commercial potential of Africa. No
wonder Noah Samara is smiling at the irony.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamental difference between one person and another,
rich or poor, is access to information,'' said Samara, who was born
in Ethiopia, raised in Tanzania and educated at the University of
California at Berkeley. ``It is kind of funny that our basic
approach of profiting from providing that access is ahead of what
is happening in the developed world.''
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, Samara's company, the WorldSpace Corp., based in
Washington, initiated satellite radio-broadcasting service in a
region stretching from Cairo to Cape Town, providing Africa with 25
audio channels of news, music, entertainment and educational
programming.
</P>
<P>
   WorldSpace's foray into Africa was a milestone for the budding
satellite radio industry. In various regions, including North
America, the idea is that an array of high-quality radio channels
will prove more attractive to many listeners than their local radio
stations _ like the way that cable television and satellite
television changed broadcast television.
</P>
<P>
   WorldSpace's digital audio broadcast system, which depends on a
solar-powered satellite beamed into space from a launch site in
French Guiana, is a harbinger of things to come. So far, the
company has showed promise in urban areas with large expatriate
communities wanting regional news, such as Indian merchants in
Kenya or Nigerians living in other African countries.
</P>
<P>
   But it will be far from Africa, on the dashboards of automobiles
in the United States, where the development of the industry is
expected to be played out with fervor.
</P>
<P>
   In four years, satellite radio is expected to grow from
virtually nothing into a $2.4 billion global industry, according to
C.E. Unterberg Towbin, a brokerage firm that focuses on the
satellite industry. In this country, the two companies seen fueling
the growth are Sirius Satellite Radio and XM Satellite Radio, which
have received the only two licenses from the Federal Communications
Commission to offer satellite radio.
</P>
<P>
   By this time next year, both companies hope to be able to
deliver 100 audio channels throughout the United States, for a
monthly charge of about $10. The service is to be available to
either fixed or mobile locations. Test versions of the receiving
antenna are small domes only a few inches in diameter that could be
attached externally to the rear windows of automobiles. Each of the
channels will be devoted to a specific theme, like jazz or
classical or salsa music, with much of the programming produced at
Sirius' studio in New York and XM's in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Sirius went public in 1994; its shares closed at $49.25 on
Friday, more than double last fall's price. XM went public in
October and announced last week that it had completed a final round
of financing with the private placement of $235 million in
convertible stock, raising its total funds to $1.26 billion. Its
publicly traded shares, which spent last fall in the low teens,
closed Friday at $40.875.
</P>
<P>
   Investors in the companies, which include major car
manufacturers and satellite companies, are wagering that consumers
in the United States will be eager to pay for CD-quality radio in
their automobiles _ on the assumption that radio is as essential to
the car as television is to the home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our business model foresees us becoming profitable if we
capture just 1 percent of the market,'' said David Margolese, the
president of Sirius. ``It's premised on the idea that a lot of
people in a prosperous, large country like this one will be willing
to spend a little extra to get top-quality radio programming when
they're in traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Sirius has distribution agreements with Ford Motor,
DaimlerChrysler and BMW, while XM has an agreement with General
Motors and is in talks to form a similar agreement with the Honda
Motor Co. When Sirius successfully launched the first of three
satellites it plans to send into space, from the Baikonur
Cosmodrome site in Kazakhstan earlier this month, its shares rose
10 percent in one day.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a chance to buy into something that could profoundly
change the way Americans consume their music,'' said Peter J.
Eichler, the president of Aletheia Research and Management, a $150
million money management firm in Santa Monica, Calif. ``It's easy;
you just have to choose between two companies because the industry
is controlled by a duopoly.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are obstacles to overcome before service is rolled
out by next year. Sirius needs to launch two more satellites, while
XM Satellite Radio also needs to launch both of its two planned
satellites, which it intends to do from a mobile launching site in
the Pacific Ocean _ the first later this year. Analysts say there
is about a 10 percent chance of a failure for each of the
companies' launches, and such a failure could mean delays in the
initiation of consumer service.
</P>
<P>
   There is also concern over the quality of reception, even though
both companies say that tests indicate listeners will have
virtually static-free coast-to-coast reception.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quality should be fine, but this might depend on the
construction of some line-of-sight apparatus on the ground to
ensure seamless transmission, and that deployment could get
expensive,'' said William Kidd, who covers the satellite radio
industry for Unterberg.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of what happens, analysts don't expect either company
to show a profit before 2004. In the time being, some people are
pondering the effect satellite radio will have on the conventional
radio broadcasting industry, which has not been shaken by a major
technical innovation since the introduction of the FM band. (Of
course, there is Internet radio broadcasting. But that requires a
computer and Internet access, and it may be years before wireless
versions are viable.)
</P>
<P>
   Since the rules regarding ownership of multiple radio stations
were loosened under the Telecommunications Act of 1996, the
broadcast industry has been through extensive consolidation, with
large media companies like Clear Channel Communications and Viacom
acquiring small radio stations throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   Two large satellite radio companies could further concentrate
power in the radio industry, critics say. ``Radio will become more
of a wasteland because satellite radio won't offer much space for
localism,'' said Robert McChesney, a mass media professor at the
University of Illinois in Urbana-Champaign. ``Remember the
mom-and-pop radio stations? They will all be gone.''
</P>
<P>
   With their large production studios, though, satellite radio
companies say that they could produce content unparalleled by small
radio stations. ``We can surpass radio's golden age,'' said Hugh
Panero, the president of XM. ``We'll be able to tailor content in
ways people wouldn't dream of.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, these are rich-country problems. WorldSpace, which is
backed by investors from Saudi Arabia and from several African
countries, plans to expand into Asia, and then into South America,
with two additional satellites.
</P>
<P>
   With a substantially different business model from those of
Sirius and XM, WorldSpace will concentrate on providing satellite
radio service to people who are stationary, and perhaps not yet
prosperous enough to buy a car. The company hopes to make money
from advertising aimed at regions with a combined population of
more than four billion people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing,'' Samara said, ``can cross the geographic and
cultural divides like radio can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
