<HEADER>
A3689 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-1090(2TAKES)-NYT     07-16 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-1090(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: FRONT-RUNNER BUSH KEEPING TO A CONSERVATIVE CAMPAIGN
STYLE
</HEADLINE>
  By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Out on the campaign trail, Gov. George W. Bush
appears to be barely be breaking a sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Town hall meetings where large audiences are free to ask
questions vanished months ago when Sen. John McCain of Arizona, the
master of spontaneity, disappeared from the presidential race. Now
audiences rarely get to ask Bush anything.
</P>
<P>
   On many days he makes no more than one or two public
appearances, and occasionally they last no more than 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's signature campaign events are small panel
discussions that more resemble seminars on social services.
Ostensibly the sessions are about new policy proposals. But Bush's
aides say they are just as much about mood, emotion and image. As
panelists tell Bush how they have overcome hardship, he responds
with emotive language, words and phrases like ``love'' or ``loving
family'' or ``willing heart.''
</P>
<P>
   The style and schedule that Bush is keeping is deliberate,
reflecting the campaign's strategic confidence that he can mold the
image he wants by creating carefully choreographed television
images in battleground states. In an era in which voters are more
and more turned off by partisanship, the events make him seem to be
governing rather than campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   It is almost as if he's running on the Rose Garden strategy,
only with the Rose Garden situated not at the White House but in a
handful of swing states across the country.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say that Bush is not working hard. His days are
filled with fund-raisers, policy meetings and interviews with the
news media. He is putting the last touches on his convention
speech, and is in the final phase of choosing a running mate.
Still, Bush's style these days could not be more different from
that of his opponent, Vice President Al Gore, who is generally
running behind in the polls and has longer, more event-packed
campaign days. Gore takes question after question from larger
audiences, showing off a detailed knowledge of everything from
immigration law to the history of the Medicare program.
</P>
<P>
   But while the presidential race is only now moving into the
critical convention period, Bush and his aides believe his method
of campaigning has produced good results and put him ahead in many
critical states and made him competitive in states that the
Democrats had counted on winning.
</P>
<P>
   At Bush headquarters in Austin, Texas, the governor's staff
monitors an array of polls and keeps a blue and red color-coded
electoral map that shows which way each state is leaning. Bush's
aides right now have a panorama showing Bush leading in states with
345 electoral college votes, Gore leading in states with 92
electoral votes and 101 votes up for grabs. A candidate needs 270
votes to win the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is I'm leading some of the polls,'' Bush told
state Republican officials gathered in Austin last week. ``The bad
news is the election isn't tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   So confident are the Republicans that after running about $5
million in ads promoting Bush's Social Security proposals, they sat
back and let the Democrats spend about $14 million on commercials
in key states promoting Gore and Democratic issues, without
responding. ``The race stayed the same,'' said one Bush adviser.
The GOP is now readying a new ad campaign to lead into the
Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides attribute the state of the presidential race partly
to a series of missteps by Gore over a rocky spring. But they also
point to Bush's turn to a policy-oriented campaign style right
after the Republican primaries ended, when he needed to erase the
bitterness of his fight with McCain and soften the hard
conservative edges he had created for himself.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor says he knew from the start that he wanted to
campaign in this softer style, much as he did in his first
governor's race in Texas in 1994. At that time he stuck to four
issues with relentless repetition: juvenile crime, welfare
overhaul, education and an overhaul of the legal system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Candidates tend to repeat the successes of the past,'' Bush
said. ``I found that ideas do drive campaigns,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is still using the same phrases that he did more than a
year ago, that he is a ``compassionate conservative,'' that he
wants to fight the ``soft bigotry of low expectations'' for
minority students in public schools, that he wants to rally ``the
armies of compassion.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he does not get bored by the repetition. ``I view it as
an opportunity,'' he says. ``What a good candidate has to
understand is every minute is an opportunity to convey a message.''
</P>
<P>
   But he has used policy proposals to give himself and his themes
more definition, showing how he is a traditional Republican and how
he is not.
</P>
<P>
   The groundwork for the policy offensive was set more than a year
ago when Bush named three senior advisers: Lawrence Lindsey for
economic policy, Stephen Goldsmith for domestic policy and
Condoleezza Rice for international affairs. He also assembled a
large think tank inside his campaign under the leadership of Josh
Bolten, who had worked in the administration of Bush's father.
</P>
<P>
   But the final plan for a spring of policy proposals leading into
the convention was put together by campaign staff at a country club
retreat just as the Republican primaries were coming to a close in
early March.
</P>
<P>
   The first speeches on education and health care and the
environment put Bush squarely on Democratic turf with reading
programs for the inner city and tax credits to help people who lack
health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Then came broad proposals to reshape Social Security and rethink
nuclear policy. They skipped all of the devilish details. But
Bush's aides say they showed voters that Bush was willing to take
risks and challenge the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Bush seems to be unveiling policies for every line item
of the federal budget _ an additional $75 million across five years
for veterans mentoring, or $400 million for after-school programs.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem small, but aides say that Bush is using these ideas
to shape his own image. In an election year in which no issue is
dominating, a Bush adviser said, ``Issues are important but they
are important as reflections of broader values and keys into a
candidate's leadership.'' He said, ``The independent swing voters
are not taking their stands on individual issues but their feelings
about what values the candidate reflects.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And the campaign is making strategic decisions about where and
how often to appear to talk to those swing voters. ``Why not three
or four events in the same media market?'' Bush said on his
campaign plane last week. ``We're trying to have a consistent
message.'' He added, ``There's no need to be stepping on my own
lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Normally the technique works and in swing state after swing
state, evening news programs usually show Bush surrounded by
winsome minority children or troubled teen-agers or
poor-but-determined single mothers talking of hopes for building a
better life. Only rarely is the script interrupted the way it was
on Friday in New Jersey when a minister challenged Bush about the
death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The dynamics of the presidential race could well change by the
fall. Gore's aides say that a vice president traditionally does not
come out from under the shadow of the president until his party's
nominating convention. And they argue that the public still favors
Democratic positions on issues, that Gore is better under pressure
and that he will shine when the two candidates meet in debates.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Bush has had the Republican Party solidified behind
him since the Republican primaries ended. His aides say they expect
that Gore will unify his own base and that will cause the race to
tighten after the Democratic National Convention in August. The
governor promised Sunday that he will not lie back and let Gore
criticize his positions and his Texas record. ``I'm a good
counterpuncher,'' he said in an appearance on the ABC program
``This Week.'' ``I am.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-00 1806EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000716.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3691 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-VOYEUR0717-COX     07-16 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOYEUR0717-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sleazy `Big Brother' makes `Survivor' look like a class act
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``Big Brother,'' meet your daddy. His name is Jerry
Springer.
</P>
<P>
   The CBS series _ which has experienced ratings mood swings as
volatile as some of the people it has trapped in a house _ is
looking more and more like Springer's much-maligned creep show.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, we've been treated to Jordan the stripper sobbing in
the bathroom and Karen and Tom's troubled marriage melting down.
America, are you having fun yet?
</P>
<P>
   Contrast that with ``Survivor,'' the other CBS series that's
been heating up the summer. To many, the two shows, ``Big Brother''
and ``Survivor,'' have been crammed under the same umbrella of
Voyeur-Vision TV _ two European imports that basically say it's OK
to be Peeping Toms so long as we pretend we're analyzing
psychological dynamics.
</P>
<P>
   As they've played out, though, the shows have diverged
considerably. ``Survivor'' seems more like grown-ups at summer
camp. Sure, they had to eat a little roasted rat, but basically
they've bonded, played games, worked on their tans and _ in the
case of Colleen and Greg _ gotten a little summer lovin'. Even with
Richard's shark-like strategizing and Susan's bite-me commentaries,
the folks on Pulau Tiga seem to be having a blast.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the competitive nature of ``Survivor,'' there is a
joyousness to the show. That could explain why its Nielsen ratings
started strong, took off like a bottle rocket and now have settled
at about 25 million viewers a week, a staggering number for the
summer doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Los Angeles, ``Big Brother'' seems increasingly
degrading. Thursday's hourlong show was where the series' inner
Springer really came out. Karen, a wife and mother of four from
Columbus, Ind., previously had trashed her husband and her marriage
on the show. In case you missed it, CBS replayed her comments.
Then, just as Springer always keeps the aggrieved partner offstage,
waiting to come on, they cut to an interview with Tom, her husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't want to discuss such things publicly,'' he
said, but of course he did, while 11 million people watched. (The
ratings, which had been diving, rebounded on Thursday as ``Big
Brother'' won its time slot; the series looks as if it will swing
wildly in the Nielsens for the rest of its three-month run.)
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that Tom and Karen have children who also are
watching, as are the kids' friends. ``Big Brother'' may not have
the ``Springer'' trademark catfights (yet), but we're being served
the same basic dish: the sad, sordid details of someone's life,
with no nutritional value whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   Also like ``Springer,'' ``Big Brother'' likes to pretend it's
higher-minded than it is. Host Julie Chen, who works for CBS News,
interviews loved ones and analysts. On Thursday, Dr. Drew Pinsky of
MTV's ``Loveline'' noted that Jamie, the beauty queen, had put on
her application that she felt rejected by her parents, so voting to
eject housemates would be difficult for her. Apparently, if you
don't bare enough, ``Big Brother'' will bare it for you.
</P>
<P>
   (Chen, by the way, is having a terrible time of it; she keeps
knocking off her journalist's hat with her cheerleader pompoms.)
</P>
<P>
   Now ``Big Brother'' is poised to boot one of its two most
interesting characters. The housemates have nominated Jordan the
stripper and William the black guy (who's either confrontational or
keepin' it real, depending on where you sit), and viewers call
1-900-740-1000 (99 cents a call) to vote on which one goes next
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   It's funny. When ``Survivor'' debuted, it was compared to ``Lord
of the Flies.'' But it has been ``Big Brother'' that's stripping
its participants (and not just Jordan) of their dignity.
</P>
<P>
   O N T H E W E B : Show updates: www.bigbrother2000.com
</P>
<P>
   HANDICAPPING `SURVIVOR' ON THE WEB
</P>
<P>
   Can't wait for Wednesday's ``Survivor'' to see who gets the
boot? Then sample www.survivorsucks.com, a Web site that has
correctly predicted the last four castaway castoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Operated by Planet Sucks, the site is dedicated to those who
hate the show. Operators agonized before making last week's
prediction that Gretchen _ rumored to be the ultimate survivor and
million-dollar prize-winner _ would douse her torch. But they were
right.
</P>
<P>
   Site operators credit ``our spies,'' ``our eyes'' (images from
show teasers), ``credible insiders,'' message board speculation and
other media.
</P>
<P>
   Check the site Tuesday for this week's guess.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
