<HEADER>
A3692 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SAFRICA-EBONY-MEDIA-N     07-16 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-EBONY-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EBONY ENDS PUBLICATION IN SOUTH AFRICA 
</HEADLINE>
  By HENRI E. CAUVIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURBAN, South Africa _ The South African edition of Ebony
magazine, introduced nearly five years ago in the afterglow of the
country's triumph over apartheid, has shut down after failing to
find profits or many readers.
</P>
<P>
   On newsstands around the country, a few left-over copies of last
month's issue are all that remains of Ebony South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Leaping aboard the post-apartheid bandwagon, Ebony's American
publisher, Johnson Publishing, had hoped to bring an institution of
African-American culture to the coffee tables of South Africa, a
country with enormous economic promise but still wrestling with the
legacy of white domination and the struggle for black equality.
</P>
<P>
   But prosperity has been slower than expected in reaching the
black majority. For Ebony South Africa, that meant a retail market
with still too little interest in advertising to black consumers
and a magazine industry with little room for a publication
celebrating a level of success that few black people here can yet
conceive, let alone achieve.
</P>
<P>
   In South Africa, blacks number about 34.6 million out of a total
population of 44.7 million, according to the University of South
Africa's mid-year estimate. But millions of them are unemployed and
the majority of them are poor, a problem that has worsened in
recent years as job losses in government and industry have
increased.
</P>
<P>
   Circulation peaked at 23,880 during the first half of 1999
before dropping to 22,477 during the second half of the year,
according to the Audit Bureau of Circulations South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Even at its highest circulation, the magazine never pulled in
enough advertising, said Christopher D. Benson, a vice president of
Johnson Publishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't see that it was going to improve, and we just had to
make the hard decision,'' Benson said in a telephone interview from
Chicago. ``I think it's a function of the commitment that we had to
the project that we held on as long as we did in the face of
mounting losses.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, according to some industry observers here, the
magazine never quite found the necessary balance of American and
African content.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they were turning out was more of an American Ebony with
a touch of South Africa rather than a South African Ebony with a
touch of America,'' said Fraser Mtshali, the editor in chief of
Bona. Based in Durban, Bona is aimed at black readers and is the
nation's best-selling lifestyle magazine. ``They were seeing South
Africa through American eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebony South Africa's final cover story, on the soccer star Lucas
Radebe, was a revealing example, Mtshali said. Despite his
popularity, Radebe is old news, Mtshali said, and without some
tantalizing new tale about the well-known athlete, there was little
to attract the average South African reader.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the last issue of Ebony South Africa were stories about
the American singer Toni Braxton, the American jazz great Louis
Armstrong and American athletes running into trouble with the law.
There was also a feature on Nelson Mandela and his wife, short
profiles of South African musical greats and a mix of health and
romance items.
</P>
<P>
   Benson, the Johnson Publishing executive, said Ebony South
Africa, which had a local staff directed by an American editor and
took some of its articles from the American edition, tried to
capture the interests and nuances of the South African audience.
``We were constantly evaluating it, through readership surveys, to
find out what readers were looking for,'' he said. ``I think the
magazine reflected that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bona, which is published in English as well as in three
indigenous languages, is looking for the same successful,
free-spending black people in their late 20s and early 30s that
Ebony South Africa was aimed at. But Mtshali said his magazine also
tried to embrace younger and older readers as well.
</P>
<P>
   The cover of the July issue of Bona advertises stories on
``Soccer's New Heroes,'' a ``Wake-up Call From God'' for a South
African singer and a ``Baby That Took Five Years to Be Born.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our market is broader,'' Mtshali said. ``We're more family
oriented.'' And yet, even Bona, which has been around for more than
four decades, has watched its circulation fall to just under
178,000 during the second half of last year, compared with 271,230
four years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   With the economy growing only modestly here, the media sector is
struggling to hold onto what share of the market it already has.
</P>
<P>
   Tribute, a 13-year-old glossy that aims for the same affluent
audience that Ebony South Africa was going for, has seen its
circulation drop from just over 16,000 in 1994 to slightly more
than 10,000 during the second half of last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's been the kind of black aspirational
success that had been hoped, and that has to have had an effect on
publishing,'' said Kerry Swift, who in the late 1970s was an
executive editor of Drum, a magazine that made its name as the
literary conscience of the struggle against apartheid.
Subsequently, Drum became a more conventional lifestyle magazine
that now has a weekly circulation of about 137,000 _ down several
thousand from its heyday 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market really hurts,'' said Swift, who is now a director
for Core Media Holdings, a South African company that publishes the
local editions of publications like PC, an American computer
magazine owned by Ziff-Davis. ``But I think there are much deeper
cultural factors at work, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
