<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3699 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CANADA-TORNADO-NYT     07-16 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-TORNADO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RADIO WARNED OF STORM MINUTES BEFORE DEADLY TORNADO STRUCK 
</HEADLINE>
  By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta _ A tornado on Friday that hit a lakeside
trailer campground 125 miles south of here was probably so deadly
because the campers did not hear storm warnings and could not see
the storm coming, Canadian officials said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The tornado at dinnertime Friday obliterated the campground with
winds of almost 200 mph. The death toll was raised to 10 Sunday
with the death of one camper who had been hospitalized. The dead
included a 2-year-old child.
</P>
<P>
   ``A trailer park like this offers absolutely no protection in
the winds of a tornado, set down in a valley where it is difficult
to see the storm approaching, and the trailers are very weak
protection,'' Dennis Dudley, an official of Environment Canada's
Calgary office, said at a news conference Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Dudley happened to be driving north from Calgary on vacation
with his family Friday evening when he spotted the threatening
weather formation and called in a warning.
</P>
<P>
   Divers searched Pine Lake on Sunday, looking for the bodies of
fishermen who may been tossed from their boats when the storm hit.
The search was complicated by low visibility. Military and police
divers also searched 60 trailers that were blown into the lake by
the storm.
</P>
<P>
   The storm injured at least half of the 300 people who were in
the private campground, sending 132 to local hospitals for
treatment, many for broken bones.
</P>
<P>
   The tornado was Canada's deadliest since July 1987, when a
tornado struck Edmonton, killing 27 people, injuring 300, and
causing $230 million in property damage. Alberta usually
experiences 16 to 20 tornadoes a year, but most are relatively
weak.
</P>
<P>
   Although a severe thunderstorm warning, with a potential for
tornados, had been issued about 40 minutes earlier, the campers
apparently had not heard the warnings on the radio, officials said
Sunday. Most were sitting down for their evening meal when the
storm suddenly roared over a hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hailstones started falling,'' Harold English, a camper, told a
local reporter. ``The wind came up and trees started breaking _
some 8 inches thick _ near our trailer. Within two minutes it was
all over.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Lapreirie, who was camping Friday with his wife, had
stitches on his face and his arm in a sling on Sunday. ``After this
thing hit, I jumped into my trailer as it was going by,'' he said.
``It was moving when I got in _ I knew my wife was in there. I
happened to get inside, and the next thing you know it's upside
down, around, then we hit the dirt.''
</P>
<P>
   Some campers were blown into the lake. Searchers believe that
most of them were able to swim ashore, but the search of the lake
is to continue through Monday.
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived at the campground and saw the destruction,
Dudley, the environmental official, said his first thoughts were of
his father-in-law, who almost died in the 1987 Edmonton tornado.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't hit me until I saw a little girl's shoe in the
sand,'' he said. ``I wish I could turn the clocks back and tap
everyone on the shoulder and say, `Get out, leave this area, this
is not safe.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
