<DOCNO> NYT20000716.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3704 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-E-COMMERCE-COLUMN-NYT     07-16 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-COMMERCE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANIES ARE SEEKING RECIPROCAL DEALS TO ATTRACT CUSTOMERS 
</HEADLINE>
  By BOB TEDESCHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before the fat lady began singing for Internet retailers in
nearly every category, the term ``customer acquisition costs''
meant little to most Web merchants. It was common to spend $100 or
more chasing down a customer, even though that person might never
buy enough in a lifetime to return the $100.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, e-tailers recognize customer acquisition numbers as
one of the vital signs they will have to monitor with the
watchfulness of an intensive care nurse if they are to survive
their brushes with fiscal mortality.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows what customer acquisition number will ultimately
work for most Internet merchants, but it is safe to say that the
figure is a lot closer to zero than the current industry level of
about $80. Fortunately, a marketing technique that is not widely
practiced in the bricks-and-mortar retail world is providing hope.
Known as reciprocal marketing, it allows companies to offer their
paying customers discounts at other online retailers. Despite
potential pitfalls, many of the merchants involved in these
programs say they have been able to attract new customers at little
expense.
</P>
<P>
   To the consumer, these efforts look a bit like chain-letter
e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Spend $40 at eToys, for instance, and get a gift certificate for
$10 at Gap.com. Spend $40 at Gap.com and get a $10 gift certificate
at ProFlowers.com. And so on. The number of Internet merchants
using reciprocal marketing is not yet large enough to link a broad
array of e-tailers together. But the increasing consolidation of
the e-tailing market and the growing popularity of the reciprocal
programs could eventually make them pervasive.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, ProFlowers.com, an online florist, will probably
expand its reciprocal marketing program to include companies other
than Gap.com, said Steven Bellach, the company's chief marketing
officer. ``These kinds of deals are the way the Internet will be
working, going forward,'' Bellach said. ``The beauty of it is that
no cash changes hands'' between the merchants, he said. ``And you
get people when their wallets are still open.''
</P>
<P>
   In the ProFlowers and Gap.com program, customers who made a
purchase of any size from ProFlowers this spring received $10 off
of any purchase at Gap.com. Customers of Gap.com who spent $40 or
more received a discount of $10 from ProFlowers. As with many other
companies engaged in such programs, ProFlowers and Gap sent
follow-up e-mails to their customers, including a coupon number for
redemption at the other site.
</P>
<P>
   ProFlowers saw the effort as a way to increase sales _ in that
case, Mother's Day sales. But the company had other uses for the
program. Because flower orders for Mother's Day typically come in
on the Friday before the holiday, and because a flood of 11th-hour
orders would cripple the delivery system, Bellach said, the company
gave the Gap.com discount only to customers who ordered from the
ProFlowers.com site in time for a delivery no later than the
Thursday before Mother's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Bellach declined to share specifics about the number of
deliveries diverted to Thursday or before, ``but the program was
very successful for us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   E-tailers who engage in reciprocal marketing deals said choosing
a partner was the most difficult part. Merchants said they
typically searched for companies outside their category, of course,
but with well-known and highly regarded brands, with extensive
customer-service capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are trying to build as many relationships with
retailers as they can, but there's a very fine line,'' said Lloyd
Cheu, vice president for strategic planning at VitaminShoppe.com,
an online seller of health supplies, which has a reciprocal
marketing program with BarnesandNoble.com (www.bn.com). ``You have
to be very careful about how you share the customer with other
people,'' Cheu said, ``and what happens to them on that other
site.''
</P>
<P>
   Cluttering the home page of a site with discounts to a dozen
other retailers could also be risky, executives said, as customers
could begin confusing the company with an online mall. Cheu said
his site would soon be able to tailor the offers of other companies
to a customer's buying habits on his site.
</P>
<P>
   Such tailored offers will enable reciprocal marketing agreements
to become much more useful to consumers, said Carrie Johnson, an
analyst with Forrester Research, an Internet consulting firm.
``What will be neat is if you buy a book about gardening at
BarnesandNoble.com, and get a link to ProFlowers.com to buy the
kind of flowers you bought the book about,'' she said. ``At that
point, these companies will be serving a complete need, not just
dumping off the consumer to other retailers.''
</P>
<P>
   Carl Rosendorf, senior vice president of BarnesandNoble.com,
said the company could not yet aim its offers with such precision.
But he said the reciprocal marketing effort, which began in
January, was evolving in other ways.
</P>
<P>
   BarnesandNoble.com actually has two separate programs _ one on
its Internet site, and one on its bookselling service on America
Online. In both cases, customers who complete their orders are
greeted with a page showing discounts available at eight Internet
merchants.
</P>
<P>
   Merchants on the BarnesandNoble.com Web site pay nothing for the
privilege, but must deliver an agreed-upon number of their own
customers to the BarnesandNoble site. Under the AOL arrangement, by
contrast, BarnesandNoble charges participating merchants $55 for
every 1,000 customers who see the offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been an absolute grand slam home run for us,''
Rosendorf said. ``There's a waiting list of companies that want to
get on with us.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the company would begin using the pay-per-thousand
approach on its own Web site this fall.
</P>
<P>
   With a few exceptions, reciprocal marketing agreements have made
little headway among traditional retailers. One reason, executives
said, is that it would be difficult to monitor a co-marketing
program in 1,000 stores around the nation, with store managers who
might not be thrilled to take up valuable counter space with offers
from other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Online retailers say they were not eager to pursue agreements
with off-line merchants for the same reason. But at least one such
relationship, between eToys and Gap stores, has paid off. The
companies have completed two such programs since November, with the
eToys.com site featuring offers to Gap and Gap.com, and Gap.com and
Gap stores returning the favor.
</P>
<P>
   Notably, the Gap stores displayed signs in key store locations,
including the cash register. Janine Bousquette, the chief marketing
officer for eToys, said there were few problems in conducting the
program. ``One of the reasons we chose them was that they run a
high-quality, disciplined in-store operation,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A Gap spokeswoman declined to comment on its co-marketing deals.
And Bousquette would not disclose statistics about the effort,
which she said tracked traffic, customer acquisition and the rate
at which visitors made purchases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both felt that it was a very efficient way to drive
business,'' Bousquette said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-00 1840EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000716.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3706 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BOX-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     07-16 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: HIS NAME IS LEWIS, NOT LOUIS (OR ALI)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Even before Lennox Lewis' second-round demolition of
Frans Botha, the heavyweight champion was spreading the gospel of
his greatness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am head and shoulders above everyone else,'' Lewis told
anyone who would listen. ``In the past people like Muhammad Ali and
Joe Louis have reigned in the same way. I have served my time and I
deserve to be up there with Louis and Ali.''
</P>
<P>
   Up there, in other words, with the best heavyweight champions
ever.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, champ, but you've rushed to judgment _ your own judgment.
Your name is Lewis, not Louis (or Ali). You're good, you're the
undisputed heavyweight champion, but you're hardly up there with
Joe Louis and Muhammad Ali just yet. Or up there with Rocky
Marciano, Jack Dempsey and Jack Johnson. Or even up there with Joe
Frazier and Larry Holmes .
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Ali began shouting, ``I am the greatest of all
times'' nearly four decades ago, it's been fashionable for boxers
to proclaim their greatness, no matter what their weight division.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, Lewis is just talking the way boxers talk
now, but he doesn't have the resume to justify it. His 37-1-1
record includes a conquest of only one undisputed heavyweight
champion, Evander Holyfield, although many credit him with another
triumph over Holyfield instead of their debatable draw at Madison
Square Garden early last year.
</P>
<P>
   But other than Holyfield, who has Lewis beaten? Up to now, he's
just the best of a bad lot.
</P>
<P>
   Botha was a typical foe. Staggered by Lewis' overhand right in
the first round, the South African crumpled through the ropes when
battered by a lethal left jab-right hand-left uppercut-right hand
combination near the end of Saturday night's second round. He
crawled back into the ring but the referee, Larry O'Connell, wisely
waved his arms.
</P>
<P>
   The World Boxing Council and International Boxing Federation
champion's other title victims include such forgettable names as
Michael Grant, Zeijko Mavrovic, Shannon Briggs, Andrew Golota,
Henry Akinwande, Ray Mercer, Tommy Morrison and Oliver McCall
(reversing Lewis' only loss, a second-round knockout by McCall in
1994 in London).
</P>
<P>
   For Lewis to put himself on a pedestal next to Joe Louis and
Muhammad Ali shows that he hasn't studied the names on the dance
card of either champion, especially Ali's card. Ali stopped Sonny
Liston twice, tortured Floyd Patterson and Ernie Terrell, lost a
15-round decision to Frazier but later beat Frazier twice, and
knocked out George Foreman.
</P>
<P>
   The young Joe Louis lost to Max Schmeling, just as the young
Lennox Lewis lost to McCall, but Joe Louis later wrecked Schmeling
in a first-round knockout. Louis fought everybody and anybody on
what was known as his ``Bum of the Month'' tour. In a friendly
conversation with Louis years later, Ali teasingly asked him to
talk about that ``Bum of the Month'' tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'da been on it,'' Louis said.
</P>
<P>
   For all of Ali's dazzle, most boxing old-timers who saw both
Louis and Ali at their best believe that Louis was better with a
better punch, that if Louis and Ali had ever fought at their best,
Louis would have knocked out Ali.
</P>
<P>
   And as inconsequential as most of the names on Lennox Lewis'
dance card have been, the names aren't about to get any better.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' next opponent, in a mandatory IBF title defense, will be
the world-renowned David Tua in November, possibly in Toronto.
Lewis' promoter, Panos Eliades, also is talking about another
London title bout next year with Wladimir Klitschko, the
6-foot-7-inch Russian heavyweight who battered Monte Barrett in a
seventh-round knockout on the undercard Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   And with Eliades professing to offer Mike Tyson $30 million to
challenge Lewis, who surely would earn as much if not more, there's
too much money involved for that fight not to materialize sooner or
later _ as long as Tyson is at large. Even if he's banned in both
Britain and the United States, he'll get a license somewhere in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look on Tyson as a disease,'' Lewis said, ``and I'm the
cure.''
</P>
<P>
   After Tyson's recent 38-second knockout of Lou Savarese, he
challenged Lewis in a snarling harangue but then backtracked,
saying he wasn't ready for a title bout. He is expected to fight
Golota next but Botha, who dominated Tyson for four rounds before
Tyson's one-punch knockout early last year in Las Vegas, compared
Lewis' power with Tyson's power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tyson hit me with a punch I didn't see,'' Botha said. ``Lennox
has that long reach; if he can keep Tyson on the outside, he can be
victorious.''
</P>
<P>
   But even a quick knockout of a tempestuous Tyson wouldn't put
Lennox Lewis on a pedestal next to those where Joe Louis and
Muhammad Ali are perched. He needs to do a lot more. And say a lot
less.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
