<SLUG> BC-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE PLANS POST-CONVENTION CRUISE TO VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ohio, Mich., Wis., Ill., Mo., Calif.)   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore plans to ply the Mississippi
River and the Great Lakes in a boat after the Democratic convention
in Los Angeles next month, campaign officials said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The water route will take Gore on a political showboat through
the industrial Midwest and some of the most contested states in the
November election. It is not clear where the boat tour would start,
but Gore and his floating entourage are expected to make stops in
Ohio, Michigan, Wisconsin, Illinois and Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to try to take advantage of the momentum _ or
``bounce'' _ that presidential candidates traditionally gain after
their conventions and a week of trumpeting their own horns without
interruption. The formula was a huge success for Bill Clinton and
Al Gore after the 1992 convention, when they hopped on a bus
together with their wives and roared across small-town America _
and secondary media markets _ where presidential candidates seldom
visit in the heat of a campaign.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Democratic convention runs from Aug. 14 though Aug.
17, putting the boat trip in one of the deadest news cycles of the
year. That means that Gore will probably not face much competition
from other news events for attention, but it also means that many
voters will be on vacation and tuned out of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gore advisers said that in any case, they expected the trip to
yield upbeat pictures of a relaxed candidate talking with real
people in the heartland. Such events can generate enormous and
generally positive local media coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Gore aides said it was unclear whether Gore's vice presidential
nominee would accompany him on the boat trip. If that person has a
connection to any of those Midwest battleground states, a joint
appearance would be likely. But Gore has remained mum on whom he
may pick or when he may announce the name.
</P>
<P>
   But the Gore camp is looking to the next several weeks as its
chance to try to catch Gov. George W. Bush of Texas in the polls.
There is talk, officials said, of Gore's announcing his vice
presidential selection in early August in an attempt to cut into
the bounce that Bush is expected to receive from the Philadelphia
convention, which starts July 31.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will try to build on the stir after his announcement of a
running mate with a pre-convention swing that takes him into Los
Angeles, but the details of that have yet to be worked out and will
depend heavily on whom he names as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign has been looking to this period as a time for
Gore to seize the attention, energize his supporters and establish
himself as his own person. Because Gore has had difficulty
establishing his own identity apart from President Clinton, the
Gore team has scheduled Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton to speak
on the convention's opening night. It then intends to devote the
remaining days to Gore and his personal biography.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Gore camp intended to get the Clintons, who are
perceived as the party's biggest celebrities, out of the way in one
fell swoop Monday night, a Gore aide said: ``The convention's
purpose is to focus on Al Gore's agenda.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
