<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, July 17, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sunshine will be more plentiful across the interior Northeast as
the low pressure system that has held steady over the region
departs into the Atlantic. Afternoon thunderstorms will still occur
in a few spots, especially near the Catskill and New England
mountains. The Southeast will stay partly sunny and hot with
isolated afternoon thunderstorms.
</P>
<P>
   A cluster of thunderstorms will dampen the central Plains Monday
morning as a flow of sultry air intercepts a stationary front.
These storms will then march southeastward, bringing heavy rain to
eastern Kansas and Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: WORD GAMES
</P>
<P>
   Weather forecasts across the Northeast this past weekend gave
considerable mention to two words: showers and thunderstorms. The
computer guidance that forecasters used to make their predictions
for the upcoming weekend had indicated that an unusually cool low
pressure system aloft would move over the region. High-altitude
chill in the summertime renders the atmosphere unstable, and thus
increases the risk for heavy thunderstorms. While portions of the
Northeast did receive copious rainfall on Saturday and Sunday, most
places actually had long stretches of rain-free weather. For those
who experienced a long rain-free period, the forecast, which called
for ``showers and thunderstorms,'' appeared to be faulty. Perhaps a
better-worded forecast would have read ``scattered showers and
thunderstorms but dry for much of the time.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
