<P>
   WEEKEND DUTY EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   IN ATLANTA: Diane Fall at 404-526-7282
</P>
<P>
   IN WASHINGTON: Art Dalglish at 301-460-6176 (home) or
301-996-3036 (cell phone).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-SUMMIT _ THURMONT, Md. _ Spot coverage of the final
status peace talks between Israel and the Palestinians, as they
kick back into high gear following a day off for the Sabbath. The
talks still focus on three issues: the future of Jerusalem; borders
of a Palestinian state; and fate of millions of Palestinian
refugees around the world. Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Expected to move on the NYT Wire in both International and
Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-IVILLAGE _ SANGPO VILLAGE _ In the words of a local
official, Sangpo Village was once a ``poor, backwards, uneducated''
speck in central China. Now, thanks to a thriving business in
sheepskin processing, it boasts private cars, cell phones and yes,
Web surfers. A look at how this village of 5,000 people got so
rich, and so wired. (Chao, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH PHOTO. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-SURPLUS _ Texas state officials rush budget estimates
showing a surplus for the state in an effort to aid Bush's
presidential campaign. (Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   CONVENTION _ LOS ANGELES _ When 4,300 party delegates begin
arriving here in about two weeks for the Democratic National
Convention, they'll book their meetings with each other online with
an Internet scheduling program. From the floor of the Democratic
National Convention, they'll be able to talk the their colleagues
on the other side of the massive Staples Center with Internet
phones or by email at kiosks throughout the building. Back home,
folks can submit party platform ideas by email, and watch every
second of the convention with Web cameras connected to the party's
extensive Internet site. Democrats are touting their Aug. 14-17
convention as the most technologically advanced ever, and _ like
the Republicans _ are relying on the Internet like never before to
get their message out. ``It's really all about providing better
access for the American people,'' said convention CEO Lydia
Camarillo. But it's also about reaching out to a new breed of
potential voters that parties can't reach through CSPAN or CNN -
and closely controlling the message they get. (Keefe, Cox News
Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   With box listing some bells and whistles and photo of workers at
Staples.
</P>
<P>
   ALLIANCE _ As trial lawyers across the country pour money from
the tobacco settlement into election efforts against Gov. George W.
Bush and other Republicans, Florida's leading pro-business lobby is
mounting a unique campaign to stop the tobacco-rich trial lawyers
here from unseating its allies in the state House and Senate. The
influential lobbying group, Associated Industries of Florida, isn't
relying on the state Republican Party for help. Instead, it has
created a for-profit corporation that can sidestep campaign finance
laws, raising as much money as it wants and spending as much it
wants and all in secret. (Palm Beach Post) 25
</P>
<P>
   CHOOSE-PLATES _ The ``Choose Life'' license plate campaign
signed into law by Gov. Jeb Bush last year but tied up in the
courts since December, has quietly been picked up by anti-abortion
activist groups in 35 states and passed into law in one. Randy
Harris, the Marion County Commissioner who came up with the idea
for the specialty plate in 1996, said the national media attention
focused on the protests and lawsuit surrounding the plate triggered
hundreds of calls from anti-abortion activists from around the
country and motivated dozens to launch campaigns of their own.
(Palm Beach Post) 30.
</P>
<P>
   HAITI-CANDIDATE _ Bonivert Claude is running for president of
Haiti. Forget that few Haitian political observers have heard of
him and that most predict Jean Bertrand Aristide will steamroll his
way back into office. And ignore that his campaign consultant, who
lives in West Palm Beach, has never been to Haiti and has never run
a candidate for office larger than state senate (of Florida). Those
potential setbacks pale in comparison with his biggest obstacle to
leading the Caribbean nation: He lives in Aventura, a Miami suburb.
So why does Claude think 6.8 million Haitians want him to lead
them? ``Haiti has been betrayed by its dictators and greed and
theft,'' he told a California audience of African expatriates.
``Given the opportunity to lead Haiti I will restore a sound
economic basis for growth.'' (Palm Beach Post) 40.
</P>
<P>
   INFECTION _ Live coverage of the the International Conference on
Emerging Infwomen's boutique. And it is. But take a closer look at
the items on display and you realize there's more to each one than
meets the eye. All the products are designed to help women as they
move through the stages of their lives. (Moss, Dayton Daily News)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MOSHING-DANGERS _ The dangers of crowd surfing and slam dancing
will be aired in courtrooms here as five lawsuits brought by
injured concert fans head toward trial. The five plaintiffs, one a
wheelchair bound man seated between the stage and the mosh pit,
claim Coral Sky should be doing something to prevent injuries.
Court records show 27 people were injured in mosh pits in 1996 and
1997, when the concerts were staged. Most of the injuries appear
minor although one teenager was hospitalized with a dislocated
shoulder. We also ask, in light of 8 deaths at a recent Pearl Jam
concert in Denmark, if Coral Sky is safe for
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-00 1850EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
