<DOCNO> NYT20000716.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3713 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0717-C     07-16 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0717-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tensions Increase as Mideast Peace Talks Continue
 &HT;    By Bob Deans and Larry Kaplow
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. President Clinton met into the night Sunday with
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, as Mideast peace talks at Camp
David lumbered through their sixth inconclusive day.
</P>
<P>
   In a reminder of the issues and passions at stake, more than
100,000 Israeli demonstrators rallied in Tel Aviv to protest
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak's approach to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   And in Washington, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.,
warned that the Republican-led Congress would not give Clinton a
blank check to pay for pledges he might make to secure a Mideast
peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   `` I think we have to be open to look at whatever they come up
with,'' Lott said during an interview on the Fox television
network.
</P>
<P>
   But, said Lott, ``there are some items that they would ask for
that clearly I don't think the Senate would be inclined to go along
with. For instance, paying for Palestinian resettlement would be of
some concern to Senators.''
</P>
<P>
   While no hard numbers have been discussed, Clinton and his
national security aides have advised Lott and other Congressional
leaders of the likelihood that any Camp David peace agreement would
require substantial U.S. military and economic aid.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have generally agreed that something in excess of $15
billion, over some
</P>
<P>
   period of time, would be expected from the United States, along
with at least that much
</P>
<P>
   from the oil rich states near the Persian Gulf as well as U.S.
allies in Europe and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want Middle East peace,'' said Lott. ``But we'd better be
very careful with how those dollars are used.''
</P>
<P>
   After attending church services at Camp David's Evergreen Chapel
with his daughter, Chelsea, Clinton spent much of Sunday afternoon
huddling with senior Israeli and Palestinian negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart insisted that Clinton still
plans to leave Wednesday for Japan to attend the annual summit of
leaders from the Group of Eight, which takes in the world's seven
wealthiest democracies and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   While it's possible to defer Clinton's departure, the G-8
meeting has imposed something of a deadline on the Camp David
talks. The urgency, said Lockhart, has increased the tensions at
the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody understands the calendar,'' Lockhart told reporters
gathered in this town of 4,400 five miles from the Camp David
presidential retreat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody understands what the issues are and what the
schedule is,'' said Lockhart. ``So I think they understand that an
intense effort is needed.''
</P>
<P>
   By nightfall, Clinton and Arafat were meeting one on one, in the
expectation that they would be joined by Barak later for a working
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to pound out an agreement to end 52 years of bloodshed
between Israelis and Palestinians, Barak and Arafat are focused on
the most difficult areas of dispute between them, including the
question of Palestinian statehood, territory and security, the
future of Jerusalem, Jewish settlers and the issue of Palestinian
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Both face strident political opposition at home from quarters
that fear the concessions their side would be asked to make in
order to reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the difficulties Barak could face selling a peace
accord back home, more than 100,000 Israelis gathered Sunday in Tel
Aviv to protest what many expect will be Israeli concessions.
</P>
<P>
   Centered in Rabin Square, the large plaza where Israeli Prime
Minister Yitzhak Rabin was killed in 1995 by an opponent of the
peace process, the rally was primarily organized by Jewish settlers
from the occupied areas of the West Bank and the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
   Israel captured the territories in the 1967 Israeli-Arab war and
has been handing over land there to Palestinians bit by bit under
the terms of a 1993 peace accord. Many of the settlers may have to
move if Barak yields more land at Camp David, as is widely
expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to influence him to change his plans,'' said
Haya Ledaber(cq), a 26-year-old resident of the Bet El settlement
in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Like other demonstrators, Ledaber fears Barak might go too far
in his efforts to grant Arafat the territory he is demanding to
build the foundations of an independent Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole country will be given away to the Arabs,'' said
Ledaber. ``The settlements will be left under the Arabs without the
protection of the army and the Jews will be pushed into the
ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak has vowed to put any peace accord directly to the Israeli
people in a public referendum, should he strike a deal with Arafat
at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 210,000 settlers in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip, areas populated by more than 2. 5 million Palestinians. The
Israelis were encouraged to move there by the government in order
to stake a claim to the land. Barak vows not to move more than
50,000, though even that could face stiff resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday in the West Bank, Israeli police forced about 30 young
settlers to give up a new hilltop they had staked out without
government permission.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
