<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3717 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-CALIF-VIOLENCE-ART-2T     07-16 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-VIOLENCE-ART-2TAKES(1145)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH L.A. STRUGGLES TO STEM A NEW WAVE OF KILLING 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photos NYT 2,3,4 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DON TERRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Helen Austin was late for work the other day,
something that almost never happens. She spent the morning at the
beauty shop, crying and praying with her hairdresser.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her only son was killed going to work three months ago,''
Austin said. ``She's having a very hard time. She's lost 30
pounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin's eyes were still red and puffy an hour later. In her
hand she held a crushed ball of tissue and a poster announcing a
reward for the young man's killer.
</P>
<P>
   But Austin wasn't just crying for her friend. She was also
crying for her own family _ two of her grandchildren had been
killed over the years. And she was crying for her community of
South Los Angeles, which in the last several months has been
bloodied, along with many other parts of the city, by a new wave of
violence and killing, a scourge that many here thought was fading
fast into the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're starting to see the start of another epidemic,''
said Billie Weiss, executive director of the Violence Prevention
Coalition of Greater Los Angeles. ``It's starting to look like the
early '90s again.''
</P>
<P>
   In more than two dozen interviews recently with teen-agers,
middle-aged ex-gang members, mothers of murdered children, social
workers, elected officials, neighborhood advocates, police officers
and a woman whose disabled brother was shot to death the day before
the interview, people here said they were afraid and baffled by the
rise in violence and just as determined to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no quick fix,'' said Gary Honroe, who speaks to youth
groups about the perils of the streets and has buried a daughter, a
brother and a sister who were all slain in the last decade. ``But
if we don't start today, there won't be a tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   After years of dropping crime rates across the city and the
county, there have been 266 homicides in Los Angeles so far this
year, a 30 percent increase from a year ago. About 42 percent of
the killings have been gang-related, according to the police
department. But no one knows for sure what is causing the surge,
beyond the usual suspects of drugs, gang disputes and too many
bored and desperate young men _ and women _ able to get their hands
on too many powerful weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I know is that it has got to stop,'' said a Los Angeles
City Council member, Mark Ridley-Thomas, whose district has been
hard hit by the violence. ``It seems to be coming on rather
ferociously.''
</P>
<P>
   Ridley-Thomas is pushing the City Council to allocate $5 million
in emergency money to create additional summer jobs and violence
prevention programs, which have been struggling because of lack of
money, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had as many as 13,000 summer jobs in the past,'' he
said. ``Now, it's down to 3,500.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in this booming economy, teen-agers and ex-cons like Melvin
Farmer, 43, say it is hard to find jobs in the inner city, despite
being so crucial in stopping the violence, many people here said.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer has spent nearly half of his life of gang membership and
street crime in and out of prison. The last time was three years
ago. He came out determined never to return and today is vice
president of the National Alliance for Positive Action, a
neighborhood and youth advocate group, headed by the author and
radio talk show host, Earl Ofari Hutchinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been out three years and I can't find a job because of my
record,'' Farmer said. ``I might go two or three days without
eating. There are a lot of temptations out here, but I'm never
going back to that life. It would kill my mother.''
</P>
<P>
   At one of at least three anti-violence meetings held last week
across the city, Los Angeles County Supervisor Yvonne Brathwaite
Burke said finding jobs for ex-cons should be a priority because so
many are beginning to return to the streets after years behind
bars.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of days later, another anti-violence meeting was held
here, this time in the City Council chambers. As dozens of people
filed in last Thursday morning, Anthony Wingate, 46, was being
helped to his chair in front of his building in South Central Los
Angeles. Wingate was partially paralyzed 12 years ago after being
shot in a robbery, his sister, Natalie, said. He liked to sit in
the chair every morning, greeting passersby.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before 9 a.m., a man walked up to Wingate's neighbor,
Clifton Adams, 24, and shot him to death. Then he turned on the
only witness in sight, the crippled man in the chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother couldn't run,'' Wingate's sister said. ``He was
handicapped. He had to be carried to the bathroom. He didn't
deserve to be killed like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, a red candle left on the stoop as a memorial to
Wingate had melted over the sidewalk like blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``That ain't his blood,'' a relative said. ``But that's some of
his brains in the grass.''
</P>
<P>
   Such stories don't faze lanky Kenneth, a 17-year-old who attends
an after-school program for troubled teen-agers called People Who
Care.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always more killing when it's hot,'' Kenneth said. ``I
might get killed myself. Three days back my friend got shot in the
hip. I just know it's a possibility every time I wake up.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth is about the same age as the slain sons of the three
friends who founded Justice for Murdered Children, LaWanda Hawkins,
Vicky Lindsey and Rita Norwood. They founded the group four years
ago because they felt left out of the system and because the
killers of their children were never caught. The group tries to
pressure local police departments to investigate inner city
homicides more aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are therapy groups we could have joined,'' Hawkins said.
``But we wanted something else. We wanted justice for our
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin wants justice for her friend's son. She got some tape to
put the poster up at Save Our Future, a neighborhood life-skills
and employment training center in South Los Angeles where she does
volunteer work. The center was founded by her stepdaughter,
Charlotte Austin Jordan, to honor her murdered children.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's 13-year-old daughter, Jamee, was killed in 1988, a
victim of mistaken identity. She was shot 15 times. ``That started
my crusade,'' Jordan said. In 1996, her 25-year-old son, Corey, was
shot and killed by a 41-year-old gang member. ``Corey had two
children and one on the way,'' Jordan said. ``The baby was born two
days after we buried my son.''
</P>
<P>
   The men who killed her children had been in and out prison since
they were young teen-agers. ``Nothing in prison happens to help
them change,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has a 15-year-old son who asked her, ``Am I going to die
like that, too?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't just say no,'' Jordan said. ``All I could say was
that I will do everything I can to make our community safe for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, she moved her family to the suburbs, ``so my
son could have his childhood back.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As she talked, a former gang member named Hakeem, 29, and his
brother Mookie, 14, came in. Hakeem is the same age as Jordan's son
would be if he were alive and she has practically adopted Hakeem.
He calls her Mom. His own mother was killed in a drive-by shooting
several years ago while he was locked up for a murder, committed
when he was 13.
</P>
<P>
   Mookie is dressed in baggy pants and is wearing a black bandanna
on his head. ``In order to stay out of trouble, you have to change
the way you dress,'' Jordan said to him.
</P>
<P>
   Mookie looked at the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just like my little cousin who got shot in his neck and
his back,'' Hakeem said. ``Now he's paralyzed. He's just 15.''
</P>
<P>
   Hakeem sounded angry and sad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shot and killed someone,'' he said. ``I know violence ain't
the answer. I don't want my little brother to be like me.''
</P>
<P>
   Mookie likes to go swimming, but the neighborhood pool is
controlled by rival gang members. ``First we fight,'' he said.
``Then we swim.''
</P>
<P>
   When his cousin was shot by one of the boys who claim the pool,
Mookie immediately thought revenge. It is the easiest thing in the
world to get a gun in his neighborhood. But he didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of my brother,'' he said. ``He told me it wasn't the
way. And I don't want to get locked up for the rest of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan smiled. At least for a day, someone was listening.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
