<P>
   MARKET-VALUE-ENERGY (Washington) _ With millions of air
conditioners humming this summer, and dire warnings of electricity
running short, a growing number of utilities are using novel
tactics to avoid blackouts and other disasters. Some are offering
cash to companies willing to reduce energy consumption at certain
hours, figuring the payments are less than the cost of providing
power at peak times. Other utilities are paying residential
customers for the right to shut off their air conditioners when
power usage is high, or to set them at higher temperatures.
Electricity has long been sold under a system under which a
kilowatt hour has a fixed price, and you can have as much as you
want until the supply runs out and there is none for anybody. But
now, utilities are pricing power the way almost everything else in
America is priced: by market value. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   1-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `f' category.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Top center: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BUSH (Washington) _ Memo about how Bush, pretty confident, is
adopting a Rose Garden strategy: not breaking a sweat, not making
news. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   1-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `p' category.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Off-lead: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PERU-INNOCENTS (Lima) _ Peruvians call the more than one
thousand people, mostly poor, who were unfairly imprisoned on
charges of terrorism or treason between 1992 and 1995 by special
antiterrorism courts, ``the innocents.'' Most have been pardoned or
absolved of any wrongdoing over the last three years; but their
lives and the lives of their families have been irreparably
tattered. Such injustice was the product of the chaos that gripped
Peru in the early 1990s, when the Shining Path, a brutal terrorist
group bent on creating a radical Maoist state, was in the final
throes of a rampage of bombings and massacres. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   4-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   3-column photo with story.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `i' category.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOLD: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMDEN-TAKEOVER (Camden, N.J.) _ This city, with a population of
83,000, has been functionally bankrupt for more than a decade, kept
afloat with cash from Trenton that now pays for 70 percent of the
municipal and public school budget. Not one residential street has
been repaved for years, and 16 percent of the city's buildings are
abandoned. So last week Gov. Christie Whitman handed the
legislature her Municipal Rehabilitation and Economic
Revitalization Act, which would strip all local power in Camden
away from the mayor, City Council and regulatory and licensing
agencies and put it all in the hands of one person, a chief
management officer appointed by the state. There have been other
takeovers of bankrupt cities and incompetent or corrupt city
administrations in recent years, but Camden's is the biggest of
them all. By Iver Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   3-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `a' category.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-HATE (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ Bernard Kouchner, the
emotional French doctor who runs Kosovo for the United Nations, has
made it through a year of ups and downs that illustrate the
failures, the progress and the strain of trying to bring together
Serbs and Albanians who are divided by the deepest hatred this
world-traveled man says he has ever encountered. By Steven
Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   1-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `i' category.)
</P>
<P>
   3-column photo, floater, local (no story).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOTTOM: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-RATINGS-HISPANICS (New York) _ The struggle over how to count
Spanish speakers in TV ratings is an indication of the rapidly
growing influence of Hispanics on American culture and business. By
Jayson Blair.
</P>
<P>
   2-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   1-column photo with story.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 9 p.m. ET in `a' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-PSYCHOLOGY (Detroit) _ Of all the mysteries facing auto
industry marketers in recent years, few have been so puzzling as
how families choose between minivans and sport utility vehicles. To
look at median income, by age, by occupation, by family size, by
where they live, people who buy minivans and people who buy sport
utilities look fairly similar, the auto makers' research has found.
Yet a growing body of research in the auto industry suggests that
buyers of these two kinds of vehicles are very different
psychologically. Sport utility buyers tend to be more restless,
more sybaritic, less social people who are ``self-oriented,'' to
use the auto makers' jargon, while minivan buyers tend to be more
``other-oriented'' _ more involved with family, friends and their
communities. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   3-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `f' category.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Washington) _ Developments from the Camp David
peace talks. By Deborah Sontag and Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 9 p.m. ET in `i' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-VIOLENCE (Los Angeles) _ In more than two dozen interviews
with teenagers, middle-aged ex-gang members, mothers of murdered
children, social workers, elected officials, neighborhood
advocates, police officers and a woman whose disabled brother was
shot to death the day before, people here said they were afraid and
baffled by the rise in violence and just as determined to stop it.
``There's no quick fix,'' said Gary Honroe, who speaks to youth
groups about the perils of the streets and has buried a daughter, a
brother and a sister murdered in the last decade. ``But if we don't
start today, there won't be a tomorrow.'' By Don Terry.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 7:30 p.m. ET in `a' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-TALK-POLITICS (Washington) _ Bush on ABC's This Week, Gore on
Meet the Press, Buchanan on Face the Nation. By Katharine Q.
Seeley.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 9 p.m. ET in `p' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-TRACK (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Olympic track trials. By Jere
Longman.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 9 p.m. ET in `s' news file.)
</P>
