<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREEN-PARTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREEN CANDIDATE POSES CHALLENGE FOR BOULDER'S DEMOCRATIC
CONGRESSMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOULDER, Colo. _ The residents here proudly recognize themselves
as citizens of ``The Peoples Republic of Boulder,'' a smart-alecky
tip of the hat to Colorado's quirkiest metropolis.
</P>
<P>
   Here, people who own pets are not pet owners, they are pet
guardians. The city council issues proclamations on foreign policy.
Buildings have height restrictions so mountain views remain
unobstructed.
</P>
<P>
   With so many freethinkers, environmentalists and cappuccino
drinkers, all of whom are likely to be wearing Birkenstocks,
Boulder was always considered a last bastion of liberalism and the
center of a congressional district that has sent a Democrat to
Washington in every election since 1974.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the streak may be in jeopardy, and in many respects,
the challenge facing Rep. Mark Udall, who is seeking a second term,
mirrors a problem that Vice President Al Gore has encountered in
his quest for the presidency: Both could lose the election because
of a Green Party candidate siphoning off Democratic votes.
</P>
<P>
   In Gore's case, a strong showing by Ralph Nader, the consumer
advocate, who draws strong support from the left, could swing an
otherwise close presidential election to Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas, the all-but-named Republican nominee. Nader is especially
popular in California, a state Gore could ill-afford to lose and
still win the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But here in the foothills of the Rocky Mountains, where many
Democratic voters feel the party has abandoned them in its
presidential year shift to the center, Ron Forthofer not only
expects to deny Udall re-election in a year Democrats need a shift
of only six seats to regain control of the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am running to win,'' he said, forecasting a result that
would make him the first Green party member to win a seat in
Congress. ``I'm concerned about Udall taking votes away from me.''
</P>
<P>
   In another district, such boasting might be dismissed as
political pipe-dreaming. But here, a steady influx of high-tech
companies has leavened the electorate in recent years, to the point
there are now more unaffiliated voters than those registered as
either Democrat or Republican. Even though President Clinton won
the district with big percentages _ 55 in 1992 and 61 in 1996 _
Udall only squeaked by in 1998 with 50 percent of the vote to 47
percent for his Republican challenger, Bob Greenlee, the Boulder
mayor.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Republican candidate will be chosen in a primary on
Aug. 14. David Baker of the Libertarian party is also running for
the seat.
</P>
<P>
   Forthofer, 56, a retired professor of biological statistics, has
never run for office before. As a longtime advocate of issues like
health care and food safety, and as one of 131 Greens running this
year for municipal, state and federal offices _ including 31 House
candidates from 13 states _ he is echoing themes that Nader has
raised, criticizing corporate welfare, military spending and the
widespread influence corporations have over Republicans and
Democrats through campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   And he is doing it on a shoestring budget. While Udall's latest
report to the Federal Election Commission show that he has raised
more than $315,000 in the first half of the year and has more than
$500,000 in the bank, Forthofer said his campaign expects to spend
no more than $35,000.
</P>
<P>
   For Udall, 49, whose father, Morris, served as an Arizona
congressman for 30 years and whose uncle, Stewart, was Secretary of
Interior under Presidents Kennedy and Johnson, the challenge from
Forthofer has been jarring.
</P>
<P>
   Udall's voting record suggests that they agree on most issues,
and some time ago, he said he pursued Forthofer as an ally, to work
together and galvanize support against the Republican nominee in
the district: For now, two have declared themselves candidates _
Carolyn Cox, a retired businesswoman, and Larry Johnson a perennial
candidate. A third, Sandy Hume, the Boulder city treasurer, could
emerge as a strong write-in choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at my record,'' Udall said. ``Nobody has been better
on the issues, and I asked him to work with me and told him that in
a two-party system, a third party often elects the greater evil.
But it was to no avail.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as Nader said upon accepting the Green's presidential
nomination three weeks ago, Forthofer dismissed the argument that
Greens only pave the way for Republican victories, insisting that
the time was right for all Greens to make their move.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make our own way now,'' he said. ``We've been told
that for how many years, that this isn't the right time. That only
prevents us from finding out how much progress we've made. But as
long as people vote only Democrat or Republican, voices will never
be tallied, and we will never know how strong we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Udall, a tireless campaigner, said that the changing nature of
the district is forcing him to regard no challenge lightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm taking his campaign seriously, and I take the Republicans
seriously,'' he said. ``I'm confident, but I'm not going to take
anything for granted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
