</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-FALDO0717-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Faldo swings back into picture
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ A few months ago it would have seemed
foolish to mention his name before the British Open. Just forget
all the victories in majors, including a masterful title at St.
Andrews a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, Nick Faldo, who went from mechanical to maniacal in the
last three years, would be fidgeting too much to hit enough good
shots this week at the Old Course.
</P>
<P>
   And now there's reason to think he might be in the mix at this
week's British Open.
</P>
<P>
   Despite how things deteriorated for Faldo on Saturday at Loch
Lomond, there's reason to believe his confidence is returning.
Consecutive back-to-back top-10 finishes haven't hurt. He finished
in a tie for seventh at the U.S. Open last month, before tying for
ninth at Lomond.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a remarkable turnaround for a golfer, who for the
past three years, wasn't certain he could order dinner error-free,
let alone handle the pressures of a major championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the next five years, there are 20 majors, and I've got to
believe there's one in there for me,'' Faldo said. ``Everything's
coming back. It's getting better and I feel it's going to happen.
I've just got to be patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Faldo, 43, is a work in progress, but he's not as bad
as Gary Player described last year. ``The guy can't play at all
now,'' Player said.
</P>
<P>
   The words hurt Faldo more than you might imagine.
</P>
<P>
   Faldo started the final 18 holes at Lomond a stroke off the
lead. Then he fizzled. After bogeying the first hole, he
double-bogeyed the second after driving into a gunch, hacking out,
then duffing a wedge from the fairway. That Faldo regrouped well
enough to shoot 73 and a tie for ninth became something of a mental
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how one bad putt and one bad drive can all of a
sudden change the whole atmosphere,'' said Faldo, who has won six
majors. ``It was painful, but all part of the learning curve I'm
on, and there were tons of positives to come out of the week. It
suddenly put the pressure on, but that's what I needed to see. . .
. There seems to be life in the old dog yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Say what you will about Faldo's strange personality _ he can be
either delightfully flippant or rudely cold _ he has never avoided
hard work. He hit 1,500 balls a day and swam laps during his
81-week stretch as the world's No. 1-ranked player. Last year he
finished 151st on the PGA Tour money list; 163rd the year before.
His last victory on the PGA Tour came at the 1997 Nissan Open.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he has changed everything but his fingerprints. He
has a new teacher, Mitchell Spearman, and a psychologist, Kjell
Enhager, who will caddie for him this week.
</P>
<P>
   Although the British tabloids insist otherwise, Faldo says his
recent resurgence has nothing to do with a recent feud with Mark
James, the Ryder Cup vice-captain, whom Faldo wanted tossed off the
team for things revealed in his book on the Ryder Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not fired up because of that,'' Faldo said. ``I'm fired up
because I've got a free run at these guys and maybe for one last
time, for however long, whether it's two months or two years, I'm
back in there and I can scare them and be considered. That's what I
want, to be considered again.''
</P>
<P>
   The low point might have been last year at Carnoustie, when
Faldo missed the cut of a British Open for the first time in his
career with rounds of 78 and 79.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no control and no plan,'' he said, ``and I was
contemplating whether a decision would have to be taken on whether
to go on playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Faldo just worked harder, trying to justify his own
goals and the commitment made by clubmaker Barney Adams, who signed
Faldo precisely as his career crumbled. Already one of golf's
better conditioned players, Faldo stepped up the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been trying to kill myself on the treadmill at home and
secretly I've been watching Tiger and a few of the exercises he's
been doing,'' Faldo joked. ``What are they? They're secret. You've
got to peer through the curtains when he's in the guy and see which
way he does his sit-ups.''
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: Georgia Tech's Matt Kuchar shot a 68 Sunday in the first
round of qualifying at Leven Links, one of four sites, and is tied
for 18th. About 10 players will make it from each site by the end
of today's second round. . . Brad Faxon is tied for third at the
Lundin qualifier on a 67. Gary Nicklaus had a 74.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
