<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3730 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GEN-CYBERSPORTS-LADN     07-16 0378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-CYBERSPORTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANYTHING TO SPARK A CONVERSATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A recent survey among members of SportsDating.com,
a Web site that tries to match boy with girl based on their
interests in athletic endeavors, tried to determine what sporting
event women preferred to go to on a first date.
</P>
<P>
   Think about this before you answer.
</P>
<P>
   About 500 men were asked what game or event they believed their
female dates would most like to attend. Obviously trying to meet
their date's desires, they figured that women's figure skating (32
percent), women's tennis (22 percent), a WNBA game (12 percent) or
women's soccer (9 percent) would do it.
</P>
<P>
   Think again.
</P>
<P>
   About 500 women polled voted 41 percent for a baseball game and
32 percent for a football game.
</P>
<P>
   Is the answer clear enough yet?
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the females responding to the survey stated that they
preferred a spot where they could converse with their date and
still follow the action,'' said Joel Benson, one of the founders of
the site. ``Baseball and football are two spectator sports where
there are enough breaks in the action to permit that.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk among yourselves.
</P>
<P>
   -With L.A.'s official entry into the XFL, might as well reveal
that the best way to inquire about actually playing for this Vince
McMahon-created league is by filling out a questionnaire on the
official Web site (www.xfl.com or go straight to
www.xfl.teamworkonline.com/playerform /).
</P>
<P>
   Be prepared to divulge such information as your nickname, Social
Security number, date of birth, high school and college experience,
medical problems, preference on special teams and the real toughie:
``Rate your true speed: Great, Good, Average, Slow.''
</P>
<P>
   That's your speed, not IQ.
</P>
<P>
   -The International Olympic Committee, U.S. Olympic Committee and
Salt Lake Olympic Committee have targeted more than 1,800
registered Internet domain names that illegally use the phrase
``Olympic'' or ``Olympiad'' or claim to represent associations with
those organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Even those who have misspelled the URLs on purpose - like
www.2004Olimpics.com - are being asked nicely (for now) to cease
operation.
</P>
</TEXT>
