<SLUG> BC-TAPE-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDER A DOMED ROTUNDA, `AURAL ARCHITECTURE' FOR MUSICAL PROTOCOLS 
</HEADLINE>
  By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One goal of the Lincoln Center Festival's Electronic
Evolution series is to demonstrate the enormous diversity of
sound-producing technologies available to composers today:
synthesizers, digital keyboards, sophisticated computer software
and whatnot.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday night's program at the Low Library Rotunda at
Columbia University, the third of five concerts, was devoted to
what could be called the original instrument of electronic music:
the tape recorder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Masterpieces of 20th-Century Multichannel Tape Music,'' as the
program was called, offered six works written between 1956 and
1990, each created by cutting and splicing segments of tape. And
true to the historically accurate protocols from the early decades
of electronic music, the audience at this concert sat passively in
the darkened space listening to works played through loudspeakers.
</P>
<P>
   For this purpose the enormous rotunda, with its domed ceiling
and echoing stone walls, was an ideal performance space: The
audience sat in the middle of the floor encircled by speakers. The
one modern innovation was that each work was introduced with
``electronic program notes'' and accompanied by computerized visual
representations of the sounds being heard.
</P>
<P>
   The program began with one of the first acknowledged
masterpieces of electronic music, Edgard Varese's ``Poeme
Electronique'' (1958). It's interesting that composers during this
period who were most fascinated by the possibilities that the new
electronic technology offered for exploring sound were mostly those
also drawn to the 12-tone aesthetic. So, though Varese's work can
in no way be called a 12-tone composition, its montage of sounds
assiduously avoids tonal references and even regular pulse.
</P>
<P>
   What gives it shape is Varese's keen sense of aural
architecture. Also, unlike so many works that came in its wake,
long episodes of ``Poeme Electronique are strikingly quiet,
restrained and gentle.
</P>
<P>
   Karlheinz Stockhausen's ``Gesang der Juenglinge'' (``Song of the
Youths''), from 1956, combines electronically produced sounds with
the recorded fragments of boy sopranos, representing the youths in
the Book of Daniel who were thrown into a furnace by King
Nebuchadnezzar for refusing to worship an idol. And whenever a
faint, intact snippet of a sung melodic line comes through the
rustling collage of sounds, the effect is deeply touching.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Lansky's ``Night Traffic'' (1990) could not have been more
different. Lansky relishes tonality and consonance. So here the
recorded sound of whooshing cars passing by on highways is
presented against a backdrop of sustained, sweetly angelic tonal
chords. Though pretty, it sounds like some tape of New Age music
for a group meditation class.
</P>
<P>
   After a while pieces for multichannel tape recorder start to
sound alike. For all the ingenuity involved in creating strange
sounds, Jean-Baptiste Barriere's ``Chreode'' (1983) and Denis
Smalley's ``Vortex'' (1982), the next two works on this program,
just ran on and on.
</P>
<P>
   Smalley, who cares intensely about musical form, has written of
using ``attacking events'' to demarcate structural points in his
tape pieces. Such talk seems like so much technobabble. Haven't all
composers, from Bach to Little Richard, used attacking events like
downbeats and accents to indicate new phrases and musical
structure?
</P>
<P>
   At 23 minutes, Iannis Xenakis' ``Bohor'' (1962) also has a
run-on quality to it. But the fascinating sources he drew from to
create this sound montage include a Laotian mouth organ, Iraqi
bell-trimmed jewelry and Hindu chant. Somehow the waves of sound
that flow by, crackling with static and buzz, seem organic. Still,
it must be said that seeing the passing sounds represented in
intricate, multicolored, up-to-date computer imagery certainly made
the listening experience more engaging.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
