<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3734 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-BRITISH-WOMEN0717     07-16 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-WOMEN0717-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Women could suffer in British Open shadow's open
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In any other year, the U.S. Women's Open golf
tournament would be the marquee event of the week. It would have
the highest stakes, summon the most history and attract the
nation's top golf writers.
</P>
<P>
   But this year it begins on the same day as a tournament that
could knock it off the green. The British Open features the hottest
name in golf, Tiger Woods, at the place where golf was born, St.
Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of things kind of conspiring against the
Women's Open on this one,'' said Dave Seanor, editorial director of
Golfweek magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Whether bumping heads with the British causes a headache for the
women's event remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's such a bad thing,'' said Atlanta's Rosie
Jones, who will be playing her 19th Women's Open this week at the
Merit Club, about 45 minutes north of Chicago. ``The British Open
is being played over in Scotland; nobody's actually going there.
They're going to be watching us. It's probably a good warmup for
watching us in the afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said she wasn't aware of the scheduling situation until
last week I think people are going to watch women's golf regardless
of if the British Open is on,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   TOP GOLF WRITERS OVERSEAS
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the U.S. Golf Association, which puts on the
event, and the LPGA are taking a wait-and-see attitude. They point
out that because the Women's Open airs on NBC an hour after ABC
ends its coverage of the British, the women will have the afternoon
to themselves. Usually, the Women's Open competes against a PGA
Tour event.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that it's probably not going to hurt us and could in
fact help us,'' said Rob Neal, the LPGA's vice president of
tournament business affairs. ``The British Open will finish before
we even hit the airwaves, and people will be sort of pumped up for
golf on that day.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the women still have to compete against the men for
attention in the print media. Golfweek's Seanor is sending two _
instead of the usual three _ writers to the Women's Open this year.
He'll send five to the British, with one staffer already in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how it can't have a negative effect,'' he said.
``So many of the primary golf writers will be overseas. I know they
think that with people watching the British in the morning, that
may prime them to watch the women in the afternoon, but people may
be golfed out by then, or even mowing their lawns.''
</P>
<P>
   Most golf beat writers are going to Scotland, although major
newspapers are sending staff writers to the Women's Open. The two
tournaments will vie for a finite amount of space, especially with
football training camps and the U.S. Olympic Track and Field Trials
added to the mix this week, too.
</P>
<P>
   THE WOODS FACTOR
</P>
<P>
   Betsy Hamilton, the director of women's championships for the
USGA, said organizers were concerned about the low number of print
credential applications until a couple of weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our numbers are looking better, but I have a feeling in some
cases we may have lost a few people,'' Hamilton said. ``Last year
after the Women's Open, Golfweek was able to do a huge, huge
spread, along with the front cover. I doubt that we'll get that
this year. Hopefully, we'll get half of it.''
</P>
<P>
   And Hamilton allows that coverage could depend on who's leading
the British. ``If Tiger's in the lead, that could be possibly a
negative for us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The major golf magazines agree that if Woods wins, the cover is
his. But otherwise, they're making no promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Women's Open will get the same coverage it has in bygone
years,'' said Terry Galvin, editor of Golf World. ``Our big
question will be which would be the better story come Monday
morning.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, what if Nancy Lopez wins? Or 14-year-old Naree Song
Wongluekiet, whose twin didn't qualify.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had a run-of-the-mill winner of the British Open, and
Julie Inkster, Karrie Webb or Annika Sorenstam won the Women's Open
in a much more compelling event,'' Galvin said, ``we wouldn't
hesitate to put that one on the cover.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he noted that the British Open would probably have
three or four more pages than the women.
</P>
<P>
   In Sports Illustrated, the Women's Open probably will appear
only in the Golf Plus section, which goes to one-fifth of the
magazine's readers, instead of the main magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take a back seat, no question,'' said SI managing
editor Bill Colson, who is sending most of his top golf writers and
photographers to Scotland. ``When there are two big events in the
same sport going on in the same week, one of them has to suffer.
Unless something extraordinary happens at the Women's Open, it's
going to be the one to suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
