<HEADLINE>
WRITER OFFERS BACKING FOR SIRICA CHARGES  
 A NEW PATRON SAINT OF BOOK PUBLISHING  
 USA MUTTERS `OUCH' TO WWF'S SLAM  
 

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In January, Simon &AMP; Schuster published ``Gone: The Last Days of
The New Yorker,'' by Renata Adler, a former New Yorker critic. In
the book, Adler wrote that Judge John J. Sirica, who supervised the
Watergate trial and who died in 1992, had ties to organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had found that, contrary to what he wrote, and contrary to
his reputation as a hero, Sirica was in fact a corrupt,
incompetent, and dishonest figure, with a close connection to Sen.
Joseph McCarthy and clear ties to organized crime,'' Adler wrote on
page 125, in explaining why she declined to review the judge's
autobiography, published in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   John J. Sirica Jr., the judge's son, requested that Simon &AMP;
Schuster retract the organized crime charge. Simon &AMP; Schuster
declined. A media column and an editorial in The New York Times
raised questions about why Adler did not provide evidence
supporting the accusation.
</P>
<P>
   Adler said she would present proof at a time of her choosing. In
the August issue of Harper's magazine, which arrives on newsstands
on July 24, Adler presents her argument in a 12-page article that
is critical of The Times' coverage of the accusation.
</P>
<P>
   Adler points to the judge's career as a professional boxer and
promoter of boxing events in the 1920s, before he became an
attorney. Adler asserts that professional boxing in this country
``was at the time, and had been since at least 1903, controlled by
organized crime.'' At the time, boxing was illegal in the District
of Columbia, where Sirica was doing some of his boxing. Because
illegal boxing at the time required a large criminal network, Adler
writes, Sirica therefore knowingly had ties to organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   Adler also cites the ownership by Sirica's father of a
barbershop at which the barbers sold liquor to clients during
Prohibition and suggests that Sirica, who was then serving in the
U.S. attorney's office, must have known of his father's criminal
dealings.
</P>
<P>
   Without citing a direct source, Adler writes that the police in
the barber shop's precinct were ``paid off _ and there was whatever
protection was implied'' by Sirica's service in the U.S. attorney's
office at the time. She also raises questions about why the judge,
while still a law student, formed what she described as implausibly
close friendships with powerful Washington figures like the real
estate mogul Morris Cafritz and Milton Kronheim, a liquor
distributor.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the younger Sirica said that Adler had not presented
adequate proof.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take the issue of saying that he had ties to organized crime
very seriously,'' he said. ``To me, that means someone is either a
member of the Mafia or is benefiting financially from their
endeavors. To me, this is a lot of innuendo strung together in an
effort to salvage her reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   Adler could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Lapham, the editor in chief of Harper's, issued a one-line
statement: ``It is a fine essay and a fine piece of reporting.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
<P>
   A NEW PATRON SAINT OF BOOK PUBLISHING
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Time Warner Trade Publishing acquired a book proposal
by Jack Welch, the chairman of General Electric and one of the most
widely admired businessmen, for a record advance of $7.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   That, however, is just the beginning of what the publisher
offered. It also promised a record-breaking marketing campaign,
capitalizing heavily on its ties to Time Warner's Internet,
broadcasting and magazine businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``This goes way beyond anything that we have ever done before,''
said Laurence Kirshbaum, chairman of Time Warner Trade Publishing
and himself an avid fan of Welch. Fifteen executives spent a full
day preparing a 10-page, single-spaced marketing plan to show
Welch. About a third of it was devoted to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner plans an onslaught of online promotion, including
advertisements on America Online Inc., which is acquiring Time
Warner, but extending far beyond AOL. The Internet allows narrow
focusing of advertising, which is well suited to the modest size of
the book market, Kirshbaum said, and Time Warner knows books like
Welch's sell fast online _ Bill Gates' recent book became a best
seller on Amazon.com the day it appeared. Time Warner also plans
special promotional campaigns to sell electronic versions online
and ads on Web sites aimed at human resources managers.
</P>
<P>
   Kirshbaum has plans to take advantage of his parent company's
other media outlets, too. He envisions Welch filming a half-hour
segment in CNN's studios for broadcast over the Web and over
in-store TV networks proliferating at bookstore chains and other
stores.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner's magazine distribution sales force will help stock
copies of the book in nontraditional outlets like Home Depot, and
push for premier placement near the front of the stores. Time
Warner magazines like Fortune may also help promote Welch's book by
holding conferences and seminars featuring Welch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack Welch is our patron saint,'' Kirshbaum said confidently.
</P>
<P>
   _ DAVID D. KIRKPATRICK
</P>
<P>
   USA MUTTERS `OUCH' TO WWF'S SLAM
</P>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Stephen Chao, the USA Cable president, just
can't get a break when it comes to the World Wrestling Federation,
which, after a prolonged court battle, won the right last month to
pull its top-rated wrestling programs from the USA network and take
them to Viacom's TNN and MTV networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I had WWF, I spent time defending the show,'' Chao said
after a meeting with reporters gathered at the Ritz-Carlton here.
``Now, I have to defend the fact that it's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   That defense seems to becoming a full-time job for Chao. Ever
since USA lost the WWF, he and his fellow USA executives have been
denying that losing the franchise would have any real effect on the
network.
</P>
<P>
   Their public optimism has often seemed Orwellian. USA's WWF
editions are regularly the top-rated programs in prime time on
cable, drawing audiences upward of 7 million viewers. Monday
night's ``Raw Is War'' program is the highest-rated show in all of
cable television. No other show does nearly as well for USA, which
is the No. 1 cable network in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   The USA executives have insisted that losing WWF will not be a
problem because: a) they had a backup plan; and b) the show was not
all that valuable anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Chao revealed that back-up plan: Instead of the
immensely popular Monday night program, the cable channel will run
movies. But could they possibly draw anywhere near the same
audiences as wrestling?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not, Chao admitted, but that does not matter. First of
all, he said, USA did not make a large amount of money on wrestling
because it had to split the profits with the WWF. Secondly, he
said, the audience that watches wrestling does not necessarily
watch USA's other shows, so promotional possibilities were limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really an oddball fit for us in the first place,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Chao said network research showed that USA still came in first
place in prime time, even without wrestling, though its leadership
position was ``diminished.''
</P>
<P>
   _ JIM RUTENBERG
</P>
</TEXT>
