<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000716.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3740 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-LEAHY-PROFILE-NYT &LR;      07-16 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAHY-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CYBERSENATOR SEARCHING FOR THE FREEDOMS OF THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Patrick J. Leahy admits it can all become a
little obsessive. When he stumbles out of bed in the morning, his
first destination is not the kitchen for a cup of coffee or the
doorstep for the morning paper. It's to turn on his home computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first thing I do before anything, I flip on the
computer,'' says the man known to his colleagues as the
cybersenator. As the computer warms up, he gets the cup of coffee.
``And then I come back with the coffee, in my pajamas, and I see
what's come in,'' Leahy says.
</P>
<P>
   What comes in? E-mails from staff members in Washington and
constituents in Vermont. Petitions from colleagues in the
international campaign to ban land mines, one of Leahy's favorite
causes. Family photographs that have been scanned into cyberspace
by his three grown children.
</P>
<P>
   He will surf the Internet for breaking news. His bookmarks on
the World Wide Web include sites for the Supreme Court (as ranking
Democrat on the Judiciary Committee, he needs to monitor the
court's rulings), The Irish Times (he has an abiding interest in
the land of his ancestors), and the music group the Grateful Dead
(www.dead.net).
</P>
<P>
   A white-haired 60-year-old grandfather and a 25-year veteran of
the Senate, Leahy is a proud Deadhead, as the cultlike followers of
the band are known. He takes pride in having introduced Jerry
Garcia, the band's founder who died in 1995, to Strom Thurmond,
R-S.C., the Senate's oldest member _ and the senator perhaps least
likely to have heard of Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   Leahy's twin passions for the Dead and for cyberspace came
together last week in a Senate hearing room, as he sat with a
laptop computer and tried to download a copy of a favorite Dead
anthem, ``Touch of Grey,'' as his colleagues on the judiciary
committee watched with amusement.
</P>
<P>
   The download from the Internet site Napster was taking a long
time. ``It went from `Touch of Grey' to `Touch of White' by the
time it downloaded,'' Leahy said, drawing laughter from a packed
audience.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing was called to consider whether Congress needs to
intervene to control Napster, Gnutella, MP3 and other Internet
sites that allow music to be shared freely among millions of fans,
without copyright payments to artists and recording companies.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing's star witness was Lars Ulrich, drummer of the
heavy-metal band Metallica, who complained that his work was being
stolen off the Web. The band has sued Napster for copyright
violations.
</P>
<P>
   Leahy doesn't know how Congress should respond to the issue. ``I
don't know what the solution will be,'' he said after the hearing,
taking a seat in the small office just off the Senate chambers that
he is granted by virtue of his seniority; it has a magnificent view
toward the Washington Monument. ``Obviously artists deserve to be
paid,'' he said. ``But our responsibility in the Congress is not to
stifle innovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not like U.S. Steel evolving over decades. This could
be a brilliant 19-year-old in a college dorm figuring out Gnutella
or some like it. You can't stop it. You couldn't stop it even if
you wanted to. What we need to do, I think, is make sure copyrights
and patent laws actually reflect the new reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Leahy draws a comparison between the arrival of Napster and its
cyberspace kin, and the advent of the videocassette recorder in the
1970s, which was initially described by the Hollywood studios as a
threat to their survival because of copyright violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you can't make a movie without figuring videos into the
whole equation,'' he said. ``Some movies that are real turkeys in
the theaters recoup their money in video.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome, Leahy knows how passionately some fans
feel about their ability to grab music off the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   An e-mail campaign organized by music-sharing Internet companies
jammed his electronic mailbox in the Senate with more than 17,000
messages last week, so many that he had to shut it down
temporarily. ``I got more on this subject than I got on
impeachment,'' the senator said. ``We turned it off because I don't
want to crash the rest of my system.''
</P>
<P>
   In Silicon Valley and the other outposts of the Internet
industry, Leahy is seen as one of the champions of cyberspace
freedom. But the senator knows that his work on the issue carries a
political cost, especially after he led opposition to the 1996
Communications Decency Act and other popular legislation designed
to block access by children to sexually explicit Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   His critics _ mostly outside Vermont, where he remains so
popular that he won the 1998 election with 72 percent of the vote _
have charged that Senator Leahy is siding with pornographers and
pedophiles.
</P>
<P>
   But he is unrepentant, especially about the Communications
Decency Act, and his opposition on the law on free-speech grounds
was vindicated in 1997 by the Supreme Court, which agreed
unanimously that the law was unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Leahy noted that as a state prosecutor in Vermont, ``I sent
child molesters to prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I yield to nobody in the Senate on the First Amendment,''
he said. ``I am not going to vote for a law that is so broadening
that you could finish up closing down just about every library.''
</P>
<P>
   The responsibility for policing the Internet, Leahy says, has to
rest largely with parents, who can purchase software that restricts
access to Internet sites that feature pornography or that promote
racism and other forms of intolerance. ``Maybe parents need to
spend some time with their kids on the computer, figuring out what
they're looking at,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean it is much fun for a politician to stand up
for the rights of those who use the Internet to distribute graphic
sexual images or messages of hate. The fight for free speech and
other freedoms on the Internet can be a lonely one, Leahy says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is in favor of the First Amendment,'' he said. ``But
we'd have a hell of a time ratifying it today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
