<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALTEON-PRODUCTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALTEON PLANS TO OFFER NEW SYSTEM FOR NET 
</HEADLINE>
   By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alteon Websystems, a player in a fiercely contested segment of
the Internet industry, is expected to raise the competitive heat
with the announcement Monday of new technology for managing data
traffic on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Alteon, headquartered in San Jose, Calif., will offer a system
called an integrated service director, which is designed to enable
companies conducting electronic commerce to build the efficiency
and speed of their transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Among the benefits, the company says, will be making encryption
and decryption of online transactions faster, a capability in huge
demand as e-business becomes more commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   A part of the new equipment will be the so-called Akamaizer,
which prepares content to be used on networks assembled by Akamai
Technologies of Cambridge, Mass. Akamai has a worldwide network
that allows companies to distribute material efficiently over the
Internet to farflung users.
</P>
<P>
   When yoked to other Web-switching equipment, Alteon's new
technology is expected to allow companies to process secure
transactions about 10 times faster than other systems, the company
said.
</P>
<P>
   With the announcement, the company will be stoking the
competition in an industry that pits start-ups like Alteon and
Foundry Networks against established networking companies like
Cisco Systems. In May, the industry was rocked by Cisco's $6
billion acquisition of ArrowPoint Communications, the top
competitor to four-year-old Alteon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that allows you to make your online transactions more
efficient will provide your company with the opportunity to have
sales that are greater and more varied,'' said Eric Thompson, an
analyst in the enterprise networking group at Gartner
Group/DataQuest, a research and consulting firm. ``It looks like
Alteon will breathe more energy into e-commerce transactions with
this new technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Anticipation of the new technology, combined with favorable
forecasts on its financial performance, have also breathed life
into Alteon's stock recently. In the last month, the company's
shares have climbed more than 50 percent to close at $112 on
Friday. Alteon said last week that it would surpass analysts'
revenue and earnings expectations for its second-quarter results,
scheduled for this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet would not become what dot-com dreamers want it to
be without a company like Alteon,'' said Paul Johnson, a managing
director at Robertson, Stephens covering the networking and
telecommunications industries. ``With Alteon the type of advice I
provide is, if you own a house, sell the house and buy this
stock.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
