<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBAL-EXODUS-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOBAL CROSSING-EXODUS DEAL SAID TO COLLAPSE 
</HEADLINE>
   By LAURA M. HOLSON and SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A deal between the telecommunications company Global Crossing
and Exodus Communications collapsed over the weekend as the two
companies failed to agree on a price, people close to the companies
said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Executives for Global Crossing had been in talks in recent days
to sell its Web site-hosting unit, Global Center, to Exodus in a
stock swap valued at $7 billion. For Exodus, the transaction would
have allowed it to enlarge its leading role in the hosting
industry, in which companies provide services like security and
high-speed connections for other companies' Web sites. Recently,
Nippon Telegraph and Telephone of Japan entered the market through
its $5.5 billion acquisition of Verio Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Early last week, the two companies agreed on several issues,
including that Global and Exodus would form a joint venture in Asia
and that Global would receive about 151 million shares of Exodus
stock in exchange for Global Center, people close to the talks
said. But as shares of Exodus soared after rumors of the talks
leaked _ up 39 percent for the week _ executives for Exodus wanted
to revise the number of shares. The final offer from Exodus, said
the people close to the talks, was for $6.6 billion in stock, or
about 120 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   Both boards met on Friday, and the deal was not approved.
Executives for Global Crossing, one person said, were concerned
that as quickly as Exodus' stock price had risen it could fall and
were asking for some kind of price protection if that happened.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Global Crossing will most likely proceed with plans to
sell shares of Global Center in a public offering. Global Center
filed documents last month with the Securities and Exchange
Commission to issue tracking stock in the company.
</P>
<P>
   For Global Crossing, which is based in Hamilton, Bermuda, the
possible sale of its Web site-hosting business would have
represented a departure from its earlier strategy of providing a
wide array of telecommunications services to its clients. Global
Crossing, founded in 1997, sells time on its global undersea fiber
optic network, in addition to other activities.
</P>
<P>
   According to analysts, Global Crossing could be preparing to
enter the fray of big telecommunications mergers by shifting the
focus of its operations to make itself more attractive for a
possible suitor. Large European companies like Deutsche Telekom
have shown eagerness recently to expand in the United States, where
Global Crossing is strongest.
</P>
<P>
   Global Crossing reportedly entered into, and then broke off,
negotiations with Deutsche Telekom, Europe's largest telephone
company, in March. And in its own effort to expand through
acquisitions, Global Crossing tried to buy Equant NV of the
Netherlands, a deal which would have given it access to the world's
largest data network. But talks with Equant ended last month after
a series of disagreements between the two companies.
</P>
<P>
   Under the direction of Leo J. Hindery Jr., the chief executive
who recently joined the company, Global Crossing could also be
trying to concentrate better on the niche of providing
international data and voice services over its worldwide network.
Last week, for example, the company sold its slow-growing local
telephone unit to Citizens Communications of Stamford, Conn., in a
$3.65 billion transaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're obviously putting a new coat of paint on the house,''
said Jeffrey Kagan, an independent telecommunications analyst.
``It's another example showing that the sharks are circling the
U.S. telecom industry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
