u a BC-CAMDEN-TAKEOVER-1STLD     07-16 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMDEN-TAKEOVER-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY TO TAKE OVER A FLOUNDERING TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Expands 5th graf. Changes ``83,000'' to ``85,000'' in graf
that begins ``It's like ...'') 
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMDEN, N.J. _ The sewers were backed up at Seventh and Elm
streets again, and pools of scummy liquid had collected in the
collapsing gutters and rutted street in front of the Bible
Tabernacle Church.
</P>
<P>
   It stank.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Heyward Wiggins of Bible Tabernacle was there, talking
about his hopes for his stricken city, now that the state has given
up on Camden's local government and is set to begin the first city
takeover in the state's history, amounting to the imposition of a
benign but absolute dictator. It is also to be the biggest city
takeover in the United States since the Great Depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask people what they want, they would say they want
Camden to be comfortable to live in again,'' Wiggins said. ``They
would say they just want to sit on their front porch without
someone harassing them or sneaking in the back door. They want the
streets cleaned and the sewers fixed. They don't want big things.
They want little things.''
</P>
<P>
   But delivering services, little or big, is just what Camden's
city government has been unable to do. Done in by government
corruption, poverty and the flight of manufacturing industries, it
has been functionally bankrupt for over a decade, kept afloat with
cash from Trenton, which now pays for 70 percent of the municipal
and public school budget.
</P>
<P>
   In this city across the Delaware River from the chiseled,
historic skyline of Philadelphia, not one residential street has
been repaved for years, and 16 percent of the buildings are
abandoned. The high school dropout rate is 50, 70 or 80 percent,
depending on whom you ask, and the infant mortality rate is three
times that of the suburbs whose borders lie less than a mile from
where Wiggins stood.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 open-air drug bazaars are in operation, but there
are only 80 city police officers on duty at one time. In March,
Milton Milan became the third Camden mayor in 20 years to be
indicted on corruption charges.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman toured Camden in 1996 and looked around in
despair. ``I thought to myself, `There's no way you can raise a
child here,''' she said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   So last week, Whitman handed the Legislature her Municipal
Rehabilitation and Economic Revitalization Act, which would strip
power from the mayor, City Council and regulatory and licensing
agencies in Camden and put it all in the hands of one person, a
chief management officer appointed by the state.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature is out of session now, but is expected to pass
the bill with minor changes when it reconvenes in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The manager would have the power to break contracts, ignore
Civil Service rules in hiring and firing, issue or revoke licenses
and direct all appointments and spending decisions. The manager's
only obligation to the public would be to consult with a
state-selected board of local citizens and to hold two public
hearings a year.
</P>
<P>
   The reason, said Ulrich H. ``Al'' Steinberg, director of the
division of local government services, is that Camden's city
government has simply ceased to function.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like quicksand,'' Steinberg said in an interview. ``You
look in the books for something and you find there's no solid
footing. There is paper and there are words, but they are empty.
There's no basis for what they say.'' These days, state agencies
bypass the city government and deal directly with a shadow
government of nonprofit social and housing groups to bring
everything from new housing to day care to health care to Camden's
85,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
   There have been three other takeovers of bankrupt cities and
incompetent or corrupt city administrations in recent years, but
Camden's is the biggest of them all. Michigan took over the tiny
Detroit suburb of Ecorse in 1986; Massachusetts took over the
Boston suburb of Chelsea, population 35,000, in 1992; and Illinois
has been operating East St. Louis, population 39,000, since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Camden is mostly black and Hispanic. The idea of a white
governor like Whitman and a Republican administration in Trenton
abolishing self-government in a mostly minority city resonates in
threatening ways among city leaders. This racial disparity gave
state officials their most delicate task of alliance building
inside the city before they could let the hammer fall.
</P>
<P>
   Gwendolyn A. Faison, president of the Camden City Council and a
black woman, practically levitated out of her seat with anger when
word came, during a recent council session, that the takeover bill
had been introduced.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father was beaten off the courthouse steps in Clinton,
North Carolina, just for asking to register to vote,'' Faison
declared. ``To register! Do they think we are going to give up the
right that my people fought for and died for?''
</P>
<P>
   But it is a measure of Camden's desperation, and of the state's
careful cultivation of local allies, that the city's grass roots
leaders, including black leaders, think exactly that.
</P>
<P>
   On June 13, two major church groups, Camden Churches Organized
for People _ a mixed group of Roman Catholic Hispanic and black
congregations _ and the all-black Concerned Black Clergy filled St.
Joseph's Cathedral with 1,500 city residents to invite the state to
take over their city.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for the grass-roots support, the state agreed to a
manifesto presented by the church leaders that describes the city's
ills and lists timetables for solutions _ such as demolishing 362
condemned buildings within a year, shutting down 200 drug markets
within three years, and working to raise the graduation rate from
Camden high schools to 70 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
