<HEADER>
A3751 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-CYC-TOUR0717-COX     07-16 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR0717-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WBy Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COURCHEVEL, France _ He is a slight man, one who wears a neon
pink uniform when he cycles. He is known for his shaved head and
his bandanas. And he is a terror in the mountain stages, attacking
at random, leaving strong riders cringing when they see him fly by.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian press refer to him as ``Il Pirata.'' And until last
year, everyone called Marco Pantani the top cyclist in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Then Lance Armstrong took that title from him by winning the
Tour de France. And Armstrong, especially after his performance
Sunday, likely will win cycling's most prestigious race again when
it ends in Paris in six days.
</P>
<P>
   But Pantani, the 1998 Tour de France champion, has something to
prove this year. Armstrong may take the eventual glory ride on the
Champs Elysees, but Pantani is stealing the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   The charasmatic Italian won stage 15 Sunday with a powerful trek
over 107.5 miles. The route, lined by thousands of rabid fans,
featured two climbs that were so difficult they were beyond
classification. Pantani made his last attack on the longest ascent
of the Tour, riding 13.7 miles uphill into Courchevel, a ritzy ski
town high in the Alps.
</P>
<P>
   While most cyclists wave wildly and blow kisses to heaven when
they cross the finish line for a career-making Tour stage win,
Pantani gave only a slight wave Sunday afternoon when he finished
his ride. It was his second stage win in the past four days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much more satisfying to finish alone,'' Pantani said.
``There's a different taste to victory when you leave everyone
behind. It's the taste of triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the best Pantani today, but I'm not far away.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, meanwhile, remained zero for 15 in stage wins, but
his fourth-place finish Sunday allowed him to pick up valuable time
over Jan Ullrich, the German rider who basically has the only
chance of catching him.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong picked up 2 minutes and 32 seconds on Ullrich to give
him a commanding 7:26 lead over his nearest competitior coming into
today, the Tour's final rest day. To put that lead in perspective,
Armstrong won last year's event by 7:21 over Alex Zulle, and that
margin of victory was the fourth-largest in the past 20 Tours.
``There's still one week left to race,'' Armstrong said. ``I refuse
to say that I've won until I arrive in Paris. To say here and now
that I've won wouldn't be fair to the others.''
</P>
<P>
   Pantani, who didn't fare well in the Tour's earlier, flatter
stages, moved into seventh place Sunday, when he finished the stage
in 5 hours, 34:46 minutes. He still was 9:57 behind Armstrong,
although he has come from 25th to seventh place in the past week.
</P>
<P>
   Pantani finished 41 seconds ahead of Jose Maria Jimenez on
Sunday, with Roberto Heras and Armstrong finishing third and
fourth, although each was 50 seconds behind Pantani.
</P>
<P>
   Pantani's career has been clouded by drug allegations. He faces
charges of sports fraud in his home country, based on two blood
tests that showed his percentage of red blood cells to be
abnormally high, suggesting the use of EPO, a banned blood booster.
In 1999, Pantani was suspended from the Giro d'Italia a day before
the race concluded. At the time of his suspension, he was
dominating the competition. He then announced that he would not be
competing in the 1999 Tour de France because it's route was too
flat.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, Pantani returned to competitive cycling.
</P>
<P>
   Ullrich, who has been in second place in the Tour standings for
the past week, was 15th Sunday, 3:21 behind Pantani. Ullrich's
disappointing effort allowed Spain's Joseba Beloki to close to
within two seconds of the German, who won the 1997 Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Pantani and Armstrong seemingly have formed a bond in the past
week, with the American and the Italian riding together in key
stretches in the mountains. The same happened Sunday, but Pantani
left Armstrong with about nine miles remaining in the stage.
Pantani then made up ground on Jimenez, passing the Spainard with
just under two miles remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armstrong is very difficult to drop,'' Pantani said. ``But
today I did it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hold Armstrong in very high regard. I'm not saying that to
flatter him because that's not my way.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
