<HEADER>
A3756 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-GLF-BRITISH-OPEN-2TAK     07-16 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-OPEN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS PREPARES IN COOL AND QUIET SOLITUDE FOR HIS GRAND SLAM
QUEST  
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tiger Woods knows golf history. He knows golf has been played at
St. Andrews, Scotland, for centuries. He knows he could make
history at St. Andrews, becoming the first person to win all four
major tournaments _ the career Grand Slam _ by age 24. He knows
that nobody has won the U.S. Open and the British Open in the same
year since 1982, when Tom Watson did it.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing all that, and knowing he annihilated the field last
month at the United States Open, Woods will begin Thursday's
opening round of the British Open with huge motivation, not only to
win, but also to add to his legacy. And there is no better place to
make history than the Old Course at St. Andrews, often referred to
as the home of golf, where great champions like Bobby Jones, Sam
Snead, Peter Thomson, Jack Nicklaus, Seve Ballesteros and Nick
Faldo have prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   In golf, Woods is used to getting what he wants. And because the
British Open is the one major he does not have, it has become the
major he covets most.
</P>
<P>
   ``St. Andrews is very special,'' Woods said last week before
leaving for Europe. ``To have a chance to complete the career Grand
Slam at the course where it all started is very symbolic. I'd love
to win there. Any golfer would.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody would be shocked to see Woods win at St. Andrews. In
fact, it would be more shocking if he did not contend. Coming off
his record-setting 15-stroke victory at the U.S. Open, Woods enters
the tournament as a huge favorite. And based on his stunning
performance at Pebble Beach, the pressure of being the favorite is
hardly unsettling.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the favorite heading into the Masters, he was the
favorite heading into the U.S. Open, he's the favorite heading into
the British, and no matter what happens, he'll be the favorite
heading into the PGA,'' said Mark Steinberg, Woods' agent. ``Think
about it. When isn't he the favorite? It's part of the deal. He can
handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Old Course at St. Andrews seems to fit Woods' game like a
tailored suit. Depending upon the direction and strength of the
wind, Woods may be able to reach the green off the tee on two or
three of the par-4 holes. He can also fly past many of the bunkers
that come into play for other golfers. Shot-making around the
greens will be crucial, and who has a more creative short game than
Woods?
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the weather plays a significant role at St. Andrews,
particularly the wind, which can change directions whimsically.
Yet, with his penetrating ball flight, coupled with his ability to
work the ball right-to-left or left-to right, Woods welcomes the
wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it howls, all four days,'' Woods said, smiling. ``In
any golf tournament, the wind separates guys who are striking the
ball really well from those who aren't.''
</P>
<P>
   What does Woods think when he hears people say St. Andrews suits
his game? He smiled again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any course suits my game when I'm playing well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, even great players have difficulty winning majors on a
regular basis. Jack Nicklaus won the first of his 18 professional
major championships at the 1962 U.S. Open, and he won his last
major at the 1986 Masters. During that span, Nicklaus won 18 of 96
majors, a winning percentage of 18.7. Starting with his victory at
the 1997 Masters, Woods has won three of the last 14 majors, a
winning percentage of 21.4. And Woods has yet to win two majors in
the same year, which Nicklaus did six times.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus also completed the career Grand Slam at a British Open
in Scotland, winning at Muirfield in 1966, at the age of 26.
Nicklaus had already won the U.S. Open (1962) the Masters (1963 and
'65) and the PGA Championship (1963).
</P>
<P>
   It took Nicklaus five attempts to win his first British; Woods
has already played the British five times. Woods' first British was
at St. Andrews in 1995, where he tied for 68th as a 19-year-old
amateur. His performance at the British has improved as his game
has become more complete. In 1998 Woods tied for third at Royal
Birkdale and last year at Carnoustie tied for seventh.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   To increase his chances of playing well this week, Woods
followed his normal pre-British routine, spending last week in
Ireland, golfing, fishing, relaxing, getting adjusted to the time
change and cooler temperatures. Be wary of Woods after a rest; he
has entered seven tournaments this year after taking at least a
week off, four of those times, he has won.
</P>
<P>
   Since last month's dominant performance at Pebble Beach, Woods
has been working on shots he will need at St. Andrews _
low-trajectory shots, bump-and-run shots, long lag putts that could
be crucial on the spacious greens. Practicing can be almost as
enjoyable for Woods as competing, and he hopes his preparation for
the British Open will yield the same results as his practice before
the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons why I play better after I take time off is
because I can prepare in solitude and peace,'' Woods said. ``When
you're at a tournament practicing, you can't practice the same way.
It's impossible. You can't go out with a cart, play a quick five
holes, test out what you did, then come back to the range.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his worst showing of the year last week, a tie for 23rd
at the Western Open, Woods saw encouraging signs. He drove the ball
well, and his iron play was excellent. John Daly proved how
important length is at St. Andrews by winning the last British Open
played there in 1995. Control is also important at St. Andrews,
however, as evidenced by Faldo's victory in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   But even Woods could be hindered by some of the quirks that make
St. Andrews distinctive. The weather changes so quickly and so
dramatically that golfers are often at its mercy. Calm mornings can
turn into nasty afternoons, and on those days, players with early
tee times have a huge advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There'll be some luck of the draw involved if the weather
fluctuates,'' Woods said. ``That's one of the variables of the
British Open. You just have to deal with whatever you face, don't
let it get to you.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1995 British, Woods shot 74-71-72 but ended with a
final-round 78 in blustery conditions. He is a far better player
now, yet if he draws bad-weather tee times, it will be difficult to
break 70.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played a practice round at St. Andrews where I played 18
straight holes into the wind, just because the tide changed,''
Woods said. ``The tide was going out, then it was coming back in
when we were finishing. That's the way that golf course can play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we got a chance to play links courses more often. It's
so much different than the golf we play here in the States, target
golf, where you're trying to hit the ball an exact distance all the
time. One day at St. Andrews, I hit 2-iron, sand wedge on the first
hole. The next day, on the same hole into the wind, I hit driver,
4-iron. That's one of the reasons why we love that course.''
</P>
<P>
   Scottish golf fans are eagerly awaiting Woods, who appreciates
the astuteness of European fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The galleries over there are so knowledgeable,'' he said.
``Over here, if you get the ball airborne, everyone goes crazy.
Over there, if you have an easy wedge, and you land it on the green
30 feet from the hole, you won't hear anything. But if you have a
long iron into a difficult wind, and you play an approach shot that
lands anywhere near the hole, they'll give you loud applause. They
know how difficult certain shots are, and they have an appreciation
for good golf. It's a great atmosphere. I love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods will love the atmosphere even more should he win. He has a
history of rising to special occasions. And in golf, having a
chance to complete the career Grand Slam at St. Andrews, is about
as special as it gets. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
