<HEADER>
A3763 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-TV-TALK-POLITICS-2TAK     07-16 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TALK-POLITICS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE AND BUSH GIVE VOTERS A SIDE-BY-SIDE COMPARISON 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore and Gov. George W. Bush have
yet to meet face-to-face in a debate, but Sunday they gave voters a
chance for the first time to make a side-by-side comparison as the
two sat for hourlong interviews on network television.
</P>
<P>
   Gore faced aggressive questioning from Tim Russert of NBC's
``Meet the Press'' on his record and past statements, while Bush
was asked questions of a more political nature by Sam Donaldson and
Cokie Roberts on ABC's ``This Week.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither candidate revealed anything about his vice-presidential
selection process. Bush said that while retired Gen. Colin Powell
was not interested in the vice presidency, he might accept another
post. Speculation has centered on secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   The questioning highlighted some stark differences between the
candidates, for example on Social Security, the death penalty and
abortion. The side-by-side comparison also showed that Gore's 25
years in public office have left him not only with a deep
familiarity with issues but also with a lengthy record that can be
examined for its consistency.
</P>
<P>
   The interviews also underscored the political needs of each
candidate as the campaign heads toward the conventions. Bush, who
leads in the polls, seemed content to keep the conversation vague,
a posture that allows voters to read what they want into him. Gore,
on the other hand, has been eager for direct debates with Bush. His
advisers believe that once voters can compare Gore's grasp of
policy and his center-left positions with what they say is Bush's
right-wing bent, Gore will win the election.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the third-party candidates, Ralph Nader and
Pat Buchanan, also appeared on talk programs. Nader said on CBS'
``Face the Nation'' that he was not worried about siphoning votes
from Gore, even if it could cost Gore the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be running if I were worried about taking votes
away from Al Gore or George W. Bush,'' Nader said. ``Nobody is
entitled to votes. They have to earn them.''
</P>
<P>
   On the same program, Buchanan was asked whether Bush might
choose a running mate who favored abortion rights. ``Mr. Bush is
blowing smoke,'' Buchanan said. ``He would have an explosion at his
convention.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore underwent scrutiny of his Social Security plan. Russert
said repeatedly that Gore's proposal was based on a rosy scenario
that anticipated budget surpluses for the next 40 years. Gore said
that his plan would keep the Social Security trust fund sacrosanct
and, by eliminating the national debt by 2012, would help extend
the life of the entitlement program.
</P>
<P>
   Russert noted that the Clinton-Gore budget for 2000 had proposed
increasing the money for Social Security by investing some of the
budget surplus set aside for Social Security ``in corporate
equities or other private financial instruments.'' Russert
described the difference between the two candidates' approaches
this way: ``You want the government to invest in the market; George
Bush wants individuals to invest.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that he did not support that proposal, even though it
was in the administration's budget, and he called it a trial
balloon. The vice president said that Bush's plan for privatizing
part of Social Security would be a ``catastrophe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What he wants to do is to divert 16 percent of the money
that's going into the trust fund and put it into the stock market
now,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Bush has not specified an amount that he would allow
individuals to invest in the market from their Social Security
payroll tax.
</P>
<P>
   Bush seemed deliberately vague and refused to answer whether
under his plan the government would protect individuals against any
losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``A safe return _ the safest of all investment vehicles _ yields
about twice what the Social Security Trust is getting today,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Governor,'' Donaldson said, ``if this were 1929, we'd
probably make the same statement and then those awful years came
forward and people would have lost money.'' Donaldson then
reiterated his question about ``whether you think the government
should make good any losses for retirees.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said, ``There's going to be a lot of discussions about the
particulars of the plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he agreed with the details of one of the proposals
on Capitol Hill to overhaul Medicare, Bush said, ``I believe the
next president must put Republicans and Democrats in a room and
say, `Let's reform Medicare.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also took a pass on whether the Republican Congress should
accept a deal with President Clinton to cut the marriage penalty in
exchange for funding Medicare to cover prescription drugs. ``That's
up to this current Congress and this current president,'' Bush
said. ``What the people need to know about me is that this is where
I'm going to lead the Congress when I become the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Russert also highlighted some of the changes that Gore has made
on various issues over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who favors abortion rights, was asked if he believed that
life began at conception. ``No,'' he said. Asked when life did
begin, Gore said: ``There is a developmental process during which
the burden kind of shifts over time,'' citing the first trimester
of a pregnancy as being different from the third, but not
pinpointing a time when he thought life began.
</P>
<P>
   Russert pointed out that in 1987, Gore had opposed federal
funding for abortions for poor women and had called abortion
``arguably the taking of a human life.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore acknowledged that he had changed his position, saying he
did so about 15 years ago. ``I talked to a lot of women who taught
me about the kinds of circumstances that can come up and the kinds
of dilemmas that women can face,'' he said. ``I've come to the very
deep conviction that a woman's right to choose must be protected
regardless of the woman's income.''
</P>
<P>
   Of a vote that he had cast that would define the term ``person''
to include the unborn, Gore said, ``That was a very odd procedural
vote.''
</P>
<P>
   He suggested, without saying directly, that he would not require
parental permission for a minor to have an abortion. He said that
such requirements have tended to be used as a back-door way to try
to eliminate abortion altogether.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On the death penalty, Gore said he did not support a national
moratorium on it for the 21 federal prisoners who are on death row.
But he said he did support the moratorium on the death penalty in
Illinois ``based on the extraordinary number of errors'' found in
those cases.
</P>
<P>
   Gore had been quoted as saying that with the death penalty,
``there are always going to be some small numbers of errors.''
Sunday Gore said he wanted zero errors but sometimes because of
human imperfection, even jury verdicts ``sometimes produce a
mistake.'' But he said he was unaware of any involving the trials
of the 21 federal death-row inmates.
</P>
<P>
   He also hinted that any state with questionable executions would
do well to consider a moratorium. Bush has said that he was certain
that every execution in Texas had been warranted, that the inmates
had been guilty and had had full access to the appeals process.
Bush said: ``If you ask me whether or not I think we've ever
executed an innocent person, my answer to you is no, I don't
believe so. And I've reviewed every single case.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore was also asked about a recent Supreme Court decision that
said the Boy Scouts could exclude gay members. Gore said he had not
read the opinion and offered none of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Russert posed a series of questions on the investigations into
Gore's financial activities in the 1996 campaign. Gore said that
Russert was ``beating a dead horse.'' Asked if his visit to a
Buddhist temple in 1996 was a fund-raising event, Gore said: ``I
believe it was not,'' adding, ``There was no request for funds, no
money changed hands.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
