<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SRILANKA-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SRI LANKA'S TAMIL REBELS CONSCRIPTING TEENS FOR JAFFNA CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Tamil rebels preparing for a showdown with the
Sri Lankan Army for control of the island's most important Tamil
town have been invading schoolrooms and rounding up boys and girls
in their early teens to send into battle, a Tamil rights
organization said this week.
</P>
<P>
   In a report issued Tuesday, the University Teachers for Human
Rights in Jaffna, the focus of the impending battle in Sri Lanka's
north, describe a reign of terror in the region. They say rebels of
the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam intimidate teachers and public
officials, pull the biggest children out of classes, raid
orphanages and go to homes to demand that families turn over
teen-age sons and daughters. Rough estimates indicate that hundreds
of children, some as young as 9 or 10, are being conscripted.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials here and in Colombo, Sri Lanka's capital, have
condemned the rebels' recent increasing use of child soldiers.
Olara Otunnu, the U.N. official responsible for trying to end the
military use of children, confirmed in an interview that since the
Tamil Tigers began a campaign late last year to recapture the
Jaffna peninsula, the recruitment of children has soared.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the Tigers promised Otunnu to stop recruiting
children under 17 and to stop sending anyone under 18 into battle.
</P>
<P>
   Otunnu said the situation in Sri Lanka showed how difficult it
was to translate international agreements against child soldiers
into action, particularly when irregular forces are involved.
</P>
<P>
   Otunnu said the practice of recruiting child soldiers is
confined in Sri Lanka to the Tigers. He said there had never been
any evidence of recruitment of children by the government army.
</P>
<P>
   Otunnu added that the report from the Jaffna Tamil rights group
was supported by independent information he has collected from
other private organizations and U.N. officials in Sri Lanka. Colin
Glennie, Unicef's representative in Colombo, said, ``We don't have
figures, but we know it's happening.''
</P>
<P>
   For more than a quarter of a century, Tamil rebels have been
fighting for a separate Tamil homeland in northern and eastern Sri
Lanka, an island dominated by ethnic Sinhalese.
</P>
<P>
   Since the mid-1980s, the Tigers _ secretive, ultranationalistic
and radically leftist _ have eliminated all moderate rivals and
raised the level of violence nationwide with suicide bombings and
assassinations. These have decimated a generation of Sri Lankan
leaders from both ethnic groups and cost them some support even
among Tamils.
</P>
<P>
   In December, President Chandrika Kumaratunga survived a bomb
attack that cost her sight in one eye. Under her administration,
the army pushed the Tigers out of Jaffna five years ago, inflicting
bombing raids and retaliatory ground attacks on Tamil civilians,
human rights groups say. The Tigers recaptured the crucial pass
connecting the Jaffna peninsula to the rest of Sri Lanka in May.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels have suffered considerable losses in recent months _
as many as 1,500 dead of a core army of 7,000, the Tamil human
rights group said. They are seeking replacements for the assault on
Jaffna, the group said, and meanwhile feed themselves by by seizing
food aid intended for civilians.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, which is on the U.S. list
of terrorist organizations, raises money to buy arms, often
coercively, from a Tamil diaspora in Southeast Asia, Canada and
Britain, among other places. But, if attempted, the overseas
recruitment of fighters has apparently not been so easy. The Tigers
``needed considerably more recruits to make another attempt at
taking Jaffna. This comes out clearly in its propaganda meetings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Teachers who try to protect the children from recruiters are
marked,'' the University Teachers said.
</P>
<P>
   The group has operated underground since the assassination in
1988 of its founder, Dr. Rajani Thiranagama of Jaffna University's
medical faculty.
</P>
<P>
   The report mentioned torture, public and secret executions and
the chaining of young prisoners to bunkers when they try to leave
the ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Girls have been in a large majority in the current round of
recruitment in schools,'' said the report, which told of a
15-year-old girl who escaped from the rebels and ran home, where
her desperate father hid her and armed himself to prevent her
recapture with the only weapon he could find, a shark jawbone. The
daughter was apparently left alone.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure on children recently has been greatest in a region
known as the Vanni, south of the Jaffna peninsula and north of the
town of Vavuniya. It is the base of the Tigers' leader, Velupillai
Prabhakaran, a reclusive strategist who, the Jaffna group says, has
begun referring to himself as the Sun God. In April last year, he
ordered compulsory military training for schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   The report told of one school where only four children in the
14-15 age group were recruited before April 1999. From then until
early this year, 15 children were recruited. The number jumped to
24 in seven weeks from early May until late June. The pattern in
other schools was similar, the report said. The report figures that
only about 5 percent of child soldiers volunteer; the rest are
taken with varying degrees of coercion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of the 15 who joined between April 1999 and early 2000, the
bodies of six were brought to their school for display before being
laid to rest,'' the report said of the school it profiled. ``This
ceremony is intended to give the dead an aura of heroism and to
make others guilty about not joining.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
