<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3771 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ZOO-ELEPHANTS-NYT &LR;      07-16 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZOO-ELEPHANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZOO HELPS KEEP DOWNTOWN INDIANAPOLIS OPEN BEYOND 5 O'CLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARL H. LAVIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Lesley Mackie, an elephant keeper at the
Indianapolis Zoo, nudged the 400-pound baby aside with her hip. The
baby, Amali, made elephant history with her birth March 6, the
first African elephant ever conceived through artificial
insemination. But on this summer afternoon, she was grabbing a
visitor's shirt with her trunk and chewing on the seam.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a toddler,'' Mackie said. ``Everything goes in the
mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Amali's birth has captured an unusual amount of attention at the
zoo and around town. A name-the-baby contest drew 6,000 entries.
(Amali, an Arabic word meaning hope, was submitted by a local
librarian.) Crowds packed the viewing area for weeks as soon as the
baby made her first public appearance with her mother, Kubwa.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday the zoo held a contest for visitors, to guess the
combined weight of four female elephants. After the elephants
trundled around a small ring, and took turns on a scale (together,
they were just over 29,000 pounds), each strode to the side for
children and grownups to touch the smooth, hard tusks, the supple
leathery ears, and the bristly tufts on the wrinkled gray skin.
</P>
<P>
   These days a world-class zoological achievement is just one more
item on a list of new downtown attractions that are helping
Indianapolis shine. Public and private investment downtown totaled
$3 billion during the 1990s and another $1.5 billion worth of
projects will open over the next two years. Much of the activity
including a minor league baseball park, a new stadium for the
Pacers basketball team, a $14.5 million botanical garden next to
the zoo and a new 165,000-square-foot headquarters for the Indiana
Historical Society came during the tenure of Mayor Stephen
Goldsmith, now a top domestic policy adviser to the presidential
campaign of Gov. George Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``A decade ago, there wasn't a lot of there there,'' said Tamara
Zahn, president of Indianapolis Downtown, a not-for-profit group
that promotes development. ``Downtown kind of rolled up around 5
o'clock.''
</P>
<P>
   The men's basketball Final Four brought the spotlight to town in
the spring, and will return in 2006. A steadier measure of growth
is the number of hotel rooms downtown. In five years it is
increasing from 3,677 to 4,558. Promoters like Zahn like to brag
also about last year's move of the National Collegiate Athletic
Association's headquarters here from Kansas City, Mo. This spring
the NCAA opened a museum on the west side, also near the zoo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The zoo has been an anchor on the west side since they opened
and have done an excellent job of adding attractions and being a
national model,'' Ms Zahn said. ``Amali its one more unique thing
that Indianapolis has to offer. For example, Shaq when he was in
town made a point of visiting Amali.'' Shaquille O'Neal, the
Laker's star player, and other zoo visitors saw an unquestionably
cute baby. They may not have realized that Amali was the result of
more than a decade of scientific work aimed at improving elephant
birth rates in captivity. As the wild populations have dropped
sharply to 500,000 African elephants and to 50,000 Asians, exports
from those regions have grown more and more difficult. The fewer
than 500 elephants of both species in North America have produced
four or five births a year, a rate that will lead to a population
crash in a few decades, according to. Robert J. Wiese, a population
biologist at the Fort Worth Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Elephant bulls can be belligerent during certain times in their
mating season and many zoos hold only females. Transporting
elephants for mating is tricky enough. Theoretically, it is easier
to transfer semen.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the routines of human fertility clinics are touchstones
of elephant artificial insemination trays of blood samples, charts
of hormone levels, files of ultrasound images, worry about the age
and physical condition of the mothers-to-be. Each attempt cost from
$10,000 to $20,000 and depended on precise timing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are not getting your animals bred by the time they are
30 you've sort of missed the boat,'' said Dr. Janine Brown, a
Smithsonian researcher who is an expert on elephant hormones. Her
work, together with advances from other researchers, have made it
possible for scientists to use fluctuations in hormone levels and
new ultrasound techniques to predict ovulation.
</P>
<P>
   After birth, elephants still face many dangers, from indifferent
mothers, to fast-moving viral infections to aggressive acts from
adult elephants that do not know how to act around babies. Ivory, a
three-ton teen-ager at the Indianapolis Zoo, knocked into little
Amali once, sending the baby into shock.
</P>
<P>
   The first conceptions using artificial insemination were two
years ago. The first birth, of an Asian male named Haji, was in
November, at the Dickerson Park Zoo in Springfield, Mo. Amali was
born three months later.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Ivory, has herself been artificially inseminated. Zoo
keepers say she will give birth next month. ``We are very convinced
that she will be a good mother, once the hormones kick in and she
has a baby of her own,'' said Deborah Olson, an Indianapolis zoo
official. Two other pregnancies from artificial inseminations have
been confirmed of an African elephant in Austria, and of an Asian
elephant at the National Zoo in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   This baby boomlet is meant to supplement, not replace, natural
breeding, explained Dr. Dennis Schmitt, an associate professor of
veterinary medicine at Southwest Missouri State University, who
attended the births of Amali, and 13 other elephants since 1985 and
who developed many of the techniques used in the artificial
inseminations.
</P>
<P>
   Zoo elephants pose special reproductive problems, Schmitt said.
``We tend to like elephants in captivity that are round and fat,''
he added. ``That's not what you want; you want an elephant that's
not overweight. We want them to be physically fit.''
</P>
<P>
   In Indianapolis, Amali's mother was on a rigorous exercise
program that included leg lifts and daily walks. Now Ivory is on
the same regimen. Soon another regimen will begin, one that is
likely to bring more throngs of tourists downtown, where officials
hope the zoo will be just one of many stops they will make in
Indianapolis. This regimen is the birth watch, a 24-hour-a-day
vigil for several weeks using video cameras, volunteers and zoo
workers. They will look for rocking, unusual pacing or other signs
that Ivory is about to go into labor.
</P>
<P>
   Ivory's relative youth is a plus, and so is the recent
experience zoo workers gained when Amali was born. But in elephant
reproduction nothing can be taken for granted, especially for
African elephants, which over the years have reproduced more poorly
than the Asians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now getting Africans on the ground is a phenomenal
thing,'' said Brown, the Smithsonian endocrinologist who will be
testing Ivory's blood to help determine when labor is about to
begin. ``To have two is absolutely outstanding.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
