<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMSTRONG-TOUR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG SEES EVERYTHING AS PERFECT EXCEPT THE HOTEL ROOM 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COURCHEVEL, France _ Best-selling author, inspirational speaker,
endorser of products ranging from cereal to sunglasses, foundation
official, family man and wearer of the Tour de France's yellow
jersey as its leader, the conglomerate Lance Armstrong confirmed
that life is good. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Perfect,'' the Tour's defending champion said. ``I don't know
what perfect is, but this is perfect enough for me.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just plain living is good, he said, referring to his recovery
from cancer and the effects of chemotherapy in 1996. Beyond that,
his way of life is good _ his wife, Kristin, his 10-month-old son
Luke, his job _ he is happy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How does it feel to be the proverbial man who has everything? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a big part of my success is the lifestyle, the comfort
that I have now, the happiness that I have now,'' he said. ``Not
that I was unhappy before, but this is certainly the happiest I've
ever been in life, period. I don't know if I have everything, but I
have everything I need. I don't know what everything is, but I have
enough. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The money thing is relative. I have enough to not have to do
this, but I love this, this makes me happy. The bike, the training,
the sport, the atmosphere. Even the travel, the training camps,
everything that goes with it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He paused in his litany of euphoria. ``Not this hotel,'' added
the native of Austin, Texas. Lounging on his bed after a 45-minute
massage, Armstrong gestured around the tacky room with water stains
showing through the plush on the walls. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Especially when he is feeling feisty, the 28-year-old leader of
the U.S. Postal Service team is famous for complaining about the
sometimes dreadful hotels that race organizers assign. There is no
doubting his feistiness now. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a lot of racing to go,'' he said cautiously
before the start of three stages in the Alps. ``I'm surprised at my
fitness. I focused totally on this event and wanted this result,
but I didn't expect to be entering the Alps with a five-minute
lead. That really surprises me. Five minutes is a lot.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He brushed aside his three second-place finishes so far in the
87th Tour. ``It's not important to win stages,'' he said. ``What's
important is to win in Paris'' where the three-week race ends next
Sunday. The best comparison of a bicycle tour race is to a golf
match. In golf, victory on individual holes does not matter
compared to the overall stroke total. In the Tour, stage victories
do not determine the winner, the least overall elapsed time does. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Propping the pillow more comfortably behind his head, Armstrong
was equally uninterested in judging whether he is the best climber
in the race. His power in the mountains he ascribes to his loss of
weight _ he weighed 180 pounds in 1996, when he dropped out of the
Tour a few months before his testicular cancer was diagnosed, to
160 pounds now _ and his use of a smaller gear and increased pedal
strokes as he moves uphill.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care to be called a climber,'' he said. ``I don't care
to be called a time trialist'' another discipline in which he
excels. ``It's important to be a complete rider. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm the second-best climber and the second-best time
trialist and that wins the Tour de France, perfect. Perfect.'' He
turned to a saying from golf, a hobby that he likes to think he
shows talent: ``Short game _ drive for show, putt for dough.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said his motivation to repeat as Tour champion was his
continuing inspiration to other cancer survivors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not as big a story as it was last year, but it's still
my main purpose,'' he said. ``It's still a big part of my
motivation. This race is about surviving and survival. To do it, at
least to participate, to try to win again, hopefully win again, is
survival. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Cancer people survive now. People live the rest of their lives
normally.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is another side to his motivation, and that is Armstrong's
quiet rage against the people he thinks showed him no respect after
his victory last year. These include the news media who suggested
that he used illegal drugs and the rivals who he said implied that
he would not have won if they had been in the race. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives me drive,'' he said, speaking of the criticism.
``Absolutely. Absolutely. You've got to get motivated by
something.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What about the positive influences? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a package,'' he said. ``There's the good energy, family
stuff, my place in the cancer world, all the right reasons. Then
there are the other things that just make me mad. Like somebody
having no respect for me in the race. That I use as well. You need
both.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time for the team dinner was nearing and Armstrong rose from his
bed and edged around his open suitcase that was on a table. ``Not
much room to move in this room,'' he said, straightening the
clothing in the suitcase, including his latest yellow jersey.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite his grumblings, Armstrong said he tried to be a good
person.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an obligation to be good people,'' he said. ``I can be
mean, I can yell and scream and cuss and be seemingly a bad person.
But at the end of the day, I'm going to do whatever it takes _ if I
was checking out that night _ to prove that I was a good guy.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it was giving back to the world of cancer, giving back
to the world in general, giving back to my family, giving back to
the sport _ whether it's financially or your time, whether it's
that yellow jersey in the suitcase, if it's just giving it away,
that's what you've got to do.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
