<HEADER>
A3781 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-NYT     07-16 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALK ABOUNDS ON CAMP DAVID TALKS _ BUT NOT FROM PARTICIPANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ As the scheduled departure of President Clinton
for an overseas trip begins to crowd in on the Camp David summit
talks, the stream of chatter by Israelis and Palestinians on the
outside who say they know what is going on inside rose steadily
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   And what they say _ some of it gloomy, some of it upbeat and all
of it calculated to influence opinion back home in the Middle East
_ is that it is still too early to tell whether there will be an
agreement at all or, if there is one, what kind of agreement it
will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say it is impossible to know where it is heading,'' said
an official who has spoken to summit participants by telephone.
``That's the good news.''
</P>
<P>
   A common assumption is that it will not be clear until Tuesday,
the eve of Clinton's scheduled departure for Japan, whether the
talks are ``going in the right direction or not,'' the official
added.
</P>
<P>
   Only then would the White House decide whether the talks were
ripe enough to warrant keeping Clinton at Camp David and sending
Vice President Al Gore to the meeting in Okinawa of the leaders of
the world's major industrial nations, known as the Group of Seven.
Clinton is scheduled to leave on Wednesday to join other leaders
there and meet the Russian president, Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has been saying since the opening of the summit
meeting that Clinton would go to Okinawa. But in the lead up to
Camp David, and in private, Clinton administration officials have
said that, for the president, the Okinawa trip was not necessarily
written in stone.
</P>
<P>
   One reason that it was premature to assess whether there would
be any kind of accord was that, so far, there has been no real test
of wills, according to those who have spoken to participants. The
Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat, and the Israeli prime minister,
Ehud Barak, have not yet been through a major blow-up on the
substance of the issues, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Those issues are the most nettlesome separating the two sides,
including borders, water rights, the fate of Palestinian refugees
and what to do about Jerusalem, which both Israelis and
Palestinians claim as their capital.
</P>
<P>
   Only once a ``big crisis'' occurs _ a threat to walk out, a
defiant refusal to compromise on an issue _ will it be known
whether there is going to be a breakdown or a breakthrough, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, there was what one official called a ``small
crisis'' involving Arafat when he was presented with some proposals
on resolving the status of Jerusalem. The Palestinians let it be
known that Arafat threatened to leave because the proposals,
apparently presented by the Americans, were too close to the
Israeli public position.
</P>
<P>
   But one Palestinian official said the flareup appeared to be
tactical. If he is to compromise, Arafat, who has insisted for
decades that East Jerusalem must be the capital of a Palestinian
state, could not afford to stay hidden at Camp David and then
emerge having deviated significantly from his stance, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel Sunday, where tens of thousands demonstrators marched
in Rabin Square in Tel Aviv against proposals that would allow some
settlements to remain inside a Palestinian state, there was a flow
of gloomy talk &UR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister David Levy, who refused to come to the summit
meeting with Barak, said that the gaps between the parties remained
as wide as ever. Justice Minister Yossi Beilin, who tends to be
less harsh in his judgments, told Israeli Radio: ``It is hard at
this point to give some kind of impression of optimism more than
yesterday, or the day before yesterday, because there has been no
breakthrough.''
</P>
<P>
   In Jerusalem, Mayor Ehud Olmert held a meeting at City Hall to
express concern about the future of the city. Eli Yishair, the
leader of the Shas party, which quit Barak's government just before
the prime minister's departure for Camp David, told the gathering:
``The president of the United States has to understand that here,
the people of Israel are mostly united. Most of the people are
against dividing Jerusalem. Most of the people are for a untied
Jerusalem under Israeli sovereignty.''
</P>
<P>
   A cabinet minister, Haim Ramon, again spoke out about Jerusalem
on Sunday, sending a warning that concessions on the city were
impossible and that, as he has often stated, the future status of
Jerusalem should be decided at another time.
</P>
<P>
   And in keeping with this fairly stern line from the home front,
Israel Radio reported from the summit meeting that the Israeli
delegation at Camp David believed Palestinian officials were
spreading upbeat interpretations about the talks in order to avoid
being blamed for a breakdown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-00 2043EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000716.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3782 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ALLIANCE0717-COX     07-16 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLIANCE0717-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Alliance dodges laws for election
 &HT;    By Marcia Gelbart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ As trial lawyers nationwide pour money from
the tobacco settlement into election efforts against Republicans,
Florida's leading pro-business lobby is quietly mobilizing to
protect its business-friendly allies in the state legislature.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual twist, the influential lobbying group, Associated
Industries of Florida, isn't relying on the state Republican Party
for help. Instead, it has created a for-profit corporation that can
side-step campaign finance laws, raising as much money as it wants
from whomever it wants and spending any or all of it on any
candidate _ all in secret. This is the result of a December court
ruling that allows corporations and political committees to operate
unchecked in influencing elections.
</P>
<P>
   Called the Alliance for Florida's Economy, the corporation
illustrates how the business community in Florida and across the
nation is increasingly intervening to elect candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now you have got 11 law firms in Florida that have just
become the recipients of $300 million apiece,'' said Tom Slade,
former chairman of the Republican Party of Florida. ``To think they
would not try to change the philosophical makeup of the
legislature, you'd be naive.''
</P>
<P>
   Slade is president of the Tallahassee firm Tidewater Consulting,
which jointly owns the for-profit corporation with Associated
Industries of Florida. AIF will continue to donate money through
its own political committee.
</P>
<P>
   Their goal _ detailed in a 12-page plan that reads like a
marketing strategy _ is to raise $2.75 million from up to 20
companies before the Sept. 5 primary. The money will be used for
direct mail, phone polls, commercials and advertisements to elect
pro-business candidates in 16 House races and four Senate races
(neither races nor companies are identified in the plan). Excluding
dollars set aside for salaries and other costs, that amounts to
$75,000 per House race and $300,000 per Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because political parties at the state level do not get
involved in primary elections, it is possible that business dollars
contributed to the state parties will be used to support
anti-business candidates in the general election,'' states the
plan, mailed anonymously to several Florida newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The aim is not to compete with the Republican Party for
contributions but to augment what they get, Slade said.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes this election year are high, with more than a third
of the legislature guaranteed to turn over in November because of
term limits and the redistricting decisions that the victors will
make in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Formed in February before the start of the annual lawmaking
session, the corporation is the first known group to take advantage
of a new campaign finance loophole that eliminates all reporting
rules about campaign disclosures. Legislators knew throughout the
session that the loophole existed and maintain they wanted to mend
it. But that never happened because of a last-minute bill change on
the last day of session; time simply ran out, GOP leaders said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the corporation's existence gains more notice, some
political observers aren't so sure failure to close the loophole
was an accident. ``It raises suspicions in my mind,'' said Ben
Wilcox of the nonprofit watchdog group Common Cause.
</P>
<P>
   Slade said he lobbied nobody about keeping the loophole open.
``There's nothing secret about the fact that there is an
organization called the Alliance,'' he said. ``But we're not
required legally to disclose, and unapologetically, again, we are
not going to disclose.''
</P>
<P>
   One near-certain beneficiary of the corporation's goodwill is
Republican Rep. Art Argenio, a Stuart chiropractor who faces a
primary rematch against attorney Joe Negron, also a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he needs some help, he will get it,'' Slade said Friday,
calling the race ``a clear example of our purpose.'' He described
Negron as ``an anti-business, pro-trial-lawyer candidate,'' while
noting that Argenio scored first among his 119 House colleagues in
an end-of-the-year scorecard by the Associated Industries of
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   To Slade and others, the corporation is the business community's
response to the trial lawyers' nasty campaign attacks two years
ago. That's when the Academy of Florida Trial Lawyers, through a
front group called the Coalition for Family Safety, dumped almost
$400,000 into campaigns against five legislators who each voted for
lawsuit reforms.
</P>
<P>
   The business community sat back, stunned when two of those
legislators lost, Sen. Charles Williams, D-Tallahassee, and Rep.
Ralph Livingston, R-Fort Myers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no such thing (in 1998) as what we are attempting to
put together, to step in and defend Williams against the economic
onslaught of the trial lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said his group doesn't intend to launch the first attack
in any race, only to react if and when the Coalition for Family
Safety or another trial lawyer-backed group fires first. It's like
this, Slade said: ``You build a military force if you are a nation
and hope you never have to use it. We hope we don't have to
deploy.''
</P>
<P>
   But raising all the money _ less than half has so far been
collected, Slade said _ could prove tough, especially from GOP
donors. With Republicans already in control of the executive and
legislative branches, the challenge will be to convince
contributors of the urgency to give money.
</P>
<P>
   The corporation's written plan addresses that urgency by
highlighting the need to ``effectively counter the Academy of
Florida Trial Lawyers and other anti-business forces in their
efforts to upset the pro-business climate in the Florida
Legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   Lance Block, the academy's president and a West Palm Beach
attorney, is far from surprised. ``We're the face on the dartboard
every two years when they want to raise money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the political agenda of the trial attorneys has been
stymied by the Republican-dominated legislature, the business
community has had tremendous successes in capping civil lawsuit
awards. ``What is it that they didn't get in 1999? Do they want to
close the courthouse down?'' Block said.
</P>
<P>
   As to the trial lawyers' own political intentions this campaign
season, Block said no decisions have been made.
</P>
<P>
   Barney Bishop, who once helped run the political wing at the
Academy of Trial Lawyers, said the corporation is doing little
different from what other organizations have done in the past, in
terms of candidate assistance and campaign involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop _ a former executive director of the Florida Democratic
Party and the corporation's only Democrat on its board of directors
_ said the corporation, with its for-profit status, is an example
of taking that involvement to the next step.
</P>
<P>
   And, noting the surprise losses of 1998 campaigns, he said:
``It's the legacy of those elections.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
