u s BC-OLY-LONG-JUMP-NYT &LR;      07-16 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-LONG-JUMP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES JUMPS PAST HER CONCERNS, BUT JOYNER-KERSEE FALLS SHORT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ The warning signs for failure had been
there all season. And when Marion Jones looked to see whether her
second long jump Sunday had been fair or foul, she saw the official
raise a red flag. Foul. She had stepped beyond the takeoff board.
One more foul, or a jump shorter than 20 feet 11\ inches, and she
would be out of the Olympic trials. Any hopes of winning five gold
medals at the 2000 Summer Games would be gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a blink of any eye, I said, `OK, I've got one more. If I
don't get into it, this dream will be over,''' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Then she looked into the stands and saw her coach, Trevor
Graham, and her husband, C.J. Hunter, making encouraging gestures.
No problem, she thought. If she got a legal jump, it would be far.
She had to make the top eight to qualify for the final three jumps,
and she comfortably sailed into fourth place with a leap of 22-1},
puffing her cheeks and exhaling in relief afterward.
</P>
<P>
   But she was not finished. Before the competition was over, Jones
had jumped 23-0{. It was the fourth-longest jump in the world this
year and clear evidence that she could compete for a gold medal in
the event at the Summer Olympics in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Dawn Burrell, who defeated Jones at the 1999 national
championships, was second at 22-10{, and Shana Williams was third
at 22-6{.
</P>
<P>
   The comeback of Jackie Joyner-Kersee, however, fell short. The
greatest female athlete of her generation finished sixth at 21-10},
never seeming comfortable on the runway, chopping her steps and
never making a serious threat to qualify for her fifth Olympic
team.
</P>
<P>
   However, Joyner-Kersee, 38, is a friend and idol to Jones, and
she spoke some assuring words before Jones took her pressure-filled
third jump. ``Just get a fair jump and you'll be easily into the
finals,'' Joyner-Kersee said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was quite concerned,'' Jones said. But if she was, she did
not show that to her competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marion's a great competitor, but what I admire is that she
knew exactly what to do,'' Joyner-Kersee said. ``If you're going to
be the best in the world, you can't be worried about what's
happening, only about what you have to do to execute. I didn't feel
any concern in her voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Her winning jump was nearly a foot short of her career best of
23-11}, but it was within a few inches of the year's best of 23-3\
set by Fiona May of Italy. As significant as the distance of
Jones's victory was her grace under pressure and the fierceness of
her desire to prevail.
</P>
<P>
   She had won the 100 meters on Saturday in 10.88 seconds, the
second-fastest time in the world this year, and she needed three
jumps Sunday to adjust her searing speed to the runway. She also
needed time to acclimate herself to a strong tailwind that pushed
her toward the takeoff board, forcing her to chop her steps on her
first two jumps, both fouls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was aware of the wind,'' Jones said of her third jump. ``I
stayed on the runway until I had a nice gust and it worked out
perfectly.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, facing much criticism about her clumsy technique,
Jones decided to simplify her style, dropping any pretense at
technical expertise and relying on her speed to jump far. ``I tried
to change too much, to turn her into a power jumper,'' said Trevor
Graham, her coach. ``Last year, she tried to get a big hop on the
takeoff board, but she didn't go anywhere. She went up and right
back down. This year, we're forgetting all about that and we'll use
her speed.''
</P>
<P>
   She began the season with a disappointing jump of 20-7 in May in
Japan, then leaped 22-10{ on June24 at the Prefontaine Classic in
Eugene, Ore., but her jumping remained erratic. She qualified only
fifth on Friday night at the trials with a mediocre jump of 21-6},
and seemed to wince in the pit after one ungraceful landing.
Several jumping experts, including the world-record holder Mike
Powell, have offered to help Jones, but each time they have been
rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
   ``She might do something right and the world record could
happen,'' Powell said. ``But it's better to know for sure `I can do
this,' as opposed to rolling the dice. She needs to know how to run
the runway and jump instead of just sprinting.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham said that others were just seeking news media attention
and Jones said she would never abandon the coach who had nurtured
her career to such dominance in the sprints. She did, after all,
win three national titles and a bronze medal at the 1999 world
championships with Graham as her coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to criticize regardless,'' Jones said.
``We've decided we're going to focus on what Marion has to do. I
knew I still had a long jump in me and I was able to carry
through.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyner-Kersee, however, did not have a long jump in her, and she
could only match a distance that she had jumped back in her college
days at UCLA. She retired in 1998 and, in her comeback, did not
show any of the form that won her an Olympic gold medal in the long
jump in 1988 and bronzes in 1992 and 1996. She said she felt some
discomfort in her left leg, passed on her fifth jump, then ran
through the pit on her sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't there,'' she said, adding that she had no regrets
about attempting a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was a long shot,'' Joyner-Kersee said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said that this would in no way diminish the
accomplishments of her idol.
</P>
<P>
   ``This doesn't take anything away from Jackie,'' Jones said.
``In my opinion, she's the greatest ever. Nothing will take away
from that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
