u e BC-FLAMENCA-DANCE-REVIEW     07-16 0384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAMENCA-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOCHE FLAMENCA: HOT AND GETTING HOTTER 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Noche Flamenca has acquired a large and enthusiastic
following since its founding in 1993. The company knows how to put
on a stylish show. And it did that on Saturday night at the
Connelly Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Soledad Barrio, the company's lead dancer, has grown immensely
as an artist. Always fiery, she seemed possessed by smoldering,
do-or-die flamenco passion in the solea, her one solo on the
program. The dance built, too, to a fever pitch of intensity.
</P>
<P>
   There was none of the elegance of the traditional long flamenco
back here either, but rather a carved arch, in a short and sturdy
body that had all the earthy urgency of the program's impressive
singing. Barrio's hard-working, articulate feet had the same rough
beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Santangelo, the company's founder and director, achieves
a remarkable balance between the new and the old in his savvy
staging of the program. His new piece, ``La Plaza,'' places chairs
and shifting performers about the entire stage space to achieve the
sense of a crowded place and then magically proceeds to create a
separate and solitary world as one by one each dancer rises and
moves among the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Mark London's lighting designs are a fugue of hard, glistening
daylight and dense shadow. The coolness and somewhat distanced
virtuosity of the program's other dancers provide a welcome respite
from Barrio's scorching fire. An entire evening of her dancing
would probably fill the city's coronary wards.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno Argento was the group's shimmering lead pyrotechnician,
but conciseness would have made his solo more powerful. Alejandra
Ramirez's slightly teasing minimalist approach to flamenco was
charming, in a fine company completed by Ana Romero, Eva Marin and
the boyish Noe Barroso.
</P>
<P>
   The exuberant, impressive musicians were Silverio Heredia and
Antonio Vizarraga, both singers; the guitarists Arcadio Marin and
Jose Valle, and the percussionist Jose Antonio Galicia, whose
opening number was a soul-stirring tour de force of theater.
</P>
<P>
   Noche Flamenca performs through Aug. 13 at the Connelly (220 E.
4th St.) and will appear Aug. 22 to 27 at the Jacob's Pillow Dance
Festival in Becket, Mass.
</P>
</TEXT>
