<HEADER>
A3786 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BOX-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-     07-16 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUA WOULD BE TRUE TEST FOR LEWIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ OK, with that out of the way, it gets interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Lennox Lewis, who disposed of overmatched Francois Botha in less
than two rounds on Saturday in London, is expected to face the No.1
contender and his most legitimate challenger - David Tua - in
November.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Tua is the next fight,'' said Panos Eliades, Lewis'
promoter. ``We're negotiating.''
</P>
<P>
   Tua, a Samoan who fights out of New Zealand, is much like Mike
Tyson but younger and better at this point. And he doesn't seem to
be the type who would be overwhelmed by the moment, as Michael
Grant was against Lewis in April.
</P>
<P>
   Like Tyson, Tua is relatively small, about 5-foot-10, probably
too small for the 6-5 and immensely strong Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   However, he's legit. He has the ferocity and power to take
anyone out - no one who has seen him fight would dispute that - and
can hold his own in terms of boxing skills. In other words, he
probably won't beat Lewis - but it's a realistic possibility.
</P>
<P>
   And that's all we can ask: A big, strong, talented heavyweight
champion against a hungry challenger bent on taking his head off
and the ability to do it.
</P>
<P>
   No fight fan will want to miss it.
</P>
<P>
   And then comes Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming Lewis beats Tua, it'll be tricky to make a match with
the former champion: Lewis is an HBO fighter, and Tyson has a
contract with Showtime and neither network will be eager to allow
its fighter to perform on the rival network.
</P>
<P>
   A comment made by Seth Abraham, head of sports at HBO,
illustrates the potential problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got the heavyweight champion, they've got the
challenger.... We've got the jewels,'' he told Reuters but failed
to mention that Tyson is the much bigger draw.
</P>
<P>
   However, one has to think they'll find a way for all parties to
make gobs of money and make the fight.
</P>
<P>
   And although Tyson probably wouldn't beat Lewis, he has nearly
the same puncher's chance as Tua to win the championship for a
third time.
</P>
<P>
   More important, Tyson would bring his star power and intrigue to
what would be a huge money maker. Eliades said Tyson could earn as
much as $30 million in a fight with Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, boxing fans will buy into it in a big way even if Tyson
has little chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Tua and Tyson, there is a wasteland. For example, Lewis'
handlers have mentioned Vladimir Klitschko as a potential opponent
in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, enjoy this period of heavyweight boxing. It
might not be as competitive as we would like, but it's hard to turn
away when Tua and Tyson are fighting, particularly when they're
fighting Lewis - or, perhaps, each other.
</P>
<P>
   If Tua beats Lewis, a fight with Tyson would be very easy to
make. Tua also is a Showtime fighter and both have the same
promoter.
</P>
<P>
   Step aside? Tua, who faces Robert Daniels on Friday in Las
Vegas, was asked during an interview on ESPN2 whether he'd accept a
significant amount of money to step aside and allow Lewis to fight
Tyson in his next bout.
</P>
<P>
   His response: No way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to step down for nobody,'' he said. `` ...My
destiny will not be unfulfilled. Not Tyson, not Evander Holyfield,
not even the networks will stop me from fulfilling my dreams and
from fulfilling my destiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way Lennox Lewis will not face David Tua come
November is if his wife tells him to retire. There's only one
problem with that: Lennox isn't married.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker watch: Lance ``Mount'' Whitaker (20-1, 17 KOs) faces
David Dixon (21-3-2, 19 KOs) on the Tua-Daniels undercard - his
second fight after returning from knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The Valley product is normally very quiet but unloaded on Dixon
verbally at a news conference when Dixon said he knocked Whitaker
down with a jab during a sparring session a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Whitaker said, he pounded Dixon for two rounds and
Dixon never returned. The two sparred before Dixon became a
replacement opponent for Whitaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him he's dead meat (at the news conference),'' Whitaker
said. `` ... He said he knocked me down with a jab. He could have
at least said he knocked me down with a right hand. Geez.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker said the year off from boxing did him good.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole mental state has changed,'' he said. ``I'm more
serious now than I've ever been. I'm stronger in every way. And I
think I know what it takes now to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what I can do. I'm confident. I've found myself a
little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker hopes to fight for a world title next year.
</P>
<P>
   New beginning: Jeremy Williams, the talented heavyweight from
Long Beach with the questionable chin, said he's moving down to
cruiserweight (190 pounds) and hopes to fight as early as next
month.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who is 6-foot-2 but fought at a relatively slight
215-220 pounds, has always had ability but couldn't handle big
heavyweights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a toll on my body and my spirit,'' Williams said of
fighting bigger men. ``I'm already down to 205. A little
dedication, a little dieting and I'll be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban Ramon Garbey is one possible opponent for Williams, who
doesn't want to ease into the division.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbit punches: Former champ Michael Nunn missed a big
opportunity when he canceled his bout with Clinton Woods on the
Lewis-Botha undercard.
</P>
<P>
   Nunn, who said he injured his hand in sparring, would have been
in line to face Roy Jones Jr. had he won.
</P>
<P>
   The fight still could take place when Nunn recovers, but he
missed out on valuable exposure and, at 37, he has no time to
waste....
</P>
<P>
   Julio Cesar Chavez, 38, reportedly has trained hard and long for
his July 29 challenge of WBC super lightweight champ Kostya Tszyu
and promises a knockout.
</P>
<P>
   He reportedly was a few pounds above the 140-pound limit a month
before the fight. However, even if that were true, don't expect
much from him: He's simply not the fighter he once was. Let's just
hope one of the great champions of our time doesn't embarrass
himself or get hurt....
</P>
<P>
   The Aug. 12 Evander Holyfield-John Ruiz fight on Showtime will
be available on pay-per-view to those who don't subscribe to the
cable station.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield and Ruiz are fighting for the WBA heavyweight belt,
which was unrightfully stripped from Lewis....
</P>
<P>
   Showtime has an interesting card set for Aug. 5 in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Zab Judah, one of the better fighters pound-for-pound in the
world, defends his IBF junior welterweight title against former
champ Terronn Millett and rising lightweight contender Juan Lazcano
faces another former champ, Jesse ``James'' Leija.
</P>
<P>
   Millett was stripped of the IBF championship and Judah knocked
out Jan Bergman to win the vacant title.
</P>
<P>
   Lazcano, of Sacramento, has won nine consecutive fights, eight
by knockout....
</P>
<P>
   Tim Austin defends his IBF bantamweight belt against Arthur
Johnson on Aug. 11 in New York, also on Showtime....
</P>
<P>
   WBO flyweight champion Isidro ``Chino'' Garcia faces Jose
Mugaldo in a nontitle bout Thursday at the Irvine Marriott.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-00 2046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
