<DOCNO> NYT20000716.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3788 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MORRIS-DANCE-REVIEW-N     07-16 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORRIS-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARK MORRIS DANCE GROUP: STAYING COOL AND IN CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK ANDERSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.C. _ As a maker of dances, Mark Morris is
unpredictable. Sometimes his choreography is wonderfully inventive.
At other times it is merely facile. It was both on the night of
July 13 when the Mark Morris Dance Group performed as an attraction
of the American Dance Festival in Page Auditorium on the Duke
University campus here.
</P>
<P>
   One thing about Morris remains predictable. He loves to have his
dances accompanied by live music. On this occasion a chamber
ensemble of instrumentalists and singers was in the pit under the
direction of Ethan Iverson. They did much to make the program
theatrically exciting.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately ``Sang-Froid,'' Morris' premiere, did not show him
at his choreographic best. The production was commissioned by the
festival through the Doris Duke Awards for New Work. Much of the
choreography to Chopin piano music played by Iverson fit the title
by being determinedly controlled. Although it initially attracted
attention because of its unruffled composure, it ultimately proved
as drab as the simple black costumes Elizabeth Kurtzman designed
for the dancers.
</P>
<P>
   Feet pattered. Dancers slapped the floor with their hands,
collapsed and straightened up again. In one effective sequence, to
the so-called ``Minute Waltz,'' some dancers kept trying to hurry
past other dancers who stood in their way like turnstiles or
roadblocks.
</P>
<P>
   There was a deliberate lack of energy to much of the
proceedings. One episode was to a mazurka that Michel Fokine early
in the 20th century used in ``Les Sylphides,'' his great ballet to
Chopin. Fokine created exultant leaps to this music. Morris also
devised leaps. But these were low ones.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas Chopin's music was always emotionally juicy, Morris'
choreography stayed dry. One wondered what his reasons were for
showing so much sang-froid at such great length.
</P>
<P>
   It was also hard to care much about ``The Argument,'' even
though this work to Schumann depicted quarreling couples. These
squabblers moved brusquely and stamped their feet a lot, yet with a
surprising lack of commitment. At this performance ``The Argument''
lost its sting.
</P>
<P>
   Both ``The Argument'' and ``Sang-froid'' were offered before the
intermission. After the intermission the choreography and the
dancing steadily improved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bedtime'' was accompanied by Schubert songs about the night.
At first night seemed a quiet time. Dancers moved gently, as if to
solace other people who were curled up like sleepers on the floor.
Dancers also darted lightly, as if symbolizing pleasant dreams.
Then dreams turned into nightmares, as dancers rushed wildly to
``The Erl-king,'' a song about a little boy abducted by an evil
spirit. Some passages of hopping, which possibly were intended to
be grotesque, looked comic instead. But the choreography as a whole
was appropriately feverish.
</P>
<P>
   Bouncy piano pieces by Richard Cumming, played by Iverson,
inspired Morris to create bouncy choreography for Joe Bowie and
Matthew Rose in ``Silhouettes.'' This was a duet. Yet it was one in
which the two dancers never touched. Nevertheless they always
appeared to sense each other's presence. They stayed emotionally
together even when the dance steps drew them apart.
</P>
<P>
   The evening came to a warmhearted conclusion with ``Dancing
Honeymoon,'' a work of 1998 that is one of Morris' most felicitous
creations in recent years. People cavorted in a breezy nonchalant
manner to a suite of old pop songs sung by Eileen Clark. The
dancers also kept shifting, standing on and climbing over a set of
folding chairs. Eventually they tossed the chairs back and forth
through the air in an eccentric game of catch. ``Dancing
Honeymoon'' was a buoyant choreographic excursion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
