<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3791 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-HAITI-CANDIDATE0717-C     07-16 1498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITI-CANDIDATE0717-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aventura Haiti president
 &HT;    By Noah Bierman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Bonivert Claude is running for president
of Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   Forget that few observers of Haitian politics have heard of him
and that most predict Jean Bertrand Aristide will steamroll his way
back into office.
</P>
<P>
   And ignore that his campaign consultants live in West Palm
Beach, have never been to Haiti and have never run a candidate for
national office (of any country).
</P>
<P>
   Those potential setbacks pale in comparison with his biggest
obstacle to leading the Caribbean nation: He lives in Aventura, a
Miami suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Its mixture of retirees from New York and young professionals _
equipped with golf clubs and laptops, Buicks and minivans _ doesn't
exactly resemble the population of his homeland, where 60 percent
of the people don't have jobs.
</P>
<P>
   So why does Claude think 6.8 million Haitians want him to lead
them?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Haitian people are fed up. They want a change,'' he said
Thursday. ``But they are afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   Claude, 55, doesn't come without a strong resume. From 1991 to
1994, he governed the country's central bank. The economist
graduated summa cum laude from Haitian business and law schools and
received additional training in Washington, D.C., from the
International Monetary Fund Institute.
</P>
<P>
   A few Latin American and Caribbean candidates _ notably Aristide
_ have lived abroad before taking the presidency, but their exile
has usually been forced and their following traditionally has been
established before they had any hope of winning office. Aristide,
for example, won the election while he lived in Haiti; he came to
the United States only after a military dictatorship prevented him
from taking office.
</P>
<P>
   In a more recent example, Eddie Varon Levy, a Los Angeles
resident, is expected to take a position in the Mexican Congress
because his party scored enough votes in the July 2 election to
place him there, according to newspaper accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the present era, politics is not the same,'' Claude said.
``We have to campaign internationally.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Claude tapped West Palm Beach consulting firm
Patriot Games to lead his money-raising effort. Patriot Games
partners Richard Giorgio and Francine Nelson hope to use this
international foray to propel their own careers. While their
consulting practice has grown to include candidates from around the
state since its founding five years ago, neither of them has
ventured beyond Florida's borders for clients. Claude came to them
through contacts he made in the Jewish Federation, who Giorgio had
worked with in the past, Giorgio said.
</P>
<P>
   Giorgio and Nelson have spent late nights in front of Internet
pages studying Haitian politics, a subject in which even academics
are reluctant to claim expertise. They won't say what they're
charging Claude, just that the great workload demands a higher fee
than they charge domestic clients.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign reports from March elections showed Boca Raton City
Councilor Susan Haynie paid the firm $6,000. Haiti does not require
candidates to disclose how campaign contributions are spent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see how this goes, but I would hope that this would be
only the beginning of our role there,'' Giorgio said.
</P>
<P>
   It's a stretch to compare this fledgling duo with the
international spin doctors who helped make Bill Clinton president
and Tony Blair prime minister, but the trend is similar. American
political experts are increasingly working abroad. Blair consulted
with American Democrats in Washington and hired Clinton's pollster.
James Carville, Clinton's gregarious strategist, advised Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak in his winning bid last year.
</P>
<P>
   Local consultant Daryl Glenney routinely works abroad for human
rights organizations, training people in developing countries to
build democracy. In the 1980s, after years of Washington politics,
she worked on a losing Venezuelan presidential campaign. Glenney
points out that many American tactics fail in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're dealing with the fourth pink house on the right,
it's hard to do a direct mail campaign,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Giorgio and Nelson acknowledge these problems as well. Their
greatest victories have come in local elections. They represented a
majority of the current West Palm Beach City Commission. They
worked for state Rep. Lois Frankel, D-West Palm Beach. They've won
referenda, including the one that made Wellington a city. They've
lost other elections, including one to overturn the sale of the
West Palm Beach auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   Neither has a history with major Washington contributors. They
cannot write campaign posters in Creole or French.
</P>
<P>
   And they have yet to see the country of their new candidate _
which, they say with considerable understatement, is not receptive
to political consultants.
</P>
<P>
   Partisans assassinated 15 people in weeks leading to recent
parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
   Haitians are scheduled to vote again in a December presidential
elections, but delays are common in Haitian elections.
</P>
<P>
   People who've heard about Patriot Games' new client always ask
whether the consultants will travel to Haiti, Giorgio said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say `hopefully' and Francine says `No, I'm chicken,' ''
Giorgio said. Nelson said she can work on American operations while
Giorgio meets with supporters in Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   Giorgio and Nelson don't know how much name recognition Claude
has in Haiti, if any.
</P>
<P>
   He did govern the central bank during the four years between
Aristide's election and his placement in office. Claude says he
refused to relinquish his position at the bank, despite pressure
from the military government, because the senate had legally placed
him there.
</P>
<P>
   But Anthony Maingot, a professor of sociology at Florida
International University who monitors politics in Haiti says, ``In
Haiti, you're going to run _ what? _ on your name. Being governor
of the central bank, who cares about that?''
</P>
<P>
   And opinion polls are difficult to conduct in a country with few
reliable telephones.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Claude has been working stateside, something political
observers question. The votes are in Haiti and, if he ever became
an important candidate, opponents could criticize him as an
American pawn, they caution.
</P>
<P>
   Since announcing his candidacy in February, Claude has met with
five U.S. Congressman. He's hoping they'll speak out in his favor.
So far, none have.
</P>
<P>
   His main message is unity. He wants to end political
assassinations and international condemnation that's led to a lack
of foreign aid and investment. He wants American political leaders
to put more pressure on Haiti for fair democratic elections.
</P>
<P>
   Patriot Games' role is to help him raise $5 million to $10
million, much of it from Americans, which he believes he needs to
field a successful campaign against what's expected to be a crowded
field of candidates led by Aristide. Rene Preval, the current
president, took office as Aristide's hand-picked successor in 1996
because the Haitian Constitution forbids presidents from succeeding
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Robert Wexler, D-Boca Raton, like other American
political leaders, has been disappointed that Haiti's recent
elections were fraudulent, as judged by international observers. He
said he was impressed with Claude's desire to improve the country
and hopes others like him emerge, but that's as far as he'll go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just not generally comfortable with America getting
involved with other countries' elections in any direct way,'' said
Wexler, who met with Claude two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. State Department spokesman said the agency is aware of
Claude but would not comment on his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Although U.S. troops occupied Haiti in 1994 to restore Aristide
to office after a military coup there kept him out of office, few
now expect a strong role for America in the coming presidential
election. Many in Washington seem frustrated that recent efforts
have failed to bring democracy or economic stability to Haiti and
may give up on trying.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's Haiti exhaustion in the United States,'' Maingot said.
International observers have denounced Aristide's supporters for
marring two rounds of elections in recent months with questionable
ballot-counting methods. Still, Maingot expects Aristide to crush
any opposition and wait out global skepticism until it's forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Claude said he will participate in December's election only if
the international community accepts its legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
   University of Florida Latin American Studies Professor Terry
McCoy said another candidate's presence is not likely to make a
difference. Aristide's opponents have not been able to unify
against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not unusual for Haitian elections to have lots of
candidates,'' he said. ``And most of them don't have a snowball's
chance in Haiti of winning anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
