<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BLUEJAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS QUESTION UMPIRE'S CALLS AFTER LOSS TO BLUE JAYS
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ More and more often, the names and the strike zones
are unfamiliar to Al Leiter, who has been in the major leagues
since 1987. For years, there was little turnover among umpires, and
when a new umpire came into the league, Leiter said, he was like a
young pitcher added to a veteran staff: the experienced crew around
him lifted his performance.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after 22 umpires lost their jobs in a failed labor strategy
last summer, young umpires often serve on the same staff together.
Two first-year umpires worked at the Skydome Sunday, when Leiter
and the New York Mets lost to the Toronto Blue Jays, 7-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think some of the young guys have been a little intimidated
and overmatched,'' said Leiter, the Mets' left-hander. ``It
happened to us in the Yankees series. There were a couple of times
when I've noticed the young umps _ not the older guys _ just seem a
little bit less sure of themselves. And it's understandable. It's
just like young players in the big leagues. You're not really
sure.''
</P>
<P>
   The home plate umpire Sunday was Mike Fichter, who is listed by
Major League Baseball as a spring training umpire for 2000. Leiter
retired the first 11 Blue Jays in order, then walked three in the
fifth, leading to two runs, and allowed a grand slam to Marty
Cordova in the sixth. Leiter was dismayed at the umpiring, adding
that he hoped the people evaluating the performance of umpires take
note of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just a little frustrated with the most inconsistent
umpiring I've ever had in my 12 years in the big leagues,'' Leiter
said. ``And it wasn't just us.''
</P>
<P>
   Gone, Leiter said, is the umpires' familiarity with a pitcher's
repertory.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy had no clue I have a slider that breaks late and
sharp,'' he said. ``I don't know how many sliders he's seen like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays agreed with Leiter's general assessment. One
Toronto player said the strike zone changed three or four times
during the game. ``It seemed like they missed as many calls as they
made, for both teams,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter walked Craig Grebeck to lead off the sixth, and Raul
Mondesi singled up the middle. After an out and a Tony Batista
single knocked down by the shortstop, Melvin Mora, Cordova came to
bat.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter fell behind, 2-1, then made a pitch he thought was an
obvious strike. ``I have to pitch now,'' Leiter said. ``It's 3-1, a
beautiful hitter's count.''
</P>
<P>
   Not wanting to walk Cordova with the bases loaded, Leiter tried
a slider, but it was not his best one, he said, because he wanted
to get a strike or to have Cordova hit it at somebody. Cordova hit
it to the relievers in the left-field bullpen, giving the Blue Jays
a 6-3 lead with his first career grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter retired the next hitter, but two singles followed and he
left after 5 2/3 innings, matching his season-low for innings
pitched. He allowed six runs, a season-high, and his record dropped
to 10-3.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had chances. They left 11 runners on base, and Todd
Zeile made inning-ending outs three times, stranding seven runners.
In the first inning, his line drive to center field held up just
long enough to be caught. In the ninth, he grounded to second.
</P>
<P>
   But the out that really bothered Zeile, and helped embolden
Leiter in making his post-game comments, was the called third
strike that ended the seventh inning with the bases loaded. The
Blue Jays' catcher, Alberto Castillo, set up outside, Leiter said,
but the pitch came in and was still called a strike. Zeile stood at
home plate and argued the call _ ``I can't believe you called that
a strike,'' he said _ as Fichter walked away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not somebody who assumes that's an easy job back there,
having caught,'' Zeile said. ``But I'm also somebody who is very
selective at the plate and I feel I've got a pretty good idea of
the strike zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Zeile said he did not want to be ejected, and neither did
Leiter, though he admitted he was ``that close'' to snapping. He is
not alone among his teammates, who grumbled privately about losing
to a pitcher, Roy Halladay, whose earned run average before the
game was 11.68.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have not played badly lately, but they have lost 9 of
12 games since Leiter beat Atlanta on July 1 to pull the Mets
within a game of first place. Now, the Mets are six games out,
further from first than they have been since May 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think guys realize it's not going our way in bunches,'' said
Mets manager Bobby Valentine. ``It'll come our way in bunches.
That's the way the game is. But we've got to make it happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
