<HEADER>
A3793 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-MOSHING-DANGER0717-CO     07-16 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOSHING-DANGER0717-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Concert dangers draw lawsuits
 &HT;    By Bill Douthat
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Crowd-surfing, body-slamming and other forms
of mayhem popular at heavy metal concerts was not what drew Jeff
Mostow to Ozzfest '97.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a music fan,'' he said. ``I certainly didn't expect
anything like that to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   That, the 33-year-old said, was the trampling of his knee when
he was caught in a stampede by fans rushing from one stage to
another.
</P>
<P>
   Mostow, of Issaquah, Wash., is suing Coral Sky Amphitheatre,
claiming Coral Sky failed to warn him of unsafe conditions. He
lived in Palm Beach County at the time of the concert.
</P>
<P>
   His lawsuit, scheduled for trial next month, is one of five
against Coral Sky or its successor, MARS Music Amphitheatre, by
patrons claiming injuries at rock concerts.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the suits, including two filed Thursday, were brought
by patrons who use wheelchairs who say they were caught in crowd
surges.
</P>
<P>
   A sixth suit, brought by Miranda Patricella of Fort Myers, was
settled in May, according to court records. She got a $29,000
settlement on her claims that when she was 15 she was dragged into
a mosh pit, fell and broke her ankle during a performance by Green
Day in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   It was the girl's first rock concert and she had no clue what to
expect, said her attorney, Robert Scharf.
</P>
<P>
   Moshing, a kind of demolition dancing, caused more than 27
injuries at Coral Sky at six rock concerts in 1996 and 1997,
according to court records. Most injuries were minor.
</P>
<P>
   Officials for the amphitheater did not return phone calls
concerning this story, but spokesmen for other concert arenas and
promoters say their businesses don't encourage the rowdy dancing
and have no control over the behavior.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Yvonne Emmons _ who claimed she was forcibly
lifted up by the crowd at a 1998 concert and ``surfed'' overhead on
the hands of the moshers until she fell _ a concert sponsor
suggested she should have foreseen the danger.
</P>
<P>
   Emmons ``assumed risk of injury by attending and participating
in an event where she was aware moshing could occur,'' said Palm
Beach Broadcasting, a defendant in the case because its station,
The Buzz (WPBZ-FM 103.1), sponsored the concert.
</P>
<P>
   Emmons says in court papers that the liability is not hers. The
concert sponsor and amphitheater failed to ban moshing or evict
those responsible, her lawsuit says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The experts say that a sufficient show of force deters crazed
youngsters from running amok throughout the venue,'' said Craig
Goldenfarb, Mostow's attorney. ``In my case, witnesses say there
was no security in the area where this happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Concert promoter Jon Stoll, who is not involved in the lawsuits,
says moshing is difficult to control.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people are going to act in an irresponsible manner, there
is only so much you can do,'' said Stoll, head of West Palm
Beach-based Fantasma Productions.
</P>
<P>
   Stoll said the lawsuits are driven by personal injury attorneys
who have discovered a new market for slip-and-fall claims.
</P>
<P>
   A researcher of concert injuries says moshing has become part of
the heavy metal concert culture because it is glamorized on videos
and in advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moshing is hip, cool and cutting edge and no one knows the
danger until it's too late,'' said Peter Wertheimer, head of Crowd
Management Studies. ``Suddenly the mosh swirls over them like a
tornado and they are in the middle of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wertheimer, who often testifies in court for plaintiffs, became
interested in the subject when he was a city public information
officer in Cincinnati in 1979. He led a task force investigating
the trampling deaths of 11 people rushing for seats at a concert by
the British rock band The Who. He regularly visits concerts to
study crowd control.
</P>
<P>
   Wertheimer says there are thousands of injuries each year and,
occasionally, deaths. The most dangerous area is the mosh pit,
where heavy-booted dancers engaged in butting, bucking, skanking
(shadow boxing) and kicking while moving in a circle, Wertheimer
said.
</P>
<P>
   A 14-year-old boy died in April of last year when he fell to the
concrete floor while crowd surfing at a Napalm Death concert in San
Bernardino, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen people knocked out, bloodied and women attacked and
assaulted in mosh pits,'' said Wertheimer, who has been hired to
testify in the Mostow case. ``It's unbelievably reckless.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-00 2052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
