<HEADER>
A3794 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JAPAN-TAX-435&AMP;ADD-NYT     07-16 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-TAX-435&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT URGES JAPAN TO RAISE TAXES 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Underscoring the effects of a rapidly aging population,
low birth rates and skyrocketing fiscal deficits in Japan, the
prime minister's tax advisory council released a report on Friday
strongly suggesting that tax increases are necessary if the country
is to avoid financial disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The Tax Commission recommended lowering the minimum income level
at which taxes begin, raising sales taxes and forcing even the 60
percent of Japanese corporations that report losses to pay local
taxes based on their size rather than their profitability.
</P>
<P>
   It noted that corporate tax rates have fallen to levels
comparable to those in the United States and that Japan's
income-tax revenue is among the lowest in major industrialized
countries. At 5 percent, Japan's sales tax is also one of the
lowest among its economic peers, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The report poses a problem for the Japanese government, which
has struggled for the last decade to get the economy back on its
feet after the burst of the asset bubble that marked Japan's heady
ascent in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think Japan faces a policy bind _ no matter what you do,
you wind up creating problems in other areas,'' Vincent J. Truglia,
co-head of sovereign risk at Moody's Investors Service, the credit
ratings agency, told Bloomberg News on Friday. Moody's is
considering another downgrade of Japan's credit rating.
</P>
<P>
   The report is not binding. But the ruling Liberal Democratic
Party's tax panel, which makes policy, has in the past made its
revisions to the tax code in line with the Tax Commission's
reports.
</P>
<P>
   The implications of the report are sobering. Higher individual
taxes would hurt spending, which accounts for some 60 percent of
economic activity here at a time when policy-makers are heavily
relying on consumption to fuel Japan's sputtering economic
recovery.
</P>
<P>
   That will no doubt come under discussion on Monday when the Bank
of Japan's policy board meets. Economists have placed even odds
that the board will vote to increase interest rates, abandoning its
policy of maintaining rates at virtually zero.
</P>
<P>
   But the prospect of higher taxes combined with rising interest
rates would most likely choke whatever economic revival is under
way. An increase in the consumption tax a few years ago slammed the
brakes on what was shaping up as a mild economic recovery, a memory
that remains especially painful for the Liberal Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the report is somewhat embarrassing for the party,
which criticized the opposition Democratic Party for suggesting
during parliamentary elections last month that taxes must rise.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The report's recommendations stand in stark contrast to steps
that other countries are taking to reduce the tax burdens on their
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   The same day that the Tax Commission released its report,
Germany enacted a package of tax reforms intended to enhance the
competitiveness of its industries.
</P>
<P>
   That package is likely to push Germany's neighbors to adopt more
liberal tax policies, which would leave Japan to buck the trend
alone among the major industrialized nations.
</P>
<P>
   But Japan's problems, while not singular, are more exacerbated
than those of its biggest trading partners. The Japanese population
is aging far more rapidly and its birth rate is falling more
rapidly than those of any other country. Japan's effort to spend
its way out of a decade-long economic downturn, rather than
adopting more painful structural remedies, has left it with the
highest deficit of any industrialized country.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's tax revenue covers less than half its expenditures, and
thus the Organization for Economic Development estimates that
Japan's debts will exceed its gross domestic product by almost 18
percent this year. In contrast, Germany's debt stands at 63 percent
of gross domestic product and the United States' at 51.7 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-00 2052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000716.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3796 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-MILLER-NYT &LR;      07-16 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MILLER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
F.D. MILLER, 55, GREEN BERET AND HERO IN VIETNAM WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD GOLDSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Franklin D. Miller, who won the Medal of Honor in the Vietnam
War for single-handedly repulsing an attack on his patrol after he
had been shot in the chest, died June 30 at a hospital in Bay
Pines, Fla. He was 55 and lived in St. Petersburg Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to receiving the Medal of Honor, the nation's
highest award for valor, Miller was awarded the Silver Star, two
Bronze Stars, the Air Medal and six Purple Hearts in four years in
combat, prompting Gen. Henry H. Shelton, the chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff, to call him ``an icon to what service in the armed
forces is about.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Miller was sent to Vietnam in 1966, he hardly seemed
destined to have his portrait hanging in the Hall of Heroes at the
John F. Kennedy Special Warfare Center and School at Fort Bragg,
N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, a native of Elizabeth City, N.C., was a private first
class in training with the Special Forces, popularly known as the
Green Berets, when he received his orders for Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day I was the dining-room orderly, and the night before
I'd been running around all night, so when I thought no one would
miss me, I went up to the barracks and I fell sound asleep,'' he
recalled in an interview in 1998 with an Army publication at Fort
Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first people to wake me up were the company commander and
the first sergeant, who were inspecting the billets. The first
sergeant said, `You can take your punishment from me, or you can go
see the old man.' I'd never been in trouble before so I said I'd go
see the old man. I figured he would just chew me out. He said,
`We've got your reassignment orders to Vietnam.'''
</P>
<P>
   Miller was sent to the First Cavalry Division as an infantryman,
remained with the division in Vietnam for two years, then
transferred back to the Green Berets. After a promotion to staff
sergeant, he was assigned to the Fifth Special Forces Group in
Kontum Province, South Vietnam, a staging point for patrols into
Laos and Cambodia seeking intelligence on North Vietnamese troop
movements.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 5, 1970, while Miller was leading a seven-man patrol of
American soldiers and Montagnard tribesmen in Laos, a booby trap
injured five of his men and alerted a North Vietnamese
reconnaissance patrol, which opened fire and continued its attack
throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   In the ensuing firefight, every man in the patrol was wounded,
and then Miller was hit in the chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I was being drowned,'' he said and added that he
was about to panic when ``I had something of a religious
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The image of his mentor from his days in the First Cavalry
Division _ Sgt. Roy Bumgarner, whom he regarded as a ``Superman''
soldier _ appeared to him.
</P>
<P>
   As Miller remembered, ``Sergeant Bumgarner was right there, and
he said, `Calm down, otherwise you'll scare yourself into shock.' I
tried to calm down and think about what I had to do.''
</P>
<P>
   What Miller did was repel two attacks, firing from a solitary
exposed position, after an evacuation helicopter had been driven
off by enemy fire and he was the only member of the patrol able to
keep fighting. Four of the seven patrol members were killed, but at
nightfall, when Miller was running out of ammunition, a relief
patrol evacuated him and the other two survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Miller received the Medal of Honor from President Richard M.
Nixon at the White House on June 15, 1971. He retired from the Army
in 1992 as a command sergeant major, then became a benefits
counselor for the Veterans Administration.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by a son, Joshua; a daughter, Danielle; and a
brother, Walter, of Palmer, Alaska, who is also a retired command
sergeant major of the Special Forces.
</P>
<P>
   Miller occasionally visited Fort Bragg and spoke to Special
Forces trainees. His credo: ``Share your fears with yourself and
your courage with others. You will inspire people to do things that
are incredible.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
