<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3798 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-TV-RATINGS-HISPANICS-     07-16 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-RATINGS-HISPANICS-ART-1050(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISPANIC BROADCASTERS STRUGGLE FOR FAIR SHARE OF RATINGS PIE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT8 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nielsen Media Research, the television ratings
company, had a problem. Univision, the nation's largest
Spanish-language broadcaster, wanted credit for a larger audience
than Nielsen was reporting.
</P>
<P>
   But executives at most of the English-language stations believed
that if Nielsen added more Spanish-speaking households, their
programs stood to lose ratings points to programs on
Spanish-language television. With lower ratings, the stations would
have to charge less for commercials. The executives feared losing
up to $50 million in advertising in New York each year.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen, whose officials estimated that they were undercounting
Spanish-speakers in the New York City market by about 300,000
households, was worried about its credibility. So last year,
company officials called a meeting of New York television
executives to talk about the Spanish-language sample.
</P>
<P>
   The executives at the English-language stations were not happy.
They disputed Nielsen's findings _ that Spanish speakers make up 8
percent of the television viewers in the New York market _
complaining that the company's survey had used faulty sampling
techniques. Executives at Univision dismissed those complaints as
stalling tactics.
</P>
<P>
   After Nielsen announced that it wanted to increase its number of
Spanish-speaking households, Dennis Swanson, the president and
general manager of the NBC affiliate, WNBC, said that he had asked
half-jokingly: ``Can't they wait for a couple of years until I
retire?''
</P>
<P>
   The struggle over how to count Spanish speakers in the Nielsen
ratings is another indication of the rapidly growing influence of
Hispanics on American culture and business.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Spanish-language television was a backwater of the
broadcast industry. Nielsen did not even begin to calculate ratings
for Hispanic programs until 1992. But growth of America's Hispanic
population has changed the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``As more and more Hispanics have come to the United States it
has become more complicated,'' said Harry R. Stecker, the Nielsen
executive who manages the ratings system for local television
stations. ``We might have the right number of households that are
Hispanic by origin in our sample, but we do not have the right
number of people who primarily speak Spanish.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem was that the sample included too many Hispanics who
primarily spoke English.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen officials admit undercounting Spanish speakers in almost
every major market with a large Hispanic population, from Chicago
to Los Angeles. Naturally, Univision executives say they want
action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ratings are the real problem, because they are the real
currency of the broadcast industry,'' said Michael Wortsman, the
president of Univision's national station group. ``Nielsen is
discounting our currency because it is using an inaccurate
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics are the fastest growing segment of the American
population and are getting close to overtaking blacks as the
nation's largest minority group. There are more than 32 million
Hispanics in the United States, compared with 23 million 10 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The growth of Hispanic immigrants in New York has been just
astronomical in the past three years,'' said Andrew Beveridge, a
demographics expert and sociology professor at Queens College.
Given that, he said, ``it makes a lot of sense to distinguish those
who primarily speak Spanish.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaching Hispanic consumers has become more important to
advertisers. The estimated annual buying power of the Hispanics is
expected to surpass $440 billion this year, according to federal
statistics. In the New York television market, the nation's
largest, Nielsen estimates that Hispanics make up more than 1
million of the 6.8 million households with televisions. If
Nielsen's estimates are right, Spanish is the dominant language in
about 500,000 of those households.
</P>
<P>
   Investors in the stock market seem to believe in the strength of
Univision's market and its business model. The company's stock has
jumped to about $110 per share, compared with $54 per share in a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   But the Nielsen numbers, Univision officials say, have not kept
up with the demographic changes.
</P>
<P>
   At one time or another, nearly every broadcaster complains about
Nielsen's ratings numbers. But in this case, Univision officials
were able to get Nielsen's attention.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen's field agents conducted door-to-door surveys to
estimate the New York area's Spanish-speaking population. (Stecker,
the Nielsen executive, said that his company could not use federal
census data because it was 10 years old and did not ask the right
questions about language preference.)
</P>
<P>
   Based on the results from the survey, Nielsen estimated that
Spanish-dominant households should be represented by 43 of the 500
households in the New York area with television-viewing meters;
there are now only 21 Spanish-dominant households in the sample.
</P>
<P>
   But local English-language broadcasters are fighting the
changes, which would include removing meters from English-language
households. Their arguments vary, but mostly center on claims that
Nielsen's estimates used to determine the number of Spanish
speakers in the market are inflated. They argued that Nielsen's
estimates of the size of the Spanish-speaking population was biased
through leading questions and beginning the interviews with
Hispanics in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen now concedes those problems and attributes them to
insufficient research into Spanish-language polling techniques. The
company plans to compile new estimates, but still believes that
Spanish speakers are underrepresented.
</P>
<P>
   Although Nielsen originally wanted to begin increasing the
number of Spanish-dominant households in the New York sample last
September, this was delayed because of the complaints about the
surveys. The plan was again delayed in January. ``There are two
sides to every story,'' Swanson of WNBC said in an interview.
``But, ultimately, these are difficult issues because of the money
that is at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   The networks have watched their ratings drift downward in recent
years, in part partly because of the growth of cable and niche
television stations. Gone are the days when CBS' ``Cosby Show''
could rank No. 1 among black, white and Hispanic viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Even under the current Nielsen counting system, Univision's New
York affiliate, WXTV Channel 41, has been consistently beating
UPN's New York affiliate, WWOR Channel 9, and occasionally beating
the major networks in key time slots.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the May sweeps, for example, the Nielsen ratings reported
that an average of 144,375 households were tuned into WXTV from 6
to 7 p.m. on weekdays (a rating of 2.1). But a separate Nielsen
service, called the Hispanic Ratings Index, which Nielsen set up in
1995 as a compromise between English-language stations and
Univision officials clamoring for changes in the ratings, reported
236,168 households, or a 3.4 rating, during the same time period.
</P>
<P>
   The February sweeps numbers provide a telling example of how the
undercount affects Univision.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the Hispanic Index reported that ``Noticiero
Univision'' beat ``NBC Nightly News,'' ``ABC World News Tonight''
and ``The CBS Evening News with Dan Rather'' among adults 18- to
49-years-olds. In Nielsen's general ratings, ``Noticiero
Univision'' finished behind all of the programs except ``The CBS
Evening News.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is like going to the bank and getting a report that says
you have $10 and $10 million in the same account, at the same
time,'' said Cristina Scwartz, the general manager of WXTV. ``They
both can't be right.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Scwartz says that Mr. Swanson ``knows that his market is not
a wide English-speaking audience.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has put together programs that reach out to Hispanic
audiences,'' she said, ``and I can't say that about everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   WNBC recently won the rights to broadcast the National Puerto
Rican Day Parade. It has a number of Hispanic reporters, manages a
Hispanic scholarship fund and refused to rerun of episode of
``Seinfeld'' that was offensive to many Hispanic viewers.
</P>
<P>
   But WNBC officials acknowledge that they are able to reach only
a limited segment of the Hispanic audience. ``We are not going to
do Spanish-language programming; that is not the business we are
in,'' he said. That is why, Swanson says, he is so concerned that
any increase is accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Univision officials said they were concerned that the delays
were an attempt to get Nielsen to revise its estimates of what
percentage Spanish-dominant households make of the market. ``Yes,
they are right in taking into consideration those concerns,'' said
Mimi Berry, the research director at WXTV. ``But why not start the
process of beginning to correct the sample numbers now and then
re-evaluate the estimates. Let's get it started now, instead of two
years from now.''
</P>
<P>
   But Stecker, of Nielsen, said that Univision officials did not
need to worry about English-language broadcasters weakening the
company's resolve, even though some the English-language
broadcasters had initially threatened to pull themselves from the
service. (They have threatened in the past to create their own
ratings service, a notion that is considered unlikely given the
high costs.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really react to threats, because I wouldn't be doing
my job if I did,'' Stecker said. He said that the company had not
been cautious due to fear, but because because it was ``measuring a
medium that involves a lot of complexity and that is going through
rapid changes.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that Univision officials could be guaranteed there
would soon be some changes. ``We know how important the data is,
how it is used and how much money it allocated because of it,'' he
said. ``But we have to take the high road and do the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Stecker said Nielsen would begin adding meters in
Spanish-dominant New York homes, installing at least five meters _
representing about 50,000 households _ in September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
