u f BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT     07-16 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE  

</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Utilities Seek New Ways To Change Use of Power
</P>
<P>
   With millions of air conditioners humming and dire warnings of
electricity running short at hours of peak demand, a growing number
of utilities say there is plenty of power around if only they can
allocate it properly.
</P>
<P>
   Utilities are using some decidedly novel tactics to do so,
particularly new methods of pricing energy and new ways for
managing energy demand, like installing radio-controlled switches
on central air conditioners, to turn them off at peak hours, and
paying companies not to use electricity.
</P>
<P>
   General Mills in Deal for Pillsbury
</P>
<P>
   In the latest merger between food companies seeking strength
from scale, General Mills will pay $10.5 billion for Diageo's
Pillsbury unit. Under the deal, to be announced Monday, Diageo will
receive $5.1 billion in cash and $5.4 billion in General Mills
shares.
</P>
<P>
   Mind Behind the Sport Utility Buyer
</P>
<P>
   Research by automakers is finding that buyers of sport utility
vehicles and minivans are different psychologically. Sport utility
buyers tend to be more ``self-oriented'' while minivan buyers tend
to be more ``other-oriented.'' The carmakers find the research
persuasive enough that it is affecting the way vehicles are
designed and advertised.
</P>
<P>
   Cooperating to Attract Customers
</P>
<P>
   Before Internet retailers were expected to make a profit, they
could easily spend $100 or more chasing down a customer. Those days
are over, but a technique known as reciprocal marketing, which
allows companies to offer their paying customers discounts at other
online retailers, allows merchants to attract customers at little
expense. For example, consumers who spend $40 at eToys get a gift
certificate for $10 at Gap.com. Those that spend $40 at Gap.com get
a $10 certificate at ProFlowers.com. And so on.
</P>
<P>
   Qwest Joins Deutsche Telekom List
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom has made informal overtures about reinitiating
merger talks with Qwest Communications, executives close to the
companies said.
</P>
<P>
   Global Crossing Deal Falls Apart
</P>
<P>
   A deal between Global Crossing and Exodus Communications
collapsed over the weekend as the two companies failed to agree on
a price, people close to the companies said.
</P>
<P>
   Icann Votes to Add Domain Names
</P>
<P>
   Regulators who manage addresses on the Internet voted to
increase the number of suffixes at the end of every e-mail address
and Web page by an unspecified number.
</P>
<P>
   Ebony Shuts Down in South Africa
</P>
<P>
   The South African edition of Ebony magazine, introduced nearly
five years ago in the afterglow of the country's triumph over
apartheid, has shut down after failing to find profits or many
readers. Prosperity has been slower than expected in reaching the
black majority. For Ebony South Africa, that meant a retail market
with too little interest in advertising to black consumers and a
magazine industry with little room for a publication celebrating a
level of success that few blacks in the country have achieved.
</P>
<P>
   Alteon to Introduce Net System
</P>
<P>
   Alteon Websystems is expected to introduce a system Monday that
is designed to help companies increase the efficiency and speed of
their online transactions.
</P>
</TEXT>
