u p BC-BUSH-SURPLUS0717-COX     07-16 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-SURPLUS0717-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas budget surplus report released early
 &HT;    By Gary Susswein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Hoping to squash nationwide speculation about a
fiscal crisis in Texas, the state comptroller on Sunday released
projections of a budget surplus for 2000-01 _ five months before
any numbers were expected.
</P>
<P>
   Comptroller Carole Keeton Rylander confirmed that the state will
collect at least $1.1 billion more than expected during the budget
cycle that ends Aug. 31, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Most of that will pay for $610 million in budget overruns
revealed last week.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have accused Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican
candidate for president, of being fiscally irresponsible and blamed
the overruns on tax cuts he supported. Bush defended his record
Sunday and pointed to Rylander's preliminary projections as proof
that the state is in good shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did have a projected surplus. We still have a surplus. As a
matter of fact, the comptroller will tell you that the surplus is
going to be $1.1 billion,'' Bush said on ABC's ``This Week.''
</P>
<P>
   Rylander said her decision to release the projections is meant
to instill confidence in Wall Street analysts who will set the
state's bond ratings next month _ not as a boost to Bush's
campaign, as some Democrats charged.
</P>
<P>
   But she acknowledged that Bush's run for the White House has
focused unprecedented attention on the state's financial health,
creating theimpetus for the preliminary estimates, which will be
formally released later this week and updated in December.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic candidate
for president, has raised the budget overruns to suggest Texas is
on the verge of a crisis, Rylander said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president has been putting out inaccurate
information,'' Rylander said. ``There's been all sorts of
misinformation, inaccurate information, going around these United
States, and my concern is that could damage the state of Texas if
unanswered.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore appeared Sunday on NBC's ``Meet the Press'' from his
residence in Washington, ready to make Texas an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opponent has put forward economic proposals that would
start increasing the debt again and put us back into deficit. And,
incidentally, that's what he has done in Texas,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Ray Sullivan said he believes Rylander's
projections should blunt those criticisms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president has continually made false attacks in the
face of the truth, but we do hope a thorough look at our balanced
budget and our surplus will help Americans realize that Texas has a
fiscally responsible and balanced budget,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The state will spend $610 million more than expected this year
because Texas' prison population and the cost of prescription drugs
are higher than projected. It also will collect $1.1 billion extra
from sales and automobile taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Rylander had not planned to release those numbers until
December, just before the Legislature meets. Now, she said, she
wants the figures available for August meetings with analysts who
will set the state's bond ratings. Those ratings will determine
interest rates for $3.9 billion in bonds to cover expenses over the
next year.
</P>
<P>
   The state has used the short-term notes since the 1980s,
Rylander said, and could save millions of dollars by securing a
lower interest rate.
</P>
<P>
   But the state Democratic Party chairwoman said she thought it
was politics, not policy, that prompted the projections.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who believe in fiscal responsibility will be concerned
when Bush and the Republicans dismiss the state's budget situation
as no big deal,'' said Mary Beth Malcolm. ``It is highly unusual to
release a revenue estimate so early because so much can change. But
they are trying to put a mask on a situation that can be
devastating to Bush's presidential campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
