<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3805 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MACKINTOSH-TROUBLES-2     07-16 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACKINTOSH-TROUBLES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A THEATER MAVERICK SAYS HE'S NOT FRETTING ABOUT A LEAN SPELL 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Martin Guerre'' didn't make it to Broadway last
season. ``Oklahoma!'' is no longer coming next season. ``Cats'' is
closing. So is ``Saigon.'' ``Putting It Together'' did not last
earlier this year. And whether there will be a future for ``The
Witches of Eastwick,'' which opens in London Tuesday night, is
anyone's guess.
</P>
<P>
   Whither Cameron Mackintosh, the guiding force behind them all?
The boyish British producer who brought Broadway one long-running
blockbuster after another in the 1980s and early '90s _ ``Cats,''
``Saigon,'' ``The Phantom of the Opera'' and ``Les Miserables'' _
is not turning them out as he used to. Maybe the age of the
megamusical has come and gone. Gone, too, perhaps is the age of the
maverick producer. Or has Mackintosh, 53, simply lost the touch?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had a tough 10 years,'' said Gordon Davidson, artistic
director of the Mark Taper Forum in Los Angeles. ``But he's
indefatigable.''
</P>
<P>
   Along Broadway he has a legion of admirers who don't doubt that
sooner or later he will be back with another hit; he still hopes to
bring his acclaimed revival of ``Oklahoma!'' across the Atlantic
next summer. ``He's really the only giant we have left in our
business,'' said Rocco Landesman, president of Jujamcyn Theaters.
``Cameron is the last singular idiosyncratic producer.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent interviews in London and by phone from New York,
Mackintosh did not seem particularly concerned about the state of
his career. The Sunday Times of London lists him as one of
Britain's 200 richest people, estimating his personal wealth at
$600 million. He owns seven theaters in the West End of London. He
was knighted in 1996 for his services to British theater. ``When
it's meant to stop, I can do other things,'' he said, sipping tea
in his London office of overstuffed couches and oriental rugs.
``I'm not in any way wedded to doing theater for the rest of my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Talking to Mackintosh one gets the feeling he might be ready to
hang it up, spend more time at his estate in Scotland, the vineyard
in the South of France, that dairy farm in Somerset, England. ``We
make very nice cheddar,'' he said. ``We raise our own sheep. All of
that I find equally satisfying.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is for living,'' he added. ``Life isn't just for musical
theater.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking by telephone a few days ago he sounded confident about
his musical ``Witches,'' derived from John Updike's novel and
written by two young Americans, John Dempsey and Dana P. Rowe.
``I'm enjoying it, the cast is having a good time, audiences seem
to like it,'' Mackintosh said. ``Now we need several good
reviews.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``Witches'' and ``Oklahoma!,'' while ambitious, are clearly
shows of a different order from his earlier extravaganzas in which
chandeliers crash, helicopters land, barricades revolve and tires
rise. Economics comes into play. ``Phantom of the Opera,'' which
cost about $8 million when it was originally produced in 1988,
would cost nearly twice that now. The expense of taking big shows
on the road, where much of the profit resides, have escalated as
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Costs being a great factor, the spectacle of those musicals is
very difficult to continue, except for someone like Disney,'' said
Gerald Schoenfeld, chairman of the Shubert Organization, which owns
the theaters that house Mackintosh's Broadway productions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really represented a golden age,'' he added. ``Now it is
winding down.'' (``Saigon'' and ``Cats'' are to close before the
end of the year.)
</P>
<P>
   Mackintosh said he was not preoccupied with his dwindling
presence on Broadway. ``When I grew up wanting to put on shows and
musicals, I never dreamt any would run 5 years, let alone 9 or 10
or even 20,'' he said. ``To have any sense of sadness would be
stupid, and because they're good shows, they will appear in other
guises forever. I would much rather go out still being thought of
as good shows rather than faded replicas.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Enfield, in north London, the son of a timber merchant
who played the trumpet and a secretary, Mackintosh fell in love
with theater at age 8, when his aunt took him to see ``Salad
Days,'' a musical by Julian Slade and Dorothy Reynolds. His first
theater job was as an apprentice stagehand at the Theater Royal
Drury Lane, during the run of ``Camelot'' in 1965. ``Saigon''
recently closed at that theater (not one of his), and ``Witches''
is now ensconced there.
</P>
<P>
   After he worked as a stagehand and stage manager, Mackintosh's
first big West End production was a revival of ``Anything Goes'' in
1969, which flopped. His first hit came in 1976, when he invested
in the revue ``Side by Side by Sondheim,'' which came to New York.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Mackintosh said he was disappointed that his revival of
``Oklahoma!'' would not come to New York this year, a decision
announced 10 days ago, citing scheduling difficulties involving the
show's production team. ``There isn't enough time to do it
properly,'' he said. ``That's not the way I produce things, in a
hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   In particular the show has been trying to work around the
schedule of Trevor Nunn, who is artistic director of the Royal
National Theater in London. Other members of the production team
include Susan Stroman as choreographer and Anthony Ward as set
designer. Plans to bring ``Oklahoma!'' were canceled once before,
when the Actors Equity Association refused Mackintosh's request to
bring the all-British cast to Broadway last year. For the
production that was supposed to come this season, he had agreed to
try to cast U.S. actors. (In a similar showdown, Mackintosh
successfully insisted that Jonathan Pryce play the Eurasian
narrator in ``Saigon'' despite Equity's calls for an Asian actor.)
</P>
<P>
   Mackintosh disputed a report that the problem with ``Oklahoma!''
had to do with the amount that SFX Theatrical Group was asking for
the Ford Center for the Performing Arts. ``I'm sure a deal would
have been sorted out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As to why ``Martin Guerre'' never made it to New York,
Mackintosh said that musical, which received poor reviews out of
town, was a difficult challenge. Based on a 1982 film and the
16th-century case history about a soldier returning from war, the
musical had been about four years in the making. Mackintosh said
even he turned it down at first. ``It took me a long time to get
into the subject matter,'' he said. ``I couldn't see what was
intriguing about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, Mackintosh said, he came to understand what the
authors _ Claude-Michel Schonberg and Alain Boublil, who also wrote
``Les Miz'' and ``Saigon'' _were trying to accomplish. ``I'm a huge
admirer of both of them,'' Mackintosh said. ``I made a fortune
beyond my dreams on two of their shows. My misgivings about it
initially were how you tell the story, which has been the practical
search for the authors.''
</P>
<P>
   Mackintosh is a hands-on producer who works closely with his
creative team _ asking questions, making suggestions _ and then
checks in regularly during rehearsals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is produced by committee these days,'' Landesman
said. ``There are very few producers who have their own personal
imprint on their shows.''
</P>
<P>
   Mackintosh said it was important not to hand a project to a
director too quickly, that he prided himself on being able to prod
the writers to do their best work. And when he does turn a show
over, he said, it's like letting a child venture forth into the
world. ``I'm not in charge anymore,'' he said of ``Witches.'' ``I
had to pass the baton.''
</P>
<P>
   He makes no secret of preferring old-fashioned like ``South
Pacific'' and ``Oliver!'' He will revive ``My Fair Lady'' in the
West End next season, with his longtime colleague Trevor Nunn
directing. It is ``arguably the greatest book musical ever
written,'' he said. ``Every note is perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that he was rarely attracted to anything that did not
have a strong dramatic theme, and that the work he did was almost
always based on classics.
</P>
<P>
   His love of the conventional may seem difficult to reconcile
with his love of Stephen Sondheim's work. But there is darker
Sondheim (``Passion''), and there is lighter Sondheim (``Putting It
Together''), and Mackintosh does not profess to like it all. ``He's
one of my closest friends,'' he said of Sondheim. ``Could I produce
all his other shows? I don't have the personality that has a
rapport with some of the characters he writes about.''
</P>
<P>
   After seeing ``Company,'' for example, Mackintosh said he loved
the score but not its effect on him. ``I couldn't understand why,
having been so theatrically excited, I came out of the theater
feeling gutted,'' he said. ``One of my strong suits is I still care
as much.''
</P>
<P>
   It is that caring, producers say, that suggests that Mackintosh
will be around the theater for some time to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that a few things he has done haven't worked out
doesn't mean anything,'' said Roger Berlind, a longtime Broadway
producer. ``He's an extraordinary showman. He ain't going away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
