u s BC-GLF-LPGA-NYT &LR;      07-16 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOW SHOT UNDER AN OAK TREE HELPS SORENSTAM WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ROCHELLE, N.Y. _ Annika Sorenstam and Rosie Jones, playing
in the final group of the day, were tied for the lead in the Japan
Airlines Big Apple Classic Sunday afternoon when they stepped to
the 17th tee at Wykagyl Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Things looked good for Jones when her tee shot found the fairway
because Sorenstam's shot had landed in the left rough, making a
precise shot to the green difficult. A huge oak tree stood to the
left, its branches hanging low, leaving Sorenstam only a narrow
passage to the green.
</P>
<P>
   She took the only option she had: a low, knockdown shot under
the tree. Her shot, with a 7-iron from 132 yards, ended up
pin-high, 15 feet to the right of the hole. Sorenstam proceeded to
make the putt for birdie that led to a one-shot victory over Jones
in the $900,000 tournament, the lone stop in the New York
metropolitan area for the Ladies Professional Golf Association
Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't ask me to hit that shot again,'' Sorenstam said about
her second shot on the par-4, 396-yard 17th. ``To hit a low shot
like that and get it pin-high, I had some luck there. I also knew
that if I made that putt it would be the deciding putt.''
</P>
<P>
   It was and it gave Sorenstam her second victory in a row, third
in the last four tournaments, and fifth of the season. She won for
the second time in three years at Wykagyl. The first-prize check of
$135,000 put Sorenstam, 29, on top of the LPGA tour's money list.
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam surpassed Karrie Webb, who ended at even-par 213, tied
for 18th, Sunday. It is the first time this season that Sorenstam
leads the money list. She headed that list in 1997 and 1998, and
finished fourth last season. Regaining the top spot has been
Sorenstam's goal for almost two years.
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam won the 54-hole tournament _ Saturday's third round
was canceled because of heavy rain _ with a total of 7-under 206
from rounds of 69-65-72. The 6,161-yard Wykagyl course played much
harder Sunday because of Saturday's rain, with only 11 players in
the field of 70 breaking par.
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam and Jones shot 72 Sunday, and Allison Finney, who
finished alone in third after leading the first two rounds, shot 75
for a total of 208. It was the highest finish for Finney since a
victory in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal was to make some birdies early, create some pressure
and make people notice,'' Sorenstam said. ``But I made three bogeys
on the front nine, and I was going the opposite direction. I felt
like going home, that it wasn't my day. I felt like I had no
energy. I tried to stay calm, but I was too calm. I couldn't get
going. I was just hanging around.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam hung around long enough to be in contention, but she
had plenty of help from Finney and Jones, her partners in the last
threesome of the day. While Sorenstam had three bogeys to go with
her two birdies on the day, Finney was worse. She made three
consecutive bogeys starting on No. 9 and ended the day with six
bogeys and two birdies.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who started the day a shot behind Sorenstam, made three
bogeys and a birdie. She had the lead at the turn, but failed to
stay on top with bogeys on Nos. 11 and 12 and no birdies the rest
of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Annika made a great shot on 17,'' said Jones, whose
second-place finish was her best of the season. ``She can hit a
shot like that and she is the type who can capitalize.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel pretty confident for next week,'' Sorenstam said about
the U.S. Open in Libertyville, Ill., which she captured in 1995 and
1996. ``A victory on this course is good because this course is
like the U.S. Open.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-00 2108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
