<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3808 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-INFECTION0717-COX     07-16 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INFECTION0717-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Internet helps provide speedy response to disease outbreaks
 &HT;    By Mike Toner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Internet is providing an avenue for the rapid
spread of destructive computer viruses to the far corners of the
world. But for the World Health Organization, the net is proving to
be a new tool for spotting the emergence of real disease-causing
viruses and speeding the international response to outbreaks of
infectious disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``We scour the Web every day for any mention of possible
outbreaks,'' WHO Communicable Disease Director David L. Heymann on
Sunday told the International Conference of Emerging Infectious
Diseases in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Geneva-based WHO relies heavily on official
channels for notification of outbreaks, Heymann said the resurgence
of infectious disease worldwide _ and deteriorating public health
resources in countries racked by war, famine and poverty _ have
made the Internet a valuable early indicator of possible trouble
spots, as well as a vital link in exchanging information about
confirmed outbreaks.
</P>
<P>
   In the last three years, WHO has recorded more than 600
confirmed outbreaks of infectious diseases around the world. The
agency is currently tracking a deadly outbreak of acute hemorrhagic
fever syndrome _ cause still unknown _ in Afghanistan, an outbreak
of milk-borne staph infections in Japan that have sickened more
than 13,000 people and an estimated 1,000 cases of cholera in
Micronesia.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,000 public health experts from more than 30
countries are meeting in Atlanta this week to consider why
infectious diseases, which 50 years ago were considered a problem
solved, are now the world's leading cause of premature death,
claiming more than 16 million lives a year.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the United States, public health authorities are
scrambling to deal with the spread of previously unknown disease
causing organisms _ like the appearance of West Nile fever in New
York City _ and the resurgence of old diseases, like tuberculosis,
pneumonia, and foodborne illness that have become resistant to
once-effective antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention launched
its first assault on the problem in 1994, the agency has spent $128
million to improve its surveillance and prevention of infectious
diseases.
</P>
<P>
   But James Hughes, director of the National Center for Infectious
Diseases, said the figure represents only about half of the $260
million the agency needs for the task.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are scrambling to make up for lost time,'' Hughes said.
``We never know what the next big surprise will be. We need to be
prepared for the next AIDS, for the next hantavirus. A real
emergency, like the next influenza pandemic, will expose the gaps
in the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
