<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3810 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FALCONS0717-COX     07-16 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALCONS0717-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Doing the right thing
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ Bob Whitfield is convinced it's a conspiracy,
but that's just Bob.
</P>
<P>
   When Falcons coach Dan Reeves suggested to offensive line coach
Art Shell that he might benefit from an assistant, Reeves merely
was trying to do the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   After just two days of training camp, Shell and former tight
ends coach James Daniel are wearing out Whitfield, the team's
starting left tackle for the past 112 games.
</P>
<P>
   Whitfield isn't arguing Reeves' logic. But, as usual, he has a
beef.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel, who coached the offensive line under Pat Dye at Auburn
from 1981-92, is a little more forward than Shell.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can call them a tag team torture tandem,'' Whitfield said.
``I think Daniel's job is to ride our (butts). Now, though, I think
they're competing to see who can ride our (butts) the most.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves made the suggestion to Shell after the line played poorly
last year in a season that saw eight starters for the five
positions. In `98, all five starters were in the lineup every game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got five different positions, and 15 people in the
offensive line,'' Reeves said. ``That's a lot for one man. We can
get a lot more teaching done this way.''
</P>
<P>
   So Shell took Daniel as an assistant, though he said he doesn't
understand Reeves' reasoning about five different positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not against it (having two men coach the line). I've done
it before, and a lot of people do it,'' he said. ``I don't believe
in, `You take this position, and I'll take this position.' I want
the guys to be get the same coaching from me they hear from James.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing my teaching, and James is doing a good job of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel had a summer internship with the Broncos in Reeves' last
year as head coach there, `92. The next season, Daniel was coaching
tight ends for Reeves and the Giants. He followed Reeves to Atlanta
in `97.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no ego clash, or anything like that,'' said the
soft-spoken Daniel. ``We're just trying to get better. I just like
to coach.''
</P>
<P>
   When Reeves made staff changes last offseason in a spate that
included moving former wide receivers coach Rennie Simmons to tight
ends, and passing game coordinator Jack Burns to wide receivers, he
gave Daniel and Shell some liberty.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't assign one to tackles, and the other to inside
linemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just told them to work it out among themselves,'' Reeves
said.
</P>
<P>
   All center Calvin Collins seems to know is there is a voice
coaching him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you have extra eyes out there, you'll get more
attention to detail,'' Collins said. ``Right now, one guy will have
the tackles and tight ends, and the other will have the inside
guys. Other times they switch.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Whitfield eventually concedes to the logic.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're on your neck, but that's good because now you got
someone who can see it all going on,'' he said. ``You can't cheat a
step, cheat a technique.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
