<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3811 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-YANKS-PHILLIES-NY     07-16 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKS-PHILLIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS FIND THEIR GROOVE JUST IN TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fissures have appeared this season in the dynasty
that is the New York Yankees, from the growing burdens of pressure
and time. But they demonstrated again Sunday why they will be a
dangerous postseason team, if they qualify to play in the October
games.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody does a comeback like the Yankees, who opportunistically
pieced together fragments of offense, drawing base on balls and
slapping singles, to score five runs in the bottom of the ninth to
tie the Phillies. Nobody can match the Yankees' potential for
relaxed relentlessness.
</P>
<P>
   After Mariano Rivera surrendered a two-run homer in top of the
10th, the Yankees scored three times in the bottom of the 10th,
David Justice slamming a one-out single off Jeff Brantley to win
the game, 9-8, rewarding those few among the 53,131 who stayed to
the end at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the most memorable win we've had this year,''
said Paul O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Gooden proved pivotal in his first relief appearance for
the Yankees, holding the Phillies to one run over 5 1/3 innings
after he took over for Andy Pettitte in the third inning. Bernie
Williams had a home run (No. 21) and hit singles in both the ninth-
and 10-inning rallies. The Yankees are 47-39, a half-game ahead of
Toronto in the American League East.
</P>
<P>
   It had all the makings of a crummy day, Chuck Knoblauch noted
later. Pettitte couldn't keep the ball down, was ripped for nine
hits before he left in the third inning, and the Phillies were
pounding the Yankees, 6-1, after four innings. The Yankees started
to rally a few times, all of them aborted, and their frustration
was probably heightened by the fact that the pitcher who was
shutting them down _ Paul Byrd _ does not look like a major league
pitcher. Byrd possesses the body of Wiffleball star, slight in
frame and fastball, and bends at the waist with runners on base the
way Phil Niekro did in his late 40s, his socks pulled up high.
</P>
<P>
   But Byrd, who had almost been scratched because of a stiff neck,
grittily confounded the Yankees, changing speeds, keeping his
hittable stuff just far enough out of harm's way, at the borders of
the strike zone. Scott Brosius and O'Neill flung bats angrily after
making outs; Williams dumped his helmet and bat on the ground after
whiffing to end the seventh inning, and fans poured into the
aisles, reaching into their pockets for car keys and Metro cards,
the afternoon seemingly wasted.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Thompson led off the bottom of the ninth inning for the
Yankees, the score still 6-1, and grounded to short, a routine
play. Desi Relaford fielded it cleanly, but his rushed throw pulled
Brian Hunter off the base. Scott Brosius flipped a soft liner over
shortstop. Steve Schrenk, the Philadelphia pitcher, walked
Knoblauch. Derek Jeter _ who had three walks in his previous 24
games _ waited out a four-pitch walk, forcing home a run.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Vizcaino, acquired by the Yankees in a trade last month,
said after the game that these were the type of at-bats he had seen
for years, watching the Yankees on television. ``This is why
they've won this many World Series,'' Justice said.
</P>
<P>
   There was a pitching change, the left-hander Bryan Ward taking
over for Schrenk. Jeff Brantley, the Philadelphia closer, was
warming up, but Phillies Manager Terry Francona desperately wanted
to get through the game without using Brantley, who pitched
Thursday and Friday and warmed up fully Saturday. O'Neill took a
pitch out of the strike zone, whacked at a high fastball, looking
to tie the game _ and drove it deep to left, a sacrifice fly. The
Phillies' lead was down to three runs.
</P>
<P>
   Batting right-handed, Williams punched a single through the big
hole on the right side of the infield, scoring Knoblauch as Jeter
stopped at second. Justice worked the count to three balls and two
strikes, the pressure on Ward mounting, and drew a walk. Bases
loaded. Players from both teams stood at the railing in front of
their respective dugouts.
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez blooped a single into right-center, just in front
of the diving Bobby Abreu, and Jeter scored. Phillies 6, Yankees 5,
only one out. Jorge Posada struck out, however, and with just one
out needed, Francona called for Brantley.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees manager Joe Torre inserted Vizcaino as a pinch-hitter
for Thompson, knowing that Vizcaino had four hits and two walks in
14 prior plate appearances against Brantley, a favorable matchup _
and Vizcaino smashed a liner that tipped off the glove of third
baseman Scott Rolen. The ball fell, Williams scored, the game was
tied, the Yankees were clapping and shouting in their dugout,
Martinez raising two hands.
</P>
<P>
   Brantley fell behind Brosius three balls and one strike,
struggling, before Brosius popped out, sending the game into the
10th inning.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera was in trouble immediately in the 10th. Rolen lined a
single to center to lead off _ only the fourth time in 35 games
that Rivera had allowed a hit to the first batter he faced. With
two outs, Rivera left a fastball over the middle for Hunter to
crush; the closer sat stoically in the dugout after the half
inning, the Yankees trailing 8-6.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch, leading off against Brantley, fouled off a two-strike
pitch and drew his second walk in two innings; he hadn't drawn two
walks in a game since May 19. Jeter hovered over the plate and
Brantley bounced a fastball off his elbow. All Brantley had left
physically, Francona acknowledged later, ``is guts,'' and, the
manager added, ``that's a shame.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill singled to right-center, scoring Knoblauch. Williams _
batting left-handed this time _ slapped a single to the opposite
field again, through the hole between short and third, and Jeter
scored unchallenged, O'Neill stopped at second. The game was tied
again, the fans bellowing.
</P>
<P>
   Brantley threw a ball to Justice to fall behind, 2-1, and was
shaking his head: Doomed. Justice then leaned over the plate to
drive a liner to left. Ron Gant raced back and reached up with his
glove. O'Neill hesitated between second and third, unsure _ until
he saw the ball carry over Gant's glove. Then O'Neill charged
around third and across home plate, giving high-fives to the few
teammates who hadn't rushed to hug Justice and thump him on the
helmet between first and second base.
</P>
<P>
   Before this comeback, Knoblauch said, it seems like the Yankees'
rallies mostly fell short this year. This was something different.
This seemed like old times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
