<SLUG> BC-PILLSBURY-SALE-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENERAL MILLS REPORTED TO BE BUYING PILLSBURY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn.)   By CONSTANCE L. HAYS and ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the latest merger between food companies seeking strength
through scale, General Mills has agreed to pay $10.5 billion for
the Pillsbury division of Diageo PLC, executives close to the talks
said Sunday. The deal is set to be announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of the Pillsbury brands, which had sales of $6
billion last year and include Green Giant vegetables, Haagen-Dazs
ice cream and Old El Paso Mexican food, vaults General Mills into
the No. 5 spot among U.S. food makers.
</P>
<P>
   The company will have $12.2 billion in annual sales and will be
a dominant player in the increasingly important refrigerated
section of supermarkets _ where General Mills sells Yoplait and
Colombo yogurt and Pillsbury is a key purveyor of ready-to-bake
cookies and biscuits _ and in the food-service sector, which
supplies products to restaurants and institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Less vibrant but strengthened is the baking division, where
General Mills owns Gold Medal and Betty Crocker, and the Pillsbury
Doughboy is a household name.
</P>
<P>
   ``A stronger General Mills is emerging, and that's what the
industry needs,'' said Jeffrey G. Kanter, an analyst for Prudential
Securities. With its broader lineup of brands, General Mills is no
longer as dependent on breakfast cereal for earnings. Cereals like
Cheerios, Cocoa Puffs and Lucky Charms accounted for over half the
company's earnings last year, Kanter said, but the category is
troubled by high prices and dwindling demand.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which values Pillsbury at 1.7 times last year's sales,
is the latest in a flurry that began this spring when Unilever PLC
made an unsolicited bid for Bestfoods that culminated in a $20.4
billion agreement last month. That move shook up the sluggish food
sector, which had logged little growth recently and had seen share
prices slide drastically.
</P>
<P>
   With supermarket chains consolidating into a relative handful of
strong global players over the last several years, brand-name food
makers felt their power slipping and have sought ways to regain
influence with retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Eroded stock prices played a role in the General Mills deal as
well. The company agreed to pay $4.5 billion in cash and $5.4
billion in stock for Pillsbury. The company, whose shares closed
Friday at $36.3125, also argued that its stock would rise to at
least $42.55 and agreed to cover the difference with a fee of up to
$642 million if its shares do not reach the target within the next
12 months. For tax purposes, General Mills paid the fee up front
but it will receive a rebate if its stock hits $42.55.
</P>
<P>
   One analyst applauded that detail, saying it could promote
better results from the combined company. ``It puts a little extra
pressure on their performance and adds a little more discipline to
the economics,'' said Jaine Mehring of Salomon Smith Barney, who
has a price target of $45 for General Mills over the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Diageo will have a 33 percent stake in General Mills, the
executives said, and will name two directors to the General Mills
board. One is expected to be the Diageo chief executive. Paul S.
Walsh, Diageo's chief operating officer, who recently served as
Pillsbury's chairman and chief executive, is to take the top job at
Diageo in January.
</P>
<P>
   Both Pillsbury and General Mills are based in Minneapolis. While
some job cuts are expected from combining operations, the resulting
company is likely to strengthen the area's economy, local officials
said last week. ``Any opportunity to see them grow and keep our
companies home-based is good news,'' said the mayor of Minneapolis,
Sharon Sayles Belton.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Another analyst, Erike Gritman Long of J.P. Morgan, said the
price paid was on the high side, considering how the Pillsbury
brands have been performing. ``We'll still need to get some details
from General Mills about what they think this does to their
top-line growth,'' she said. ``Some investors will argue that,
given the amount of equity they are giving away, they will need to
accelerate top-line growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for General Mills and Diageo could not be reached for
comment Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   With its Pillsbury division sold and plans under way to spin off
its Burger King fast-food restaurants, Diageo plans to focus on the
liquor business and its Guinness beer holdings. That could mean
acquiring brands in the near future and returning some cash to
shareholders, a spokeswoman said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Some premier liquor brands are up for grabs, including Chivas
Regal scotch and Martell cognac. Those brands are owned by Seagram
Co., which has agreed to be acquired by Vivendi SA, a French
conglomerate that has said it plans to sell the brands to pay off
debt.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts expect General Mills to sell brands that do not
fit its portfolio. Among those could be Green Giant, which makes
canned and frozen vegetables, and Haagen-Dazs. Unilever paid $326
million in April to acquire Ben &AMP; Jerry's Homemade, which could
help command a high price for Haagen-Dazs.
</P>
<P>
   And it is possible that the new General Mills will become a
target for a larger company. Long said last week that it was
already attractive for Nestle SA, the Swiss-based food giant, and
having Haagen-Dazs in its lineup made it even more so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
