<SLUG> BC-CANADA-TORNADO-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIVERS SEARCH FOR SURVIVORS OF CANADA TORNADO 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Recasts lead with search of lake, puts missing trailers at
70; more specific attribution for Dudley; adds details
throughout.) 
By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta _ Hoping to find survivors trapped in air
pockets, divers searched about 70 trailers Sunday that had been
hurled from a campground into a lake by a tornado on Friday evening
125 miles south of here.
</P>
<P>
   The tornado, just before 7 p.m., obliterated the campground with
winds of almost 200 miles an hour. The death toll was raised to 10
Sunday with the death of a camper who had been hospitalized. The
dead included a 2-year-old child.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said it probably was so deadly because the campers and
fishermen on the lake did not hear storm warnings and could not see
the storm coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``A trailer park like this offers absolutely no protection in
the winds of a tornado, set down in a valley where it is difficult
to see the storm approaching,'' Dennis Dudley, a severe weather
specialist for the Calgary office of Environment Canada, a federal
agency, said at a news conference Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Dudley was on vacation with his family when he spotted the
threatening weather formation and called in a warning.
</P>
<P>
   Divers searched Pine Lake on Sunday, looking for the bodies of
fishermen who may been tossed from their boats when the storm hit.
The search was complicated by low visibility and waters
contaminated by battery acid from the submerged vehicles. Military
and police divers also searched the trailers that were blown into
the lake by the storm.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Smith, the director of the search, said Sunday that he
believed that almost all of the 300 people staying at Green Acres,
a private campground, had been accounted for.
</P>
<P>
   The storm injured at least half of the people in the campground,
sending 132 to local hospitals for treatment, many for broken
bones.
</P>
<P>
   The tornado was Canada's deadliest since July 1987, when a
tornado struck Edmonton, killing 27 people, injuring 300, and
causing $230 million in property damage. Alberta usually
experiences 16 to 20 tornadoes a year, but most are relatively
weak.
</P>
<P>
   Although a severe thunderstorm warning, with a potential for
tornados, had been issued about 40 minutes earlier, the campers
apparently had not heard the warnings on the radio, officials said
Sunday. Most were sitting down for their evening meal when the
storm suddenly roared over a hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hailstones started falling,'' Harold English, a camper, told a
local reporter. ``The wind came up and trees started breaking _
some 8 inches thick _ near our trailer. Within two minutes it was
all over.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Lapreirie, who was camping Friday, had stitches on his face
and his arm in a sling on Sunday. ``After this thing hit, I jumped
into my trailer as it was going by,'' he said. ``It was moving when
I got in _ I knew my wife was in there. I happened to get inside,
and the next thing you know it's upside down, around, then we hit
the dirt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
