u p BC-MRSCLINTON-SENATE-NYT     07-16 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-SENATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON DENIES MAKING ANTI-SEMITIC SLUR 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAPPAQUA, N.Y. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton summoned reporters to a
rare news conference outside her home here Sunday afternoon to
denounce as ``absolutely false'' an allegation in a new book that
she used an anti-Semitic slur in a heated conversation with her
husband's campaign manager after Bill Clinton lost his first race
for Congress in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Her face taut, her voice trembling and her eyes welling with
tears, Mrs. Clinton said she had never used the profanity-ridden
slur against the campaign manager, Paul Fray, who is not Jewish.
She challenged the credibility of three Arkansas people cited as
sources for the incident in the book ``State of the Union,'' by
Jerry Oppenheimer, a former National Enquirer reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It did not happen,'' Mrs. Clinton said, adding: ``I have never
said anything like that. Ever. Ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton said she did not even recall the meeting in
question, a reportedly tense election night post-mortem involving
the Clintons, Fray and his wife, Mary Lee, that has been mentioned
in a number of books written about the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton issued a statement from Camp David, where he
was overseeing Middle East peace talks this weekend, backing up
this wife. ``I was there on election night in 1974, and this charge
is simply not true,'' Clinton said. ``It did not happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The three sources were the Frays and an Arkansas political
consultant who said he overheard the exchange while standing
outside the door. The Frays said in an interview Sunday night that
they stood by their accounts.
</P>
<P>
   In making such a public statement, Mrs. Clinton acknowledged
that she was drawing more attention to a report that so far has
received relatively little coverage in New York newspapers and
television. Her decision reflected clear concern that the report
could damage her standing among Jewish voters in her race against
Rep. Rick Lazio, a Republican of Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``My policy for the last eight years has largely been just to
absorb whatever insult, whatever charge, whatever accusation
anybody said,''' Mrs. Clinton, standing beside Rep. Nita Lowey, a
Westchester Democrat and a prominent Jewish member of Congress.
``Not respond, because they are so outrageous and so unfair. I
mean, I've been accused of everything from complicity in murder to
_ you know, you name it, people have been out there saying it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton released a copy of a hand-written letter she said
Fray had been written her on July 1, 1997, apologizing for negative
things he had said about her to people writing critical books and
articles about the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point in my life, I would say things without thinking,
without factual foundation, and without rhyme or remedy until it
furthered my own agenda,'' the letter writer says, adding: ``I was
wrong and I have wronged you; I ask for your forgiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   Fray on Sunday night said that he had written a letter of
forgiveness to Mrs. Clinton, but added that he needed to see the
document to determine whether what she released was what he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his remark in the letter about saying things
``without a factual foundation,'' Fray responded: ``You know, I
don't recall, to be honest with you. I'm like her: She doesn't
recall there being a meeting up there, or so I've heard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
