u s BC-SOC-U.S.-GUATEMALA-NY     07-16 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-U.S.-GUATEMALA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. IS TIED BY GUATEMALA IN WORLD CUP QUALIFYING 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMIE TRECKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAZATENANGO, Guatemala _ The U.S. men's team began their
CONCACAF World Cup 2002 Qualifying campaign Sunday by snatching a
draw from the jaws of victory. Conceding a goal in the 87th minute,
the Americans were sent home with a 1-1 tie against
lightly-regarded Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very disappointed in the result,'' coach Bruce Arena
said. ``And I am not happy with my team's effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Goalkeeper Kasey Keller said, ``We did a lot of dumb things, for
sure.''
</P>
<P>
   The match showcased two vastly different U.S. teams _ one
confident and poised, the other scrambling for cover. After
thoroughly dominating the first half of play, the United States
faded badly in the second, allowing the Guatemalan attack to
compress the Americans' defense and fire away at will.
</P>
<P>
   Keying off dynamic play from David Regis, Claudio Reyna and
Chris Armas, the United States looked as if it could do no wrong in
the first half. Crisp passes and clever ball movement allowed
forward Ante Razov to repeatedly penetrate _ and ultimately
capitalize upon _ a three-man Guatemalan back line. When Reyna and
Razov finally combined in the 45th minute with a nice drop pass
that split the defense, even the crowd seemed to sense that this
might not be the home side's day.
</P>
<P>
   But the second half was a wholly different story, with Guatemala
getting an energizing boost from forward Fredy Garcia, who promptly
began shredding the American's left side. Gone were the tight
crosses and swift counters that characterized the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any excuses,'' U.S. defender Robin Fraser said.
``We just didn't defend as well as we could have.''
</P>
<P>
   Keller said: ``Conceding a goal late is the difference between a
great team and a good team. It was the little things that we didn't
do that gave them opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Heat was clearly a factor. Staged in a rural village some 120
miles south of Guatemala City, Mazatenango was a curious choice for
a qualifier, especially since Guatemala usually enjoys a distinct
advantage in their capital _ altitude _ and would have drawn 35,000
fans to the national stadium instead of the 8,511 who could be
shoe-horned into tiny Luis Salazar Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But the site proved to be a provident choice as the game was
played in sweltering temperatures that had the Americans wilting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I hit the wall,'' Keller said.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Ruiz made them pay for those lapses when he converted a
ball chested down into the 6-yard box by Dwight Pezzarossi. A
quality strike, it also preserved Guatemala's hopes for the later
rounds. As coach Julio Cesar Cortez said, ``We had many
opportunities, but it was only when it became urgent that we were
able to come through.''
</P>
<P>
   The result gives the United States one point and raises the
stakes for its next match, next Sunday in Costa Rica. Historically
a hostile environment for the United States, the Americans must now
regroup and hope to find their three road points there.
</P>
<P>
   There were some positives to be taken away: the U.S. team looks
much tougher and crisper than it has looked at times in the past.
Reyna has blossomed into a true playmaker, but he, too, wilted in
the closing stages. And it is difficult to overlook the impact of
the loss of Eddie Pope to an injury in the 76th minute. Without the
lanky defender, the U.S. back line simply fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   And Sunday's result surely bothers the U.S. players: as Razov
put it, ``We just gave away two points.''
</P>
<P>
   How costly that could be remains to be seen. The top two
finishers in the group will advance to a six nation CONCACAF final
next year. From that will come three qualifiers for the 2002 World
Cup in Japan and South Korea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-00 2124EDT &QL; 
