<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3820 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-TAXES-NYT &LR;      07-16 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TAXES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CHANNELING THE REVENUE RIVER 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, July 17:
</P>
<P>
   If there is anything as inevitable as death and taxes, it is the
fact that the presidential candidates will be debating tax policy.
Certainly, the differing proposals by both Gov. George W. Bush and
Vice President Al Gore to cut taxes will keep the issue before the
voters. Later in the campaign, we will be looking at the details of
their plans. But at this early stage, we feel it would be useful to
define some broad principles that ought to govern the choice of
potential tax cuts. The threshold question that needs to be asked
is whether tax cuts of any kind are the best way to bring about
economic growth as well as progressive policy goals like expanded
health care.
</P>
<P>
   If there is to be a tax cut, it should make the tax code more
simple, fair and progressive. Progressivity is a time-honored
principle often forgotten in the political debates. But since the
beginning of this century, Americans have consistently embraced the
principle that calls for the wealthy to pay proportionately larger
shares of their income in taxes. The tax system became less
progressive after the tax cuts of President Ronald Reagan and more
progressive after tax increases under Presidents George Bush and
Bill Clinton. The latest Treasury estimate is that the top fifth of
American families accounts for 56.7 percent of American family
income but 65.1 percent of total federal tax revenues. The top 1
percent accounts for 14.8 percent of total income and 20.1 percent
of tax revenues. These rates do not make for an excessively
progressive tax system.
</P>
<P>
   Some argue that higher taxes on the wealthiest taxpayers _
particularly the marginal income tax rate of 39.6 percent and the
estate tax _ are destructive of the incentive to create more
wealth. But raising the highest income tax rates on the wealthiest
families in 1993 did not deter them from increasing their wealth
throughout the decade.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the importance of progressivity, fairness dictates that
taxpayers in similar categories be treated equally. But this
principle can be difficult to implement. Many in Congress argue
that it is unfair for a married couple earning the same income and
filing a joint return to pay more in taxes than an unmarried couple
filing separately. This bipartisan group wants to eliminate the
so-called ``marriage penalty.'' Doing so, however, would lower
taxes on families with higher incomes.
</P>
<P>
   The tax code is filled with quandaries like this one. A certain
amount of inequity is inevitable in the tax code. Two families with
the same income, living across the street from each other, might
pay dramatically different amounts of taxes, depending on which
took advantage of tax breaks for health care, child care, education
or tax-free investments. A major step toward simplicity was taken
in 1986, when several layers of credits, deductions and loopholes
for special interests were stripped out of the tax code so that all
taxpayers could enjoy somewhat lower rates.
</P>
<P>
   In the years since then, however, many more tax breaks have been
introduced. Faced with a Republican Congress, President Clinton has
been a master at expanding the role of the federal government, not
by spending programs but by tax credits for child care, education
and other activities. Now both Gore and Bush have moved in the
direction of more tax breaks. The Texas governor calls for new tax
credits for long-term health care, education, health insurance,
charitable giving and adoptions. Gore proposes tax credits for
health insurance premiums, after-school care, college tuition and
retirement savings. All these proposals make the tax code more
complex, adding to the billions it already costs taxpayers simply
to prepare their forms. Rather than indiscriminately handing out
more tax incentives, Gore and Bush should consider simplifying the
code and achieving the lower tax rates they think the voters are
demanding in an across-the-board but progressive way.
</P>
<P>
   Tax cuts, in the final analysis, should be tested on whether
they eat up too much of the federal surplus, leaving little money
for other needs. They must not be weighted to the wealthy, like the
repeal of the federal estate tax that has now passed both houses.
They should keep the tax code equitable and be implemented in a way
that the working poor can use to their advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The logic for large tax cuts is that the surplus ``belongs'' to
American taxpayers and should be returned to them before being used
for more federal spending. What that formulation leaves out is that
the federal debt also belongs to the taxpayers, and so does the
obligation to think about huge future costs, including the
retirement security of the current work force. Assuring that the
next generation will have the education and skills to keep the
economy growing, and a clean environment to live in, is also an
obligation that belongs to the taxpayers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-00 2127EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000716.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3822 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-TRACK-NYT &LR;      07-16 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TRACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUNYAN BECOMES FIRST LEGALLY BLIND AMERICAN TO QUALIFY FOR GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Regina Jacobs and Suzy Favor Hamilton
relied on tactics rather than record speed Sunday in the women's
1,500 meters at the Olympic trials. When Jacobs put the accelerator
down in the final lap, there was no one who could beat her to the
checkered flag. But just as impressive as her victory in 4 minutes
1.1 seconds was the third-place finish by Marla Runyan, who became
the first legally blind American athlete ever to qualify for the
Winter or Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Johnson won the 400 meters by nearly a second in 43.68
seconds, the 10th-fastest time ever, but this was the rare occasion
where he became a footnote to the day's events. The real drama
occurred in the women's 1,500 where two long-time rivals, Jacobs
and Favor Hamilton, finished first and second, and Runyan made her
historical run for third.
</P>
<P>
   Runyan suffers from Stargardt's disease, a degeneration of the
retina that began to affect her in childhood and has essentially
left her with a hole at the center of her vision. She can see the
track with her peripheral vision but her competitors are often no
more than smudges of color and fuzzy hair styles. She has 20-300
vision in one eye, and 20-400 in the other. She must use magnifying
devices to read, and to watch videotapes of her races, she must
press her face inches from the television.
</P>
<P>
   In early June, her vision impairment led to an injury while
training in Eugene, Ore. Runyan jumped out of the way to avoid a
kid on a bike on a running trail, and she twisted her left leg,
injuring the ilio-tibial band of connective tissue that runs from
the hip to the knee. She could not run on a track or a trail for
five weeks, running in a pool instead, and it was not until last
Saturday that she began to train again on dry land. Exhausted, she
began dry-heaving after Friday's preliminary round and limped off
the track in a way that seemed to suggest she had no chance of
making the Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   However, she is one of the country's most versatile and
resourceful athletes, having competed in the heptathlon at the 1996
Olympic trials. After the Atlanta Games, she decided to concentrate
on running, finishing 10th in the 1,500 meters at the 1999 world
championships in Seville, Spain. She received treatment on her leg
before stepping on the track, and even though she was in pain, she
positioned herself smartly for a final sprint to the tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's awesome,'' Runyan said of making the Olympic team. ``I
never really think of my vision as much as the media does. And I
don't think my competitors do either. I think my vision is just a
circumstance that happened. I never looked at it as a barrier. I
never said I wanted to be the first legally-blind Olympian. I jut
wanted to be on an Olympic team, me, Marla.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Runyan added, she had received a heavy amount of
encouraging mail as her story has become public and her running
career has ascended.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me feel really good that it affects people in a
positive way,'' Runyan said.
</P>
<P>
   The men's 1,500 meters was won by the eccentric collegiate
champion from Stanford, Gabe Jennings, who made a break with 550
meters to go to set a personal best in 3:35.90. Jason Pyrah took
second in 3:36.70 and Jennings' Stanford teammate, Michael Stember
finished third in 3:37.04, but must make the Olympic qualifying
standard of 3:37 to compete in Sydney. Jennings grew up without
electricity on a commune in Northern California and never saw the
Summer Games on television until four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   As the women's 1,500 began, Jacobs and Favor Hamilton dropped to
the back of the pack to avoid any early congestion, then both moved
up easily to the middle of the field. Runyan hung back also on the
outside so that her legs would not become entangled. Jacobs, a
two-time bronze medalist at the world championships, and Favor
Hamilton, the only American woman other than Mary Slaney to run
under 4 minutes, went through 400 meters in 67 seconds and the 800
in 2:12.83. The two were never more than a stride apart, and Jacobs
controlled the race from just off of Favor Hamilton's shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Runyan almost experienced disaster in the third lap when
chain-reaction bumping forced her to reach out and touch the back
of Shayne Culpepper to maintain her own balance.
</P>
<P>
   Favor Hamilton made a charge heading into the bell lap, but
Jacobs easily followed and began a fierce kick that took her around
the final lap in 57.6 seconds. Favor Hamilton sprinted desperately
but could never make up any ground, and had to settle for second in
4:01.81. Runyan began her kick with 200 meters left and held off
Culpepper to take third in 4:06.44.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming off the last turn, I shifted gears and tried to hold it
to the finish,'' Runyan said. ``I began to tighten up, but I hoped
I was able to hold them off.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Slaney's 17-year-old national record of 3:57.12 will stand
for at least another season. However, Jacobs and Favor Hamilton are
expected to challenge for a gold medal at the Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of strategy, it looked like Suzy and I had both the
same idea,'' Jacobs said. ``The race really started to go with a
lap to go. That's where I wanted to start winding it up. If I can
run a strategic 4:01, that tells me I have a lot of fitness and am
in position to run a very fast sub-4 if I get the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Favor Hamilton, who missed last season after surgery on her
Achilles' tendon, said she had just begun her speed work and was
encouraged because the Olympics were in September this year instead
of the usual month of July.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty excited because the race felt easy to me,'' she
said. ``I just need to work a little bit more on my sprinting,
which is easy to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
