<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SRILANKA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAR WITHOUT END IN SRI LANKA 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Monday, July 17:
</P>
<P>
   Few ethnic conflicts in the world are more savage than the war
in Sri Lanka, an island nation off the southern tip of India. Since
1983, more than 60,000 people have died, many times the number
killed in Northern Ireland. The fighting has so resisted outside
efforts to mediate that Michael Ondaatje, in his powerful new novel
``Anil's Ghost,'' refers to it as ``a Hundred Years' War with
modern weaponry.'' Since the spring, the war has heated up again
with an anti-government offensive by separatist Tamils in Sri
Lanka's north. But there has also been a positive development. The
United States, India and other countries are increasingly united in
trying to bring an end to the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, Sri Lanka was often hailed as a model of
stability, democracy and economic progress in the Third World. But
for many decades, Sri Lanka's Tamil minority bristled under
discriminatory policies of the government in Colombo, which is
dominated by the ethnic Sinhalese majority. With covert help from
India, a Tamil insurgency seeking independence in the north and
east made extensive military gains in the 1980s, capturing the
northern city of Jaffna. India later came to its senses and kicked
the Tamil rebels off Indian soil and sent its own troops to Sri
Lanka. The troops were later withdrawn, but Tamil rebels retaliated
by murdering former Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Jaffna is now controlled once again by the government, but in
the last two months its 30,000 troops have been besieged by the new
Tamil offensive. The obvious way to stop the fighting would be to
establish some sort of federation on Sri Lanka, with autonomy for
Tamil areas. The government has accepted the idea but not gone far
enough in its devolution proposals. Tamil rebels cling to their
goal of independence. Moreover, the main rebel group, known as the
Tigers, has killed off and wiped out rival moderate groups.
</P>
<P>
   A mediation attempt by Norway made some progress earlier this
year, but the offensive by the Tigers has put the possibility of
talks on hold. One good sign is that President Chandrika
Kumaratunga of Sri Lanka has been working with the main opposition
party to agree on a set of new Tamil autonomy proposals. These need
to be fleshed out, but the unity attempt is a step forward.
</P>
<P>
   It may not be possible to restart the negotiating process until
it is clear who will control Jaffna and the surrounding peninsula
in the north. But all sides should recognize that there can be no
military solution to Sri Lanka's troubles. The terror,
assassinations and army clashes have gone on so long that, as
Ondaatje writes, the original reasons have been all but forgotten.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
