<SLUG> BC-TWA-MEMORIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILIES OF THOSE KILLED ON TWA FLIGHT 800 BREAK GROUND ON
MEMORIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC LIPTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHIRLEY, N.Y. _ On a wind-swept point overlooking the expanse of
ocean where the fiery remnants of Trans World Airlines Flight 800
landed four years ago, relatives of some of the 230 people killed
in the crash gathered Sunday to break ground for a memorial.
</P>
<P>
   A wall of black granite _ 30 feet long, 12 feet high and etched
with the names of each passenger and crew member _ is scheduled to
be placed on the spot, surrounded by a sculpture garden, with the
entombed belongings of some of the victims. Along the entryway,
flags are to be flown, one from each of the 14 countries that had
been home to the passengers and crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say if you hold someone in your thoughts, they are not
really gone,'' said John J. Seaman of Albany, whose niece, Michele
Becker, 19, died in the crash. ``That is why today is so important
to us.''
</P>
<P>
   New York Gov. George Pataki, New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater and James Hall,
chairman of the National Transportation Safety Board, all attended
Sunday's ceremony, a day before the fourth anniversary of the crash
on July 17, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing any of us says can change what happened here or bring
back the ones you love so much or miss so dearly,'' Pataki told the
crowd, gathered under a tent at the edge of Smith Point beach on
Long Island, near Shirley. ``But I do hope that this memorial will
always remind you that the people of our nation _ indeed, the
people of the world _ continue to mourn the loss of 230 very
special people.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal government is in the final stages of the Flight 800
investigation. Federal officials met Sunday with relatives of the
victims to brief them. One of the issues discussed, according to
one participant, were steps being considered for other airplanes to
prevent similar crashes. The safety board, which is scheduled to
meet next month to consider a report on the cause of the crash, has
already blamed an explosion in the center fuel tank, although what
ignited the explosion has not been determined conclusively.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of the estimated $1.5 million needed to build the
memorial has been raised, including $355,000 from the state,
$200,000 from New York City, $25,000 from Suffolk County and about
$100,000 from law firms representing families, organizers said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Gallagher of Seaford, N.Y., raised additional money last
week when he made a six-day, 51-mile swim from near Kennedy
International Airport to Smith Point, following the path of Flight
800. Organizers are holding off until they collect the remaining
money before starting construction, but they said they hoped to
complete the memorial by next July, and to hold an official opening
on the fifth anniversary of the crash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
