<HEADER>
A3828 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-YOUNG-IVY-RULE-NY     07-16 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-YOUNG-IVY-RULE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IVY LEAGUE RULE LIMITS BASEBALL PROSPECT FROM PRINCETON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  By STEVE POPPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The rule is buried in the Ivy League Presidents' Agreement,
adopted at the league's inception 25 years before Chris Young was
born. Young did not know the rule existed when he entered Princeton
in 1998, but it may alter his athletic career.
</P>
<P>
   The rule, Section IV-A-7, prohibits an Ivy League athlete from
signing a contract with a professional team and participating in
another intercollegiate sport. Every other conference allows this
sort of flexibility, allowing someone like Drew Henson to play
minor league baseball and still play quarterback at Michigan in the
fall, or Danny Ainge to take Brigham Young's basketball team to the
NCAA tournament while playing for the Toronto Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   But in those rare instances when a two-sport Ivy League athlete
is held in high enough regard to be wooed by the pros, a player
must decide. And Young, who plays both basketball and baseball at
Princeton, has a decision to make.
</P>
<P>
   Young is a 6-foot-10-inch center for the basketball team, good
enough to start from his first day at Princeton. He was the Ivy
League rookie of the year and last season became the sixth player
at Princeton to be named all-Ivy as a sophomore. He led the Tigers
in scoring (13.5 points), rebounding (5.8) and blocked shots (73)
and was second in assists (87).
</P>
<P>
   He was also a pitcher for the baseball team, good enough to be
named all-Ivy as a freshman and become the first male athlete in
the league to be rookie of the year in two sports. As a sophomore
this spring, he was 5-0 with a 1.82 earned run average, and in the
NCAA tournament, he held fifth-ranked Houston hitless for four
innings before leaving with the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Another rule that Young was not aware of allows a baseball team
to draft a player once he turns 21, superseding the normal process
of drafting a collegian after his junior year. Young turned 21 in
May and was drafted in the third round last month by the Pittsburgh
Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   He has also heard rumblings from basketball scouts that he will
be a first-round selection if he enters the NBA draft following his
junior year.
</P>
<P>
   If Young signs with the Pirates, however, he gives up his final
two years of basketball at Princeton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough decision,'' he said. ``And at times it's been
frustrating, but I've been trying to keep an optimistic attitude
about it. So many kids are not so lucky. I'm just in a very
fortunate position and I'm just trying to enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Young is spending most of his summer on the beach on Cape Cod,
relaxing. But every fifth night, he treks to the mound for the
Chatham A's of the Cape Cod League, and this has only made his
decision more difficult. In one of the most prestigious amateur
leagues, Young has been one of the best pitchers. He is 2-2 with a
2.78 ERA and 41 strikeouts in 321/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   If he returns to college this fall, the Pirates lose his rights
the first day he goes to class. Young would most likely move up in
the baseball draft, however, having dropped as far as he did
because he made it clear that even if he signs and gives up on
basketball, he is committed to returning to Princeton to finish his
degree in politics and fitting in professional baseball after that.
He also remains adamant that it will take first-round money to get
him to sign. The lowest bonus for any of the first-round picks who
have signed so far this year was $950,000, and the final
first-round selection got $1,225,000.
</P>
<P>
   Young said the Pirates had offered him what they gave their
third-round pick last year (believed to be in the $500,000 range).
But he said he had set up financial parameters for signing, which
he feels are ``reasonable to get me to give up basketball and
baseball at Princeton.''
</P>
<P>
   There is talk at Princeton of addressing the rule, which the
basketball coach, Bill Carmody, called archaic. Few Ivy League
players have been in position to raise the issue, the last being
Mark DeRosa, a football player and shortstop at Penn whom the
Atlanta Braves drafted in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But any change would be too late to accommodate Young now. And
as much as money may be the deciding factor, he has tried to follow
his passion, too. For someone who grew up in Texas idolizing Nolan
Ryan and whose fastball has been clocked at 94 miles an hour with
control that would have made Ryan envious at this age, the passion
is baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think his whole life, while he really likes basketball and
enjoys playing at Princeton, until his junior year of high school
he thought he was just going to be a baseball player,'' said Scott
Bradley, Princeton's baseball coach, who spent nine seasons in the
major leagues as a catcher. As much as Young likes basketball,
Bradley said, ``since he's a little kid, when he goes to sleep, he
dreams about pitching in the big leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley acknowledged, however, that in basketball, Young keeps
getting better. ``He's a 6-foot-10 kid who shoots 3-pointers,
blocks shots, can run and do so many things,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not blessed as explosively fast or a great leaper,''
Bradley said. ``But he's an athlete in the purest terms. He's got
the feel, a real feel for the game, for both games. I think what
people see is the 6-foot-10 body and the first thing they think is
Randy Johnson. I played with Randy and caught him, but Chris is
like Greg Maddux in Randy Johnson's body.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm convinced he's going to pitch in the big leagues
someday.''
</P>
<P>
   His father, Charles Young, said, ``Ever since he's been a little
kid he always wanted to play professional baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   But Chris Young maintains his options. ``It might seem that
baseball is more my love now because it's come up quicker,'' he
said, ``but my dream has always been to be a professional athlete.
Which sport, it's hard for me to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the tough part. People say, `Why not go back and
concentrate on just one or the other and make yourself a
first-rounder?' That's something that would be nice, but I've
always played both, and my love is so great, it's tough to choose
and give one up.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes the decision harder is that no one is certain which
sport provides a brighter future. Coaches and scouts agree that
when Young leaves one sport behind, he will grow in the other. He
has squeezed work for one sport within the confines of the other's
schedule, walking over to the baseball diamond after basketball
practice to throw, and shooting baskets during his downtime on the
diamond.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-00 2143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
