<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3829 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-YOUNG-IVY-RULE-2N     07-16 0202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-YOUNG-IVY-RULE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: diamond.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is also the tantalizing notion that he will get better and
the offers will be greater in a year in both sports. On the
basketball court, he has outplayed Chris Mihm of Texas, the first
center taken in the draft this year. That starts the math going in
Young's mind: a first-round draft pick in the NBA earns a
three-year guaranteed contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``People talk about him in baseball as being polished, a big guy
with control,'' Carmody said. ``As a basketball player, it's the
same thing. He came in and was a good passer right away, understood
where to throw the ball. He's different than guys we've had before
in that he's a legitimate center with a center's body. He was
picked No. 89 in baseball and next year's he's at worst in the top
20 in basketball. But it has to be from the kid's heart. Is there a
passion of one over the other?''
</P>
<P>
   Young said that if there were no obstacles, ``there's no doubt
I'd like to go back to Princeton.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough decision, and I'm going to have to weigh whether
I think next year will improve my status,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he said, ``I'm going to enjoy it, whatever I
decide.''
</P>
</TEXT>
