<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: IN THE LONG JUMP AND BEYOND, THE DAWN OF A NEW DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Sunday afternoon, a crowded stadium roaring
like the three-ring circus that is track at its best. High jumpers,
pole vaulters and sprinters all competing at once.
</P>
<P>
   For about an hour Sunday afternoon all eyes focused on the
long-jump pit, where history was unfolding and folding up. All eyes
were on Jackie Joyner-Kersee, who has competed in four Olympics and
is one of the most outstanding athletes of the last century.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday she was chasing the rising sun, Marion Jones, 25, who
wants a shot at winning five gold medals in September at the Games
in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Joyner-Kersee, 38, won her first Olympic gold medal in 1984,
when Jones was 9 but already developing her sprinting resume.
</P>
<P>
   Inactive since 1998, Joyner-Kersee decided to give the Olympics
one final try. No one was jumping out of the box, and besides, she
wasn't going to let Jones or anyone else inherit her mantle by
default. Jones would have to take it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't give up,'' Joyner-Kersee said.
</P>
<P>
   She did not give up, and Jones took it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sunday afternoon Section 102 was a tense section of family,
friends and coaches. The front-row scene was classic, a photo of
aspirations: past, present and future. There was C.J. Hunter,
Marion Jones' husband. Next to him was Trevor Graham, Jones' coach.
</P>
<P>
   To Hunter's right sat Al Joyner, Jackie's brother and the
husband of Florence Griffith-Joyner, the the sprinter who died two
years ago. Sitting in his lap was their 9-year-old daughter, Mary.
For Joyner-Kersee, Sunday was a direct challenge, not so much to
Jones but to the coming generation of athletes Jones leads.
</P>
<P>
   Joyner-Kersee had not jumped since 1998; she watched track and
field from afar, spending most of her time managing her foundation
in East St. Louis, tending to her NASCAR interest. But out of the
corner of her eye she watched the distances of the female long
jumpers. She noticed, as July approached, that nobody, including
Marion Jones, was jumping out of the box. No one was long jumping
so fantastically that Jackie Joyner-Kersee would be intimidated
from even competing.
</P>
<P>
   So here she was. And here she learned the lesson all great
champions inevitably learn when their time has passed. Younger legs
and stronger arms make up in strength what they lack in experience,
and make up in speed what they lack in frame of reference. Watching
from afar is one thing, but in the end it ain't nothing like the
real thing.
</P>
<P>
   Joyner-Kersee performed a minor miracle by making the cut for
the second round. At one point Jones was fourth with a longest jump
of 22 feet 1} inches. Joyner-Kersee was fifth at 21-10}.
</P>
<P>
   Now she jumped 20-11\; Jones uncorked a jump of 22. On that
jump, Hunter, who had sat stoically, jumped up and clapped. Moments
later Bobby Kersee, her husband and coach, walked by and in a
gesture quick and subtle, stuck out his hand to Hunter. They shook
hands. Joyner-Kersee kept moving. History kept moving. This was a
special day of demarcation, when the weight of being the face,
heart and soul of track and field shifted from Joyner-Kersee to
Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of how I did, I wanted to give it my best shot
before I ended my career,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   This was special day for 9-year-old Mary Griffith-Joyner, too.
</P>
<P>
   Before today she never saw her aunt Jackie compete in person.
``It was always on tape or on television,'' Al Joyner said. ``All
her classmates would write book reports about Jackie, but I wanted
her to see her perform. I wanted her to see this. She saw her aunt
dig down deep just to make it to the second round.''
</P>
<P>
   I wondered how Joyner felt as he watched his sister compete for
the last time with his daughter at the first major race he attended
since his wife died. He wore a shirt she had made, with her world
record printed on the back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been tough,'' Joyner said. ``I've been growing, maturing.
But it's been tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday afternoon his daughter _ their daughter _ saw the
remarkable tide of history. Her aunt was the tide going out, Marion
Jones, the tide coming in.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, Flo-Jo, is like the omnipresent ocean. When
historians talk about the 100 meters, they talk about her mother,
who has the fastest time ever run and four of the five fastest
times ever run. When historians talk about the 200 meters, they
talk about her mother, who owns three of the top five times. And
when historians talk about great female athletes, they talk about
her aunt Jackie.
</P>
<P>
   Marion Jones was 9 when Jackie Joyner-Kersee won her first
Olympic gold medal. That's the distinguishing virtue of this sport.
Dawn after dawn after dawn.
</P>
<P>
   No sunsets.
</P>
<P>
   Just dawns. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
