<SLUG> BC-AETNA-ING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AETNA'S PLAN TO SELL UNITS TO ING SAID TO HIT SNAGS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LAURA M. HOLSON and MARY WILLIAMS WALSH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aetna Corp., which has been in talks to sell its financial and
international units to ING Groep, the Dutch financial services
company, has yet to resolve key issues in the deal, people close to
the talks said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Aetna's board tentatively endorsed the transaction,
which is likely to exceed $7 billion, including debt, according to
several people close to the companies. But Aetna and ING executives
still have to resolve issues related to Aetna's domestic business,
particularly how Aetna can avoid paying a huge tax bill as a result
of the sale to ING.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies had originally planned to announce Monday that a
deal had been struck. But if they can come to terms in the coming
days, the people said, the sale could be announced by the middle of
the week.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna executives initially thought they could get a better price
by auctioning off the businesses in pieces instead of selling them
as a whole. But it found few takers and was worried about a huge
tax bite.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna began talks with ING several months ago, but those
discussions stalled over price. The financial services unit
includes the annuity and asset management business, while the
international unit is made up of businesses that include life
insurance and health care, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of both Aetna and ING would not comment on the
discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Lane, an analyst at Salomon Smith Barney, said that for
Aetna shareholders pondering the talks between Aetna and ING, the
central question was not the ``minutiae'' of credit ratings and tax
planning, but the underlying value of Aetna's health-care unit. If
the sale goes forward, he said, current Aetna shareholders would
most likely be left with shares in a new company that is made up of
Aetna U.S. Healthcare and some cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the math that people should be thinking about, and
there's no visibility on it,'' Lane said. ``The management team has
not been willing to comment on the outlook for earnings in the U.S.
Healthcare segment. They haven't given a definitive earnings
outlook for two and almost three quarters.''
</P>
<P>
   One scenario that has been described is Aetna spinning off its
health-care unit to shareholders before it completes the sale with
ING. If Aetna and ING did that, Lane said, it would be a much more
shareholder-friendly deal because the tax bill would be lower.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna has been under pressure from shareholders to sell assets
and improve its health-care operations, thus lifting its stock
price. The company has sold seven of its international units and
ventures over the last 10 months.
</P>
<P>
   Lane said that Aetna's operations were so diverse that it was
hard to find synergies among them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-00 2150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000716.0181 </DOCNO>
