<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATER-WAR-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. JOSEPH RESIDENTS BRISTLE AT HARD WATER AND PROSPECT OF HIGHER
BILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GRAHAM  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. JOSEPH, Mo. _ The thirsty in St. Joseph can agree on only
one thing about the drinking water _ it's wet.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, one person's refreshing thirst quencher from the
kitchen faucet is liquid yuck to another.
</P>
<P>
   A water war regarding taste buds and the film that floats on
coffee has raged since the private Missouri-American Water Co.
opened the valves on a new $72 million treatment plant in April.
Complaints prompted the Office of the Public Counsel, the state's
utilities consumer advocate, to ask the Missouri Public Service
Commission to investigate whether the water is drinkable.
</P>
<P>
   This comes as the commission considers Missouri-American's
request for a 51 percent rate increase to pay for $100 million in
capital improvements in Missouri operations, including the St.
Joseph plant.
</P>
<P>
   Those involved in the rate case have until today to file
responses regarding quality, and then the commission will decide
whether to investigate. A decision on the rate increase is expected
in September.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Department of Natural Resources is testing St.
Joseph's water because of complaints, said Bill Hills, an
environmental engineer based in Kansas City. Those results are
incomplete. But after inspecting the treatment plant and drinking
the water from a public fountain, Hills thinks it tastes OK and
will meet all standards.
</P>
<P>
   But some residents disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the water got worse as far as the taste and the
color,'' said Cheryl Licht, 40. ``I'm afraid of what we're
drinking. It tastes like there's a thickness to it, like it's not
pure water. I won't let my kids drink it.''
</P>
<P>
   But down the street in the city's old north side, near North
26th and Folsom streets, a neighbor drinks it heartily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had any problems,'' said Jim Pillsbury, 65. ``The
water's got a different taste. But it doesn't stink and it still
makes good ice cubes. I drink four glasses a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Drink up, says Bob Amman, Missouri-American's manager for
operations in northwest Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   The water has been tested and it meets all federal and state
drinking water standards for the company's 32,000 customers, about
100,000 people, in St. Joseph and surrounding rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drink this water every day and I notice no problems with
taste and odor,'' Amman said.
</P>
<P>
   But what has changed, he said, is the ``hardness'' or calcium
content, because the water is being drawn from a new source.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri-American formerly pumped water directly out of the
Missouri River into a treatment plant near the river. Plans at one
time called for a $30 million or $40 million upgrade of that plant
to modernize and keep up with St. Joseph's growth.
</P>
<P>
   But the 1993 flood prompted a change in plans.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than trying to floodproof the old plant,
Missouri-American built a new one on high ground. Also, to avoid
intake problems as water levels vary, aquifers 120 feet below the
riverbed were tapped with a series of wells.
</P>
<P>
   But those aquifers have water that's been trapped for thousands
of years and is much heavier in dissolved minerals such as calcium
than river water, Amman said.
</P>
<P>
   St. Joseph customers in April went from Missouri River water
with 250 to 350 parts per million calcium content to well water
with more than 400 parts per million calcium, he said.
Missouri-American officials expect the calcium level to drop as
older water is pumped out of the aquifer and newer water filters
in. The water should eventually be only slightly harder than
before, Amman said.
</P>
<P>
   But calcium levels in the water haven't dropped as quickly as
expected.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the calcium content in Kansas City's water is
about 150 to 180 parts per million.
</P>
<P>
   About 75 percent of Kansas City's water comes from the Missouri
River, and about 25 percent from wells along the river.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Water Services Department adds softening agents
to help save on soap costs and reduce buildup of calcium deposits
inside pipes.
</P>
<P>
   Amman said St. Joseph's water has always been hard and problems
should diminish as fresh water seeps into wells.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's terrible,'' said Shirley Jones. ``My biggest problem is
my dishes are not getting clean. They're spotted now, and the
dishwasher just doesn't do the job. When you make coffee, there's
kind of scum on top.''
</P>
<P>
   Amman said he, too, has seen the film atop coffee in his cup.
Natural oils in coffee and tea will accumulate around calcium in
heated water.
</P>
<P>
   Those who don't like the water are not as optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't like the way it tastes, so we had a Culligan water
softener installed,'' said Carrie Shindorf, 34. ``I think it's
gotten worse, and I've talked to a lot of women who say their
dishes are just not getting clean.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Ward, 28, spent $4,000 for a complete water treatment
system for his home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was oily and made the tea taste bad,'' Ward said,
``and it just tasted different to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The taste doesn't bother Mark White, 28, who recently slaked his
thirst at water fountains in Noyes Elementary School during breaks
from tearing up floor tile.
</P>
<P>
   But he finds an annual increase in customers' bills of $204 to
$309 to pay for the plant offensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see anything wrong with the plant they had before,''
White said. ``Now the rate increase just seems outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   Amman believes the price increase is the real reason that some
customers are unhappy with the water.
</P>
<P>
   The rate increase could also affect Missouri-American's
Northland customers in the Parkville and Riverside areas. But water
for those areas is treated in Parkville.
</P>
<P>
   The city's water quality dominated a recent rate hearing in St.
Joseph, said John Coffman, deputy public counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been hearing from hundreds of customers who don't
believe the quality is adequate,'' Coffman said.
</P>
<P>
   St. Joseph City Manager Stet Schanze said City Hall has fielded
numerous complaints about the water and forwarded them to city and
county health officials. But St. Joseph officials have been assured
the water is safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal opinion is, I haven't noticed a change in the
water,'' Schanze said. ``We drink out of the tap.''
</P>
<P>
   Missouri-American may benefit from a water-quality
investigation, Amman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confident they won't find anything but the hardness
issue,'' he said, ``and if people want to pay more, we can do
something.''
</P>
<P>
   But rather than saddling all customers with more expensive
bills, Missouri-American believes individual homeowners can buy
water softeners if they desire, Amman said.
</P>
<P>
   Some customers are happy with the new water.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't notice a difference in the smell or the flavor,'' said
Melissa Birdsell, 36.
</P>
<P>
   She sometimes notices a film on drinking glasses. But she has no
trouble getting her dishes clean.
</P>
<P>
   Other neighbors say the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``I noticed a little film on the coffee, but nothing to get
upset about,'' said Mike Leach, 42.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Tighe, 35, finds the controversy shallow compared with
water problems in the world's impoverished nations, and she doesn't
mind St. Joseph's new water.
</P>
<P>
   But she does have an in-house dispute among her teen-age
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daniel likes new water better,'' she said, ``but Brooke
doesn't care for the taste.''
</P>
<P>
   The Star's Lynn Horsley contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
