<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3843 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-FARM-HERITAGE-KAN &LR;      07-16 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARM-HERITAGE-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Farmers and enthusiasts honor machinery of the past  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GRAHAM  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BONNER SPRINGS, Mo. _ A smokestack belched black coal smoke as
the tractor's steam-driven flywheels clanged in rhythm, powering an
early 1930s grain thresher fed by men not afraid to work on a
sweltering summer day.
</P>
<P>
   Like Fred Tinbird. At midday on Sunday, the 80-year-old stood
atop a gray, galvanized metal thresher as the machine spouted wheat
grain into a wagon, straw into a heap on the ground and dust
skyward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm probably the only one out here today who actually ran
one,'' said Tinbird, who learned to operate such machinery by
necessity on a Leavenworth County farm.
</P>
<P>
   Most of his co-workers at the Farm Heritage Days and Steam Show
were self-taught through curiosity. They gathered at the National
Agriculture Hall of Fame to show off restored antique farm
equipment and celebrate what replaced the horse and mule on
America's farms _ man-made power and mechanical ingenuity.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Reilly, 38, watched as a massive iron tractor shaped like
a small locomotive backed up and then pulled forward with barely a
whisper of escaping steam, its water boilers pressurized and
firebox dampers closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so quiet,'' Reilly said. ``You've got 11 tons moving
along and you can't hardly hear it, yet it mashes the ground down
under the wheels.''
</P>
<P>
   His grandfather's first tractor, a four-cylinder
McCormick-Deering Farmall, was rusting away on his family's
northeast Kansas farm when the restoration bug struck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 15 or 16 and my dad told me if I could overhaul it and
get it to running, I could have it,'' Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he lives near Tonganoxie and works as a mechanical
engineer for a company that manufactures airplane parts. But he
fires up Grandpa's old tractor at shows and tinkers with other
early steam and gasoline tractors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just like the challenge involved,'' Reilly said. ``These
machines only work as well as they're worked on.''
</P>
<P>
   Old tractors have knobs and levers to do what a few buttons and
a steering wheel do on a modern tractor.
</P>
<P>
   ``These machines are based on the skills of the operator,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some farmers were slow to switch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grandpa's tractor was made in 1930, and he didn't get it until
1947,'' Reilly said. ``He farmed with horses all through the
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The tractors pulled plows, and farmers attached belts to side
wheels to operate machinery such as threshers and saws.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father bought a thresher when I was 8, and when I was 10 I
could belt it and adjust wheels and things,'' Tinbird said. ``I
haven't forgot too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, one person driving a modern combine can cut and thresh
vast wheat fields in a single day while riding in an
air-conditioned cab.
</P>
<P>
   Tinbird remembers when wheat stalks were cut and bound, then
hauled from the fields on a wagon. A July 4 to Aug. 4 threshing
season followed, with men using machines to separate wheat grain
from straw and chaff.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer heat, his mother and neighbor women labored over
wood stoves to cook large meals for threshing crews, usually 13 men
including the water boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know how they did it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Leaning against a thresher, clad in Big Smith overalls,
long-sleeved blue work shirt and straw hat, he remembers when many
worked long, hard days in sizzling heat and thought little of it.
</P>
<P>
   It's good for people to remember the work that came before,
Tinbird said, and the connection between farmers and food.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids come up to us here and ask what we're doing, and I say
threshing wheat,'' he said. ``Then they ask, `What's wheat?'''
</P>
<P>
   America owes a great debt to the farmers and engineers who made
farm production more efficient, Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It freed people to work in other jobs,'' he said, ``and there
was always plenty of cheap food available.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City's past was tied to outlying farms. A large red brick
building in the West Bottoms still bears the visible lettering,
``John Deere Plow Company, farm implements and wagons.''
</P>
<P>
   But few who drive old machinery now, fond as they are of it,
wish to return to the days when men rode bare steel tractor seats
for a living.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's 100 degrees or minus 20,'' Reilly said, ``I'm glad I
can work inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the young are drawn to the old machinery.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Uhler, 19, drove an old two-cylinder tractor in the
``parade of power'' as her fiance, D.J. McGrath, also 19, rode on
the fender. The Grantville, Kan., youths met at an antique tractor
show and will marry in August.
</P>
<P>
   McGrath, a welder, grew up attending antique equipment shows. He
took his turn operating the old steam tractor on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting to compare what they had then to now,'' he
said. ``There's so many similarities. They were really ahead of
their time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
