<DOCNO> NYT20000716.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3852 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-CAPITAL-PUNISHMENT-KA     07-16 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITAL-PUNISHMENT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN POTOSI, SITE OF MISSOURI'S DEATH ROW, EXECUTIONS AREN'T BIG
NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MALCOLM GARCIA  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WITH SIDEBAR SLUGGED EXECUTION-STATS
</P>
<P>
   POTOSI, Mo. _ The flurry of legal activity that put the
execution of convicted murderer Mose Young on hold last week made
headlines from St. Louis to St. Joseph.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the news made barely a ripple in the small town
where the state carries out Missouri's executions. No smaller a
ripple, though, than the earlier news that he was scheduled to die.
</P>
<P>
   Capital punishment, it seems, is no longer a life-and-death
issue in Potosi.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably controversial,'' said Karen Gomas, a clerk at
the Super 8 Motel in Potosi, a town of about 2,000 people in
southeastern Missouri. ``Executions aren't so talked about. Most
people don't even know about them.''
</P>
<P>
   Young, 44, on death row since 1984, had been convicted of
fatally shooting three persons in a pawnshop in St. Louis. He was
scheduled to die at 12:01a.m. Wednesday. But about six hours before
the execution, an appeals court judge ruled that his due process
had been violated. Just after midnight, the U.S. Supreme Court
refused the state's request to vacate the stay.
</P>
<P>
   So on Wednesday morning, the sun rose for Mose Young. But it was
just another day in Potosi.
</P>
<P>
   The town's collective uninterest in events a mile outside the
city limits was evident as the clock ticked toward Young's
scheduled death. Residents went about their day waving at one
another from passing cars in the bumper-to-bumper downtown
district, which, with its squat stone and brick buildings, retains
the look of a frontier town.
</P>
<P>
   Crowds of people, many with squawking infants, fanned out across
the parking lot of the local Wal-Mart, shopping carts heaped with
goods. It's a short hop from there for a quick bite to eat at the
Hardee's up the road.
</P>
<P>
   From his office downtown, Washington County Sheriff Ronnie
Skiles echoed the business-as-usual sentiments of others in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one time, executions were new to Potosi and new to law
enforcement here,'' Skiles said. ``It's pretty well settled down
now. People are people and, sure, we talk about it, but it's no big
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the country, executions have become a big deal.
Illinois placed a moratorium on its executions earlier this year
after several death-row inmates were cleared of charges against
them, and lawmakers in New Hampshire voted to abolish that state's
death penalty. In Virginia and Texas, new DNA testing was ordered
for a convicted rapist and a murderer _ the latter decision, by
Gov. George W. Bush, thrusting capital punishment into the arena of
presidential politics.
</P>
<P>
   Young would have been the third Missouri inmate put to death by
lethal injection this year and the 44th since use of the death
penalty resumed in the state in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before Young's execution, the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals ruled that St. Louis Circuit Attorney Dee Joyce-Hayes had
violated Young's right to due process. The court said she might
have interfered with testimony from a witness who could have helped
Young avoid the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The court ordered U.S. District Judge Jean Hamilton to
reconsider Young's appeal. Now that the U.S. Supreme Court has
refused to vacate the stay, the execution is postponed.
</P>
<P>
   No other executions have been scheduled this year.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over use of the death penalty has taken on a renewed
vigor in Missouri and throughout the country, with opinions
reflecting deep divisions. A poll commissioned recently by /{The
Kansas City Star/}, for example, found Missourians opposed to a
moratorium on the death penalty, 47 percent to 38 percent, with 15
percent undecided.
</P>
<P>
   But in Potosi, the issue generates little emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Don Strauser, a barber at Legendary Cuts, dismissed news about
Young with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never gave the death penalty much thought, but I'm all for
it,'' Strauser said. ``We're used to it. It's not a big thing. If
Young has killed someone, he should get the same.''
</P>
<P>
   About a mile east of town stands the Potosi Correctional Center,
a 140-acre prison complex rising out of a rolling field burned
brown from the sun. Its huddled groups of flat, tan buildings give
it the look of a college campus. Rolled rows of barbed wire and
steel gates, however, remind passers-by just what the buildings are
really for.
</P>
<P>
   About 400 people work at the prison, where about 80 inmates are
on death row and the inmate capacity is about 815. Many of the
employees live in and around Potosi, said Kris Richards, a former
president of the Potosi Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to get the prison here,'' Richards said. ``For the
jobs. It's maximum security. People won't just walk away from
there. We never see them. It makes executions an anonymous thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Richards said that if administrative parking spaces at the
prison were empty on Wednesday morning, he'd know an execution had
taken place.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means that the executives had to stay out late, so
something was going on. When a person is in prison, we don't know
who they are. We're like the rest of the state. If it didn't happen
in your town.''
</P>
<P>
   Employees at Lomax's, a restaurant downtown, have had firsthand
experience with executions: In the past, the restaurant has
prepared the last meals of condemned inmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd call about 6 p.m.,'' said waitress Christine DeClue.
``Always something different. Never the same meal twice. No one
talked about it much. Those men did bad things. Doesn't bother us
because of the murders they committed.''
</P>
<P>
   For the pastor and staff at St. James Church, a Catholic church
in Potosi, the subject of executions is at best a delicate issue,
since some parishioners work at the prison.
</P>
<P>
   The pastor of St. James declined to comment on his church's
dealings with the death penalty, but a spokesman for the
archdiocese of St. Louis acknowledged that the situation called for
a ``certain sensitivity,'' given the church's historical opposition
to capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church's teachings on the death penalty and justice are
clear,'' said spokesman Steve Mamanella. ``The pastor and his staff
have to address that in the way they feel is best for their church.
A parish in that situation will have issues of just treatment of
prisoners and victims' rights more at the front of their radar
screen.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Brewer, the associate pastor at the First Baptist Church of
Potosi, acknowledged that the issue of wrongful convictions had
made executions more complicated but said he didn't see the level
of interest rising much.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know it's done because it's publicized,'' Brewer said.
``It's kind of here, but it's a distant thing. There are those who
are for it, some against it and some apathetic. We talk about it;
it's nothing that's hidden.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that's just done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-00 2209EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
