<DOCNO> NYT20000716.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3854 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-AUGUST-PRIMARIES-KAN &LR;      07-16 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUGUST-PRIMARIES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXT MONTH'S PRIMARIES HERALD A LIVELY ELECTION YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIT WAGAR  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The summer calm cloaking the political
landscape will soon be shattered as candidates in both Missouri and
Kansas gear up for primary elections early next month.
</P>
<P>
   The primary campaigns kick off one of the most hotly contested
election years in Missouri history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Missouri is a battleground state,'' said Roy Temple, executive
director of the state Democratic Party. ``It has close races for
president, Senate and governor; competitive congressional races;
and the legislative chambers are in play. It's the grand slam and
the Triple Crown of elections.''
</P>
<P>
   From president and governor to treasurer and secretary of state,
even low-profile statewide races are shaping up as potential fights
for every vote. Many of the races carry national implications.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of congressional races in Missouri's 6th District
and Kansas' 3rd District could help determine whether Democrats
regain control of the U.S. House. A Democratic victory in
Missouri's U.S. Senate race would weaken Republican control of that
chamber.
</P>
<P>
   And Missouri's reputation as a presidential bellwether has both
major parties looking to the state as a key to winning the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   This year, even races for the General Assembly resonate in
Washington. That is because lawmakers elected this year will draw
new legislative and congressional districts based on the 2000
census. And Missouri Republicans see this year as their best chance
in decades to take control of the legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats hold only an 18-16 majority in the Senate and an 87-76
advantage in the House.
</P>
<P>
   In the marquee races for U.S. Senate and governor, the Aug. 8
primaries appear to be mere formalities. The Senate race will pit
incumbent Republican Sen. John Ashcroft against Democratic Gov. Mel
Carnahan.
</P>
<P>
   For governor, the Republicans have all but nominated U.S. Rep.
Jim Talent of St. Louis County, and the Democrats have all but
anointed state Treasurer Bob Holden of Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   But the race for lieutenant governor features hard-fought races
in both major parties. On the Democratic side, state Sen. Joe
Maxwell of Mexico is running against state Rep. Gracia Backer of
New Bloomfield. Both are respected within the party and have raised
hundreds of thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The race has been quiet so far as both have concentrated on
building organizations and meeting with local groups. That doesn't
surprise Temple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically, the primary is hand-to-hand combat among party
insiders,'' he said, ``until the last two or three weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, St. Charles County Executive Joe
Ortwerth is running against former state Treasurer Wendell Bailey.
Through the end of March, neither had raised more than $100,000.
State Sen. Bill Kenney of Lee's Summit had been expected to win the
Republican nomination, but he dropped out of the race in May.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Steve Gaw of Moberly is the favorite among
Democrats running for secretary of state. State Rep. Matt Blunt of
Springfield has emerged as the favorite among Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In the treasurer's race, Platte County prosecutor Todd Graves
appears to have the inside track on the Republican side. Democrats
have a three-way race between state Reps. Brian May of St. Louis
and Scott Lakin of Kansas City and former Rep. Nancy Farmer of St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The surplus of high-quality candidates stems at least partly
from term limits, which begin to affect most lawmakers in 2002.
Many are trying to continue their political careers by seeking
higher office. That, in turn, opens up their current seats to new
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   John Hancock, executive director of the Missouri Republican
Party, described the situation as a sinkhole. When Talent ran for
governor, five Republicans and a Democrat filed for his seat in
Congress. They included state Sen. Franc Flotron of St. Louis
County. Two state representatives then filed for Flotron's Senate
seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Term limits are a looming ax on the horizon,'' Hancock said.
``Any open seat creates a ripple effect. Big primary fields for an
attractive seat are going to become the norm.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas, which holds its primary Aug. 1, the featured races
involve the 3rd Congressional District and the seat on the Kansas
Board of Education now held by Linda Holloway.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway was chairwoman of the Kansas board when it decided last
year to de-emphasize certain aspects of evolution in the state's
science curriculum standards. The decision touched off protests
across the country by science teachers who said it represented
religious intrusion into science education.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway is being challenged by Sue Gamble, a member of the
Shawnee Mission school board. The winner will face Ron Patton, a
Democrat, in November.
</P>
<P>
   The congressional races for Kansas' 3rd District and Missouri's
6th District are attracting national attention. Both parties see
them as crucial to winning control of the chamber, where
Republicans hold a 222-211 majority.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Moore, a former Johnson County district attorney, was the
first Democrat elected from the 3rd District in nearly 40 years
when he defeated a Republican incumbent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Moore benefited from a split between conservatives and moderates
in the Kansas Republican Party. The district includes Johnson,
Wyandotte and Miami counties and most of Douglas County.
</P>
<P>
   Three Republicans _ Overland Park Councilman Greg Musil, state
Rep. Phill Kline and Olathe physician Gary Morsch _ are seeking the
Republican nomination to challenge Moore in November. They span the
ideological spectrum within the Kansas GOP. Each Republican claims
to be the only candidate who can beat Moore.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri's 6th District was considered a safe Democratic seat
until Rep. Pat Danner suddenly withdrew in May. Four Democrats,
four Republicans and a Libertarian are seeking the seat.
</P>
<P>
   The district covers 27 counties in northwest Missouri, including
Kansas City, North, from the Missouri River to the Iowa state line.
</P>
<P>
   John Petrocik, chairman of the political science department at
the University of Missouri-Columbia, said the two races are likely
to attract significant resources from national parties.
</P>
<P>
   Because 95 percent of incumbents are re-elected, only about 20
congressional races are truly competitive in a given election, he
said. So the parties focus on open seats, such as Missouri's 6th
District, and officeholders who don't seem to fit their districts,
such as a Democrat representing Kansas' heavily Republican 3rd
District.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever comes out of the primary will attract national money
and will have help from pollsters, managers and other major figures
from the national party,'' Petrocik said. ``They typically will
have their campaign steered toward fund-raisers and campaign aides
from inside the Beltway.''
</P>
<P>
   Petrocik said the winning presidential candidate is likely to
have coattails long enough for his party to control the House.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star's Jim Sullinger contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-00 2216EDT &QL; 
