<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3855 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0717-1     07-16 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0717-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: re-tops, updates and writes thru with comments from Clinton
. . .
 &HT;    TENSIONS INCREASE AS MIDEAST PEACE TALKS CONTINUE
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS AND LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ President Clinton said Sunday that he was
``slogging'' through the sixth day of Mideast peace talks, and he
called the negotiations ``the hardest thing I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from Camp David by telephone with a reporter from the
New York Daily News, Clinton cited ``some progress'' in the peace
summit he's hosting between Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more optimistic than I was when they got here,'' last
Tuesday, said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   He stressed the difficulties over the gains, though, and
emphasized that the outcome remains in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be totally misleading if I said I had an inkling that
a deal is at hand,'' Clinton said. ``That's just not true. But
we're slogging.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who has struggled through seven years of on-again
off-again Mideast peace efforts to cast a hopeful light on the
process, declined to predict success.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might make it, I don't know,'' Clinton said. ``God, it's
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's remarks were the first in which he has characterized
the Camp David negotiations since he opened the talks July 11. The
White House press office released a transcript of the comments late
Sunday to reporters staking out the peace summit from this mountain
hamlet five miles from the presidential retreat.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Clinton compared the talks with other peace
initiatives he's overseen concerning conflicts in Northern Ireland,
Bosnia and even earlier phases of peace talks between Palestinians
and Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Camp David summit, an effort to resolve the toughest
issues at the core of 52 years of bloody conflict between Israelis
and Palestinians, is the greatest diplomatic challenge of his
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like nothing I've ever dealt with,'' he said. ``All the
negotiations with the Irish, all the stuff I've done with the
Palestinians before this and with the Israelis, the Balkans at
Dayton. What's really troubling is that (Arafat and Barak) know if
they make a peace agreement half of their constituencies will have
to be angry at them for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also left open the question of whether he would leave on
schedule Wednesday for a trip to Japan. That journey, to attend the
annual summit of leaders from the so-called Group of Eight
democratic powers, has provided a de facto deadline for the ongoing
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he would leave as planned, though, Clinton was
noncommittal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope so; I'm gonna do my best to finish here,'' he said.
``There's been some progress, but I can't say I know we'll
succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Clinton, ``It's really hard. It's the hardest thing I've
ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met into the night with Arafat, and White House
spokesman P.J. Crowley told reporters that the president planned to
spend the night again at Camp David and get back to the negotiating
table on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In a reminder of the issues and passions at stake, more than
100,000 Israeli demonstrators rallied in Tel Aviv Sunday to protest
Barak's approach to the peace process. There were scattered
demonstrations in Palestinian-controlled territory as well by Arabs
fearing that Arafat might concede too much in an effort to strike a
deal.
</P>
<P>
   And in Washington, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.,
warned that the Republican-led Congress would not give Clinton a
blank check to pay for pledges he might make to secure a Mideast
peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have to be open to look at whatever they come up
with,'' Lott said during an interview on Fox News Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But, said Lott, ``there are some items that they would ask for
that clearly I don't think the Senate would be inclined to go along
with. For instance, paying for Palestinian resettlement would be of
some concern to Senators.''
</P>
<P>
   While no hard numbers have been discussed, Clinton and his
national security aides have advised Lott and other Congressional
leaders of the likelihood that any Camp David peace agreement would
require substantial U.S. military and economic aid.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have generally agreed that something in excess of $15
billion, over some
</P>
<P>
   period of time, would be expected from the United States _ along
with at least that much
</P>
<P>
   from the oil-rich states near the Persian Gulf, as well as U.S.
allies in Europe and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want Middle East peace,'' Lott said. ``But we'd better be
very careful with how those dollars are used.''
</P>
<P>
   After attending church services at Camp David's Evergreen Chapel
with his daughter, Chelsea, Clinton spent much of Sunday afternoon
huddling with senior Israeli and Palestinian negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   Barak and Arafat are focused on the most difficult areas of
dispute between them, including the question of Palestinian
statehood, territory and security, the future of Jerusalem, Jewish
settlers and the issue of Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Both face strident political opposition at home from quarters
that fear the concessions their side would be asked to make in
order to reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the difficulties Barak could face selling a peace
accord back home, more than 100,000 Israelis gathered Sunday in Tel
Aviv to protest what many expect will be Israeli concessions.
</P>
<P>
   Centered in Rabin Square, the large plaza where former Israeli
Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin was killed in 1995 by an opponent of
the peace process, the rally was primarily organized by Jewish
settlers from the occupied areas of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
   Israel captured the territories in the 1967 Israeli-Arab war and
has been handing over land there to Palestinians bit-by-bit under
the terms of the 1993 Oslo Accords. As many as 40,000 settlers may
have to move if Barak yields more land at Camp David, as is widely
expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to influence him to change his plans,'' said
Haya Ledaber, a 26-year-old resident of the Bet El settlement in
the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Like other demonstrators, Ledaber fears Barak might go too far
in his efforts to grant Arafat the territory he is demanding to
build the foundations of an independent Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole country will be given away to the Arabs,'' Ledaber
said. ``The settlements will be left under the Arabs without the
protection of the army and the Jews will be pushed into the
ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak has vowed to put any peace accord directly to the Israeli
people in a public referendum, should he strike a deal with Arafat
at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 210,000 settlers in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip, areas populated by more than 2. 5 million Palestinians. The
Israelis were encouraged to move there by the government in order
to stake a claim to the land. Barak vows not to move more than
50,000, though even that could face stiff resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday in the West Bank, Israeli police forced about 30 young
settlers to give up a new hilltop they had staked out without
government permission.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow's E-mail address is: larryk(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-00 2226EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000716.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
