</P>
<P>
   Like other demonstrators, Ledaber fears Barak might go too far
in his efforts to grant Arafat the territory he is demanding to
build the foundations of an independent Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole country will be given away to the Arabs,'' Ledaber
said. ``The settlements will be left under the Arabs without the
protection of the army and the Jews will be pushed into the
ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak has vowed to put any peace accord directly to the Israeli
people in a public referendum, should he strike a deal with Arafat
at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 210,000 settlers in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip, areas populated by more than 2. 5 million Palestinians. The
Israelis were encouraged to move there by the government in order
to stake a claim to the land. Barak vows not to move more than
50,000, though even that could face stiff resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday in the West Bank, Israeli police forced about 30 young
settlers to give up a new hilltop they had staked out without
government permission.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow's E-mail address is: larryk(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
