<DOCNO> NYT20000716.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3860 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-DNC-SPONSORS-2takes-L     07-16 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNC-SPONSORS-2takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORPORATIONS PICKING UP POLITICAL CONFABS' TABS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL HILLBURG 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - Generous corporate hosts and wealthy individuals
will be making the most of the Aug. 14-17 Democratic National
Convention in Los Angeles, footing 64 percent of a record $48.8
million budget for what is expected to be Vice President Al Gore's
four-day coronation ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Convention planners say the contributions fill a gaping hole in
funding the national events, but critics contend the heavy
corporate involvement amounts to influence peddling under the guise
of civic-mindedness.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just another loophole in campaign financing law that
allows people to influence people and lawmaking,'' said Holly
Bailey, a researcher for the Center for Responsive Politics, a
Washington-based watchdog group. ``Donors say this is all about
civic pride, but it's just another form of lobbying.''
</P>
<P>
   The outlay for the DNC, as reported by the Federal Election
Commission and convention organizers, includes:
</P>
<P>
   --$13.5 million in taxpayer funds donated via a checkoff on
income-tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   --$4 million in tax money given to the committee by the city of
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   --$31.3 million in goods, services and cash collected from
private and corporate donors by L.A. Convention 2000, the
Democrats' official host committee.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers say the massive outlay, up $5 million from what the
Democrats and their Chicago hosts spent on their 1996 confab, is
needed to offset a serious shortfall in public funding. Under
campaign reforms enacted by Congress in 1971, conventions are to be
primarily funded by voluntary taxpayer contributions.
</P>
<P>
   They also argue that the convention will be worth every penny,
as it will bathe Los Angeles in positive publicity aimed at
national and international audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what it costs to put on a convention. It's a gigantic
undertaking, and there are no frills in our budget,'' said Ben
Austin, director of communications for L.A. Convention 2000.
``We're spending $4 million on special community events, and we
also have high costs for transportation and other services.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin also stressed that organizers estimate that the
convention will draw 35,000 visitors and pump $135 million into the
region's economy.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign reform laws - which allow host committees to collect
money and help bankroll conventions to ``promote the commerce of
the host city during the convention'' - also contains a loophole
for the political parties.
</P>
<P>
   Party convention spending is strictly limited to the grant of
taxpayer funds from the FEC. That means the Democratic National
Committee, which recently confirmed it has more than $30 million in
cash on hand for the fall campaign, won't be dropping a dime of it
on the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Herbert Alexander, professor emeritus of political science at
the University of Southern California and a veteran convention
watcher, agreed that corporate sponsorship of conventions is
worrisome. But he said that flaws in federal law have made it a
necessity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make a mockery of the law by establishing public funding
for conventions and then not supplying enough money,'' Alexander
said. ``You can't put on a decent convention with such small
grants. If the federal government was willing to put up $40 million
for each party to pay for these events, there would be no problem.
But that's just not going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   FEC officials agreed that their grant program, which debuted at
the 1976 conventions, has proven woefully inadequate. The basic
grant of $4 million to each party has not changed since 1976. This
year's $13.5 million grant to both Democrats and Republicans only
represents a cost-of- living adjustment for 24 years of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The FEC also reported that its source of grant funds is
diminishing. In 1980, 28 percent of all taxpayers chose to
participate in the checkoff program on Internal Revenue Service tax
forms. That level has since fallen annually and now stands at 16
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and their L.A. hosts are quick to point out that
Republicans are spending even more on their July 31-Aug. 3
convention in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The FEC estimates the GOP's total at $63.5 million, up $20
million from the amount the party and its host committee spent in
San Diego in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   It includes the $13.5 million FEC grant and $7 million forked
over by the taxpayers of the City of Brotherly Love.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. convention organizers also point to the fact that they have
refused donations from tobacco companies. The Republicans'
corporate lineup includes a $250,000 donation from cigarette maker
Philip Morris.
</P>
<P>
   (Second take to come)
</P>
<P>
   Local boosters, including Mayor Richard Riordan, a registered
Republican who gave $1 million to the Democrats' host committee,
see the convention as a sure-fire vehicle for showcasing the
Southland's comeback from such setbacks as the 1992 riots, the 1994
Northridge Earthquake and a massive post-Cold War paring of the
aerospace industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way Los Angeles could have put on this event even
four years ago,'' Austin said, ``There were just too many serious
problems to deal with. But there has been a remarkable turnaround.
This isn't about putting L.A. on the map, everyone knows about us
through Hollywood and other sources. This is about redefining the
new L.A. to a national and international audience.''
</P>
<P>
   The convention's estimated crowd of 35,000 will include 15,000
journalists, as well as 4,368 voting delegates and 600 alternates.
</P>
<P>
   Also attending will be AT&AMP;T, which has contributed $1 million
worth of communications equipment, expertise and cash to the host
committee. AT&AMP;T is also giving $1 million to the Republicans'
Philadelphia host committee.
</P>
<P>
   Spokeswoman Rochelle Cohen said her company was doing its civic
duty by assisting the Democrats and the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   ``AT&AMP;T has a long and proud history of involvement with the
conventions and the democratic process,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen also said that AT&AMP;T plans to donate 100 used cell phones
to disadvantaged youths in Southern California after conventioneers
are through with their freebies.
</P>
<P>
   Researcher Bailey said other considerations may be behind AT&AMP;T's
largess. She noted that the telecommunications giant is currently
lobbying Congress to bless its merger with MediaOne, a major cable
TV and Internet provider, and to keep its cable lines closed to
other providers.
</P>
<P>
   American International Group, a New York-based insurance and
financial services conglomerate, gave the host committee $2
million. Bailey noted that AIG is lobbying for approval of
permanent normal trade relations with China, a measure passed by
the House but tied up in the Senate. AIG has already begun training
agents in China in anticipation of the opening of Chinese financial
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey said corporate giving appears to be a sound investment
for donors.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the conventions, you are dealing with an elite audience of
decision makers,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In her recent report on corporate convention giving, Bailey also
questioned whether host cities are going to get bangs for their
bucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a healthy sum of money for an event that has drawn a
collective yawn from the major TV networks,'' she wrote. Bailey
noted that ABC-TV plans to shoehorn opening-night Democratic and
GOP convention coverage into halftime of a pair of ``Monday Night
Football'' NFL preseason games.
</P>
<P>
   USC's Alexander, who attended every Democratic and GOP gathering
from 1960 to 1992, disagreed with the impact of the conventions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't downgrade them,'' he said. ``They are still
important kickoffs for the candidates and forums for issues. And
besides, the conventions are a lot of fun. It's only once every
four years that party activists can get together, socialize and
network.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander had one caution for Southland merchants expecting a
convention bonanza.
</P>
<P>
   ``Restaurants usually don't do very well,'' he explained.
``There are so many receptions and buffets that you rarely have to
pay for a meal.''
</P>
<P>
   x x x
</P>
</TEXT>
