<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS LOSE ON ERROR IN 10TH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO -- There were some big home runs in Sunday's game
between the Angels and San Diego Padres, but the hit that
ultimately won the game traveled all of 60 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Owens' bases-loaded bunt handcuffed Angels pitcher Al
Levine, allowing Kory DeHaan to score from third with the winning
run in the bottom of the 10th inning in the Padres' 6-5 victory
before 28,941 at Qualcomm Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had erased a three-run deficit in the ninth inning
with four runs against Padres closer Trevor Hoffman, only to lose
it one inning later on Levine's error.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting to a guy like Hoffman happens about as often as going
65 mph on the Hollywood Freeway,'' Angels manager Mike Scioscia
said. ``Right now it stings a little bit. ... When you get ahead
and think you have the game and can't close it out, sure it stings
a little bit. But this team has been good at turning the page. It's
one more loss and that's it. If you allow it to carry over, you're
really setting yourself up for trouble down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Home runs by Bret Boone, Joe Vitiello and Ben Davis gave the
Padres a 4-0 lead in the fourth inning. Darin Erstad's RBI double
in the seventh cut the Angels' deficit to 4-1, and it stayed that
way going into the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   But in the ninth the Angels rallied against Hoffman, who went
into the day with 23 saves, second most in the National League.
Adam Kennedy began the inning with a double, and one out later went
to third on a single by Erstad, his third hit of the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Stocker, who had already struck out three times in the
game, followed with a triple to the right-center field gap to score
Kennedy and Erstad and cut the Padres' lead to 4-3. Mo Vaughn then
gave the Angels their first lead of the day at 5-4 with a two-run
homer to right field, his 24th of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was thinking sacrifice fly in that situation, Vaughn
smiled and said: ``I'm never thinking sacrifice fly. I'm in a
position to take some chances, especially early in the count.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels closer Troy Percival entered the game in the bottom of
the ninth, but the Angels soon found themselves fighting to extend
the game. Al Martin led off the inning with a double and after a
sacrifice bunt by Kevin Nicholson, Owens tied the game by driving
in Martin from third with a sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the inning, ex-Angel Phil Nevin had a chance to win it
but Percival struck him out with the bases loaded to send the game
to extra innings.
</P>
<P>
   With Levine pitching in the 10th, DeHaan led off with a pinch
double and went to third on a grounder to second by Davis. After an
intentional walk to Martin, the Angels brought in Erstad from left
field to form a five-man infield.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out they didn't need the extra infielder because
Levine struck out Nicholson for the second out. Erstad then
returned to left field and Levine walked Ryan Klesko intentionally
to bring up Owens.
</P>
<P>
   Owens tried to push the ball past the mound to the right, but
didn't hit it hard enough. Levine got to the ball in plenty of time
but fumbled it for an error and the game was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took my eye off the ball and that was it,'' Levine (1-2)
said. ``I wanted to throw it before I caught it. I had plenty of
time. It was a mental mistake, really. ... When it costs you the
game, it really sucks. The guys battled and a play like that costs
us the game. It hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels wasted numerous opportunities to score early in the
game against Padres starter Adam Eaton. They had runners on first
and second with nobody out in the second inning and didn't score.
Kennedy was stranded after a leadoff triple in the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   Then in the fourth, the Angels loaded the bases with none out
but again squandered the chance. Troy Glaus struck out looking,
Bengie Molina popped to shallow right field and Kennedy flied to
center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't pick those guys up,'' Scioscia said.
``Obviously that changed the whole complexion of the ballgame. With
a little better situation hitting, it's a different game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I told somebody the other day, they all sting,'' Vaughn said
of the loss. ``Regardless of how, they all do. But the thing about
this ballclub is the ability to come back. We dropped the first
game in L.A. and played well the next two.''
</P>
</TEXT>
