<HEADER>
A3887 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBO-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-16 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Baseball's biggest need: fewer teams
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOHN P. LOPEZ
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ If your child is sick, the prescription is medicine.
It's as simple as that.
</P>
<P>
   You don't go into committee meetings with other parents and talk
about various ways to circumvent the illness. You don't ignore the
symptoms and keep shooing the kid toward the playground _ his eyes
drawn, his face flush, his fever rushing higher and higher.
</P>
<P>
   You go to the doctor.
</P>
<P>
   You don't crater to the convenient love of the favorite uncle _
we'll call him the Players Association _ who usually shows up only
when times are good, offering gifts and money, but is rarely around
in the middle of the night when the kid is wheezing and coughing.
</P>
<P>
   You make the child well. No matter how much it might hurt and no
matter if the tears break your heart, you do what is best for the
child's condition before it becomes dire and dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball is sick.
</P>
<P>
   While some teams flex and strut, the Minnesota Twins, Florida
Marlins, Montreal Expos, Tampa Bay Devil Rays and Oakland
Athletics, to name just five, wallow and deteriorate.
</P>
<P>
   The disparity in competitive balance in baseball today is grave,
and the realistic hope for long-term health is a joke.
</P>
<P>
   It's time for owners to swallow hard and do what is best for
their game, which is contraction, or de-expansion, or whatever
label MLB owners might want to place on the only thing that will
make the game well.
</P>
<P>
   At 30 teams, the game has at least two too many for its own
good. Maybe four.
</P>
<P>
   It's always painful to admit to mistakes, and it is easy for
those of us whose baseball teams would survive such a drastic move
to tell fans in Minneapolis and Montreal that we're sorry.
</P>
<P>
   But eliminating at least two teams from baseball, which is
something owners unofficially discussed at meetings this past week,
is the simple prescription that will work.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of trading for pitcher Denny Neagle, the New York
Yankees' payroll for the 2000 season is $115 million. The Twins
reportedly have a payroll of just over $17 million, only slightly
more than Dodgers pitcher Kevin Brown will make this year.
</P>
<P>
   Mountain climbing might have a playing field as slanted as this,
but little else does.
</P>
<P>
   Among the possibilities offered last week by a committee
investigating ways to increase competitive balance were:
</P>
<P>
   Imposing a 50 percent luxury tax on payrolls exceeding $84
million.
</P>
<P>
   Having teams share 40 to 50 percent of local revenues after
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Forming a ``competitive balance draft'' for players born outside
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Relocating franchises ``when necessary'' to address competitive
issues in some cities.
</P>
<P>
   Expanding baseball's domestic and international promotion of the
sport.
</P>
<P>
   But with a wound so deep, bandages don't stop the bleeding.
Besides, competitive balance is only one wound. Another problem is
the game itself.
</P>
<P>
   Even a revenue-sharing plan won't make pitching better or
reverse the growing trend of going to a major-league ballpark and
watching a beer-league softball game break out. A 5.00 ERA used to
mean a ticket to the minor leagues. Today, it's worth a five-year,
$16 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   When the first century of ``modern baseball'' ended last year,
only two men _ Hank Aaron and Babe Ruth _ had hit more than 700
home runs in a career. Within six or seven years, three players of
the same era _ Mark McGwire, Barry Bonds and Ken Griffey Jr. _
might have joined them.
</P>
<P>
   Home runs are coming cheap, but the game is cheapening itself,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another wound self-inflicted by owners is the not-so-subtle
arm-twisting done to cities, forcing them to build new baseball
palaces or else. The owners have thrown out All-Star Game plums as
prizes, as if this is all cities need to remain ``big-league.''
</P>
<P>
   But baseball clearly has underestimated the public's craving for
competitiveness, fallen victim to its own circus act called the
All-Star Home Run Derby and overestimated the value of cosmetics.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos have perhaps the game's best manager in Felipe Alou
and maybe the best player in Vladimir Guerrero _ a bona fide
long-ball whiz. But attendance is horrid in Montreal because fans
realize the Expos' chances of winning are zilch.
</P>
<P>
   Some might tell you that all the Expos need is a new stadium,
but that would only draw fans for the short term, perhaps much like
Enron Field is doing for the Astros today.
</P>
<P>
   What baseball needs is to swallow hard and admit its mistakes.
It needs to take its medicine and get better.
</P>
<P>
   Less is more.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-00 2259EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000716.0213 </DOCNO>
