<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4014 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-RUN-USTRIALS-LADN     07-16 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-USTRIALS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES SOARS, JOYNER-KERSEE FALLS SHORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL OBERJUERGE  
 San Bernardino Sun 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  SACRAMENTO -- Marion Jones took a great leap forward in her
bid for five gold medals. Jackie Joyner-Kersee's career ended,
again, with a game effort.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Johnson fended off his opponents, then shrugged off
critics. A legally blind woman qualified in the 1,500-meter run, an
Olympic first, and a pair of twins made another first by qualifying
out of the men's 400.
</P>
<P>
   It was a day of triumphs, clutch performances, upsets and
precedents a tthe U.S. Olympic Track and Field Trials on Sunday at
Sacramento State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is guaranteed at the trials,'' Johnson said after
winning the 400 in 43.68 seconds. ``Nothing is easy. Nobody gives
you anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones averted disaster in the women's long jump, the weak link
in her ambitious scheme for an unprecented five track-and-field
gold medals at Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   After fouling on her first two tries, she popped a jump of 22
feet, 1 3/4 inches on her third jump, putting her into the final
group of eight.
</P>
<P>
   She won the event on her fifth jump, a season-best 23-0 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a blink of an eye there, I though `I've got to get the
next one, or this dream is over,''' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Joyner-Kersee, Jones' idol, said she was as confident as was
Jones that Jones would get a qualifying mark on her third leap.
``She knew exactly what she had to do,'' Joyner-Kersee said. ``She
didn't even have to hit the board to qualify, and she knew it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones hopes to win gold in the 100, 200, long jump and both
relays. She now has secured Olympics berths in three events (the
100, the long jum p and the sprint relay), and has five days off
before beginning her bid for a 200 berth on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Joyner-Kersee, 38, ended her quixotic comeback bid with a
nothing-to-be-ashamed of leap of 21-10 3/4, good for sixth. She
came out of retirement only two months ago, and the trials was her
first meet since 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could never be disappointed,'' she said. ``I was on four
Olympic teams. This really was a longshot.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was pushed slightly in the 400, but never seemed in
trouble while winning the men's 400 in 43.68.
</P>
<P>
   He was asked if he could have threatened his world record of
43.18 had he pushed hard the entire race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Records, records, records!'' he said with some exasperation.
``That's all anybody ever talks about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Records don't happen every day, and to set a record, you have
to take risks, and this isn't the place for it. In Sydney, I want
to run the race of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he takes no umbrage at sniping at him by other track and
field athletes, particularly Maurice Greene and Inger Miller.
Miller on Saturday suggested the curls in Johnson's coiffure ``were
too tight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people have never been criticized, I guess,'' Johnson
said. ``A veteran athlete, a mature athlete, knows that all that
matters is what you do on the track.''
</P>
<P>
   Twins Alvin and Calvin Harrison ran second and fifth in the 400.
Alvin will compete in the individual 400 competition, and Calvin
very likely will be part of the relay team.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is wonderful, for twins to be on the same team,'' Alvin
said. ` `Always before, one got left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Marla Runyon refused to be left behind in the women's 1,500,
finishing a strong third in 4 minutes, 6.44 seconds, to make the
Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   Runyon is legally blind, and nearly fell when she bumped into a
competitor on the second lap, but said she doesn't think about her
condition, known as macular denegeration (which leaves her with
20/300 vision) as much as do people watching her.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I don't think my competitors do,'' she said. ``I'm
definitely an athlete. My vision is just a circumstance that
happened. I never really looked at it as a barrier. I never said to
myself, `I want to be the first legally blind Olympian.' I just
said I wanted to be on an Olympic team.''
</P>
<P>
   Regina Jacobs won the 1,500 in 4:01.01, making her fourth
Olympic team , and Suzy Favor Hamilton was second.
</P>
<P>
   In other events on a busy Sunday at Hornet Stadium:
</P>
<P>
   -- Lawrence Johnson took advantage of a field stripped of
American world-record holder Jeff Hartwig, who no-heighted in
qualifying, to win the pole vault at 19-1 1/2. Nick Hysong was
second, and Chad Harting won a jumpoff, the first at the trials
since 1936, according to meet organizers, with Derek Miles for
third.
</P>
<P>
   -- Gabe Jennings threatened the men's 1,500 trials record of
3:35.15 seconds before finishing first in 3:35.90. Jason Pyrah and
Michael Stember also qualified in the metric mile.
</P>
<P>
   -- Latisha Colander-Richardson won the women's 400 in 49.87,
well below her previous best, and veteran Jearl Miles-Clark was
second. San Diego prep Monique Henderson was eighth.
</P>
<P>
   -- Karol Damon was the surprise winner of the women's high jump
with a modest leap of 6-4. Amy Acuff, formerly of UCLA, won a
jumpoff with pre-meet favorite Tisha Waller for the third berth.
</P>
<P>
   -- Michelle Rohl won the women's 20,000-meter race walk.
</P>
</TEXT>
