<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-VALUE-ENERGY (Washington) _ With millions of air
conditioners humming this summer, and dire warnings of electricity
running short, a growing number of utilities are using novel
tactics to avoid blackouts and other disasters. Some are offering
cash to companies willing to reduce energy consumption at certain
hours, figuring the payments are less than the cost of providing
power at peak times. Other utilities are paying residential
customers for the right to shut off their air conditioners when
power usage is high, or to set them at higher temperatures.
Electricity has long been sold under a system under which a
kilowatt hour has a fixed price, and you can have as much as you
want until the supply runs out and there is none for anybody. But
now, utilities are pricing power the way almost everything else in
America is priced: by market value. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients. Photo
[NYT10) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-PSYCHOLOGY (Detroit) _ Of all the mysteries facing auto
industry marketers in recent years, few have been so puzzling as
how families choose between minivans and sport utility vehicles. To
look at median income, by age, by occupation, by family size, by
where they live, people who buy minivans and people who buy sport
utilities look fairly similar, the auto makers' research has found.
Yet a growing body of research in the auto industry suggests that
buyers of these two kinds of vehicles are very different
psychologically. Sport utility buyers tend to be more restless,
more sybaritic, less social people who are ``self-oriented,'' to
use the auto makers' jargon, while minivan buyers tend to be more
``other-oriented'' _ more involved with family, friends and their
communities. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-RESEARCH (Redmond, Wash.) _ For decades, Microsoft has
held a reputation in the computer industry as an imitator, not an
innovator. That reputation rankles deeply inside the software
giant, which has gained a Rodney Dangerfield-like complex about the
criticism in recent years. Partly as a result, the company is
spending heavily in research in a range of areas from tablet
computing to voice recognition. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT-STRIKE-MEDIA (Sterling Heights, Mich.) _ On its fifth
anniversary, the last great newspaper strike of the 20th century, a
ghost with a living grievance, still haunts Detroit. If the strike
is a memory, though, its consequences are not. ``It's incredibly
tragic that the unions and companies couldn't come to some middle
ground,'' said David Crumm, a religion writer for The Free Press.
``As it is, we've educated a whole generation of readers that they
don't need to read our newspapers. So we all lose.'' By Felicity
Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   JDS-UNIPHASE-ASSESS (Undated) _ With its $41 billion deal last
week to acquire SDL Inc., the fiber-optic equipment company JDS
Uniphase agreed to its ninth acquisition since last September. What
is the strategy at work here, and what are its prospects for
success? A news analysis. By Laura M. Holson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphics have been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-HITS-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ The breakout this year of sudden
hits like ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' and ``Survivor'' has
created a new type of strategizing by advertisers who are trying to
determine which programs to sign onto early, and how to scramble
when a property that didn't seem to have much potential suddenly
becomes hot. And while the Nielsen jury is still out on ``Big
Brother,'' that program, too, illustrates the new kind of
odds-making by marketers and media-buying agencies. By Stuart
Elliott.
</P>
