<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-CAMP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGE IS IN THE AIR AS THE COWBOYS OPEN TRAINING CAMP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ The Dallas Cowboys arrive at Midwestern
State University on Monday to begin training camp for a third
summer in a row, but that's about where the sameness leaves off and
the newness begins.
</P>
<P>
   What will Camp Campo be like? How quickly until Jack Reilly's
new adaptation of an old Cowboys' offense becomes second nature?
Who will replace Deion Sanders at right cornerback?
</P>
<P>
   The Dave Campo era begins at 3 p.m. Monday when all players are
scheduled to report and be checked into their dorm rooms. Two-a-day
workouts then get under way Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Sanders missed all of training camp and raised a
major question over when he would be able to play after undergoing
big-toe surgery three months earlier. Michael Irvin reported to
Wichita Falls amid a controversy over what then-coach Chan Gailey
outlined as a reduced role for Irvin in the offense.
</P>
<P>
   But a year ago, at least Sanders and Irvin were Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders is now a member of the NFC East rival Washington
Redskins after the Cowboys opted not to re-sign the 32-year-old
cornerback/return man for salary-cap reasons and the 34-year-old
Irvin retired because of a spinal condition. Irvin now begins a
broadcasting career with Fox Sports Net.
</P>
<P>
   Most Cowboys fans recognize that receiver Joey Galloway was
acquired by the Cowboys from Seattle in February to serve as a
complement to Rocket Ismail and a replacement for Irvin. The deal
cost owner Jerry Jones two first-round draft picks and a seven-year
deal worth $42 million, including a $12.5 million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys fans probably are less aware that Cleveland free agent
Ryan McNeil was acquired a couple of weeks after Galloway to become
Sanders' replacement.
</P>
<P>
   While Galloway has been impressive in each of the Cowboys' four
organized workouts at Valley Ranch this off-season, McNeil looked
``rusty'' to the defensive coaches until the final minicamp, June
12-14, when he started to find his niche.
</P>
<P>
   But confidence has never been a problem for McNeil, 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest asset is that I'm able to adjust and adapt,'' said
McNeil, who finds himself playing for his fourth NFL team (Detroit,
St. Louis, Cleveland and Dallas) and seventh defensive coordinator
in eight NFL seasons.
</P>
<P>
   McNeil and veteran Kevin Smith enter training camp as the
Cowboys' starting corners. Smith missed half of the 1999 season
with lower back and hamstring injuries. Injury-plagued Kevin
Mathis, who opened the '99 season as a starter and started four
games at cornerback last season, was traded this off-season to New
Orleans for linebacker Chris Bordano.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys haven't tried to hide their concern at cornerback.
They used three of their top four draft picks to take cornerbacks
Duane Goodrich, Kareem Larrimore and Mario Edwards to compete with
McNeil, Smith, Charlie Williams and NFL Europe star Duane
Hawthorne.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to say that (cornerback) is a weak link,'' said
defensive coordinator Mike Zimmer, ``but it is an area of concern
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   McNeil feels it's just a matter of learning the defense before
he begins to help erase some of those concerns. He's a tall corner
(6-foot-2) with a good burst to the ball. Two years ago with the
Rams, he led the NFL with nine interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be a lot of question marks (at cornerback) around
here,'' said McNeil, ``but not on my part.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys appear deeper at wide receiver than they have been
in years with Galloway and Ismail backed up by James McKnight, who
already has shown signs of coming back strong from major
reconstructive knee surgery 11 months ago, plus the 1999 emergence
of TCU grad Jason Tucker. Also figuring into the mix will be Chris
Brazzell, Wane McGarity and another NFL Europe star, Jeff Ogden.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback? It's a different kind of depth there. Training camp
will be used to sort out the contenders from the pretenders. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
