<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRUGGLE CONTINUES FOR PERCIVAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO -- Angels closer Troy Percival was given the ball to
start the bottom of the ninth inning Sunday afternoon at Qualcomm
Stadium, asked to save a 5-4 lead. The Angels had just scored four
runs in the top of the ninth off Padres closer Trevor Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of getting his 22nd save, Percival was tagged with
his sixth blown save when the Padres scored once to tie the game
and send it into extra innings. The Padres eventually won in 10
innings, 6-5.
</P>
<P>
   Percival faced seven batters in all, and it wasn't pretty:
Double, sacrifice bunt, walk, sacrifice fly, hit batter, walk,
strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is expected to be successful every time, but Percival's
postgame comments showed he still is searching to find a consistent
rhythm that has eluded him most of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was probably physically as good as I've felt in four
years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Percival threw mostly curveballs, staying away from his 95-mph
fastball because ``I had an open base with fastball hitters coming
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Martin doubled on Percival's first pitch of the inning, a
fastball. But Percival, normally not afraid to challenge hitters
with his fastball, stayed away from it most of the time, though he
did strike out Phil Nevin on a fastball to end the inning. In
between, though, the Padres pushed across the tying run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably could have thrown a few more fastballs than I
did,'' Percival said. ``But I'm not going to second-guess myself. I
had good stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Percival said his only mistake was a fastball away to Eric
Owens, who went the other way and hit a sacrifice fly to right
field that tied the game. Percival said he should have thrown the
pitch inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy's had a lot of success,'' Angels manager Mike
Scioscia said. ``He's got a good feel for what he has to do out
there. Sometimes it works and sometimes it doesn't. He feels good
with his breaking ball. If he feels he needs a breaking ball to get
out of an inning, he'll use it.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Jarrod Washburn threw six innings innings Sunday,
five of which were scoreless. But it was the one inning that hurt
him and the Angels. The Padres hit three homers in the fourth,
scoring four runs.
</P>
<P>
   ''Wash was getting behind a lot of the hitters, and it caught up
with him,'' Scioscia said.
</P>
<P>
   Washburn struck out seven to tie his career high, but the one
bad inning was the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I left some balls up,'' Washburn said. ``They were the right
pitches, just in the wrong spots and they made me pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Lou Pote was optioned to Triple-A Edmonton after
Sunday's game to make room for Brian Cooper, who was activated and
will start tonight's game. ... Garret Anderson, who missed
Saturday's game because of a sore right knee, returned to the
lineup Sunday and went 4 for 5, extending his hitting streak to 10
games.
</P>
</TEXT>
