<HEADLINE>
MISSION ACCOMPLISHED: COWBOYS SIGN FINAL PICKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Dallas Cowboys' chief negotiator Stephen
Jones has fulfilled his promise to have all the rookie draft picks
signed for the start of training camp Monday at Midwestern State
University.
</P>
<P>
   Jones made good on the promise Sunday when the team's first and
last picks came to terms. Cornerback Dwayne Goodrich (second round)
and linebacker Orantes Grant (seventh round) joined the team's
three other picks _ cornerbacks Kareem Larrimore (fourth round) and
Mario Edwards (sixth round) and running back Michael Wiley (fifth
round) _ with contracts just in time for camp.
</P>
<P>
   Players are scheduled to report to camp by 3 p.m. Monday. The
first practice is set for Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always want to get everybody in camp on time,'' Jones
said. ``We actually got a day or so to spare. This is early for us.
We are usually not done until midnight before the first practice.
This might be a record.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodrich signed a four-year deal with a $1 million signing
bonus. His base salaries are $250,000 in 2000, $312,500 in 2001,
$375,000 in 2002 and $437,500 in 2003. His deal will count just
$500,000 against the Cowboys salary cap in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Grant's deal calls for him to receive $193,000 in 2000, $275,000
in 2001 and $356,000 in 2002. He also got a $30,000 signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie free-agent offensive tackle Jonathan Gray, who played at
Texas Tech, surprised the Cowboys by deciding to retire from
football. .MDBU/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
