<HEADLINE>
LACK OF TIMELY HITTING SINKS RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Tony Bennett mighthave left his heart in San
Francisco, but the Texas Rangers seem to have left their clutch
hitting in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The big hits that carried them to two thrilling victories
against the Diamondbacks were notably absent on a cold afternoon at
Pacific Bell Park on Sunday when the Rangers went 1-for-11 with
runners in scoring position and fell to the San Francisco Giants,
6-4.
</P>
<P>
   The loss left the Rangers 2-2 on the current 11-game road trip
and dropped them 8 1/2 games behind the Seattle Mariners in the
American League West.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating we couldn't get the big hit,'' shortstop
Royce Clayton said. ``But we kept battling back. This team doesn't
quit. If we keep doing that and keep playing good baseball, we'll
be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Esteban Loaiza took the loss by allowing five runs in five-plus
innings and the Giants got an extra run in the eighth when a fan in
left field reached over the wall to snag Rich Aurilia's long fly
ball when it appeared Rusty Greer was going to catch it.
</P>
<P>
   But Rangers manager Johnny Oates wasn't interested in talking
about his enigmatic starting pitcher or the home run that could
have been caught. Instead he focused on the Rangers' ``missed
opportunities,'' a lament that echoed throughout the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had three or four opportunities where one or two big hits
would have led to big innings,'' Oates said. ``But we couldn't get
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers gave Loaiza a 3-1 lead going into the sixth, but it
disappeared quickly into the gloom. Loaiza walked Barry Bonds to
start the inning, Jeff Kent singled to left and J.T. Snow, jumping
on the first pitch, lined a home run to right to give the Giants a
4-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   After Ellis Burks singled to center, Loaiza was pulled.
Francisco Cordero took over andwalked Aurilia, then gave up a
single to Bobby Estella to make it a two-run game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Loaiza was fine,'' Oates said. ``It's not always Loaiza's
fault. He gave us five-plus innings against the best hitting team
in the National League. Two base hits at the right time and instead
of leaving the game trailing 4-3, he's leading 7-4 and we're
talking about how well he pitched.''
</P>
<P>
   There were four such innings where a key hit could have won it
for the Rangers against Giants starter Shawn Estes or left-handed
reliever Alan Embree.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers started the first with a single by Luis Alicea and a
double by Greer. But they got just one run on Ivan Rodriguez's
grounder. Estes struck out David Segui and got Chad Curtis on a
grounder back to the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis' run-scoring double in the fourth, giving the Rangers a
2-1 lead, also left them with runners on second and third with no
outs. But they got just one more run on Gabe Kapler's grounder to
short. On the same play, first baseman Snow cut down Curtis, who
was trying to go to third.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers loaded the bases with one out in the seventh off
Estes. After Embree took over, they got only one more run on
Greer's sacrifice fly as Rodriguez, in a 1-for-13 slump, struck
out.
</P>
<P>
   With the Rangers trailing 5-4, Segui and Curtis started the
eighth with singles. But Scott Sheldon, pinch hitting for pitcher
Mike Venafro, bunted too hard back to Embree and Segui was forced
at third. Embree, who had a 16.20 career earned-run average against
the Rangers coming into the game, then struck out Mike Lamb and
Clayton looking.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at my numbers in the past against Texas, they
haven't been the best,'' Embree said. ``I think I had one good
outing against them and that was in long relief. That's something
you hope that down the line, you'll get the monkey off your back.''
</P>
<P>
   Aurilia's controversial home run made it 6-4, but Giants closer
Robb Nen breezed through the ninth, which is why there was little
complaining in the Rangers' clubhouse afterward about the umpires
costing them the game. The Rangers knew this one was lost at the
plate, or left behind in Arizona. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
