<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HOME RUN THAT WAS THAT MAYBE SHOULDN'T HAVE BEEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The San Francisco Giants got a potentially
important, but controversial insurance run in the bottom of the
eighth inning Sunday when Rich Aurilia hit a home run off Tim
Crabtree. But the Texas Rangers contend fan interference should
have been called because a spectatorappeared to reach over the
left-field wall and catch the ball before left fielder Rusty Greer
could.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it appeared the two gloves bumped. But the fan's glove
was higher and replays also showed it was in front of Greer when he
caught the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt something,'' Greer said. ``But I was focused on the
ball so I don't know what it was. I can't say definitely I would
have caught it, but I felt I had a chance to make the play.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Royce Clayton, who led the argument with second
base-umpire Steve Rippley, said, ``My whole thing was I don't think
the ball would have gone out. I saw Rusty go up for it and hit the
fan. I thought fan interference would have been called.'' HISTORIC
DAY FOR SEGUI
</P>
<P>
   David Segui started at first base Sunday to earn his niche in
baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   The game was Segui's 1,000th at first base, which qualified him
to be listed among the all-time fielding percentage leaders at the
position.
</P>
<P>
   Segui has a .99590 career percentage, which places him second
behind Steve Garvey (.99594) and just ahead of Don Mattingly
(.99582).
</P>
<P>
   Oates, with the designated hitter not being used at the National
League park, started Segui because left-hander Shawn Estes was on
the mound. It also gave him a chance to rest Rafael Palmeiro for
two consecutive days.
</P>
<P>
   Oates said Palmeiro will start the next two games in San
Francisco, which end the Rangers' interleague schedule. But he also
plans on giving Palmeiro more time at designated hitter in the
second half than before the All-Star break. The Rangers have fewer
days off in the second half and Oates wants to keep Palmeiro
strong. He said it falls under the same philosophy of giving
catcher Ivan Rodriguez more time off in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Palmeiro not being in the lineup gave Oates a terrific
pinch hitter on the bench. But he could never get him in the game.
Oates did use two pinch hitters, Scott Sheldon in the seventh and
Frank Catalanotto in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   With the Rangers trailing by one, Sheldon batted with runners on
first and second and nobody out. With left-hander Alan Embree on
the mound, Oates wanted a sacrifice bunt. Instead Sheldon bunted
too hard and forced Segui at third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to hit Raffy off a left-hander,'' Oates said.
``We're bunting there.'' OLIVER JOINS RANGERS
</P>
<P>
   Darren Oliver rejoined the Rangers Sunday, but manager Johnny
Oates is still unsure when Oliver will return to the rotation.
Oates said Oliver would likely pitch either Wednesday or Thursday,
either for the Rangers or on medical rehabilitation assignment for
Triple-A Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to pitch,'' Oliver said. ``We'll see what happens.
It's not always my decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers could create an opening for Oliver by trading
Esteban Loaiza, going back to a 12-man pitching staff or dropping a
reliever, either Doug Davis or Francisco Cordero. GLYNN FOR
DRANSFELDT
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are planning to activate pitcher Ryan Glynn off the
disabled list Monday and send shortstop Kelly Dransfeldt back to
the minors. Dransfeldt was promoted the week before the All-Star
break when shortstop Royce Clayton was sidelined because of a
strained left side muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Dransfeldt is 1-for-5 with the Rangers, his only hit being a
double off Randy Johnson on Saturday. Dransfeldt is hitting .224
for Triple-A Oklahoma. Despite his lack of offense, Johnny Oates
says of Dransfeldt's defense, ``he's as good as any shortstop in
the majors.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
