<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-16 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4029 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-GLF-OPEN-STANFORD-TEX     07-16 0463
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-STANFORD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU GRAD ANGELA STANFORD EXCITED TO CONTINUE GOLF EDUCATION AT
OPEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ This won't be a summer forgotten anytime
soon by Angela Stanford, and ``I'm only halfway through,'' she
says, with the exuberance of 5-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford, who received her degree from TCU this spring, spent
most of June in England representing the United States at the
Curtis Cup, and later competed at the British Women's Amateur.
There, she qualified for match play and beat four opponents in two
days, before losing in the semifinals to eventual champion Rebecca
Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   And, Stanford's selection to the U.S. Curtis Cup squad also
ensured her berths in the U.S. Women's Amateur Championship and the
U.S. Women's Open Championship, which begins Thursday at Merit Club
in Libertyville, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always wanted to play in the Open,'' Stanford said. ``But
if the Open experience even touches the experience I had at the
Curtis Cup, I'll be shocked. The experience I had those two weeks
in England was probably the best golf experience I'll ever have.
But I'm thinking the Open will come extremely close.
</P>
<P>
   ``My best friend called me a couple of nights ago, and she said,
`I saw your pairings for the Open,' '' Stanford continued. ``That's
when I lost it. That's when it was like, `Oh, wow!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford will be paired with Sherri Turner and Melissa McNamara,
and the best the LPGA offers _ players such as Karrie Webb, Pat
Hurst, Grace Park, Beth Daniel, Pat Bradley and Kelly Robbins _
will be playing in the four groups behind her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be teeing the ball up in front of Beth Daniel and
Pat Hurst,'' Stanford said. ``I think that's when it hit me. I'm
more concerned about who's behind me. I'm telling you that it's
going to be hard because I'm going to be wanting autographs.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford's primary goal this week will be to survive the cut and
then set her sights on finishing as the tournament's low amateur.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's going to be overwhelming,'' she said. ``I know I'm
going to have to play better than I feel like I've ever played
before.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Open, Stanford will begin preparing for the U.S.
Women's Amateur Championship, scheduled Aug. 5-12 in Portland, Ore.
She will likely turn professional after that.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford plans to enter the LPGA's first sectional qualifier,
scheduled for Aug. 21-25 at The Plantation Golf and Country Club in
Venice, Fla., and attempt to earn a berth in the final LPGA
qualifying tournament, scheduled Oct. 16-20 at LPGA International's
Champions Course in Daytona Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, the Open awaits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm like a kid in a candy store right now,'' she said. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
